前言：我们的故事

Preface: Our Story

有太多的沉默需要打破。

There are so many silences to be broken.

—奥德丽·洛德，《局外人姐妹》（1984年）

—Audre Lorde, Sister Outsider (1984)

从某种意义上说，这本书代表了“一个心灵和两个身体”的思想。它就像我们，同卵双胞胎，用一个 DNA 和两种经历在生命的画布上勾勒出一幅草图。它来自一个羊膜囊和两次呼吸。它是通过两种性别的眼光看待一种成长的产物。这本书的起源既是一又是二，既是我又是我们，既相同又不同，反映了好奇心本质的核心张力。好奇心是一个词、一串字母、头脑中的一个概念，但好奇心也有多种表现形式、多种实践和许多身体中的同类类型。就像一个属跨越物种或我们的母亲拥抱她的十一个孩子一样，好奇心既是一又是多。好奇心的一和多性质是实现认知自由的机会：我们可以好奇！但它也是造成认知不公正的责任：我们被允许以更少的方式好奇。

In a sense, this book represents the thought of one mind and two bodies. It is like us, identical twins, a sketch upon the canvas of life drawn by one DNA and two experiences. It was penned from one amniotic sac and two breaths. It is the product of one upbringing seen through the eyes of two genders. Both one and two, both I and we, both same and different, the origination of this book reflects the central tensions of curiosity’s nature. Curiosity is one word, one string of letters, one concept in the mind, but curiosity also has multiple manifestations, a plethora of practices, and kindred kinds in many bodies. Like a genus spanning species or our mother embracing her eleven children, curiosity is both one and many. The one-and-many nature of curiosity is an opportunity for the attainment of epistemic freedoms: we are permitted to be curious! But it is also a liability for the perpetration of epistemic injustices: we are permitted to be curious in less than many ways.

小时候，我们坐在同一张桌子旁，呼吸着一种独特的、充满好奇的家庭关系空间的空气。我们的教室毗邻客厅，紧邻厨房，位于宾夕法尼亚州中部的一座石头农舍里。周围有上千本书籍，在母亲的一句口头禅的指导下，我们热爱学习，看到了知识的美妙之处。“掌控你的她会说：“首先，我们需要学习知识，没有人会填鸭式地教育你。先搞清楚你想知道什么，然后想办法学。”随着家庭的壮大，母亲很快教会我们自学，用家庭教师的教学手册和解答题来给自己的作业打分，不断反复做题，直到找出错的原因。她鼓励我们每天、每月、每年选择学习科目的顺序和性质。一整个学期都学骨头？没问题。用附近树林里的有毒植物做实验？当然。每天练习勃拉姆斯的《B 小调狂想曲》，作品 79 号，第 1 号，持续 11 个小时？为什么不呢？历史、科学、语言和艺术课程都以蘑菇为中心？答案是肯定的。母亲的目标是追随我们的兴趣，联系概念，激发我们的疑问，打开大门，将我们的探究置于不同的历史轨迹和知识社区中。具体而言，我们获得了对认识论自由和责任的好奇心的素材。

As children sitting beside one another at identical desks, we breathed the air of a uniquely curious space embedded in familial relations. Our schoolroom was adjacent to the living room and beside the kitchen in a stone ranch house in Central Pennsylvania. Surrounded by more than a thousand books and guided by our mother’s one mantra, to love learning, we saw the beauty of what could be known. “Take control of your education,” she would say, “no one is spoon-feeding you. Figure out what you want to know and then figure out how to learn it.” As the family grew in size, our mother quickly taught us to teach ourselves, to grade our own work using the homeschooler’s teaching manual and solution key, and to rework problems until we figured out why we had gotten them wrong. We were encouraged to choose the order and nature of subjects each day, each month, each year. A full semester on bones? No problem. Devising experiments with poisonous plants from the nearby woods? Sure. Practicing Johannes Brahms’s Rhapsody in B minor op. 79, no. 1 for eleven hours per day? Why not? Centering history, science, language, and art curricula all around mushrooms? A definitive “yes.” Our mother’s goal was to follow our interests, connect concepts, fuel our questions, and open doors, situating our inquiries in divergent historical trajectories and knowledge communities. In concrete ways, we were given the fodder for a curiosity of epistemic freedom and accountability.

然而，在我们这个美丽而又充满好奇的小世界里，自由在时间、身体和概念空间上受到限制。女孩注定要长大成人，结婚生子，照顾家庭，顺从丈夫；上大学和工作不在计划之内。男孩注定要长大成人，掌握一门手艺，养家糊口，掌管家务，选择妻子的朋友，安排女儿的婚姻。我们用双眼看着对方，然后看着我们的世界，问道：“为什么？你给了我们铁锹。我们打算挖土。”一路上，在意想不到的盟友的善意鼓舞下，我们打破了墙壁，跨越了界限，攀登了高峰，成为了今天的跨学科学者——致力于认识和抵制我们周围和充斥着的认知不平等的学者。我们绝对不是我们本该成为的样子，但我们正在遵循我们心中不断形成的好奇心的轨迹：一条跨越、连接、包容和建设的轨迹；一条欣赏我们内心和通过它们认识的逆流和联盟的轨迹。教育家亚伯拉罕·弗莱克斯纳写道：“人类真正的敌人不是无所畏惧和不负责任的思想家，无论他是对还是错。”“真正的敌人是那些试图塑造人类精神的人，以至于它不敢展翅翱翔。” 1虽然我们的周围世界就是这样的敌人，但母亲灌输给我们的好奇心却是一剂解药、一个对照剂、一个朋友。

Yet in our beautiful little curious world, freedom was circumscribed, in time, body, and conceptual space. Girls were meant to grow up into women, get married, have babies, care for the home, and be submissive and obedient to their husbands; college and career were not in the cards. Boys were meant to grow up into men, acquire a trade, provide financially for their families, and rule the household, choosing their wife’s friends and arranging their daughters’ marriages. With twin eyes, we looked at each other, then out at our world, and asked, “Why? You gave us spades. We plan to dig.” Buoyed by the kindness of unlooked-for allies along the way, we broke down walls, crossed boundaries, and scaled heights to become the interdisciplinary scholars that we are today—scholars who are committed to recognizing and resisting the epistemic inequities that surround and suffuse us. We are definitively not what we were meant to be, but we are following the ever-becoming trajectory of the curiosity instilled in us: one that spans, one that connects, one that embraces, and one that builds; one that appreciates the crosscurrents and coalitions within and through which we come to know. “The real enemy of the human race is not the fearless and irresponsible thinker, be he right or wrong,” writes educator Abraham Flexner. “The real enemy is the man who tries to mold the human spirit so that it will not dare to spread its wings.”1 While our local world was just such an enemy, the curiosity our mother instilled in us was an antidote, a counterpoint, a friend.

有些人会觉得我们的故事有些令人惊讶，当然很奇怪，甚至可能完全是异类。然而，许多人会认为我们的故事相当平常，完全在意料之中。我们的故事令人不可思议的熟悉感源于一个令人不安的事实：好奇心无处不在。好奇心的界限只针对某些人，不针对其他人，不针对某些时间，不针对其他人，不针对某些空间，并不局限于人类生活的小岛屿，而是遍布整个人类社会。不同性别的人被赋予天赋和经历，以鼓励他们在某些方面而不是其他方面产生好奇心。在某些文化中，某些种族或民族背景、阶级、性取向和能力的人会受到开放，而其他人则不会。弱势群体受到限制，而特权阶层则获得了自由，他们的思想可以在田野里漫游，攀登顶峰，在思想的小径上蜿蜒曲折，寻求知识。即使在高等教育机构中，我们可能认为这是人类精神可以展翅翱翔的地方，学者们也往往在工作属于预先指定的领域时才被聘用：一个部门、一个孤立的学科，或者一个简化规定的思想历史或方法论。好奇心的缩小、限制和支配从何而来？为什么存在所谓正确和错误的好奇方式？值得和不值得好奇的话题？天生好奇和天生不好奇的人？

Some would see our story as somewhat surprising, certainly strange, and perhaps downright alien. Yet many others would view our story as fairly commonplace and fully expected. The uncanny familiarity of our story stems from an uncomfortable fact: curiosity is policed everywhere. The demarcation of curiosity for some bodies and not others, some times and not others, some spaces and not others is not sequestered to small islands of human life but rather pervades all of human society. People of differently assigned genders are given gifts and experiences to encourage their curiosity in some directions and not others. Doors are opened for people of some racial or ethnic backgrounds, classes, sexualities, and abilities and not others, in some cultures and not others. While the disadvantaged are held back, the privileged are offered freedom for their minds to roam the fields, scale the summits, and meander the byways of thought in search of knowledge. Even in institutions of higher learning, which we might expect to be the places where the human spirit can spread its wings, scholars are hired most often when their work falls into a prespecified space: that of a department, a siloed discipline, or a reductively stipulated history or methodology of thought. Where does the narrowing, the constraining, the ruling of curiosity come from? Why do there exist supposedly right and wrong ways to be curious? Worthy and unworthy topics of curiosity? The naturally curious and the naturally incurious?

部分原因在于好奇心的单一性。好奇心是一个词、一串字母、头脑中的一个概念。创造好奇心就是在心中划一条界线、一条边界、一堵墙，将好奇心与其他一切分开。当你拥有好奇心时，你也就失去了好奇心。在场的存在标志着缺席的存在。当你拥有某物时，你也必定一无所有。单一性允许二分法。单一性选择简单而不是复杂。通过使用一个词、一个概念、一段历史，我们允许好奇心被定义、参数化，并且最终被规范。人们可能常常忘记的是好奇心的多样性：它的多种表现形式、它的多种实践以及它在科学和工程中的同类类型。 多种主体。尽管好奇心具有一和多的本质，但许多人只听从前者而避开后者。但他们需要吗？什么样的世界可以接受好奇心的多样性？我们如何定义众多的好奇心？我们需要跨越哪些学科？我们可以掌握哪些关系？我们需要接受哪些谦卑和历史？我们可以建立什么样的思维架构？我们如何有意识地实践好奇心，让每个人的精神都能飞翔？在提出这些问题（以及许多同类问题）时，我们在这本书中探究了好奇心本质的核心张力。借用诗人 TS 艾略特充满爱意的话语来描述我们对好奇心的追求，我们“提起并放下”你的盘子上的每一个“问题”。我们花时间“犹豫一百次，设想一百次，修改一百次”。我们花时间思考，“我敢吗？”当我们这样做时，我们会找到一个简单的答案：好奇心确实敢。它敢于“扰乱宇宙” 。2

In part, the answer lies in the oneness of curiosity. Curiosity is one word, one string of letters, one concept in the mind. To make one is to draw a boundary, a border, a wall that separates the one from anything else. When you have one, you also have not-one. The existence of presence marks the existence of absence. When you have something, then you must also have nothing. Unity permits dichotomy. Unity chooses simplicity over complexity. In using a single word, a single concept, a single history, we allow curiosity to be defined, parameterized, and, yes, eventually regulated. What people have perhaps too often forgotten is the manyness of curiosity: its multiple manifestations, its plethora of practices, and its kindred kinds in many bodies. Despite the one-and-many nature of curiosity, many people hearken only to the former and eschew the latter. But need they? What kind of world might embrace curiosity’s manyness? How might we define a multitudinous curiosity? What disciplines might we need to span? What relations might we grasp? What humilities and histories might we need to embrace? What architectures of the mind might we build? How might we consciously practice curiosity in a manner that allows each human spirit to fly? In asking these questions (and many sibling questions), we probe in this book the central tension of curiosity’s nature. Borrowing poet T. S. Eliot’s words of love to frame our pursuit of curiosity, we “lift and drop” each “question on your plate.” We take the time “for a hundred indecisions, and for a hundred visions and revisions.” We take the time to wonder, “Do I dare?” And as we do, we find one simple answer: curiosity does dare. It dares “disturb the universe.”2

视觉媒体简介

A Brief Note on Visual Media

本书的文字由两种视觉媒体补充，每种媒体都旨在突出好奇心存在方式的不同方面。首先，我们在每一章前面都放了一张由艺术家和插画家 Poonam Mistry 创作的扉页，以精湛的视觉形式强调关键概念。Poonam 的风格融入了她对大自然的热爱，探索了图案、形状和颜色之间的关系，创作了精美而复杂的插图。她的客户包括英联邦教育信托基金、国际特赦组织、美国运通、英国石油公司、Michael O'Mara Books、Buster Books、Lantana Publishing、Tate Publishing 和企鹅兰登书屋。精心制作的插图经过长时间的缓慢塑造，突出了好奇心的永恒本质，以及数周、数月、数年和数十年来在我们心中燃烧的无数问题。这样的插图还突出了好奇心，它引导我们建立专业知识并磨练技艺。

The book’s words are complemented by two types of visual media, each chosen to highlight distinct facets of curiosity’s mode of being. First, we precede each chapter with a frontispiece created by artist and illustrator Poonam Mistry, emphasizing key concepts in masterfully crafted visual form. Poonam’s style incorporates her love of nature, and explores the relationships between patterns, shapes, and colors, creating beautifully intricate illustrations. Her clients include the Commonwealth Education Trust, Amnesty International, American Express, BP Oil, Michael O’Mara Books, Buster Books, Lantana Publishing, Tate Publishing, and Penguin Random House. Well-crafted illustrations that are shaped slowly over long periods serve to foreground the timeless nature of curiosity, and the expanse of questions that burn within us for weeks, months, years, and decades. Such illustrations also foreground the curiosity that leads us to build expertise and to hone a craft.

其次，我们在几章科学性较强的章节中加入了作者手绘的草图，描绘了我们坐在酒吧里，在餐巾纸上随意涂鸦的概念。对于科学家来说，草图是我们思考、提问和向他人传达疑问的关键部分。我们尽量不带笔或铅笔出门，你经常会发现我们在零碎的纸张或纸制品上涂鸦，包括餐巾纸、纸巾、收据、停车票和书页边距，以及黑板和白板上，或者用一根小棍子在沙子或泥土上涂鸦。人文主义者一本书、一个素描本或一块白板同样适合于素描和涂鸦。因此，从人类学角度来看，这种视觉媒体适合世界各地的学者和思想家，但它的作用不止于此。素描让我们对当下、对转瞬即逝的时间、对在我们迷失在黑暗的头脑中之前一闪而过的想法产生了好奇。素描也让我们对非常个人化的东西产生了好奇：我为你画画，你为我画画，这样我们就可以一起分享这个奇妙的空间。

Second, we pepper several of the more scientific chapters with sketches hand drawn by one of the authors and depicting the concepts as if we were sitting at the pub together, scribbling away on a paper napkin. For scientists, sketches are a crucial part of how we think, how we question, and how we communicate our questionings to others. We try not to leave the house without a pen or pencil, and you’ll frequently find us scribbling on stray bits of paper or paper products, including napkins, paper towels, receipts, parking tickets, and book margins as well as on blackboards and whiteboards, or in the sand or dirt with a bit of a stick. Humanists with a book, a sketchpad, or a whiteboard are similarly sketch- and scribble-happy. This type of visual media is therefore anthropologically appropriate to scholars and thinkers everywhere, but it is more than that. Sketches bring curiosity to the here and now, to the fleeting moment of time, to the dashing off ideas before we lose them in the dark recesses of our minds. Sketches also bring curiosity to the deeply personal: to me drawing for you, or you drawing for me, so that we may share in this curious space together.

简介：新的视角

Introduction: A New Vantage Point

虫子。有时候，有些东西就是会困扰你。1耳朵里有虫子。我们都有过这样的经历。你正在忙着过一天，突然有些事情让你开始疑惑。你仔细思考。你尝试着用这个或那个解释。然后你分心了，继续前进。或者你没有这样做，虫子会钻得更深。或者你这样做了，但那天晚上晚些时候虫子又开始蠕动。你无法摆脱它。也许你拿出手机或敲几个键——或者转向同事或 ping 朋友。天哪，现在你真的想知道了！也许你遇到了一些障碍——付费墙或偏见、意见分歧或科学的局限性，甚至对你最喜欢的项目的嘲弄。根据你是谁，你还可能遇到彻头彻尾的性别歧视或种族歧视、阶级歧视或残疾歧视——所有这些都告诉你你的虫子是失败的。忘掉这种转瞬即逝的兴趣，专注于重要的事情。不管怎样，假设你继续。也许孩子们在尖叫，或者你正在开会，或者你开车去商店买牛奶。尽管从各个角落传来轰轰烈烈的叫喊声，你还是紧紧抓住那些让你烦恼的事情，拒绝让它消失。然后事情发生了……你的大脑开始跳舞和编织。收集可能相关的点点滴滴，并将它们缝合在一起。这样就构建了最简短的网。也许它毕竟是一只蚕！这就是你好奇的大脑。

Bugs. Sometimes, something just bugs you.1 A worm in your ear. We have all had the experience. You are going about your day, and something prompts you to wonder. You mull it over. You try on this explanation or that one. And then you get distracted and you move on. Or maybe you don’t, and the worm digs in deeper. Or maybe you do, but the worm returns to its wriggling later that night. You can’t shake it off. Maybe you pull out your phone or strike a few keys—or turn to a colleague or ping a friend. Gosh, now you really want to know! Perhaps you hit a few walls—paywalls or prejudices, differences of opinion or the limits of science, or even congenial scoffing at your pet project. Depending on who you are, you might also encounter outright sexism or racism, classism or ableism—all ways of telling you that your bug is a bust. Forget this fleeting interest and focus on something that matters. Regardless, let’s say, you carry on. Maybe the kids are screaming, or you are in a meeting, or you drive to the store for milk. Despite bombastic blasts from every corner, you hold onto what’s bugging you, refusing to let it bugger off. And then it happens . . . your mind begins to dance and to weave. Collecting the bits of things that might be relevant and stitching them together. So builds the briefest of webs. Perhaps it was a silkworm after all! This is your brain on curiosity.

而你也有好伙伴。如果你愿意的话，请回溯到 1928 年。作家弗吉尼亚·伍尔夫坐在一条河岸边（也许是泰晤士河，或者卡姆河，或者伊西斯河），她脑子里想着一个问题：女人和小说。她想知道，它们到底是什么。她称之为“问题”，“未解决的问题”。她发现自己一边走一边思考，起初很平静，后来变得狂热起来。她读了勃朗特姐妹、乔治·艾略特、查尔斯·兰姆和威廉·萨克雷的作品，她不仅对女性和小说感到好奇，还对它们之间的关系以及可以描述它的几种方式感到好奇。她大步走过附近的大学，用她的话说，那里充满了过时的思想，没有身体，没有事实，摆脱了她目前正在进行的对真理的粗暴漫无目的的探索。2然后它就在那里！

And you are in good company. Rewind back to 1928, if you will. Author Virginia Woolf is sitting on the banks of a river (the Thames, perhaps, or the Cam, or the Isis) and she has a worm in her ear: women and fiction. What even are they? she wonders. “Questions,” she calls them, “unsolved problems.” She finds herself walking and thinking, calmly at first and then feverishly. Crisscrossing the Brontë sisters and George Eliot, Charles Lamb and William Thackeray, she wonders not only about women and about fiction but also about their relation and the several ways in which it can be characterized. She strides past the nearby university, a place filled—as she puts it—with obsolete old minds, bereft of body and free of fact, loosed from the roughshod rambling toward truth that she is currently undertaking.2 And then there it is!

思想——用一个比它应得的更自豪的名字来称呼它——已经把线放进了溪流。一分钟又一分钟，它在倒影和杂草之间来回摇摆，任由水流将它托起又沉下，直到——你知道那小小的拉力——一个想法突然聚集在了线的末端。3

Thought—to call it by a prouder name than it deserved—had let its line down into the stream. It swayed, minute after minute, hither and thither, among the reflections and the weeds, letting the water lift it and sink it, until—you know the little tug—the sudden conglomeration of an idea at the end of one’s line.3

这是个奇妙的想法。伸出一根线。抛出并重新抛出。耐心等待，看着河流、波浪、光线沉入生命的循环。直到你突然感觉到它：一连串的咬合，然后是拉扯，然后慢慢地，线的末端有什么东西凝聚在一起。思路凝聚在一起。它们交织在一起并成形，获得了感觉，甚至力量。啊哈！

This is curious thought. Holding out a line. Casting and recasting it. Waiting patiently, watching the river, the waves, the light, sinking into the circle of life. Until suddenly you feel it: a series of nibbles, then tugs, and then slowly something coalesces there on the end of your line. Lines of thought agglutinate. They weave themselves together and take shape, gaining felt sense and even power. Aha!

但这一切的挑战不仅仅是耐心。它还包含着难题和限制。她发现了什么鱼？是尚未发现和命名的标本吗？还是该地区常见的物种，比如鲤鱼或鲈鱼？是从一开始就很奇怪的变异鱼？还是鱼的嵌合体，某种只有中世纪学者才能完全欣赏的长鳍水生生物？分类学是否需要为此而改变或打破？还是它们会轻易被它忽略？她究竟发现了什么？她一瞬间产生了什么样的想法？我们永远不会知道，因为她很快就被一个老式的校园警察拦住了。她漫步到大学绿地上，那里禁止女性进入。“他是教务长，我是女人。这是草坪，那是小路。”她立即​​站直身子，朝图书馆走去，结果却在门口被告知需要一名男子护送她进去。唉！她一个人出去散步。在这两种情况下，她都哀叹道：“他们把我的小鱼儿躲起来了。”她下定决心，一次又一次地抛出鱼线，直到她的疑问编织出一幅挂毯：一间自己的房间。在这篇杰作中，她把两个东西拼凑在一起：思考需要钓鱼的自由，或者“如果女人要写小说，她必须有钱和一间自己的房间。” 4

But the challenge of it all is not simply patience. It is also the conundrums and the curtailments. What sort of fish did she find? Was it an as yet undiscovered and unnamed specimen? Or was it a species common to the area, such as a carp perhaps or a perch? Was it a mutant fish, strange from the start? Or was it a chimera of a fish, some fin-bearing aquatic creature that only medievalists can fully appreciate? Would taxonomies need to bend for it or break? Or would they simply breeze by it? What in fact was it she discovered? What inkling took shape for her in an instant? We will never know, for she was quickly accosted by an old-fashioned version of the campus police. She had wandered onto the college green, where women were forbidden. “He was a Beadle; I was a woman. This was the turf; there was the path.” She rights herself forthwith and heads for the library, only to be informed at the door that she needs a man to escort her in. Alas! She is out walking alone. In both cases, she laments, “They had sent my little fish into hiding.” Determined, she returns to casting her line, over and over again, until the arc of her queries weaves a tapestry: A Room of One’s Own. In this masterful piece, she puts two and two together: thinking requires the freedom to fish, or “a woman must have money and a room of her own if she is to write fiction.”4

在《好奇的心灵》中，我们从好奇思维本身的架构开始。好奇心如何运动，如何构建？这种构建的神经、认识论和社会基础是什么？你的大脑如何连接不同的想法并将概念串在一起？它如何重新配置​​旧观念并编织新观念？不同的人是否以不同的方式实践好奇心，构建不同形状和风格的知识配置？我们究竟如何一起实践好奇心？追踪共同的猜测意味着什么？或者在不同文化之间传播好奇心意味着什么？是否有可能描述好奇心在这些多个寄存器中的感受和功能？当好奇心减弱时会发生什么？好奇心被什么样的神经基础、社会结构或文化限制所削弱？就此而言，公平地促进好奇心的动态力量，培养更大的探究自由和抵消长期存在的认识论等级模式，这意味着什么？这些以及许多其他问题推动了本书的发展。

In Curious Minds, we start right there, with the architectures of (and for) curious thought itself. How does curiosity move, and how does it build? What are the neural, epistemic, and social bases of that building? How does your brain connect disparate ideas and string together concepts? How does it reconfigure old notions and weave together new ones? Do different people practice curiosity in different ways, building knowledge configurations of different shapes and styles? And how exactly do we practice curiosity together? What does it mean to track down shared hunches? Or to cross-pollinate curiosities across cultures? Is it even possible to characterize how curiosity feels and functions on these multiple registers? And what happens when curiosity falters? By what neural substrates, social structures, or cultural strictures does curiosity get curtailed? For that matter, what would it mean to facilitate the dynamic force of curiosity equitably, cultivating greater freedom of inquiry and counteracting long-standing patterns of epistemic hierarchy? These and so many other questions fuel the book in front of you.

长期以来，好奇心一直被过分简单化，现在依然如此。在日常用语中，好奇心常常被简化为举手或提问的简单动作，尤其是在办公桌或讲台后面。或者把物体转过来又转过来，或者可能只是简单地“谷歌”一下。学者们通常将好奇心归结为“寻求信息”的行为或“求知欲”。但好奇心不仅仅是一种感觉，当然也不仅仅是一种行为。好奇心也绝非单一的动作或问题。从蹒跚学步的幼儿到训练有素的学者，好奇心很少甚至从来不是直线性的。好奇心如波浪般涌来——变异、聚集、冲上岸，然后再次被冲走。每一波浪潮都会通过溢出、猛烈、汹涌或崩塌而破碎。好奇心既是寻找新视角的轻快步伐，也是在河边默默做白日梦。最日常的——甚至是学术——它的特征是使好奇心成为好奇心的线条。流浪的轨迹、编织的概念、思想的编织和知识系统的建立。总之，好奇心在概念和物理空间中的运动的本质。丢失的是思想之间和人与人之间的网络和关系。

For too long—and still too often—curiosity has been oversimplified. In everyday parlance, it is frequently reduced to the simple act of raising a hand or voicing a question, especially from behind a desk or a podium. Or to turning an object this way, then that, or perhaps simply “googling” something. Scholars generally boil it down to “information-seeking” behavior or a “desire to know.” But curiosity is more than a feeling and certainly more than an act. And curiosity is always more than a single move or a single question. From the toddler to the most well-trained scholars, it is rarely if ever a straight shot. Curiosity comes in waves—mutating, agglomerating, washing ashore, and washing back out again. Each wave breaks by spilling, plunging, surging, or collapsing. Curiosity is as much the brisk steps in search of a new vantage point as it is the silent daydreaming by a river’s edge. What falls out of most quotidian—and even scholarly—characterizations of it are the lines that make curiosity what it is. The wandering tracks, the weaving concepts, the knitting of ideas, and the thatching of knowledge systems. In a word, the very essence of curious movement in conceptual and physical space. What gets lost are the networks, the relations, between ideas and between people.

在本书中，我们提出了一种关于好奇心的新理论。我们借鉴自己在复杂系统和神经科学、文学和哲学等领域的研究，提出了一种关于好奇心的网络理论。5对我们来说，好奇心是一种网络实践，一种关系实践。它通过将想法、事实、看法、感觉和数据点联系在一起而发挥作用。然而，它也适用于人类的友谊、社会和文化网络。我们漫步于广阔的跨学科领域——正如我们习惯做的那样——我们开发了一种与人文科学和日常生活同样相关的理论。当你查询时，你就建立了联系。你不仅将一个部分和另一个部分串联在一起，而且还将其融入不断变化的个人和集体知识网络中。重要的是，这种好奇的联系绝不仅仅是自由发挥。正如伍尔夫如此巧妙地戏剧化地描述的那样，我们在充满约束的现有环境中编织我们的知识网络——这些约束不仅存在于知识的认知架构中，也存在于认知者的社会架构中。在这些页面中，我们解决了这种复杂性。好奇心将……联系起来。而且它在大脑和身体、系统和社会的结缔组织中发挥着作用。

In this book, we offer a new theory of curiosity. Drawing on our own fields of complex systems and neuroscience, literature and philosophy, we propose a network account of curiosity.5 For us, curiosity is a network practice, a relational practice. It works by linking ideas, facts, perceptions, sensations, and data points together. Yet it also works within human grids of friendship, society, and culture. Rambling over vast interdisciplinary terrain—as we are wont to do—we develop an account that is as relevant to the humanities and the sciences as it is to everyday life. When you query, you connect. And you thread not simply one piece and another together but also within a constantly changing web of individual and collective knowledge. Importantly, that curious connection is never just free play. As Woolf so deftly dramatizes, we weave our knowledge webs within existing contexts rife with constraints—constraints not only in the epistemic architectures of knowledge but in the social architectures of knowers too. Here in these pages, we tackle that complexity. Curiosity connects. And it does so within the connective tissues of brain and body, system and society.

这很重要。

And that matters.

跨越时代的好奇心

Curiosity across the Ages

好奇心的历史悠久，对好奇心的研究也有着悠久的历史。由于好奇心被认为与所有智力事物都有密切关系，因此人们通常将好奇心与身体和社会分开，并将其定位在个体的思维器官中。但当然，这种器官非常难以捉摸，因为随着时间的推移，人们对它的理解也有所不同。几千年前，人们认为好奇心存在于灵魂之中。在中世纪和文艺复兴之后，好奇心逐渐在头脑中扎根。然后，随着早期心理学和神经科学的发展，好奇心在人类大脑中占据了主导地位。好奇心最近被定位在大脑的某个地方——它的具体坐标仍有待商榷。无论好奇心位于何处，它对精神装置的持续限制都伴随着与物质身体和社会关系的稳步分离。好奇心一直被孤立。但潮流正在转变。我们越深入大脑，这种孤立就越不可能维持。人类的质量施加着一种不容置疑的引力将我们向外拉。对大脑网络基底的考虑让我们不得不重新考虑好奇心在其中发挥作用的许多其他网络。随着潮水转向，我们的探究浪潮将沙子和海藻从岸边卷走。欣赏使思考成为可能的多种架构——无论是神经网络、知识网络还是社交网络——事实上不仅对解释好奇心至关重要，而且对有意实践好奇心也至关重要。

Curiosity is as old as the hills, and the study of curiosity itself has a long and storied history. Given its presumed affinity for all things intellect, curiosity has typically been divorced from the body—and from society for that matter—and located instead in the individual organ of thought. But of course that organ is quite slippery, having been understood differently across the vagaries of time. Thousands of years ago, it was believed that curiosity lived in the seat of the soul. Following the medieval period and the Renaissance, curiosity slowly took up residence in the mind. Then with the development of early psychology and neuroscience, curiosity has most recently been located somewhere in the brain—with its precise coordinates still up for debate. Regardless of where curiosity is situated, its consistent restriction to the mental apparatus has been accompanied by a steady divorce from material bodies and community relations. Curiosity has been isolated. But the tide is turning. The deeper we head into the brain, the more impossible that isolation is to sustain. The mass of humanity exerts an unquestionable gravitational force pulling us outward. Reckoning with the network substrate of the brain sends us scrambling back out to account for the many other networks within which curiosity works. As the tides turn, our waves of inquiry pull sand and seaweed away from shore. Appreciating the multiple architectures that make thought possible—whether neural, knowledge, or social networks—is in fact crucial not only to account for curiosity but also to practice it intentionally.

圣奥古斯丁被认为是西方经典中最早、最权威的好奇心记述者。奥古斯丁是努米底亚一位受过良好教育的北非修辞学家，31 岁时皈依基督教，后来成为教会的主教，撰写了权威的信仰论文。对奥古斯丁来说，好奇心存在于灵魂中。6有时，他将好奇心描述为“眼睛的欲望”，或一种贪婪的兴趣，想要看到和了解世俗的、非永恒的事物。有时，他将其描述为一种“低级理性”，它使灵魂的光芒因肉欲和对世俗学习的喜爱而黯淡。无论具体表述如何，奥古斯丁都将好奇心理解为一种强大的力量，它使灵魂远离上帝和基督徒团契，将其越来越深地拖入易变、易腐烂的世界的认知阴谋中。因此，他说，好奇心是一种“疾病”，它扰乱了创造的秩序，将个人从其应有的位置上拉了出来。现在，虽然我们早已放弃了好奇心是一种罪恶的信念，但我们仍然坚持这样一种观点：好奇心存在于灵魂中，或者至少存在于我们思考、学习、怀疑和记忆的那部分。奥古斯丁的论述是当今心理学和神经科学对好奇心论述的直接前身。

Saint Augustine is credited with perhaps the earliest and most definitive account of curiosity in the Western canon. A well-educated North African rhetorician in Numidia, Augustine converted to Christianity at the age of thirty-one and went on to become a church bishop, writing definitive treatises in the faith. For Augustine, curiosity resides in the soul.6 Sometimes he characterizes it as a “lust of the eyes,” or a cupidinous interest to see and to know things of earthly but not eternal import. At other times he depicts it as a form of “lower reason,” which turns the light of the soul dim with fleshly desire and delight in secular learning. Whatever the specific formulation, Augustine understands curiosity as a formidable force that moves the soul away from God and Christian fellowship, drawing it ever deeper into the epistemic intrigues of a mutable, corruptible world. As such, it is a “disease,” he says, that disrupts the order of creation and wrenches an individual human from their proper place in it. Now, while we have long relinquished the conviction that curiosity is a sin, we have held onto a sense that curiosity lives in the soul, or at least in that part of us where we wonder, learn, doubt, and remember. Augustine’s account is, then, a direct predecessor of psychological and neuroscientific accounts of curiosity today.

但中间还有一步。随着罗马天主教帝国的衰落，早期现代科学兴起，随之而来的是毫无掩饰的庆祝科学探究的所有要素：观察和假设，当然还有好奇心。尽管好奇心承受着宗教上的种种恶毒攻击，前英国大法官、经验主义的坚定支持者弗朗西斯·培根却为好奇心辩护，认为好奇心在为人类服务的知识构建方面绝对“自然”，而且事实上“有用”。7同样，法国数学家、现代哲学基石勒内·笛卡尔也将探究和探索的智力动力自然化。他说，好奇心和惊奇都位于思维中，其中“动物精神”（血液中携带的力量）在心灵之眼面前呈现不同的感知印象。在惊奇的情况下，精神是稳重而平静的；在好奇的情况下，精神有点紧张和敏捷。通过慷慨的兄弟姐妹情感（或者用笛卡尔的话来说，是“激情”），好奇心和惊奇可以激发有机体获取有益于整个社会的知识。8将好奇心从灵魂提升到思想，早期现代时期将其直接与生物学根植的内眼联系起来。从那里开始，大脑也紧随其后。

But there is an intermediary step. As the Roman Catholic empire waned, early modern science arose and, with it, the unabashed celebration of all the elements of scientific inquiry: observation and hypotheses, yes, but also curiosity. Against all the religious vitriol curiosity had sustained, Francis Bacon, onetime lord chancellor of England and staunch proponent of empiricism, defends it, characterizing it as absolutely “natural” and in fact “useful” when tasked with building knowledge in the service of humankind.7 Similarly, René Descartes, French mathematician and cornerstone of modern philosophy, naturalizes the intellectual impetus to inquire and to explore. Curiosity and wonder, he says, are both located in the mind, where “animal spirits” (forces carried in the blood) hold up different perceptual impressions before the mind’s eye. In the case of wonder, the spirits are staid and calm; in the case of curiosity, they are a bit jittery and quick. Through the sibling emotion (or as Descartes has it, the “passion”) of generosity, curiosity and wonder can fuel the organism’s acquisition of knowledge beneficial to society as a whole.8 Lifting curiosity from the soul and to the mind, then, the early modern period directly links it to the biologically rooted inner eye. From there, the brain is not far behind.

在当代心理学和神经科学中，好奇心位于大脑中，并且根据研究的不同，位于大脑的特定部位。这种定位很有道理，因为这些领域目前将好奇心理解为一种信息搜索行为，其目的是填补信息空白。那么好奇心自然会位于信息处理中心：大脑。9但好奇心位于大脑的哪个位置呢？心理学家 Daniel Berlyne 将好奇心定位于网状唤醒系统和大脑皮层中“神经组合”的相互作用中。10在神经科学家 Jacqueline Gottlieb、数据科学家 Min Jeong Kang 和心理学家 Celeste Kidd 等人的后续研究中，好奇心根据研究对象的不同而在灰质轨道上迁移。当好奇心与探索相关时，它出现在额极皮层、顶叶内沟或后扣带皮层；当好奇心与新奇相关时，它出现在腹侧纹状体；尾状核和额下回负责处理琐事；海马体、多巴胺能区域和伏隔核负责处理学习和记忆；额顶叶系统负责处理注意力和决策。11虽然神经系统遍布全身，并受环境和社会因素的调节，但当今的科学正确地坚持认为大脑及其对好奇心的贡献具有重要的独特性。

In contemporary psychology and neuroscience, curiosity is located in the brain and, depending on the study, in specific parts of the brain. This localization makes good sense given that these fields currently understand curiosity to be an information-seeking behavior that is driven to fill information gaps. Curiosity would then naturally be located in the information processing center: the brain.9 But where in the brain? Psychologist Daniel Berlyne locates curiosity in the interplay between the reticular arousal system and “neural assemblies” in the cerebral cortex.10 In the subsequent work of neuroscientist Jacqueline Gottlieb, data scientist Min Jeong Kang, and psychologist Celeste Kidd, among others, curiosity has migrated across gray matter tracks depending upon the object of study. When curiosity is associated with exploration, it appears in the frontopolar cortex, intraparietal sulcus, or posterior cingulate cortex; with novelty, it appears in the ventral striatum; with trivia, in the caudate nucleus and inferior frontal gyrus; with learning and memory, in the hippocampus, dopaminergic regions, and nucleus accumbens; or with attention and decision-making, in the frontoparietal system.11 And while the nervous system extends throughout the body, and is tuned by environmental and social factors, today’s science rightly insists that the brain—and its contribution to curiosity—is importantly unique.

然而，你按压得越深，你就必须向后旋转得越远。在那里，在一层又一层的胶状组织中，有大量的细胞核、轴突和突触，在纷乱的神经活动网络中来回传送电信号。这些神经元远非混乱，它们是成群工作的，是的，但也跨群工作。这些集群会摆动甚至跳舞。此外，它们这样做的方式部分取决于遗传和表观遗传基质、环境影响（现在和过去）和社会互动。如果曾经有过复杂的系统，那它就是一个复杂的系统。一场名副其实的交响乐。值得称赞的是，网络科学——以 20 世纪 60 年代和 70 年代的社会学、艺术理论和哲学为基础——再次邀请我们关注大脑中的这些网络，也关注这个复杂神经系统在其中发挥作用的知识网络和社会网络。这一领域要求我们不仅要欣赏思维器官的网络结构，还要欣赏思想本身以及当今和过去的思想家。在这本书中，我们响应了这一号召。

The deeper into the brain you press, however, the farther back out you have to pivot. There, in fold after fold of gelatinous tissue, are masses of cell nuclei, axons, and synapses, shuttling electrical signals this way and that in a riotous web of neural activity. Far from chaotic, those neurons work in clusters, yes, but also across clusters. And these clusters swing and even dance. They do so, moreover, in ways partially determined by genetic and epigenetic substrates, environmental influences (both present and past), and social interactions. This is a complex system if there ever was one. A veritable symphony. To its credit, network science—building on sociology, art theory, and philosophy from the 1960s and 1970s—provides a renewed invitation to attend to these networks in the brain, but also to the knowledge networks and social networks within which that complex neural system functions. The field summons us to appreciate the network architectures not only of the thinking organ but also of thought itself as well as thinkers of today and yesteryear. In this book, we heed that call.

并且来得正是时候。在从灵魂到心灵再到大脑的史诗般的征程中，我们一路上与某些事物失去了联系。我们失去了网络的踪迹。我们基本上忘记了好奇心如何建立或破坏社区，无论是与其他人还是与超人类的现实。我们基本上忘记了询问好奇心与情绪、创伤和其他情感身体现象的关系。我们几乎没有想过好奇心还寄宿在身体的哪个部位。而且，我们基本上没有探索好奇心与身体运动（或整个运动知觉）的关系。此外，我们如此真诚地相信好奇心对社会成就至关重要，以至于我们很少花费精力去培养它与社会慷慨的协调。我们几乎没有停下来问一问好奇心与文化、社会价值观甚至政治之间究竟有哪些联系被激活（或处于潜伏状态）。12

And none too soon. In the epic march from soul to mind to brain, we have lost touch with some things along the way. We have lost track of the networks. We have largely forgotten to wonder how curiosity builds or breaks community, whether with other humans or with a more-than-human reality. We have largely forgotten to ask about curiosity’s relationship to emotions, to trauma, and to other affective bodily phenomena. We have hardly wondered where else in the body curiosity is lodged. And we have left largely unexplored curiosity’s relationship to bodily movement—or kinesthetics—as a whole. We believe so heartily that curiosity is crucial to societal achievement, moreover, that we have spent little energy in cultivating its attunement with societal generosity. And we have barely paused to ask just what links are activated (or lie dormant) between curiosity and culture, social values, and even politics.12

还有太多东西需要研究！将好奇心作为连接因素来突出，使我们能够重新关注大脑作为一个复杂的系统。它促使我们思考其他复杂系统（如语言或音乐等其他学科——这些学科可能有助于探究好奇心。它还将我们的注意力集中在使大脑首先发挥作用的认知和社会系统上。它促使我们探究学习器官本身，同时探究学习内容的结构以及学习者在此过程中的安排。毕竟，要真正理解好奇心，不仅要考虑学习什么和如何学习，还要考虑与谁一起学习和在哪里学习。因此，我们提出的网络账户将带来更丰富的分析回路，为我们打开一个全新的世界。

There is so much left to investigate! Foregrounding curiosity as connectional allows us to turn renewed attention to the brain as a complex system. It prompts us to ask what insights other complex systems—such as language or music—might provide in the project of probing the curious mind. It also attunes our attentions to the epistemic and social systems that enable the brain to function in the first place. It prompts us to ask about the organ of learning itself, and simultaneously about the architecture of what is learned and the arrangement of learners in the process. To really understand curiosity, after all, it matters not simply with what and how one learns but with whom and where as well. As such, the network account we propose invites ever-richer circuits of analysis, opening up a whole new world behind and ahead of us.

人行道和飞行路线

Footpaths and Flight Ways

在《好奇心》中，我们通过这个问题的网络追踪一条路径。我们绝不会想象这是唯一的或最直接的路径。如果是这样，我们会感到失望。相反，我们希望这条路径有自己的生命力。有时我们紧跟已知的事物，有时我们伸出手去触摸尚不了解的事物。我们尝试立足，重新规划飞行路线。我们轮流从人文学科的深度和科学的高度获取坐标。在这样做的过程中，我们惊叹并愉快地探索网络方法为好奇心研究开辟的广阔前景。

In Curious Minds, we trace a path through this network of questions. In no way do we imagine that this is the only, or indeed the most direct, course. We would be disappointed if it were. Rather, we hope the path takes on a life of its own. Sometimes we hue closely to what we know and at other times we stretch out to touch what we do not yet know. We try our footing, we reroute our flight. We take our coordinates from the depth of the humanities and the height of the sciences by turns. In so doing, we marvel at and blithely explore the vast landscape that a network approach opens up for the study of curiosity.

在第 1 章“好奇心的科学”中，我们首先指出了好奇心对于科学精神和实践的核心地位。没有好奇心就没有科学。然后我们转向当代的好奇心科学，重点关注心理学和神经科学的最新贡献。心理学研究利用定量和定性测量来了解好奇心的功能，而神经科学研究则利用脑成像技术（例如功能性磁共振成像 [fMRI]）来识别好奇心的神经基础。无论使用哪种方法，每个领域都在阐明信息搜索的行为和神经成分方面取得了巨大进步。然而，这项工作仍然存在一个重要的限制。它主要基于信息差距理论，根据该理论，好奇心是填补知识差距的内在动机。在信息搜索框架内，好奇心仍然是习得性的，是一种获取和积累信息的行为。但这并不是好奇心的唯一功能。

In chapter 1, “The Science of Curiosity,” we begin by noting the centrality of curiosity to the very spirit and practice of science. There is no science without curiosity. We then turn to the contemporary science of curiosity, focusing on the recent contributions of psychology and neuroscience. Studies in psychology utilize quantitative and qualitative measurements to understand the function of curiosity, while studies in neuroscience make use of brain-imaging techniques (e.g., functional magnetic resonance imaging [fMRI]) to identify the neural substrates of curiosity. Whatever the methods, each field has made immense strides in illuminating the behavioral and neural components of information seeking. There remains, however, an important limitation to this work. It functions largely on the information gap theory, according to which curiosity is an intrinsic motivation to fill a knowledge gap. Within an information-seeking framework, curiosity remains acquisitional, a project of acquiring—and amassing—information. But this is not curiosity’s only function.

在第 2 章“好奇心作为边缘工作”中，我们确定了好奇心获取模型的根源，即心理学和神经科学的长期前身：哲学。传统上，哲学将好奇心描述为了解某事的渴望或胃口。然而，受网络理论的启发，我们从好奇心作为节点获取的范式转向好奇心作为边缘工作。我们提出了一个新的框架，将好奇心理解为一种联系的实践，一种在知识者、知识和已知事物的系统之间建立关系的方式。为了开发这个框架，我们重新审视哲学史，挖掘好奇心的不同谱系——强调的不是信息单元，而是关系。我们在西方和土著血统中都发现了将好奇心概念化为连接器而不是征服者的先例。最后，我们反思了这种观点为当今心理学和神经科学带来的极具前景的研究方向。

In chapter 2, “Curiosity as Edgework,” we identify the roots of the acquisitional model of curiosity in the longtime predecessor of psychology and neuroscience: philosophy. Traditionally, philosophy characterizes curiosity as the desire or the appetite to know something. Inspired by network theory, however, we pivot from the paradigm of curiosity as nodal acquisition to curiosity as edgework. We propose a new framework that understands curiosity as a practice of connection, a way of building relations between and among systems of knowers, knowledges, and things known. To develop this framework, we revisit the history of philosophy and excavate a different genealogy for curiosity—one that emphasizes not informational units but relations instead. We find precedent in both Western and Indigenous lineages for this conceptualization of curiosity as a connector rather than conquistador. Finally, we reflect on the immensely promising lines of study that this view poses for psychology and neuroscience today.

在第 3 章“网络范式”中，我们通过网络科学本身的术语和方法资源，发展了好奇心作为边缘工作的理论。具体来说，我们建议将好奇心定义为知识网络构建的实践。利用网络科学、神经科学、心理学和语言学的概念和工具，我们假设知识是一个网络，并且它实际上可以用数学表示。此外，如果知识是一个网络，而好奇心是该网络的增长原则，那么从理论上讲，使用网络科学工具可以定量地描述和数学建模这种增长。也就是说，我们可能能够绘制出想法如何慢慢积累成个人和集体知识的架构。我们在此提出的建议将我们对好奇心的许多直觉形式化为关系，并通过这种形式化为构建可测试假设的基础，以供未来的实证工作使用。

In chapter 3, “The Network Paradigm,” we develop the theory of curiosity as edgework through the terminology and methodological resources of network science proper. Specifically, we suggest defining curiosity as a practice of knowledge network building. Drawing on concepts and tools from network science, neuroscience, psychology, and linguistics, we posit that knowledge is a network and that it can in fact be mathematically represented as such. Moreover, if knowledge is a network, and curiosity is the growth principle of that network, then it is theoretically possible to quantitatively characterize and mathematically model that growth using tools from network science. That is, we may be able to graph how ideas slowly accrete into architectures of individual and collective knowledge. Our proposal here formalizes many of the intuitions we have about curiosity as relational, and by that formalization it provides the foundations from which to construct testable hypotheses for future empirical work.

在第 4 章“好奇心有风格”中，我们提出了一系列合乎逻辑的问题。如果好奇心是一种网络构建活动，那么是否存在不同的架构和风格？安东尼·高迪和弗兰克·劳埃德·赖特、碧昂丝和妮娜·西蒙妮？这些差异会因神经特质、个性、社会文化价值观等因素而变化吗？简而言之，我们的答案是“是”。回到西方思想史的核心，超越其边缘，我们发现了三种相对一致的好奇心风格：好管闲事者、猎人和舞者。在他们好奇的轨迹中，好管闲事者收集信息碎片，猎人专注于某一特定兴趣，舞者则发挥想象力进行创造性飞跃。每一种都有独特的动觉特征，分别创建松散的知识网络、紧密的网络和环状网络。此外，在观念和社会领域，每种风格都有独特的功能，通过知识网格规划出不同的路线，并在社交网络中开辟路径。

In chapter 4, “Curiosity’s Got Style,” we ask the next logical series of questions. If curiosity is a network building activity, are there different architectures and styles? The equivalent of an Antoni Gaudí and a Frank Lloyd Wright, a Beyoncé and a Nina Simone? And might these differences vary with neural idiosyncrasies, personalities, sociocultural values, and more? In short, we answer “yes.” Diving back into the heart of Western intellectual history, and out past its edges, we identify three styles of curiosity that are relatively consistent across time: the busybody, the hunter, and the dancer. In their curious trajectories, the busybody collects informational tidbits, while the hunter barrels down on one particular interest, and the dancer takes creative leaps of imagination. Each has a distinct kinesthetic signature, creating loose knowledge networks, tight networks, and loopy ones, respectively. In ideational and social spheres, moreover, each style has a unique function, mapping out different routes through knowledge grids and cutting paths across social networks.

在第 5 章“知识网络”中，我们问道，但这些路径在实证研究中可追溯吗？构建风格在实验室环境中可观察到吗？确实可以。我们报告了对维基百科用户知识网络构建的研究，参与者从爱管闲事的人（浏览松散连接的维基百科页面）到猎人（浏览紧密连接的页面）。然而，这只是未来工作的开始。如果人们的知识网络构建风格不同，这些差异将如何影响教育或其他学习环境和活动？我们知道，人类大脑比随机或无序的网络更能学习集群或模块化网络。这些集群是否会以不同的方式聚集到不同的认知者身上？在通过书籍、讲座和课程计划线性传授信息的学习环境中，如何实现聚类风格？最终，我们要问，如何在课堂内外最好地促进学习者兴趣和能力的广泛多样性？

In chapter 5, “Webs of Knowledge,” we ask, But are these paths traceable in empirical research? Are styles of building observable in laboratory settings? They are indeed. We report on our study of knowledge network building among users of Wikipedia, where participants spanned from busybodies (who surfed among loosely connected Wikipedia pages) to hunters (who surfed among closely connected pages). Yet this is only the beginning of future work. If people have different styles of knowledge network building, how might those differences affect education or other learning environments and activities? We know that human brains learn clustered or modular networks better than random or disordered ones. Might those clusters be clustered in different ways for different knowers? And how would styles of clustering even be achieved in a learning environment where information is taught linearly through books, lectures, and lesson plans? Ultimately we ask, How might the vast variety of learners’ interests and capacities be best facilitated in and beyond the classroom?

在第六章“好奇心散步”中，我们暂停一下。在网络科学中，人们穿越网络的路径被称为“散步”，网络上的不同散步遵循不同的约束。同样，人们穿越知识网络的路径也可以是特定约束内的散步。散步是一种思考方式——一种协商或产生知识的方式——这一观点在人文主义传统中根深蒂固，其相反的观点也是如此：思考是一种行走方式。我们在这里研究四种行走方式，它们本身涉及特定形式的好奇思维：哲学行走、精神行走、环境行走和政治行走。这些穿越物理空间的方式映射到穿越概念空间的方式。因此，我们提出，将哲学和好奇心网络科学结合在一起的一个关键方法正是将这些探究地理和笔法结合在一起思考。

In chapter 6, “Curiosity Takes a Walk,” we pause for a moment. In network science, the path by which one traverses a network is called a “walk,” and different walks on a network conform to different constraints. Likewise, the path by which one traverses a knowledge network can be a walk within specific constraints. The suggestion that walking is a way of thinking—a way of negotiating or generating knowledge—has long roots in the humanistic tradition, as does its converse suggestion: that thinking is a way of walking. Here we investigate four sorts of walks, which themselves involve specific forms of curious thought: the philosophical walk, the spiritual walk, the environmental walk, and the political walk. These ways of moving through physical space map onto ways of moving through conceptual space. We therefore propose that one critical way to cinch together a philosophy and network science of curiosity is precisely by thinking these geographies and graphologies of inquiry together.

在第 7 章“好奇心下的大脑”中，我们提供了关于好奇心网络神经科学的最系统和实验性的描述。正如我们所论证的，好奇心不仅仅是关于获取知识，还关于连接知识的边缘工作，因此我们不仅探索构成大脑的关系（和网络），还探索它们在大脑中编码的原理，以及它们是如何学习和记忆的。我们尽可能自由地从神经科学、诗歌、音乐甚至词典学中汲取灵感，研究好奇心在大脑中究竟发生了什么。大脑的结构与它产生和处理的知识的结构之间有什么对应关系？通过讨论大脑区域的功能及其相互关系，我们强调了它们之间必要的灵活性。然后，我们推测神经科学对知识网络构建的神经基础的研究的当前轨迹。

In chapter 7, “Your Brain on Curiosity,” we offer our most systematic and experimental account of the network neuroscience of curiosity. Because, as we argue, curiosity is not solely about the acquisition of a piece of knowledge but also about the edgework of connecting pieces of knowledge, we explore not only the relations (and networks) that make up the brain but also the principles by which they may be encoded in the brain, how they are learned and remembered. Drawing as freely from neuroscience as from poetry, music, and even lexicography, we investigate what actually happens in your brain on curiosity. What correspondences does and might the architecture of your brain have with the architectures of the knowledge it produces and processes? Canvasing the function of brain regions and their interrelations, we emphasize the necessary flexibility between them. We then speculate on the current trajectory of neuroscientific inquiry into the neural basis of knowledge network building.

在最后一章“重新构想教育”中，我们退后一步来审视全局。如果好奇心最好被理解为知识网络构建的实践，即连接和关联信息位和信息知晓者，那么教育应该是什么样的？我们如何以不同的方式、更有活力、更公平的方式重新构想学习？为了回答这个问题，我们建议重新关注所涉及的三个关键网络：神经网络、社交网络和知识网络。认识到每个网络子结构中都存在着巨大的多样性，我们勾勒出了一种更具包容性、动态性和跨学科性的教学方法。在这项调查中，我们深入研究了神经多样性作家东田直树、民权运动自由学校和杰出的跨学科学者列奥纳多达芬奇的案例研究。致力于减少社会不平等，放松突破学院所面临的传统学科界限，我们的目标是让每个人的好奇心自由地去追求看似无法比拟的想法和应用。

In our final chapter, “Reimagining Education,” we take a step back to appreciate the big picture. If curiosity is best understood as a practice of knowledge network building, of connecting and relating informational bits and informational knowers, what should education look like? How can we reimagine learning differently, more energetically, more equitably? To answer this question, we propose renewed attention to the three key networks involved: neural, social, and knowledge networks. Recognizing the immense diversity that exists within each of these network substructures, we sketch out the paths to a more inclusive, dynamic, and transdisciplinary pedagogy. In that inquiry, we dig deeply into the case studies of neurodiverse writer Naoki Higashida, the civil rights movement’s Freedom Schools, and interdisciplinary scholar par excellence Leonardo da Vinci. Committed to reducing the social inequalities and loosening the traditional disciplinary boundaries that subtend the academy, we aim to facilitate freedom for everyone’s curiosity to pursue seemingly incommensurable ideas and applications.

《好奇心》以我们对好奇心未来的思考作为结束。我们将反思锚定在跨学科和社会正义承诺上，分享我们在解放探究方面采取的下一步措施，以及我们旅程中的路标。当我们想象好奇心的活力和多样性将获得更大的自由时，我们不仅会想到尚未建立​​的网络，还会想到需要破解的网络，以便为新网络腾出空间。最后，我们反思了裂缝及其在为所有好奇心创造一个更公平的世界中所起的作用。

Curious Minds closes with our own ruminations on the future of curiosity. Anchoring our reflection in our interdisciplinary and social justice commitments, we share what we take to be the next steps in the emancipation of inquiry, the signposts on our journey. As we imagine greater freedom for the dynamism and diversity of curiosity, we think not only of the networks yet to be built but also of the networks that need to crack in order to make room for new building. We close, then, with a rumination on cracks and their role in crafting a more equitable world for all curious minds.

振荡

Oscillations

我们在此提供的说明，与许多将思想和领域交织在一起的想法一样，是在耐心、有时杂乱无章的创造力空间中发展起来的。它既蹒跚而行，又轻轻地跨越了时间——准确地说是五年。学术生活提供了各种各样的共同思考的机会，无论是演讲、写论文、做实验、参加 Zoom 电话会议，还是周末喝一杯纯艾雷岛苏格兰威士忌。在这个项目成形的过程中，我们交换了许多午夜短信和白天的欢愉。对我们来说，这一切都始于一场奇思妙想。如果我们一起创作一些学术作品会怎么样？我们各自的专业领域会在哪里相遇？我们的领域可以以何种方式相互影响？从哲学到神经科学，从文学到物理学，我们注意到，我们一起陶醉于古代和现代的思考方式。我们如何思考、为什么思考、思考什么、与谁一起思考、在哪里思考？我们基于什么来声明、感叹或质疑？作为人类，我们与内心和外部世界有着如此戏剧性的互动，就像柔软的毛茸茸的大黄蜂在绣线菊丛的微型花草甸上扭动、漫步和摇晃。完全着迷。完全沉迷其中。是什么魅力吸引我们，吸引我们，并让我们质疑？好奇心。好奇心是一种可以很好地穿越内心广阔空间的概念以及我们各个领域之间的联系。但是好奇心如何实现呢？我们开始侦查。作为学者，我们做什么？作为人类，我们热爱什么？这告诉我们关于好奇心、关于我们如何实践好奇心以及如何将其理论化？《好奇心》记录了我们的旅程。

The account we offer here, as with many ideas intertwining minds and fields, has been developed in the patient, sometimes haphazard space of creativity. It has both lurched and lightly danced across time—five years to be exact. The academic life provides all kinds of opportunities for thinking together, whether giving talks or lectures, writing essays, conducting experiments, jumping on Zoom calls, or catching a weekend Islay Scotch (neat). We swapped many a midnight text and daylight delight as this project took shape. For us, it all began with a flight of fancy. What if we were to produce a bit of scholarly work together? Where might our respective areas of expertise meet? In what ways could our fields inform one another? From philosophy to neuroscience, from literature to physics, we noticed that together we revel in ancient and modern ways of thinking about thinking. How, why, what, with whom, and where do we think? On what grounds do we declare, exclaim, or question? As humans, we engage so dramatically with our inner and outer worlds, like soft fuzzy bumblebees wriggling, rambling, and waggling on the miniature flower meadows of spirea bushes. Absolutely enthralled. Completely enmeshed. What is this enchantment that draws us out, draws us in, and calls us to question? Curiosity. Curiosity was the kind of concept that could travel well across the vast space within and between our fields. But curiosity how? We started to sleuth. What do we do as academics, what do we love as humans, and what does that tell us about curiosity, about how we practice it, but also about how we might theorize it? Curious Minds is the record of our journey.

那么，你们面前的正是集体努力的成果。如果没有我们共同思考，也就是说，没有我们的关系，这里提出的想法就不可能生根发芽或结出硕果。我们共同实践好奇心，将哲学和神经科学、文学和心理学、社会正义和网络科学联系起来，从而构建一个具有其独特知识网络架构的特定想法。话虽如此，就这项工作而言，我们承担着不同的作者责任。Dani 是第 1、3、5 和 7 章的主要作者，而 Perry 是第 2、4、6 和 8 章的主要作者。我们没有做任何事情来掩盖我们写作和思考风格的独特性。相反，我们邀请读者加入我们的旅程。这本书不是独白，而是对话。而且，它并不是最直截了当的书；它没有遵循精心设计的路径。相反，这是一项动态调查，一个生动的询问。我们把分散的碎片收集起来，钻进兔子洞，跨越广阔而整洁的空间，只为看看我们能落在哪里。我们这样做是有目的的。

What you have before you, then, is truly a collective effort. The ideas developed here could not have germinated or borne fruit without us thinking together—that is, without our relationship. We practiced curiosity collectively, connecting philosophy and neuroscience, literature and psychology, social justice and network science, so as to build a specific idea, with its very own idiosyncratic knowledge network architecture. That said, for the purposes of the work, we had distinct authorial responsibilities. Dani holds the primary authorship of chapters 1, 3, 5, and 7, while Perry holds the primary authorship of chapters 2, 4, 6, and 8. We have done nothing to mask the distinctiveness of our writing and thinking styles. Rather, we invite readers to come along on our journey. This book is not a monologue but rather a dialogue. And it is not, as such, the most straightforward of books; it does not follow well-trimmed paths. Instead, this is a dynamic investigation, a live-wire query. We gather disparate pieces together, dive down rabbit holes, and leap across vast swaths of cleanly curated space, just to see where we land. And we do that purposively.

但无论是在形式还是内容上，这场大漩涡都有着清晰的方法。当我们在各自的声音、领域和行走的节奏之间切换时，我们便会设计出一种在前进过程中不断扩展和收缩的探究。我们援引不同的经典，探索不同的边缘，并根据我们对特定领域的期望承担不同高度的学术风险。我们这样做是因为我们相信好奇心的承诺，也相信好奇心带来的乐趣。我们将物理学延伸到音乐和诗歌，同时将批判理论延伸到笔迹学和神经学。我们的合作在这里具有灵活性，就像是跳了一点摇摆舞。你会发现佩里在档案馆里漫步，看到丹妮站着不动，盯着实验室里的大脑图像。但你也会注意到佩里坐下来进行分类，看着丹妮跑去讲故事。然而，有什么比在学科和认知方式之间穿梭、在前进过程中打破边界和界限更好的方法来追随好奇心的召唤并追求意外发现呢？

But there is also a clear method to the maelstrom, in both form and content. As we toggle between our voices, our fields, and the cadence of our respective walks, we craft an inquiry that expands and contracts as it goes. We call up different canons, explore different peripheries, and take scholastic risks of different altitudes depending on our field-specific expectations. We do this because we believe in the promise of curiosity, but also the pleasure of curiosity. We stretch physics to music and poetry, while we stretch critical theory to graphology and neurology. And there is a flexibility in our partnership here, a little swing dance. You will spot Perry ambling among the archives and see Dani standing still, staring at brain images in the laboratory. But you will also notice Perry sitting down to taxonomize and watch Dani running off to tell stories. What better way to follow the call of curiosity and to court serendipity, though, than to weave between disciplines and ways of knowing, defying borders and boundaries as we go?

作为一种协调的媒介，我们培养一种文学风格，追求与声音和修辞形式的协调，以增强我们的论点并更好地装备我们的探索。语言的灵活性，在其诗歌的躯体中蕴含着深刻的智慧。此外，为了与这种文学品质保持一致，我们慷慨地引用其他作家的话，不仅为他们所说的天才而着迷，而且为他们说话的方式而着迷。作为思想艺术家，我们从事混合媒体工作，从语言的枝条和种子、染料和油灰中收集精神材料，这些材料跨越时代，以各种流派和不同的声音书写。在作家、学者和艺术家几个世纪以来的作品中隐含着对好奇心网络叙述的基本见解。此外，在我们的旅程中交织他人的声音不仅仅是风格丰富或证据证明的策略。我们将好奇心概念化为关系型好奇心，这就要求我们借鉴并建立多种认知者和认知方式，无论是在我们自己的学科和学术领域内，还是在其边界之外。

As a medium of consilience, we cultivate a literary style, courting an attunement to sound and rhetorical form in a way that enhances our arguments and better equips our explorations. There is a depth of wisdom in language’s flexibility, in the soma of its poetry. In step with that literary quality, moreover, we quote other writers generously, mesmerized by the genius not only of what they say but of how they say it. As thought artists, we work in mixed media, assembling mental material from the twigs and seeds, dyes and putties of language, written across times in various genres and by distinct voices. Implicit here in the work of writers, scholars, and artists centuries in the making are the elemental insights of a network account of curiosity. Furthermore, interweaving the voices of others throughout our journey is no mere ploy of stylistic enrichment or evidentiary justification. Our conceptualization of curiosity as relational necessitates that we draw from and build upon multiple knowers and ways of knowing, whether cradled within our own disciplines and the academy or out past their edge.

然而，在这项探究中，我们每个人都有独特的支柱。我们分别是训练有素的哲学家和物理学家，在批判社会理论和网络神经科学这两个各自的领域工作。因此，在整本书中，我们在精神和社会、大脑和其他归属结构之间切换。在这样做的时候，我们的行为有点像真菌学家。13毕竟，蘑菇通常会以其闪亮的大头抢尽风头，但在它们的下面和周围，却有绵延数英里的菌丝体，整个地下真菌群落。同样，大脑通常会将好奇心的功劳归于自己，但它在一个庞大的互联系统中运作，而正是这个系统使好奇心成为可能。在《好奇的心灵》中，我们在蘑菇和菌丝体、大脑和社会体之间来回穿梭，以便在神经网络和社会网络中追踪好奇心的所在之处。

There is nevertheless a distinctive anchor for each of us in this inquiry. We are a trained philosopher and physicist, respectively, working in our own fields of critical social theory and network neuroscience. As such, we toggle throughout this book between the mental and the social, between brains and other structures of belonging. In doing so, we behave a bit like mycologists.13 After all, mushrooms typically steal the show, with their big shiny heads, but beneath and around them there stretches mile upon mile of mycelia, a whole underground fungal community. Similarly, the brain typically takes the credit for curiosity, but it functions within a vast interconnective system that makes curiosity possible. In Curious Minds, we shuttle back and forth between the mushrooms and mycelia, the brain and the social body, in order to track curiosity where it lives, across neural and social networks.

我们邀请读者一起踏上这段旅程，与我们一起散步。既要把握我们论点的脉络，也要陶醉于其中的即兴发挥和离题。这本书表现出了它所说的好奇心。因此，我们邀请读者不仅要欣赏，还要参与其中——对这本书充满好奇，而不仅仅是好奇。好奇心会吸引未知并享受着认识的过程；我们在写作中赞美的正是这条道路（而不仅仅是这条道路的目的地）。我们鼓励读者与我们一起思考，在学科共鸣之间切换，并在这个新编排的空间中翩翩起舞。我们在这里提供的既是一种体验，也是一种想法。我们这样做是因为我们坚信，一个强大的理论比任何规定性的“操作”手册都更有力。通过它，各种各样的读者都可以在日常生活中以无数种方式重新想象探究的实践。

We invite our readers to come along on this journey, to take a walk with us. To hold the thread of our argument, but also to revel in the riffs and digressions. The book performs the curiosity of which it speaks. As such, we invite readers not only to appreciate but also to participate—to be curious with the book, not simply about it. Curiosity engages the unknown and relishes in the process of coming to know; it is that path (and not solely the path’s destination) that we celebrate in our writing. We encourage readers to wonder with us, to toggle between the disciplinary resonances, and to dance in this newly choreographed space. What we offer here is an experience as much as an idea. And we do so with the conviction that a robust theory is more powerful than any prescriptive “how-to” manual. Through it, readers of all sorts can reimagine the practice of inquiry in innumerable ways in their everyday lives.

为什么和理由

Whys and Wherefores

想象一下，好奇心不像是储存宝藏，而是在生命之树的树枝上荡来荡去。那棵树是构成知识森林的众多树木之一。这片森林永远在生长，根据土壤的构造、太阳的方向，甚至地球的年龄而变化。此外，这些对知识森林生长的自然限制并不孤单。你和许多其他人类和非人类生物一起培育森林，引导它的生长，分配它的腐烂，并分配一部分供你使用。这也是好奇心。好奇心是森林生态系统中一种生长原则，由知者和已知者、潜在知者和潜在已知者组成。这种生态系统会根据先前的生长模式以及种植者之间的权力斗争和慷慨而变化和塑造。好奇心在地下扎根，在树枝上编织出头顶的树冠，这是一种令人愉快的机会和偶然。但社会逻辑和神经约束也常常决定哪些想法树在什么时候、在什么地方得到最好的培育和最受推崇。

Imagine that curiosity is less like stockpiling treasures than swinging from branches on the tree of life. That tree is one of many trees that make up a forest of knowledge. This forest is forever growing and changing based on the configuration of the soil, the directionality of the sun, and even the age of the earth. These natural constraints on the growth of the knowledge forest, moreover, are not alone. You, alongside many other human and nonhuman creatures, cultivate the forest, shepherding its growth, distributing its decay, and appropriating portions for your use. That too is curiosity. Curiosity is a growth principle in a forest ecology of knowers and knowns, would-be knowers and would-be knowns. And that ecology shifts and shapes depending on prior growth patterns as well as power struggles and generosities between growers. There is a delightful chance and happenstance to the roots curiosity threads underground and to the branches curiosity weaves in a canopy overhead. But there are also societal logics and neural constraints that often determine which idea trees get nurtured best and celebrated most, at what times and in which places.

毕竟，好奇心就像蠕虫和蜘蛛网、鱼和森林一样，存在于更大的生态系统中。那么，好奇心思维在其中发挥作用的相关分布模式、关系和相互依赖性是什么呢？在本书中，我们通过现场研究好奇心来追求生态效度。注意好奇心的生存环境，特别是它存在于事物之间。在相互竞争的知识网络之间、在新旧节点之间以及在知识网络构建者之间。好奇心存在于边缘。它走在一条线上。因此，不可能正式将其孤立出来。它不能被简化为简单的单一行为，也不能被统一并消除所有裂缝。在重新想象好奇心时，我们将神经科学和心理学、哲学和文学融合在一起，以了解真实的故事：好奇心是一种网络实践，一种关系实践。

Curiosity, after all, like worms and webs, fish and forests, is situated within a larger ecology. What then are the relevant distribution patterns, relationships, and interdependencies within which curious thought functions? Throughout this book, we aspire to ecological validity by studying curiosity in situ. Noticing it where it lives, specifically where it lives between things. Between competing knowledge networks, between old nodes and new, and between knowledge network builders. Curiosity lives on the edge. It walks a line. As such, it is impossible to formally isolate. It cannot be reduced to simple, singular acts, nor can it be unified and relieved of all its cracks. In reimagining curiosity, we bring neuroscience and psychology, philosophy and literature, to converge on the real story: curiosity as a network practice, a relational practice.

为什么这很重要？这很重要，部分原因在于这是我们好奇的头脑在工作——在片刻间，在令人愉悦的自由行为中，我们找到了喘息的空间。更根本的是，这很重要，因为并非所有好奇的头脑都是自由的。也并非所有的好奇心都有喘息的空间。伍尔夫的挫败感仍然在我们耳边回响。而她并不孤单。塔-纳西西·科茨回忆起自己在巴尔的摩的黑人童年，遗憾地发现学校要求“顺从”多于鼓励“好奇心”。14类似的见证比比皆是，表明社会不平等如何剥夺了拉丁裔和土著人、残疾人和神经多样性人群以及 LGBTQ 人群等群体的好奇心权利。15我们深思所有代表性不足的科学家和理论家，他们的创新工作一再被忽视。16我们不禁要问，我们如何才能将我们的界限连接在一起？我们如何才能帮助这片森林生长？我们在此提供的只是一条逃生路线——通过这条路线，我们可以将我们的大脑和心灵延伸到世界的边缘之外。17

And why does this matter? It matters in part simply because this is our curious minds at work—for a moment, in a delightful act of freedom, we have found a space to breathe. More fundamentally, it matters because not all curious minds are free. Nor are all curiosities given the space to breathe. Woolf’s frustrations still ring painfully in our ears. And she is far from alone. Ta-Nehisi Coates, reflecting on his own Black boyhood in Baltimore, regrets that schools exacted “compliance” more than they encouraged “curiosity.”14 Similar testaments abound, showing the ways in which societal inequities refuse Latinx and Indigenous people, disabled and neurodiverse people, and LGBTQ people, among other groups, the right to curiosity.15 We think deeply of all the underrepresented scientists and theorists whose innovative work is repeatedly passed over.16 And we ask, How might we thatch our lines together? How might we help this forest grow? What we offer here is but one line of flight—one by which we stretch our brains and our hearts out beyond the brink of the world.17

1

好奇心的科学

The Science of Curiosity

他拿起了铁锹……

He picked up his spade . . .

—弗兰西丝·霍奇森·伯内特，《秘密花园》（1911年）

—Frances Hodgson Burnett, Secret Garden (1911)

当你伸手拿起这本书时，你感到好奇。好奇是什么？它是动物、植物还是矿物？它是虚无缥缈的还是有形的？像懒猴一样，好奇可以归类吗？还是像爱情一样，好奇很难定义？选择精确的词语来回答这些问题似乎是不可能的。然而，好奇似乎应该是可以定义的，因为……好吧，因为……因为它很简单。也许它看起来很简单，因为它很常见。

You were curious when your hand reached out to pick up this book. What is that curiosity? Is it animal, vegetable, or mineral? Is it ethereal or tangible? Like a loris, can it be categorized and classified, or like love, is it difficult to define? It feels impossible to choose precise words to answer these questions. And yet curiosity seems as if it should be definable because . . . well, because . . . because it is so simple. And perhaps it seems so simple because it is so common.

好奇心无处不在——孩子嗅着摇曳的野花，年轻人弹奏着光鲜的新曲子，成年人从书架顶部抽出一本布满灰尘的书。好奇心无处不在，中世纪的人可能会怀疑，好奇心是否只是存在于我们周围的空气中。我们是否吸入了它，让它充满我们的肺部，然后在呼气时与他人分享？空气本身是否让我们感到好奇，因为空气中飘动的分子蕴含着好奇心的本质？

Curiosity is everywhere around us—in the child sniffing the wavering wildflower, the youth playing a glossy new track, the adult pulling a dusty volume from the top shelf. It is so pervasive that a medieval mind might wonder if curiosity is simply in the air about us. Do we imbibe it, fill our lungs with it, and then share it with one another as we exhale? Does the air itself make us curious because its flittering molecules house the essence that is curiosity?

也许吧。正如英国作家、哲学家和牧师约瑟夫·格兰维尔所说，空气确实很奇特，因为它对周围环境感兴趣。空气对钟摆振动的兴趣导致其空气体弯曲，而这种弯曲有助于传播声音。1空气弯曲的结果，即声音本身，在运动的性质上看起来很奇怪，试图填充空间并塑造体积空气。这些和其他许多动作都反映了人类好奇心的本质。笛手的手指看起来很好奇，因为他们探索可用的琴键以形成最悦耳的声音。步行者的双脚看起来很好奇，因为他们探索可用的地形以环游最令人惊叹的景色。人类的思想看起来很好奇，因为它探索可用的知识以分离出最吸引人的想法。

Perhaps. As English writer, philosopher, and clergyperson Joseph Glanvill suggests, air is certainly curious in the sense that it takes interest in its surroundings. Air’s interest in the vibrations of pendulums leads to a bending of its airy body, and that bending serves to propagate sound.1 The fruition of air’s bending, the sounds themselves, appear curious in the nature of their movements, seeking to fill spaces and to mold volumes of air. Movements like these and many others reflect the nature of a being’s curiosity. The fingers of a flutist appear curious as they explore the available keys to shape the most pleasing sounds. The feet of a walker appear curious as they explore the available terrain to circumnavigate the most awing vistas. The mind of a human appears curious as it explores the available knowledge to isolate the most engaging thoughts.

好奇心表面上简单又普遍，这不禁让人质疑它的价值。好奇心就像灰尘、铁锈和霉点一样，如果好奇心无处不在，我们为什么要关心它呢？为什么要读（或写）一本关于好奇心的书？几千年来，人类选择看重的不是常见的事物，而是不常见的事物。我们不太看重红桤木、纸桦树和北美枫杨等落叶乔木的叶子——它们数量如此之多，覆盖了整个地球；相反，我们珍视猴面包树和南美楝树等濒临灭绝的物种。同样，我们不太看重片麻岩、石灰岩和页岩等常见的岩石；相反，我们珍视蓝宝石、黑蛋白石和海纹石等矿物晶体——它们数量如此之少，以至于每种矿物晶体在地球上只出现过一次。在选择要颂扬的美德时，我们不会考虑许多动物的共同性格，包括螳螂和变形虫；相反，我们选择那些不常见的、大多数人确实难以获得的品质，包括谦逊、真诚、慷慨和真实。2但人类是否只珍视稀有的东西呢？或者好奇心不一定稀有才会被珍视？也许好奇心的价值在于它的潜在性（而非现实性），在于它所带来的可能，在于它所打开的大门，以及它所带来的可能性。好奇心之所以有价值，也许因为它是一个过程，有时可以引导我们找到稀有的东西：一堆真理的珍品，然后我们把它放在我们的精神宝库里。对世界的深刻准确了解被誉为既稀有又有价值，好奇心通过洞察力、观点和直觉等相关途径引导我们获得这些知识。好奇心使我们能够了解我们的同胞、我们的世界以及我们的过去和未来。它是各种探究的基础，无论是实践的还是理论的、幼稚的还是有教养的，它涉及从科学到人文、从情感到亚原子粒子等所有主题。

The apparent simplicity and ubiquity of curiosity call into question curiosity’s value. Like dust, rust, and must, if curiosity is everywhere, why should we care about it? Why read (or write) a book about curiosity? For millennia, humans have chosen to place value not on that which is common but rather on that which is uncommon. We place little value on the leaves of deciduous trees such as red alder, paper birch, and box elder—so plentiful that they cover the earth in a rather audacious abundance; instead, we prize species that are endangered such as baobab and monkey puzzle trees. Similarly, we place little value on common rocks such as gneiss, limestone, and shale; instead, we prize mineral crystals of benitoite, black opal, and larimar—so scarce that each appears in only a single spot on the planet. When choosing virtues to extol, we do not consider dispositions common to many animals, including the mantis and amoeba; instead, we choose those that are uncommon and indeed often difficult for most humans to attain, including humility, sincerity, generosity, and authenticity.2 But do humans only and ever value that which is rare? Or is it possible that curiosity need not be rare to be valued? Perhaps curiosity is valuable in its potentiality (as opposed to its actuality), in what it makes possible, in the doors that it opens, and the possibilities that it brings to life. Perhaps curiosity is valuable because it is a process that can sometimes lead us to that which is rare: a curio of truth that we then place in our mental cabinet. Deeply accurate knowledge of our world is extolled as both rare and valuable, and curiosity leads us toward that knowledge through the relevant byways of insights, perspectives, and hunches. Curiosity allows us to arrive at knowledge about our fellow humans, about our world, and about our past and future. It is fundamental to inquiry of all kinds, either practical or theoretical, naive or educated, and about all topics, from the sciences to the humanities, from emotions to subatomic particles.

好奇心与探究之间的关系是一元的，因为它是根本性的。好奇心（至少在一定程度上）就是用头脑去探究。然而，好奇心与探究之间的关系也是二元的、三元的、四元的，更普遍地说是多元的，因为要理解好奇心，我们必须探究探究，然后我们必须探究关于探究的探究。当我们站在两面镜子之间时，我们寻求的答案就存在于我们自己和我们头脑的无限倒影中。我们不会试图解开每一个倒影，而是在这里关注好奇心与探究的关系。在本章后面，我们将转向互补的反思：探究与好奇心研究的关系。

The relation between curiosity and inquiry is unary in the sense that it is fundamental. To be curious is (at least in part) to use the mind to inquire. Yet the relation between curiosity and inquiry is also binary, ternary, quaternary, and more generally multiary in the sense that to understand curiosity, we must inquire into inquiry, and then we must inquire into the inquiry about inquiry. And the answers we seek lie somewhere in the infinite reflections of ourselves and our minds as we stand juxtaposed between two facing mirrors. Rather than attempting to unpack each reflection, here we will focus on how curiosity is relevant for inquiry. Later in this chapter, we will turn to the complementary reflection: how inquiry is relevant to the study of curiosity.

好奇心是如何在探究中发挥作用的？作为焦点，我们可以以对自然世界的探究为中心，然后思考好奇心是如何在科学中发挥作用的。人们有时认为科学包括在精心设计的实验中定向寻找特定信息。但事实上，科学同样是无方向观察的实践和结果，没有任何特定的实验设备。3寻求无用的知识是现代科学事业中备受推崇的堡垒之一。虽然人们可以有理由回想起亚里士多德，但在近代，弗朗西斯·培根也许是简单无方向观察的典型支持者之一。4他在他的书《新工具论》（或《对自然解释的真实建议》）的开篇中声称：“人类作为自然的使者和解释者，所做的和理解的都是他对自然秩序的观察，无论是关于事物还是心灵，他既不知道也不能够做得更多。” 5培根为《大复兴》 （1620 年）选择的卷首插图是一幅特别引人注目的视觉作品，它赞美了无方向的观察，佛兰德斯雕刻家西蒙·范德帕斯在其中蚀刻了两根立在岩石海岸上的柱子，柱子另一边有一艘船驶入广阔的水域。6没有一朵涟漪比另一朵更有价值；没有一个分子比另一个更像水。在将未知转化为已知的过程中，每一次观察、所有观察都是同等必要的。

How is curiosity used in inquiry? As a focal point, we might take inquiry regarding the natural world and then question how curiosity is used in the sciences. Science is sometimes thought to comprise the directed seeking of a particular piece of information in well-crafted experiments. But in fact science is just as much the practice and result of undirected observations, without any particular experimental apparatus.3 The seeking of useless knowledge is one of the venerated bastions of the scientific enterprise in modern history. Although one could justifiably hark back to Aristotle, in more recent times Francis Bacon is perhaps one of the quintessential proponents of simple undirected observation.4 He opens his book Novum Organum (or True Suggestions for the Interpretation of Nature) with the claim, “Man, as the minister and interpreter of nature, does and understands as much as his observations on the order of nature, either with regard to things or the mind, permit him, and neither knows nor is capable of more.”5 A particularly compelling visual that lauds undirected observation is the frontispiece that Bacon selected for his Instauratio Magna (1620), where Flemish engraver Simon van de Passe etched two columns standing on a rocky shore, beyond which a ship sails into a vast expanse of water.6 No ripple appears more valuable than another; no molecule is more truly water than another. Each observation, all observations are equivalently necessary in the labor of transforming the unknown into the known.

这种无指向的观察在《伦敦皇家学会哲学学报》（1662 年首次出版）中占有同等地位以及数学证明和实验室实验报告。最早的此类轶事报道了人类静脉中的牛奶、“一头非常奇怪的怪异小牛”的存在，以及威斯特伐利亚一处奇怪泉水的描述。7有些文章甚至预测了未来可能发生的观察结果，例如题为“奥祖特先生对地球和月球上可能被其各自居民发现的变化的推测”。8加拿大哲学家伊恩·哈金将这些事情统称为“旅行者的故事”，强调无方向观察的轶事是当时新兴的科学期刊类型的关键组成部分，也是培根好奇心案例的重要组成部分。9 与这些早期的优先事项形成鲜明对比的是，随后几个世纪的压力促使研究人员实践功利主义的好奇心，主要是通过解决实际使用的问题。 20 世纪初，压力如此之大，以至于教育领袖亚伯拉罕·弗莱克斯纳 (Abraham Flexner) 创立了高等研究院，让科学家可以再次思考那些有趣的问题，而不管这些问题是否有用。弗莱克斯纳在他现在的经典文章《无用知识的有用性》中指出，我们对有用性的概念可能“已经变得过于狭隘，无法满足人类精神的漫游和反复无常的可能性”。10在最好的情况下，科学可以在所有未知的水域中航行，以道德为舵，扬帆起航，带着求知的进步价值，而不是拥有已知事物的占有价值。

Such undirected observation takes an equal place in the Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London (first published in 1662) alongside mathematical proofs and reports of laboratory experiments. The earliest such anecdotes report milk in human veins, the existence of “a very odd monstrous calf,” and an account of a strange spring in Westphalia.7 Some articles even provide predictions about what observations might be possible in the future, such as that titled “Monsieur Auzout’s Speculations of the Changes, Likely to Be Discovered in the Earth and Moon, by Their Respective Inhabitants.”8 Ian Hacking, a Canadian philosopher, refers collectively to these items as “traveler’s tales,” emphasizing that anecdotes from undirected observations were a key component of the emerging genre of scientific journals at the time and an important component of Bacon’s case for curiosity.9 In contrast to these early priorities, the pressures of the ensuing centuries induced investigators to practice a utilitarian curiosity, chiefly by tackling questions of practical use. In the early 1900s, the strain was so great that educational leader Abraham Flexner founded the Institute for Advanced Study as a place where a scientist could once again think about questions that were simply interesting, irrespective of their utility. In his now-classic essay “The Usefulness of Useless Knowledge,” Flexner suggests that our conception of what is useful may “have become too narrow to be adequate to the roaming and capricious possibilities of the human spirit.”10 At its best, science roams all unknown waters, with ethics at its helm and sails spread with the processive value of coming to know rather than the possessive value of owning the known.

好奇心与科学方法

Curiosity and the Scientific Method

思考、收集和观察的好奇心与科学探究过程息息相关。在同一篇文章中，弗莱克斯纳写道：“好奇心可能会或可能不会产生有用的结果，这可能是现代思维的突出特征。” 11在指导无用和有用知识的获取方面，好奇心是寻找真理和克服不确定性的科学工具。但是，尽管好奇心是必要的，但它可能不足以获得科学家经常希望获得的确定性。为了理解这一点，让我们回到 1661 年左右的格兰维尔。他刚刚出版了《教条主义的虚荣》，呼吁宗教宽容迫害和思想自由战胜经院哲学。在论文中，他质疑，当我们对科学（和物质世界）有如此深刻的不确定性时，我们怎么能对宗教（和非物质世界）固执己见。12他通过描述人类是多么无知来建立自己的观点，表明我们无法解释我们的感官，讨论我们无法破译人类记忆，揭示我们对物质的了解是多么少，并强调我们无法理解甚至像车轮运动这样的简单动作。（请注意，后一种无知在几年后得到了显著改善，当时艾萨克·牛顿于 1686 年发表了他的《自然哲学的数学原理》。）格兰维尔问道，在如此缺乏了解的情况下，我们有什么资格监督彼此的思想和信仰？

The curiosity to think, to collect, and to observe is germane to the process of scientific inquiry. In the same essay, Flexner writes, “Curiosity, which may or may not eventuate in something useful, is probably the outstanding characteristic of modern thinking.”11 In guiding the acquisition of both useless and useful knowledge, curiosity is a scientific tool to search for truth and to overcome uncertainty. But although necessary, curiosity may not prove sufficient to obtain the certainty that scientists often wish for. To appreciate this point, let us go back to Glanvill circa 1661. He had just published The Vanity of Dogmatizing, which pleaded for religious tolerance over persecution and freedom of thought over scholasticism. In the treatise, he questions how we can be dogmatic about religion (and the immaterial world) when we have such deep uncertainty about science (and the material world).12 He builds his case by describing how incredibly ignorant humans are, demonstrating that we cannot explain our senses, discussing our incapacity to decipher human memory, revealing how little we know about matter, and underscoring our inability to understand even simple actions like the motion of a wheel. (Note that this latter bit of ignorance would be significantly ameliorated just a few years later, when Isaac Newton published his Philosophiae Naturalis Principia Mathematica in 1686.) With such little understanding, Glanvill asks, who are we to police one another’s thoughts and beliefs?

我们的无知有两种。它可能是情境性的，也可能是人性所固有的。当一种文化尚未拥有令人信服地回答科学问题、检验假设或建立合理理论所需的科学工具时，就会出现情境性的无知。当有机体（例如人类）具有易犯错的机制（例如感知或推理）​​时，就会出现内在无知，这种机制总是与真相保持距离。格兰维尔似乎在考虑第二种类型：内在无知。他声称，我们深深的无知部分是由于我们的感情误导了我们；我们热爱自己和他人的想法，我们过分崇尚古代和权威。这些特征是人类的特征，影响我们看清真相的能力，与我们的科学工具的（不）完美无关。地质学家 TC 张伯伦似乎同意这一观点。1897 年，他写道，我们仍然会成为感情的牺牲品。

This ignorance of ours comes in two kinds. It may be contextual or it may be intrinsic to human nature. Contextual ignorance can arise when a culture does not yet have the scientific tools needed to convincingly answer a scientific question, test a hypothesis, or build a justifiable theory. Intrinsic ignorance arises when an organism (e.g., human) is built with fallible machinery (e.g., perception or reasoning) that always keeps the truth at arm’s length. Glanvill appears to be thinking of the second type: intrinsic ignorance. Our deep ignorance, he claims, is due in part to the fact that our affections mislead us; we love our own ideas and those of others, and we pay undue homage to antiquity and authority. These traits are human traits and impact our ability to see the truth, independent of the (im)perfection of our scientific tools. Geologist T. C. Chamberlain appears to agree. In 1897, he writes that we still fall prey to our affections.

当一个人对一个现象给出了一个似乎令人满意的原创解释时，那一刻对他智力上的孩子的爱就产生了，随着这个解释逐渐发展成为一个明确的理论，他的父母之爱就会聚集在他的孩子身上，他对孩子越来越亲切。……在不知不觉中，他也会强迫理论符合事实，强迫事实符合理论。13

The moment one has offered an original explanation for a phenomenon which seems satisfactory, that moment affection for his intellectual child springs into existence, and as the explanation grows into a definite theory his parental affections cluster about his offspring and it grows more and more dear to him. . . . There springs up also unwittingly a pressing of the theory to make it fit the facts and a pressing of the facts to make them fit the theory.13

科学家是人，科学的进步至少部分受到人类局限性的阻碍。

Scientists are humans, and science progresses in a manner that is at least partially hamstrung by human limitations.

作为当代科学家，我们越来越认识到自身知识的局限性，以及扩展知识的工具。科学探究是对某种真理的探索。作为科学家，我们被一种对确定性的生存渴望所驱使，部分原因是我们面临着太多的不确定性。我们感到不确定，不仅是因为未知如此广阔，还因为我们的（人类）感官不完善，我们的（人类）感知有偏见。14从某种意义上说，科学探究是一种成为非人的努力。或者可能是非人类。或者是超人。有时，娱乐业把科学家描绘成有朝一日——在某个奇妙的、不真实的世界里——可能创造出超人（想想钢铁侠）的人，这感觉很讽刺；讽刺之处在于，即使是科学实验中最微小、最平凡的动作——移取一些液体、数几个细胞或对未成像的图像进行成像——也是在寻求获得非人性的行为，试图从我们不确定的存在的阴谋中创造确定性。但是，我们怎么会变得不像人类呢？我们经常尝试将好奇心的自由与科学方法的约束结合起来：归纳推理的规则。我们从一个问题开始，将问题分解为对象和过程，开发一种测量这些对象和过程的方法，设计一个假设和一个零假设，设计一个实验来反驳其中一个假设，然后进行实验以得到一个明确的结果。15 通过从特定事实推理到一般原则，该序列使我们能够从数据中得出结论。

As contemporary scientists, we increasingly appreciate the limits of our own knowledge and the tools we have to expand that knowledge. Scientific inquiry is the search for a kind of truth. As scientists, we are driven by an existential desire for certainty, in part because we are faced with so much uncertainty. We are uncertain not just because the unknown is so vast but also because our (human) senses are imperfect and our (human) perceptions are biased.14 In some sense, scientific inquiry is thus an effort to become inhuman. Or perhaps nonhuman. Or perhaps superhuman. At times it feels ironic that the entertainment industry depicts scientists as those who might someday—in some fantastic, unreal world—create the superhuman (think Iron Man); the irony arises from the fact that even the most miniscule and mundane action in a scientific experiment—pipetting some liquid, counting a few cells, or imaging the unimaged—is an action seeking to attain unhumanity, to create certainty from the machinations of our uncertain beings. But how can and do we become not human in all of these small ways? Well, we often attempt to do so by marrying the freedom of curiosity with the constraints of the scientific method: the rules of inductive inference. We begin with a question, break the question down into objects and processes, develop a way to measure those objects and processes, devise a hypothesis and a null hypothesis, devise an experiment to refute one of the hypotheses, and then carry out the experiment so as to get a clean result.15 The sequence allows us to form conclusions from data by reasoning from particular facts to general principles.

归纳推理过程当然可以帮助我们克服由不完美的感官和偏见所造成的不确定性。但有一个问题。这个过程并非万无一失。由于感官的不完美，我们只能透过玻璃看东西，感知到被错误所掩盖的现实。因为我们通过同样的不完美的暗色玻璃来观察每个实验的结果，所以我们永远无法完全实现我们的目标。科学家们试图通过两种方式来规避这个相当严峻的限制。首先，我们选择或建造一个无偏的测量仪器，如显微镜、六分仪或望远镜，然后将该仪器放在我们（人类观察者）和我们所观察的世界之间希望理解。如果所有支持假设的证据都来自测量仪器而不是人类的感知能力，也许我们可以在一定程度上摆脱偏见。然后我们将看到证据的本质：客观测量结果会或不会支持我们的理论。当然，如果我们对自己诚实，我们会承认这是一个有点乐观的观点，我们的希望只是有点现实。是的，测量仪器确保科学事业不受人类局限性的影响，但没有一种仪器是完全没有偏见的，我们对测量结果的感知也不是完全没有偏见的。第二，我们使用假设和观察的迭代方法。我们通过从观察中构建假设，使用该假设进行新实验以获得新观察，最后使用该新观察来改进假设，从而创建一个潜在的无限循环。我们可以一遍又一遍地走这个循环，以期更接近最近的知识。虽然确定性永远是我们无法企及的，但我们仍然可以使用实验设备和迭代归纳推理朝着它前进。

The process of inductive inference can certainly help us to supersede the uncertainties caused by our imperfect senses and biased perceptions. But there is a problem. The process is not foolproof. By the imperfections of our senses, we only ever see through a glass darkly, perceiving bits of reality overshadowed by errors. Because we view the results of every experiment through the same dark glass with the same imperfections, we can never fully reach our goal. Scientists seek to circumvent this rather grim limitation in two ways. First, we choose or construct an unbiased measurement apparatus such as a microscope, sextant, or telescope, and then we place that apparatus between us (the human observer) and the world we hope to understand. If all evidence in favor of a hypothesis comes through a measurement apparatus rather than through our human perceptual faculties, perhaps we can be somewhat spared from our biases. Then we will see the evidence for what it is: objective measurements that will or will not support our theories. Of course, if we are honest with ourselves, we will admit that this is a somewhat rosy perspective, and our hope is only somewhat realistic. Yes, a measurement apparatus ensures that the scientific enterprise is less tainted by our human limitations, but no apparatus is perfectly unbiased, and neither is our perception of the resultant measurements. Second, we use an iterative approach of hypothesis and observation. We create a potentially infinite loop by building a hypothesis from an observation, using that hypothesis to develop a new experiment to obtain a new observation, and finally using that new observation to refine the hypothesis. We can walk this loop over and over again in our goal to step closer to the nearest bit of knowledge. While certainty will always be just out of our reach, we can nevertheless make progress toward it using experimental equipment and iterative inductive inference.

作为科学家，我们一生都在引导好奇心去追求确定性。然而，在此过程中，我们越来越接受不确定性，并庆祝通往理解的道路，而不期望获得最终结论。我们的社区通常将博士学位描述为一个过程，不是我们创造新知识的过程，而是我们了解到我们实际上知道的很少。我们热爱科学好奇心的过程，不是因为它能带来完美，而是因为它能让我们更接近完美。我们的进步让人想起芝诺的乌龟和阿喀琉斯悖论，也让人想起亚里士多德在《物理学》中的一段话，他写道：“在比赛中，最快的跑者永远无法超越最慢的跑者，因为追赶者必须先到达被追赶者的出发点，所以慢的跑者必须一直保持领先。” 16我们接受这种不完美的奔跑，部分是因为我们看重这段旅程（例如，疫苗有 90% 的效果，或者抗生素可以杀死部分细菌，但不是全部），部分是因为我们看重偶然的发现（例如，在最意想不到的地方发现抗生素、法律、治疗方法）。成为一名科学家就像学习“温和的徒步艺术”，正如旅行作家斯蒂芬·格雷厄姆所观察到的那样，这并不我们所关注的不是所走过的风景的范围，而是我们沿途的生活。我们走在探索、推理和探究的好奇道路上，不是为了“特技”（到达终点）或“个人装饰”（达到完美之美），而是为了“在快乐的早晨流连忘返，倾听、观察、存在”，在“瞬间而不是长跑”中寻找品质。17对于科学家来说，好奇心既是一种接近世界现实的手段，也是一种沿着道路徘徊的手段，可以到达某个地方，也可以到达无处，或者到达偶然变成某个地方的任何地方。它是超越人类与普通人类之间的分界线。

We as scientists spend our lives channeling our curiosity in the service of certainty. Yet along the way, we increasingly embrace uncertainty and celebrate the paths toward understanding, without expecting its conclusive acquisition. Our community commonly describes the PhD as a process not whereby we create new knowledge but instead whereby we learn how little it is that we actually know. We love the process of scientific curiosity not because it results in perfection but instead because it can get us a bit closer.
