Our progress is reminiscent of Zeno’s paradox of the tortoise and Achilles, and also of Aristotle’s passage in the Physics, where he writes, “In a race, the quickest runner can never over-take the slowest, since the pursuer must first reach the point whence the pursued started, so that the slower must always hold a lead.”16 We embrace that imperfect scamper in part by valuing the passage (e.g., the vaccine that is 90 percent effective or the antibiotic that kills some bacteria but not all) and in part by valuing the serendipity (e.g., the discovery of an antibiotic, a law, a treatment in the most unexpected of places). Becoming a scientist is like learning the “gentle art of tramping,” which as travel writer Stephen Graham observes, is not about the extent of the landscape traversed but rather about how we live along the way. We walk the curious paths of investigation, inference, and inquiry not as a “stunt” (where the end is reached) or “personal ornament” (where the beauty is perfected) but instead in order to “linger in the happy morning hours, to listen, to watch, to exist,” finding quality “in moments, not in distance run.”17 To a scientist, curiosity then is both a means of moving closer to the reality of the world and a means of lingering along a passage, to somewhere or to nowhere, or to an anywhere that serendipitously becomes a somewhere. It is the edge that straddles the divide between the more-than-human and the simply human.

事实上，正是这些不完善之处——现有知识、现代解决方案或人类能力的不完善之处——标志着科学的潜力和特权。它们确保道路继续延伸，道路是分叉的、蜿蜒的，而不是笔直的、预先确定的。作为科学家，我们寻求近端的确定性（“这就是道路！”）和远端的不确定性（“谁能知道它会通向何方？”）。我们怀疑那些声称自己拥有最终决定权的人，因为我们知道大自然会继续说话。而这正是我们陶醉的地方。我们的游乐场是一个未解问题的世界，充满了我们周围的谜团，就像我们呼吸的空气中的水滴一样进入我们体内。科学令人着迷，因为每一步确定性都将我们带到不确定性的门槛。我们伸出手去触摸大自然秘密的悬崖峭壁；它是不可攀登的，我们因此更加爱她。森林中的每片空地都将我们带到下一片不透明的灌木丛。每条透明的溪流都坐落在模糊的岩床上。每一阵微风都不可避免地会引向模糊的乌云。正是这种对立的并置为塞壬的歌声赋予了话语。事实上，科学就是一首歌、一首诗、一首诗。它颂扬了一个复杂的整体，其中几个清晰透彻的时刻被精心雕琢，并与更大、更持久的印象基石形成鲜明对比，这些印象基石位于词语的含义之间，是实验数据之下的暗流。在诗歌中，我们在背景中听到了旋转的内涵和推论、沉淀的衍生意义线和概念历史的化石记录；在科学中，我们听到了类似的物质共鸣，当我们聆听大自然的歌词时，感觉怪异而遥远。更有趣的是，随着岁月的流逝和进化的推进，短语也在发生变化。科学的无限性没有留下遗憾的余地。人们永远不必担心最后一块拼图会被找到，从而产生完成的悲伤，以及未来谜题的永久消失。同样，人们也不必担心作者作品的最后一页会被阅读，让读者沉浸在永不复返的悲伤中。不。这是永无止境的欢乐承诺。

It is in fact these imperfections—of current knowledge, of modern solutions, or of human capacities—that mark the potential and the privilege of science. They ensure that the path continues, that the way is forked and meandering rather than straight and predetermined. As scientists, we seek proximal certainty (“Here is the path!”) just as much as distal uncertainty (“Who can tell where it might lead?”). We look askance at those who claim that they have the last word because we know Nature will speak on. And this is where we revel. Our playground is a world of unanswered questions, of puzzles all about us, and entering into us like droplets of water in the air we breathe. Science enthralls because each step of certainty brings us to the threshold of uncertainty. We reach out and touch the sheer cliff face of Nature’s secrets; it is unscalable, and we love her the better for it. Each clearing in the woods brings us to the next thicket of opacity. Each transparent stream sits upon a rock bed of ambiguity. Each sheer breeze leads inevitably to the dark clouds of vagueness. It is this juxtaposition of opposites that gives words to the Siren’s song. In fact, science is very much a song, a verse, a poem. It celebrates a complicated whole, in which a few piercingly lucid moments are carefully sculpted and set in relief against a larger and longer-lived bedrock of impression that lies somewhere between the meanings of words, an undercurrent that lies somewhere beneath the data of experiments. In poetry, we hear in the background the swirling connotations and corollaries, sedimented lines of comeanings, and fossilized records of concept histories; in science, we hear similar material resonances, eerie, and far away, as we listen to Nature’s lyrics. And to make matters more intriguing, the phrases change, as eons pass and evolution marches on. The living infinitude of science leaves no room for regret. One need never worry that the last piece of the puzzle will be found, instilling the sadness of completion, the permanent loss of future puzzling. Likewise, one need never fear that the final page of an author’s corpus will be read, soaking the reader in the grief of the nevermore. No. Here is the joyous promise of the never-ending.

好奇心与科学问题的组成部分

Curiosity and the Parts of a Scientific Question

好奇心可以引导我们找到罕见的事物（对知识的好奇心），但它并不能保证一定能做到。科学上的好奇心是人类与世界之间的一种共生关系；因此，它既受到自然法则的约束，也受到人类探究能力的制约。正如河岸定义并被水流定义一样，好奇心既定义并被探究过程定义。这种相互的给予始于问题的形成。什么是问题？在科学中，问题是对物体及其过程——或者更简单地说，事物及其作用——的探究陈述。形成一个好问题并不容易；它需要仔细选择各个部分，并精确提出这些部分相互依赖的过程。形成一个好的科学问题的过程类似于绘制句子图解，就像中学语文课程有时教授的那样。一套规则允许学生将一条河流线（思想）转换成一个多叶的树状结构（思想片段），冠词在风中摇曳，介词则像小孩一样舒适地坐在分支点上，摇摇晃晃。18 “我在树上静静地思考。”我——长长的垂直线——思考——在叶子下——静静地——沿着树枝——在——直线——树——在叶子下——一。学生在干净、整洁的纸张上画出这些图表，显示出词类之间明确且最近的依赖关系：形容词从名词词干中分支出来，而介词短语从它们修饰的词中分支出来。同样，一个好的科学问题要使明确对象和过程之间的依赖关系。在图中，我们要研究的物理物质是句子的主语，物理过程是谓语，物理物质的替代测量是谓语名词，混杂变量是形容词，调节变量是副词。只有将一个想法（句子）正确地提炼为其组成部分及其相互关系（图表），我们才能确保我们的科学过程（句子构造）准确地检验了一个合理的假设（反映了我们的意思）。

Curiosity can lead us toward that which is rare (a curio of knowledge), but it is not guaranteed to do so. Scientific curiosity is a symbiotic line of relation between humanity and the world; as such, it is at once constrained by the laws of Nature and confined by the powers of human inquiry. As the banks of a river both define and are defined by a stream of water, so curiosity both defines and is defined by the process of inquiry. The give and take begins with the forming of a question. What is a question? In science, a question is a statement of inquiry regarding objects and their processes—or more simply, things and what they do. Forming a good question is not easy; it requires a careful choice of parts and a precise posing of the processes whereby those parts depend upon one another. The procedure for forming a good scientific question is akin to diagramming a sentence, as is sometimes taught in middle school language curricula. A set of rules allows the student to transform a river line (of thought) into a leafy tree structure (of thought bits), with articles waving in the wind and prepositions sitting snugly at the branch points like small children, dangling their legs.18 “I think quietly in a tree.” I—long vertical line—think—under leaf—quietly—down branch—in—straight line—tree—under leaf—a. The student draws these diagrams on crisp, clean, unlined sheets of paper, evincing the explicit and most proximal dependencies between the parts of speech: adjectives leaf from the noun stem, while prepositional phrases branch from the words they modify. Similarly, a good scientific question makes explicit the dependencies between objects and processes. In the diagram, the physical matter we seek to investigate is the subject of the sentence, the physical process is the predicate, the alternative measurements of the physical matter are the predicate nouns, the confound variables are the adjectives, and the moderator variables are the adverbs. It is only from the correct distillation of an idea (the sentence) into its component parts and their relations to one another (the diagram) that we will be assured that our scientific process (sentence construction) accurately tests a reasonable hypothesis (reflects our meaning).

当我们描绘好奇心时，我们首先要说的是：我们感兴趣的主题或物质。我们应该选择什么样的物质来建立假设并寻找解释？在做出选择时，我们最大的挑战是选择相关的物质尺度。我们应该在亚原子粒子和费曼图的尺度上，还是在身体组织和行为主题的尺度上解决人类认知问题？对于任何特定的可观察现象，哪个尺度能提供最令人满意或最“真实”的解释，这个问题困扰了科学家几个世纪。19不幸的是，提出的答案总体上相当分歧。在某些科学领域，最常见的答案是还原论：大尺度上发生的过程只能用小尺度上发生的过程来解释，而这些过程又只能用更小尺度上发生的过程来解释，以此类推，无穷无尽。还原论的局限性有很多原因，但其中一个特别令人信服的原因在理论物理学家菲利普·安德森 1972 年发表在《科学》杂志上的题为《更多即不同》的文章中得到了很好的阐述：

When diagramming our curiosity, we begin as we often do in a sentence: with the subject or the physical matter of interest. What physical matter should we choose upon which to build a hypothesis and search for an explanation? In making that choice, our biggest challenge is to pick the relevant scale of matter. Should we address questions of human cognition at the scale of subatomic particles and Feynman diagrams, or at the scale of bodily tissues and behavioral motifs? The question of which scale will provide the most satisfactory, or the most “true,” explanation for any particular observable phenomenon is one that has plagued scientists for centuries.19 And unfortunately the proposed answers have in general been rather divisive. The most common answer in some fields of science is that of reductionism: the notion that the processes occurring at large scales can only be explained by processes occurring at smaller scales, and those processes in turn can only be explained by processes occurring at even smaller scales, and so on, ad infinitum. Reductionism is limited for many reasons, but one particularly compelling reason is well articulated by theoretical physicist Philip Anderson in his 1972 article published in Science titled “More Is Different”:

这种思维的主要谬误在于，还原论假设绝不意味着“建构论”假设：将一切归结为简单的基本定律的能力并不意味着能够从这些定律出发重建宇宙。事实上，基本粒子物理学家告诉我们的基本定律的性质越多，它们与其他科学领域的实际问题似乎就越不相关，更不用说与社会问题了。20

The main fallacy in this kind of thinking is that the reductionist hypothesis does not by any means imply a “constructionist” one: The ability to reduce everything to simple fundamental laws does not imply the ability to start from those laws and reconstruct the universe. In fact, the more the elementary particle physicists tell us about the nature of the fundamental laws, the less relevance they seem to have to the very real problems of the rest of science, much less to those of society.20

安德森与哲学家安吉拉·波托奇尼克 (Angela Potochnik) 等人的观点一致，认为不存在任何特定的解释尺度。事实上，每个尺度都有自己的规律、概念和概括，无法用任何其他尺度的规律、概念和概括来解释。

Anderson joins philosopher Angela Potochnik and others in arguing that there exists no privileged scale for explanation. In fact each scale is characterized by its own laws, concepts, and generalizations, which cannot be explained by those of any other scale.

没有任何一个分析单位与所有科学领域相关，这一观点无疑令人感到自由，但也充满挑战。我们如何选择分析单位来研究任何特定的过程？好吧，我们通过考虑科学探究中的分析单位可能具有的三个关键属性来做到这一点。首先，理想情况下，单位应该是我们可以可靠测量的东西，或者根据我们上面描述的芝诺悖论版本尽可能可靠地测量。其次，单位应该是我们假设中的概念：句子的主语。这两个特征共同确保我们以合理的方式开始我们的句子。重要的是，一旦选定，分析单位就决定了句子中其他部分的规模和性质：物理过程（动词）、调节变量（副词）、混杂变量（形容词）以及对感兴趣概念的任何其他替代测量（谓语名词）。当用语言表达时，句子是一个假设；当用数学表达时，句子是一个方程式。在这两种情况下，句子都代表系统的候选模型。后一种观察使我们发现了科学探究分析单位可能具有的第三个关键特性：即，它可以放置在一个模型中，该模型可以对它要解释的对象或过程做出简约而准确的预测。

The notion that no single unit of analysis is relevant to all areas of science is admittedly freeing, but also challenging. How do we choose the unit of analysis with which to study any particular process? Well, we do so by considering three key properties that a unit of analysis in scientific inquiry could usefully have. First, ideally the unit would be something that we can reliably measure, or as reliably as possible given our version of Zeno’s paradox described above. Second, the unit should be a concept in our hypothesis: the subject of our sentence. Together, these two features ensure that we begin our sentence in a reasonable manner. Importantly, once chosen, the unit of analysis determines the scale and nature of the other parts in our sentence: the physical process (verb), moderating variables (adverbs), confound variables (adjectives), and any alternative measurements of the concept of interest (predicate nouns). When formulated in language, the sentence is a hypothesis; when formulated in mathematics, the sentence is an equation. In both cases, the sentence represents a candidate model of the system. This latter observation leads us to a third key property that a unit of analysis in scientific inquiry could usefully have: namely, that it can be placed in a model that offers a parsimonious and accurate prediction of the object or process that it is meant to explain.

为了理解这三个标准的实用性，让我们考虑一下如何研究、建模并最终解释一只猫（随便选一个：柴郡猫、薛定谔的猫或格兰杰的克鲁克山）。物理学家以将大型哺乳动物（例如奶牛）建模为简单的几何物体（例如球体）而闻名，并且毫不犹豫地将相同的模型用于小型哺乳动物（例如猫）。哺乳动物的球形模型，无论大小，都简单、易处理且有用；大学一年级物理考试中常见的问题与一头在空中飞行的奶牛有关。然而，这样的模型也本质上过于简单。为什么不添加一些多边形呢？三角形可用于模拟猫的耳朵，矩形可用于模拟猫的尾巴。当然，我们可以继续添加更多多边形，镶嵌、隔间、组织、细胞类型、分子机器，最终是 DNA，这个过程从粗糙简单到精细复杂。模型的连续性说明了模型准确性和模型简约性之间的明显权衡。正如生理学家 Arturo Rosenblueth 和数学家 Norbert Wiener 曾经写道的那样，“猫的最佳材料模型是另一只猫，最好是同一只猫。” 21 Crookshanks 是柴郡猫的模型，但柴郡猫更准确的模型应该是它自己。然而，这个更准确的模型远非简约，而这种缺乏简约性会影响人类理解和随后认知的能力。好奇心是好奇心的准确模型，但我们从这个模型中学到了什么吗？既简约又准确的模型可以分离出可观察现象中最重要和最可测量的组成部分，并且可以以人类可以理解的方式描述组成部分之间的关​​系。既简约又准确的模型是选择了有用的好奇心探究尺度、分析单位和问题图表的模型。

To appreciate the utility of these three criteria, let us consider the question of how to study, model, and ultimately explain a cat (take your pick: the Cheshire cat, Schrödinger’s cat, or Granger’s Crookshanks). Physicists are famous for modeling large mammals (e.g., cows) as simple geometric objects (e.g., spheres), and have no qualms using those same models for small mammals (e.g., cats). The spherical model of a mammal, large or small, is simple, tractable, and useful; a common question on a first-year college physics exam has something to do with a cow flying through the air. Yet such a model is also inherently simplistic. Why not add a few polygons? Triangles could be used to model the cat’s ears, and a rectangle could be used to model the cat’s tail. Of course, we could continue to add more polygons, tessellations, compartments, tissues, cell types, molecular machines, and eventually DNA, in a process moving from the coarse and simple to the fine and complex. The continuum of models illustrates an apparent trade-off between model accuracy and model parsimony. As physiologist Arturo Rosenblueth and mathematician Norbert Wiener once wrote, “The best material model of a cat is another, or preferably the same, cat.”21 Crookshanks is a model of the Cheshire cat, but a more accurate model of the Cheshire cat would be itself. Yet this more accurate model is far from parsimonious, and that lack of parsimony impacts the human capacity to understand and subsequently to know. Curiosity is an accurate model of curiosity, but have we learned anything from this model? Models that are both parsimonious and accurate can isolate the most important and most measurable components of an observable phenomenon, and they can describe the relations between components in a way that humans can understand. A model that is both parsimonious and accurate is one that has chosen a useful scale of curious inquiry, unit of analysis, and diagram of the question.

这样，科学探究和好奇心就紧密地交织在一起。好奇心常常会引导我们去思考最初的问题。然而，这个问题往往一开始就提出得不太恰当，而且很幼稚。对实际可测量事物的限制有助于磨练分析单位，而制定假设及其相关模型的严格性有助于提高问题的精确度。反过来，好奇心又对这些严格性施加压力，问道，什么样的模型可能是真的？如果我的名词实际上是 y 而不是 x，会怎么样？这个等式是否可以这样写而不是那样写，如果可以，这种表述对我的预测意味着什么？游走在人类与自然的边缘，科学的好奇心引导着探究之河，同时也推动着河岸期待意想不到的事情。

In this way, scientific inquiry and curiosity are profoundly interdigitated. Curiosity often leads us to the original question. Yet that question just as often begins as one that is rather ill posed and certainly naive. The constraint of what can actually be measured serves to hone the unit of analysis, and the strictures of formulating a hypothesis and its associated model serve to add precision to the question. In turn, curiosity presses back on the strictures, asking, What sorts of models might be true? What if my noun actually did y instead of x? Could the equation be written this way rather than that way, and if so, what would that formulation mean for my prediction? Walking the edge between humanity and nature, scientific curiosity guides the river of inquiry while also pushing against the banks to expect the unexpected.

好奇心的科学研究

The Scientific Study of Curiosity

现在我们已经阐明了好奇心与科学的关系，接下来我们来探讨科学与好奇心的关系。假设我们对好奇心感到好奇。好奇心是什么？它的组成部分是什么和过程？我们如何选择分析单位或探究尺度？我们应该使用什么测量仪器？我们如何制定模型？我们如何构建和完善初始假设？我们希望写出什么句子，我们如何绘制它？在提出和寻求这些问题的答案时，科学家往往受到不同目标的驱使。一些科学家最受功利主义价值观的驱使。先前的研究将好奇心与幸福和创新联系起来——这两种现象在许多文化和社会中都很受欢迎。好奇心与繁荣和身体活动相关，与抑郁呈负相关。22此外，好奇的人往往是创新的人，他们有能力通过想象不同的未来来改变世界。23如果我们了解好奇心是什么，我们是否可以更好地支持甚至增强它？其他科学家最受他们自己的求知欲望的驱使，完全不受任何功利性的驱使，弗莱克斯纳如此雄辩地将其描述为“不受约束的人类精神的表达”。24也许我们希望了解好奇心只是因为它很好奇。这很奇怪，令人困惑，也令人费解。我们疑惑地抬起头。我们面前的这个奇怪的东西是什么？

Now that we have unpacked how curiosity is relevant for science, we turn to the question of how science is relevant for curiosity. Suppose we are curious about curiosity. What is curiosity? What are its component parts and processes? How do we choose a unit of analysis or scale of inquiry? What measurement apparatus should we use? How could we formulate the model? How could we construct and refine an initial hypothesis? What sentence do we wish to write and how do we diagram it? In posing and seeking answers to these questions, scientists are often driven by distinct goals. Some scientists are most compelled by utilitarian values. Prior work has linked curiosity to happiness and innovation—two phenomena that are highly desirable in many cultures and societies. Curiosity is correlated with flourishing and physical activity, and is anticorrelated with depression.22 Moreover, curious people are often innovative people who have the capacity to be world changers by imagining a different future.23 Were we to understand what curiosity is, might we better support or even enhance it? Other scientists are most compelled by their own desire to know, fully independent from any utility, which Flexner so eloquently described as the “expression of the untrammeled human spirit.”24 Perhaps we wish to understand curiosity simply because it is curious. It is strange, puzzling, and mystifying. We cock our head in a quizzical stare. What is this oddity before us?

现代科学对好奇心的研究始于心理学领域。在这一学科中，从业者会注意人类和非人类生物的生理和心理行为，并试图理解它们。人们通常认为，一种体现好奇心的行为就是将物品收集到所谓的“珍奇柜”中。以奥勒·沃姆（Ole Worm）为例，他有时也会使用这个名字的拉丁语形式，即奥劳斯·沃米乌斯（Olaus Wormius）。沃姆是 17 世纪早期哥本哈根的一位自然哲学家，他在一个名为“沃米博物馆”的地方收集稀有矿物、植物、动物和文物，并为其内容编写了一本名为《沃米博物馆》的四册目录，这是一本描述和推测的汇编。是什么促使奥勒收集、编目和策划这些物品？

The modern scientific study of curiosity began in earnest in the field of psychology. In this discipline, practitioners notice the physical and mental behaviors of human and nonhuman organisms, and seek to understand them. One particular behavior that is often thought to epitomize curiosity is the collection of items in a so-called cabinet of curiosities. Consider Ole Worm, or the Latinized form of his name that he was known to use on occasion, Olaus Wormius. A natural philosopher in Copenhagen in the early 1600s, Worm collected rare minerals, plants, animals, and artifacts in a space he called the Museum Wormianum, and he wrote a four-book catalog called the Museum Wormianum for its contents, a compendium of descriptions and speculations. What induced Ole to collect, to catalog, and to curate?

可以说，是好奇心。但为了更深入地探究，也许我们可以问这样一个问题：是什么精神或实体驱使他创建了沃尔米亚努姆博物馆？25让我们首先假设原因在于身体内部——也许是他的心脏、他的脚、他的手或他的头脑。没错，他的心脏让他活了下来，但并没有特别地驱动他的好奇心。他的脚更有希望：他们把他的身体带到任何给定的文物前。他的手从地面、壁架或他人的手中拿起文物。他的头脑渴望知道文物的意义或用途。但哪一个更接近好奇心？在时间优先链中，求知欲先于行走的双脚，而行走的双脚又先于抓握的手。所以在某种意义上，求知欲是这一连串事件中的第一个原因。头脑似乎是源头。

Arguably, curiosity. But to press deeper, perhaps we could ask the question, What spirit or entity drove him to create the Museum Wormianum?25 Let us begin by assuming that the cause lies within the body—perhaps in his heart, his feet, his hands, or his mind. True, his heart allowed him to live but did not specifically drive his curiosity. His feet are more promising: they walked his body to any given artifact. His hands picked up the artifact from the ground or ledge or another’s hand. His mind desired to know the meaning or use of the artifact. But which is more proximal to curiosity? In the chain of temporal precedence, the desire to know predated the walking feet, which in turn predated the grasping hand. So in some sense, the desire to know is the first cause in this chain of events. The mind appears to be the source.

当我们好奇时，大脑中会发生什么？大脑中的好奇心是什么？我们如何解析大脑中好奇的元素？哲学家戈特弗里德·威廉·莱布尼茨在其《走向普遍特征》（1677 年）中寻求人类思想的字母表：“必须发明……一种人类思想的字母表，通过字母的连接和对由字母组成的单词的分析，可以发现和判断其他一切。” 26 20 世纪中期，英国心理学家丹尼尔·伯林 (Daniel Berlyne) 试图提炼这样一种字母表——不是为所有思想，而是为好奇的思想。首先，他注意到字母表中没有表示信息效用的字母。他写道：“许多激发最执着地寻找答案，并在得不到答案时感到最苦恼的问题，并没有明显的实际价值或紧迫性。” 27人类很好奇他们寻求的信息是否对他们有用。如果不是效用驱动好奇心，那是什么呢？伯林 (Berlyne) 提出了感知好奇心作为另一种选择，并将其定义为一种由新奇刺激 (看！quaflet！) 引起的驱动力，并因持续接触这些刺激而减弱 (哦不，不是另一个 quaflet？::打哈欠::)。

What happens in the mind when we are curious? What is curiosity in the mind? How can we unpack the mind’s curious elements? With philosopher Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, in his “Towards a Universal Characteristic” (1677), we seek an alphabet of human thoughts: “There must be invented . . . a kind of alphabet of human thoughts, and through the connection of its letters and the analysis of words which are composed out of them, everything else can be discovered and judged.”26 In the mid-1900s, Daniel Berlyne, a British psychologist, sought to distill such an alphabet—not for all of thought, but for curious thought. First, he noted that the alphabet did not contain a letter for informational utility. He wrote, “Many of the queries that inspire the most persistent searches for answers and the greatest distress when answers are not forthcoming are of no manifest practical value or urgency.”27 Humans were curious whether or not the information they sought was useful to them. If utility was not driving curiosity, then what was? Berlyne offered perceptual curiosity as an alternative and defined it as a drive that is aroused by novel stimuli (Look! A quaflet!) and reduced by continued exposure to these stimuli (Oh no, not another quaflet? ::yawn::).

Berlyne 进一步将感知好奇心与认知好奇心进行了对比，他将认知好奇心定义为一种可通过接收和随后复述知识而减少的驱动力（什么？quaflet 是一种腿细长、蚊蚋大小的昆虫，形状像维京人的饮水角，最著名的是将一滴存在主义实现的液滴（广泛的自我启示）释放到毫无戒心的白日梦者的左眼内角？::转向朋友:: Becket，Loren，你们知道 quaflet 是一种……吗）。感知好奇心可能是许多非人类动物的特征，而认知好奇心被认为主要为人类保留。Berlyne进一步区分了特定好奇心和分散好奇心；前者指的是对某一特定信息的渴望（quaflets 会在怀疑做白日梦的人的右眼外角释放什么？），而后者指的是对任何信息的渴望（告诉我关于 quaflets 的事，做吧！）。特定好奇心和分散好奇心之间的区别让人想起弗吉尼亚·伍尔夫对热爱学习的人和热爱阅读的人的描述：前者“通过书籍寻找他所热衷的某些特定的真理”，而后者仅仅体现了“对纯粹和无私阅读的人文热情”。28 认识论到感知、特定论到分散这两个轴线共同构成了一个二维平面，每个不同的象限描述了人类广泛的探索行为。

Berlyne further contrasted perceptual curiosity with epistemic curiosity, which he defined as a drive reducible by the reception and subsequent rehearsal of knowledge (What? A quaflet is a spindly legged, gnat-sized insect shaped like a Viking drinking horn, most well-known for releasing a liquid drop of existential realization—of expansive self-revelation—into the inner corner of the left eye of unsuspecting daydreamers? ::turning to friends:: Becket, Loren, did you know that a quaflet is a . . .). Whereas perceptual curiosity might be characteristic of many nonhuman animals, epistemic curiosity was thought to be largely reserved for humans. Berlyne further distinguished specific from diversive curiosity; the first referring to a desire for a particular piece of information (What do quaflets release into the outer corner of the right eye of suspecting daydreamers?) and the latter referring to a desire for any information (Tell me about quaflets, do!). The distinction between specific and diversive curiosity is reminiscent of Virginia Woolf’s account of the person who loves learning versus the person who loves reading: the former “searches through books to discover some particular grain of truth upon which he has set his heart,” whereas the latter simply manifests the “humane passion for pure and disinterested reading.”28 The two axes of epistemic to perceptual and specific to diversive together form a two-dimensional plane, with each distinct quadrant describing a wide range of exploratory behaviors in humans.

在不同驱动力的背景下，伯林勾勒出好奇心思维中的事件顺序：字母表中的字母组合成单词，或词性组合成句子。他遵循美国心理学家和行为学家 BF Skinner 的观点，认为该顺序应该从主题探测开始，主题探测是任何引发一系列想法而不是单一想法的刺激。主题探测本身可以分为两部分：提示刺激，提供起点；动机刺激，将后续想法限制在知识空间的相关部分，同时激发人类的反应。问题是典型的主题探测，包含提示刺激和动机刺激。考虑这个问题，“为什么一丛沙丘草（上面放着一个四叶草）被沙地上的凹坑包围，凹坑的半径与草的中心相等，就像一根手指在它周围画了一个圆圈？”提示刺激是一丛沙丘草，周围是沙坑。动机刺激是短语“为什么”，它将思路限制在“为什么”概念上，并激发回答问题的动机。问题限制了随后的思维空间，这一事实与以下观点一致：存在一些条件，这些条件决定了“为什么”问题的有用答案和无用答案。29或者考虑这个问题，“风如何在沙中画一个圆圈？”提示刺激是风在沙中画一个圆圈，动机刺激是短语“如何”，它将思路限制在概念上，并驱使人类推断风吹弯了沙丘草，并将它们吹得四处乱飞，就像手指在沙子上画一个圆圈一样。30

On the backdrop of distinct drives, Berlyne sketched out the sequence of events in the thought-line of curiosity: the letters of the alphabet that together form the word or the parts of speech that together diagram the sentence. Following US psychologist and behaviorist B. F. Skinner, he reasoned that the sequence should begin with a thematic probe, which is any stimulus that elicits not a single thought but rather a train of them. The thematic probe itself can be broken down into two parts: a cue stimulus, which supplies the starting point, and a motivational stimulus, which limits the subsequent thoughts to the relevant portion of knowledge space and simultaneously motivates the human’s response. Questions are quintessential thematic probes, containing both cue and motivational stimuli. Consider the question, “Why is a clump of dune grass—on which a quaflet rests—surrounded by an indentation in the sand at a fixed radius from the grass’s center, as if a finger had drawn a circle around it?” The cue stimulus is a clump of dune grass surrounded by an indentation in the sand. The motivational stimulus is the phrase “why is,” which limits the train of thought to why concepts and evokes a motivation to answer the question. The fact that the question limits the ensuing thought space is consistent with the notion that there exist conditions that define the useful versus not useful answers to why questions.29 Or consider the question, “How does wind draw a circle in the sand?” The cue stimulus is wind drawing a circle in the sand and the motivational stimulus is the phrase “how does,” which limits the train of thought to how concepts, and drives the human to infer that the wind has bent the dune grasses and swept them around such that they act like fingers drawing a circle in the sand.30

为什么动机刺激会激励人？为什么主题探索会引发好奇心？为什么我们会继续思考？终点线是否有值得的东西在等待我们继续前进？终点是否已经到达，美丽是否已经完美？考虑到好奇心的特质，似乎即使彩虹尽头有宝藏在等待，它也不会像一罐金子一样被每个人都珍视。虽然四分卫激励了莱尔，沙丘草激励了索菲，但两者都没有点燃艾拉的火花。在 20 世纪 90 年代的一篇开创性理论论文中，美国教育家兼经济学家乔治·洛文斯坦 (George Loewenstein) 指出，人们寻求的信息似乎实际上没有特别的价值：“好奇心提出的理论难题是，为什么人们如此强烈地被信息所吸引，而根据好奇心的定义，这些信息不会带来任何外在的好处。” 31但是如果没有好处，为什么还要好奇呢？为了解决这个难题，洛文斯坦提出了所谓的“信息差距理论”。该理论解释了特殊的好奇心，这种好奇心既具体（寻求特定的信息），又具有认知性（寻求知识而非感知的信息）。洛文斯坦认为，人们已知的信息和想要知道的信息之间存在信息差距。好奇心的强度决定了人们缩小信息差距的能力，从而解决了不确定性问题。我们最终得到的就是我们一直在寻找的：确定性。完美的美是知识的结晶。因此，获得的信息的价值在于其潜力（而不是其现实性），在于它使之成为可能；它打开了理解之门。有价值的是拼图块可以填补空白。要填补这一空白，拼图块不必由黄金、蓝锥矿、黑蛋白石或海纹石制成。它必须具有正确的形状，才能从不确定性中得出确定性。

Why is a motivational stimulus motivating? Why does a thematic probe induce curious thought? Why do we follow the thought forward? Is there something rewarding waiting at the finish line that drives us tramping onward? Is an end reached or a beauty perfected? In considering the idiosyncrasies of curious thought, it seems that even if there is a treasure waiting at the end of the rainbow, it does not appear to be something like a pot of gold that everyone would value. While the quaflet drives Lyle, the dune grass motivates Sophie, and neither ignites a spark for Ira. In a seminal theory paper in the 1990s, US educator and economist George Loewenstein noted that the information people seek appears in fact to have no particular value: “The theoretical puzzle posed by curiosity is why people are so strongly attracted to information that, by the definition of curiosity, confers no extrinsic benefit.”31 But if there is no benefit, why be curious? To solve this puzzle, Loewenstein developed what he called the information gap theory. This theory offers an explanation of idiosyncratic curiosity that is both specific (seeking a particular piece of information) and epistemic (seeking information that is of knowledge rather than of perception). Loewenstein claims that the information gap exists between what one knows and what one wants to know. Then the intensity of curiosity for a piece of information tracks its ability to close the information gap, thereby resolving uncertainty. The end we reach is what we have been seeking all along: certainty. The beauty perfected is the crystallization of knowledge. Thus the information obtained is valuable in its potentiality (as opposed to its actuality), in what it makes possible; it opens the door to understanding. What is valuable is that the puzzle piece fits into the gaping empty spot. To fill that function, the puzzle piece need not be made of gold or benitoite, black opal or larimar. It must simply have the right shape to draw certainty from uncertainty.

有了伯林、洛文斯坦和其他许多人的理论，好奇的科学家现在已经准备好在他们和世界之间放置一个测量仪器，并使用由此产生的测量结果评估理论。心理学实验室中使用的一种特别常见的测量仪器是量表。32量表是一组为测量明确定义的结构或想法而开发的问题。在使用前，通常会评估量表的有效性和可靠性，并反复改进，直到有效性和可靠性达到科学界接受的某些水平。33例如，人们可以选择好奇心的定义，然后开发一组问题来测量这种好奇心：

With theory in hand from Berlyne, Loewenstein, and many others, the inquisitive scientist is now ready to place a measurement apparatus between themselves and the world, and to use the resultant measurements to evaluate the theory. One particularly common measurement apparatus used in the psychology laboratory is called a scale.32 A scale is a set of questions developed to measure a well-defined construct or idea. Before use, the scale is typically evaluated for validity and reliability, and iteratively refined until the validity and reliability reach certain levels accepted by the scientific community.33 For example, one can choose a definition for curiosity and then develop a set of questions to measure that kind of curiosity:

  • 对于以下每个陈述，请选择非常同意、同意、中立、不同意或非常不同意。
  • For each of the following statements, choose strongly agree, agree, neutral, disagree, or strongly disagree.
  • 1. 我喜欢学习不熟悉的科目。
  • 1. I enjoy learning about subjects that are unfamiliar.
  • 2. 当我遇到一个未完成的谜题时，我会想象最终的解决方案。
  • 2. When I come upon an incomplete puzzle, I imagine the final solution.
  • 3. 我对同一个问题思考过很多不同的答案。
  • 3. I think about many different answers to the same question.

有效问题是那些探究好奇心而不是其他概念（如爱书、活泼或夸夸其谈）的问题，而可靠问题是那些人们每天都会以同样的方式回答的问题，从而了解他们的性格特征。34志愿者对每个问题做出回答后，答案将被编码并汇总为一个分数，代表志愿者个人的好奇心水平，是高、低还是中等。35该量表还可用于评估支持好奇心理论的证据（定义由此而来），包括该理论的准确性和简约性的证据。例如，为了评估 Berlyne 将好奇心沿两个主要维度（认识-感知和特定-发散）分开的理论，可以首先为每个维度创建一个量表，然后评估这两个量表是否比一组相互竞争的维度更好地解释了人类在现实世界中观察到的一系列好奇行为。为了评估 Loewenstein 的信息差距理论，人们可以制定一个量表来衡量人们已知的信息与人们想要知道的信息之间的差距，并评估该差距与人们为填补该差距而表现出的好奇心程度之间的关系。

Valid questions are those that probe curiosity rather than some other construct (e.g., bibliophilia, bubbliness, or bombastry) and reliable questions are those that a person will answer the same way each day, thus accessing a trait of their personality.34 After a volunteer marks their responses to each question, the responses are coded and summarized into a score representing the volunteer’s personal level of curiosity, whether high, low, or middling.35 The scale can also be used to assess evidence in favor of the theory of curiosity from which the definition arose, including evidence for the theory’s accuracy and parsimony. To evaluate Berlyne’s theory separating curiosity along two main dimensions (epistemic-perceptual and specific-diversive), for example, one could begin by creating one scale for each dimension and then one could assess whether those two scales better explained the range of real-world curious behavior observed in humans than a competing set of dimensions. To evaluate Loewenstein’s information gap theory, one could develop a scale to measure the gap that exists between what one knows and what one wants to know, and evaluate the relation between that gap and the degree of curiosity a person manifests to fill the gap.

这是关于好奇心的心理科学：它需要将理论具体化，将理论具体化为可测量的单位和过程，并开发工具（如量表）来测量这些单位和过程以提供支持或反驳该理论的证据。

This is the psychological science of curiosity: it requires the crystallization of a theory, a concretization of that theory into measurable units and processes, and the development of instruments (such as scales) to measure those units and processes to provide evidence in favor of—or that contradicts—the theory.

思想还是大脑？

Mind or Brain?

让我们回到 17 世纪哥本哈根的 Ole Worm 和他的 Wormianum 博物馆。之前我们问过他好奇行为的最初原因。我们搁置了他的脚和手，最后落在了他的头脑上，这促使我们涉足心理科学。重新提出这个问题，我们现在可以问我们是否对我们的初步答案感到满意。可以说，Ole Worm 的求知欲促使他走向文物，随后促使他捡起文物并将其带回他的珍奇柜。求知欲据说是在头脑中产生的，这也是事实。但头脑能成为求知欲的原因吗？

Let us return to Ole Worm and his Museum Wormianum in Copenhagen in the 1600s. Earlier we had asked about the first cause of his curious actions. We shelved his feet and hands, and landed on his mind, which motivated our foray into psychological science. Resurrecting the question, we can now ask whether we are satisfied with our initial answer. It is arguably true that Ole Worm’s desire to know led him to walk toward the artifact and subsequently led him to pick up the artifact to bring it back to his cabinet of curiosities. It is also true that the desire to know is said to arise in the mind. But can the mind be the cause of the desire to know?

要回答这个问题，让我们更深入地思考一下原因的含义。可以定义几种不同类型的原因，但以下原因对于我们的研究特别有用。让我们考虑一个在时间和空间上与结果相关的原因。36在这里，原因和结果是时间相关的，因为结果不能发生在原因之前，而原因也不能发生在结果之后。同样，原因和结果是空间相关的，因为原因位于空间的某个地方，它通过空间产生影响。quaflet 是白日梦者存在实现的原因，因为它的波特色液体首先从它的身体上滴落，然后在空中移动，最后落在左眼内角，做化学物质的作用。通过其在时间和空间上与结果的连续性来定义原因是直观的。当我们有目的地在我们的世界中引起某事（或感知到某事被引起）时，我们会观察到结果发生在原因之后，并且我们观察到因果关系是由空间介导的。此外，我们的经验告诉我们，在更早的时间和更不同的空间中发生的事件无法可靠地证明产生了我们现在观察到的效果；在此期间和在平均空间中可能存在许多其他原因和结果。有了这个原因概念，我们就可以回到心灵和原因的关系上。

To answer this question, let’s think a bit harder about what cause means. Several distinct types of cause can be fruitfully defined, but a particularly useful one for our investigation here is the following. Let us consider a cause that is defined in temporal and spatial relation to an effect.36 Here, cause and effect are related temporally because an effect cannot occur before its cause, and a cause cannot occur after its effect. Similarly, cause and effect are related spatially because the cause is located somewhere in space, and it works through space to create an effect. The quaflet is the cause of the daydreamer’s existential realization because its porter-colored liquid first drops from its body, then moves through the air, and finally lands in the inner corner of the left eye to do what chemicals do. Defining a cause by its temporal and spatial contiguity to the effect is intuitive. When we purposefully cause something in our world (or perceive something to be caused), we observe that the effect occurs after the cause, and we observe that the relation between cause and effect is mediated by space. Moreover, our experience tells us that an event happening at some much earlier time and in a much different space cannot reliably be proven to have produced the effect we observe here and now; it is possible that many other causes and effects have intervened in the meantime, and in the meanspace. With this notion of cause in hand, we can return to the relation between mind and cause.

心灵是否有物理位置？心灵能否利用嵌入在时间和空间中的物理过程来引发好奇心的行为和运动？求知欲是否有物理位置？单一想法是否有物理位置？这些问题将我们引向心灵的物理基础：大脑。作为一种器官，大脑是一种组织，其中单个神经事件具有精确的物理位置。大脑使用电信号（嵌入在时间和空间中的物理过程）来驱动各种影响，例如我们人类通常归因于好奇心的行为。如果我们要寻找好奇心的首要原因，我们是否应该考虑大脑？奥勒·沃姆博物馆的大脑原因可能是什么？也许大脑中有一个好奇心区域，它会沿着一束神经元轴突向大脑的运动区域发送电信号。运动区域反过来通过外周神经系统向脚发送电信号，诱导它们走向惊奇的对象。随后发生的眼足协调有点像周围神经系统和中枢神经系统之间的乒乓球，以及视觉皮层（为眼睛提供信息）和运动皮层（注视脚）之间的乒乓球。类似的运动信号引导手抓握，随后从受试者获得的视觉、听觉、触觉和认知信息满足了好奇的冲动，填补了知识的空白。这就是一切的运作方式吗？

Does the mind have a physical location, and can it use physical processes, embedded in time and space, to cause the actions and movements of curiosity? Does the desire to know have a physical location? Does a single thought have a physical location? These questions drive us to the physical substrate of the mind: the brain. As an organ, the brain is a tissue, within which individual neural events have a precise physical location. The brain employs electrical signals, which are physical processes embedded in time and space, to drive a wide range of effects such as those behaviors that we as humans commonly attribute to curiosity. If we are seeking the first cause of curiosity, might it behoove us to consider the brain? What might a brain cause of Ole Worm’s museum be? Perhaps there is a curiosity area in the brain, and it sends an electrical signal along a bundle of neuronal axons to the motor area of the brain. The motor area in turn sends an electrical signal through the peripheral nervous system to the feet, inducing them to walk toward the subject of wonderment. The ensuing eye-foot coordination is a bit of a ping-pong between the peripheral nervous system and the central nervous system, and between the visual cortex (feeding the eye) and the motor cortex (eyeing the feet). A similar motoric signal guides the hand to grasp, and the subsequent visual, auditory, tactile, and epistemic information gained from the subject satiates the curious impulse, filling the gap in knowledge. Is this how it all works?

好奇心的神经科学

The Neuroscience of Curiosity

由于缺乏背景知识，我们直到 20 世纪后期才开始回答这些问题，当时世界上第一批神经科学系刚刚成立。神经科学是一门研究神经系统的科学，是一门令人惊讶的年轻学科。该学科的学者们试图识别和理解服务于存在和行为的神经过程。在好奇心的背景下，他们旨在识别解释寻求信息行为的区域、区域间连接和信息过程。37常用工具测量 (1) 解剖学，以形态（或形状）、组织特征、细胞结构（或组织中细胞的排列）和连接不同皮质部分的物理束分布的形式来测量；以及 (2) 生理学，以含氧血流、电磁场和电流的形式来测量。这些工具，就像心理学中的量表一样，可用于减轻我们有偏见的人类感官的局限性，并使用归纳推理方法评估支持假设的证据。让我们设想这样一个过程。

Contextual ignorance held us back from answering many of these questions until the latter half of the 1900s, around the time when the first neuroscience departments in the world were being founded. A surprisingly young discipline, neuroscience is the science of the nervous system. Scholars in this discipline seek to identify and understand the neural processes subserving being and behavior. In the context of curiosity, they aim to identify the areas, interareal connections, and informational processes that explain the behavior of seeking information.37 Common instruments measure (1) anatomy, in the form of morphology (or shape), tissue characteristics, cytoarchitecture (or the arrangement of cells in a tissue), and the distribution of physical tracts linking different bits of cortex, and (2) physiology, in the form of oxygenated blood flow, electromagnetic fields, and electrical currents. Those instruments, like the scales in psychology, can be used to mitigate the limitations of our biased human senses and to evaluate the evidence in favor of a hypothesis, using the methods of inductive inference. Let’s envision such a process.

神经科学能提供什么证据来证明大脑是好奇心的有用的“第一因”？理想情况下，为了收集完整因果链的精确证据，我们会同时全面测量大脑（中枢神经系统）的神经活动和身体（周围神经系统）的神经活动。这种同时完整的测量让我们能够以空间和时间的连续性观察大脑某一部分的活动如何导致大脑另一部分的活动，并通过脊髓推动身体移动。以我们目前的神经成像技术无法进行这种全面测量，如果好奇的人可以走动，甚至无法测量单个大脑区域。事实上，即使一个人一动不动，我们仍然无法直接测量单个大脑区域的活动；典型的研究是当一个人躺在磁共振成像（MRI）扫描仪内时间接测量含氧血流量。如果无法获得完整的因果链，我们可能会寻找相关链（A 与 B 相关，B 与 C 相关）；关联链可以与因果链相一致（但不能证明因果链的有效性）。在关联链的第一步中，我们可能发现大脑特定区域（我们的“好奇心区域”）的活动 (A) 与认知状态 (B) 相关，例如求知欲。在关联链的第二步中，我们可能发现认知状态 (B) 又与寻找信息的行为 (C) 相关，例如走向一件物品并弯腰捡起它。然后，我们可以测试神经活动 (A) 是否与寻找信息的行为 (C) 相关。从神经活动到认知状态再到行为的关联链可以提供支持好奇心因果链的证据，其中大脑是第一原因。

What evidence could neuroscience offer for the claim that the brain is a useful “first cause” of curiosity? Ideally, to gather precise evidence for a complete causal chain, we would fully and simultaneously measure neural activity in the brain (the central nervous system) and neural activity in the body (the peripheral nervous system). That simultaneous and complete measurement would allow us to watch—with spatial and temporal contiguity—how the activity in one part of the brain might lead to activity in another part of the brain and down through the spinal cord to move the body. This kind of full measurement is not possible with our current neuroimaging technologies, nor is the measurement of even a single brain region if the curious individual is ambulatory. In fact, even if a person is motionless, we still have no way to directly measure the activity of a single brain region; typical studies make indirect measurements of oxygenated blood flow as a person is lying down inside a magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scanner. Without access to a full casual chain, we might instead seek a correlative chain (A is correlated with B, which is correlated with C); correlative chains can be consistent with (but not proof of) a causal chain. In the first step of the chain, perhaps we find that activity (A) in a specific area of the brain (our “curiosity area”) is correlated with a cognitive state (B), such as the desire to know. In the second step of the chain, perhaps we find that a cognitive state (B) is in turn correlated with actions to seek information (C), such as walking toward an artifact and stooping to pick it up. Then we can test whether the neural activity (A) is correlated with actions to seek information (C). The correlative chain from neural activity to a cognitive state to an action can provide evidence in favor of a causal chain of curiosity in which the brain is the first cause.

我们如何选择合适的神经活动测量方法？我们可以通过识别和分离分析单位（主语）、相关过程（动词）和其他相关变量（介词、形容词和副词）来绘制句子图。通过绘制句子图，我们的目标是使用语言制定假设，并使用数学设计方程，以确保单位可测量、模型准确且模型简约。重要的是，评估模型的准确性可以指导我们做出有用的神经测量选择。如果在三个候选好奇心区域 X、Y 和 Z 中，只有一个区域的活动与寻求信息的行为密切相关，那么我们会选择该区域并忽略其他区域。同样，评估模型的简约性可以指导我们做出有用的神经测量选择。由三个区域的活动组成的模型（在积分和导数的某种美食数学汤中）不如由一个区域的活动组成的模型（在减法的简单三明治中）简约；如果两个模型同样准确，那么我们选择单区域模型。

How do we choose an appropriate measurement of neural activity? We can diagram the sentence by identifying and separating out the unit of analysis (subject), associated processes (verb), and other relevant variables (prepositions, adjectives, and adverbs). By diagramming the sentence, our goal is to formulate a hypothesis using language, and to devise an equation using mathematics, in such a way as to ensure that the units are measurable, the model is accurate, and the model is parsimonious. Importantly, assessing the model’s accuracy can guide us toward a useful choice for the neural measure. If of three candidate curiosity areas X, Y, and Z, only one’s activity is strongly correlated with actions to seek information, then we choose that one and ignore the others. Similarly, assessing the model’s parsimony can guide us toward a useful choice for the neural measure. A model made from the activity of three areas, in some gourmet mathematical soup of integrals and derivatives, is less parsimonious than a model built from the activity of one area, in a simple sandwich of subtraction; if both models are equally accurate, then we choose the one-area model.

在这个过程中，我们对好奇心的好奇心会引发我们最初的探索，然后大自然会用指引性的话语回应我们的呼唤，我们会发现哪些模型很合适以及原因。我们与大自然的关系有点像读者与作者的关系。我们试图阅读大自然写的书。在履行我们在这种关系中的角色时，我们听从了伍尔夫的告诫：“不要指挥你的作者；试着成为他。做他的同事和帮凶。” 38毕竟，当我们常常甚至不懂大自然的语言时，我们怎么能指挥大自然呢？但作为大自然的帮凶，我们的词汇量增加了，我们对语法和句法的理解也加深了。我们的句子的节奏——从模糊的河流变成精确的树木——越来越接近大自然所写的节奏；我们通过与自然世界交流（而不是征服）来重塑、修改和改革我们的模型。

As we move through this process, our curiosity about curiosity calls out an initial inquiry, and then Nature answers our call with guiding words as we see which models fit well and why. Our relationship with Nature feels a bit like the relationship between a reader and an author. We attempt to read the book that Nature has written. In fulfilling our role in the relationship, we heed Woolf’s admonition, “Do not dictate to your author; try to become him. Be his fellow worker and accomplice.”38 After all, how could we dictate to Nature when we often do not even know her language? But in being Nature’s accomplice, our vocabulary grows, and our understanding of grammar and syntax deepens. And the cadence of our sentences—as they transform from vague river to precise tree—inch closer and closer to those that Nature has written; we reshape, revise, and reform our models by working in communion with (not conquest over) the natural world.

通过此类实验，神经科学家发现了支持好奇行为的两种神经回路：奖励回路和认知控制回路。39奖励回路和相关动机区域横跨大脑皮层（主要位于大脑外部）和皮层下（主要位于大脑内部）。40该回路在好奇的搜索和采样过程中活跃，部分反映了获取新信息的动机、对奖励的期望以及获得新信息时的奖励感。41相反，认知控制回路支持目标导向认知，包含主要位于皮质中的大脑区域，控制搜索和采样的时间和性质。42有证据表明，内侧额极皮质特别支持无方向的探索，内侧额极皮质监测认知资源是否应保持朝向当前目标或重新定向至其他目标。43外侧额极皮质与定向探索有关，监测多个目标以进行维持或重新定向。后前额皮质与已获得知识的利用有关，实施认知控制以优化当前目标的表现。奖励和认知控制回路共同制定与寻求和获取信息相关的过程。

Using experiments of this flavor, neuroscientists have identified two neural circuits that support curious behavior: the reward circuit and the cognitive control circuit.39 The reward circuit and associated motivation areas span the cortex, which is largely located in the brain’s exterior, and the subcortex, which is largely located in the brain’s interior.40 This circuit is active during curious search and sampling, and partially reflects the motivation to obtain novel information, the expectation of reward, and the feeling of reward when that novel information is obtained.41 In contrast, the cognitive control circuit supports goal-directed cognition, and contains brain areas largely located in the cortex that control the timing and nature of both search and sampling.42 Evidence suggests that undirected exploration is particularly well supported by the medial frontopolar cortex, which monitors whether cognitive resources should be maintained toward the current goal or redirected toward others.43 The lateral frontopolar cortex is implicated in directed exploration, monitoring several goals for maintenance or redirection. The posterior prefrontal cortex is associated with the exploitation of acquired knowledge, implementing cognitive control to optimize the performance of the current goal. Together the reward and cognitive control circuits enact processes associated with seeking and acquiring information.

在探究好奇心的神经基础时，仍存在两个关键挑战。首先，在确定与特定行为相关的神经活动与了解这种关联的如何或为什么之间仍然存在差距。后者很难获得。其次，这些相同的回路似乎支持在人类中观察到的许多其他（非好奇）行为。因此，需要努力微调模型，反复评估模型的准确性和简约性。44这些挑战确保了好奇心的神经科学是一个探究子领域，并将在未来继续激励学者。

In the pursuit of the neural underpinnings of curiosity, two key challenges remain. First, there remains a gap between locating the neural activity associated with specific behaviors and understanding the how or why of that association. Obtaining the latter is difficult. Second, these same circuits appear to support many other (noncurious) behaviors observed in humans. Hence work is needed to fine-tune the model, iteratively assessing model accuracy and parsimony.44 These challenges ensure that the neuroscience of curiosity is a subfield of inquiry that will continue to motivate scholars well into the future.

* * *

* * *

在我们结束对科学的好奇心和好奇心的科学的探索时，值得指出的是一些局限性和悬而未决的问题。虽然神经行为学、行为科学和非人类动物研究方面存在互补的努力，但在这里我们专注于人类好奇心的心理学和神经科学，重点是心理测量量表和 fMRI 研究。在这种背景下，好奇心的心理科学的一个关键困难是，量表征求的自我报告可能会受到人们对他们认为是的特质的看法的影响好奇心在社会和文化中的价值。正如 Loewenstein 所说，“询问人们的好奇心程度（以及好奇心量表中包含的大多数其他项目）可以让受试者清楚地了解量表的目的。当一个人测量一种被广泛认为是社会所期望的特质时，这是一个严重的缺陷。” 45人类对量表的反应可以反映他们对好奇心目前是一种社会期望特征的看法，而不是对自己诚实。有人可能会说，神经科学更客观，因为它不依赖于自我报告，因此应该较少受到个人看法的影响。神经科学还具有物理定位单元的优势，例如神经元和大脑区域，以及信息通道和排水管的物理网络，例如神经元之间的突触或大脑区域之间的白质束。46当然，大脑的物理性与因果关系在时间和空间上连续的常见科学概念一致。但神经科学相对于心理学的优势被其劣势所抵消。我们可以测量神经活动，但我们是否更接近思考？我们可以追踪电流的流动，但我们是否更接近求知的欲望？当我们把大脑握在手中时，思维就在我们上方咯咯笑着。

As we close this jaunt into the curiosity of science and the science of curiosity, it is worth pointing out several limitations and open questions. While complementary efforts exist in neuroethology, behavioral science, and nonhuman animal research, here we have focused on the psychology and neuroscience of human curiosity, with an emphasis on psychometric scales and fMRI studies. Against that backdrop, a key difficulty in the psychological science of curiosity is the fact that the self-reports solicited by scales can be clouded by the person’s perceptions of the traits that they think are valuable in their society and culture. As Loewenstein put it, “Asking people how curious they are (and most of the other items included in curiosity scales) makes the purpose of the scale obvious to subjects. This is a serious deficiency when one is measuring a trait that is widely recognized as socially desirable.”45 Humans can respond to a scale in a way that reflects their perception that curiosity is currently a socially desirable characteristic rather than in a way that is truthful to their own selves. One could argue that neuroscience is more objective in that it does not rely on self-reports and thus should be less influenced by the person’s perceptions. Neuroscience also has the benefit of having physically located units, such as neurons and brain areas, and a physical network of informational tunnels and drains, such as synapses between neurons or white matter tracts between brain areas.46 And of course, the physicality of the brain is consistent with common scientific notions of cause and effect being temporally and spatially contiguous. But the advantages of neuroscience over psychology are balanced by its disadvantages. While we can measure neural activity, are we any closer to thought? While we can track the flow of electrical current, are we any closer to the desire to know? While we hold the brain in our hands, the mind hovers above us chuckling.

除了心理学和神经科学的学科局限性之外，最近和当前的从业者都表达了一些相当普遍的存在担忧。例如，洛文斯坦对能够定义好奇心的原因感到绝望：“剩下的问题——好奇心的原因——本质上是无法回答的。” 47同样，大脑学者有些激进地认为“阻碍我们理解的一个因素是过于关注什么是好奇心，什么不是好奇心。” 48换句话说，我们应该放弃（暂时）尝试定义兴趣现象。也许我们仍然处于报告这里奇怪的泉水和那里巨大的小牛的探索阶段，还没有准备好对句子进行图解。“我们建议定义阶段应该遵循相对稳固的好奇心特征，尽可能广泛地定义。” 49我们是否应该将自己限制在描述性特征上，而不是寻求指导性定义？但也许问题不在于好奇心的原因好奇心不可知，也不是说好奇心的定义无法实现，而是目前用来定义好奇心的学科无法应对挑战。如果我们从自然科学转向其前身——哲学，情况会怎样？对思维运作方式进行更谨慎、更有历史依据的评估，能否为好奇心提供一个全新的定义，从而指导未来科学探究其本质？50

The discipline-specific limitations of psychology and neuroscience aside, there are some quite generic existential concerns voiced by both recent and current practitioners. For example, Loewenstein despairs of ever being able to define the cause of curiosity: “The remaining question—the cause of curiosity—is inherently unanswerable.”47 In a similar ilk, scholars of the brain somewhat radically suggest that “one factor impeding our understanding has been too much focus on delineating what is and is not curiosity.”48 In other words, we should give up (for now) on attempting to define the phenomenon of interest. Perhaps instead we are still in the exploratory stages of reporting an odd spring here and a monstrous calf there, and are not yet ready for the practice of diagramming a sentence. “We recommend that the definition stage should follow a relatively solid characterization of curiosity, defined as broadly as possible.”49 Should we constrain ourselves to descriptive characterizations and not seek a guiding definition? But perhaps the problem is not that the cause of curiosity is unknowable nor that the definition of curiosity is unattainable but rather that the disciplines currently used to develop a definition are not up to the challenge. What if we were to turn from the natural sciences to their precursor, philosophy? Could a more circumspect and historically grounded assessment of the workings of the mind provide a novel definition of curiosity that could direct the future of scientific inquiry into its nature?50

2

2

好奇心作为边缘艺术

Curiosity as Edgework

奇怪的是，我们——灵魂们——站在自己领域的边缘，踮起脚尖，探向相邻的领域。

We strangely stand on,—souls do,—on the very edges of their own spheres, leaning tiptoe toward and into the adjoining sphere.

—拉尔夫·沃尔多·爱默生，《日记和杂记》，1843-1847 年

—Ralph Waldo Emerson, Journals and Miscellaneous Notebooks, 1843–1847

好奇心如果不是站在边缘并向外窥视，那又是什么呢？或者踮起脚尖去探索自己够不着的东西？对边界、边界、自己身处的泡沫感到不满。事实上，好奇心如果不是将球体边缘向彼此靠拢，以便架起桥梁、模糊和构建，那又是什么呢？最活跃的好奇心几乎不会满足于将事物弄清楚，然后将它们带回家栖息——将已确定的事物填满一个人心灵的缝隙，让它们与其他你永远不需要重新考虑的事物一起占据空间。

What is curiosity if not standing on the edge and peering out beyond it? Or leaning tiptoe toward something just beyond one’s reach? Dissatisfied with the boundary, the border, the bubble in which one finds oneself. Indeed, what is curiosity if not the edging of spheres toward one another, so as to bridge and to blur and to build? Curiosity at its liveliest is hardly satisfied with sussing things out only to bring them home to roost—lining the crevices of one’s mind with settled things and letting them take up space alongside other things one need never reconsider.

不，好奇心有一种向远方进发的倾向。它总是向前倾斜，不断地画出一条线，仿佛在世界周围伸展和移动——这个世界本身就是一个“充满边缘的世界”。1从这个意义上讲，好奇心不能仅仅是求知的需要（获得的知识会满足这种需要）或寻求信息的动机（获得的信息会满足这种动机）。相反，好奇心必须是一种延伸而广泛的本能，总是在边缘移动。事实上，还有什么比这更奇怪的呢？

No, curiosity has a penchant for striking out yonder. Pitched ever so slightly forward, it repeatedly casts a line as if stretching and inching its way around the world—a world that is itself a “teeming edge-world.”1 In this sense, curiosity cannot simply be the need to know (which would then be satisfied with knowledge gained) or the motivation to seek information (which would then be satisfied with information secured). Rather, curiosity has to be an extending and extensive instinct, always edging around. And indeed, what could be stranger?

或者至少这是我们提出的，我们有充分的理由这样做。因为尽管几千年来，好奇心在很大程度上是在知识习得的模型上被理解的，但其他概念的可能性却隐藏在同样的历史。在这里，我们从好奇心的神经科学和心理学转向好奇心的哲学。我们这样做是为了追溯习得性叙事的根源，回到它的起源，同时也是为了讲述一个不同的故事，一个关于好奇心的故事，一个关于边缘好奇心的故事。

Or at least that is what we propose, and we have good reason for doing so. For while curiosity has largely been understood on the model of epistemic acquisition for millennia, other conceptual possibilities are buried in that same history. Here we turn, then, from the neuroscience and psychology of curiosity to the philosophy of curiosity. We do so in order to trace the roots of the acquisitional narrative back to its beginnings, but also to tell a different tale, a story of curiosity in relation, of curiosity on the edge.

早在心理学使用定性和定量方法来研究好奇心作为一种心理状态或性格特征及其相应行为的科学之前，哲学就已经存在了。早在神经科学使用神经成像和数据科学来理解好奇心的神经回路和系统之前，哲学就已经存在了。事实上，经常定义好奇心的心理学和神经科学研究的信息寻求框架就源于此。从某种意义上说，哲学是原始学科，是反思世界参与的源头。因此，它常常承载着当代思想的核心。然而，在其漫长而混乱的历史中，哲学还蕴含着各种其他不同思维的可能性——这些可能性时有出现，但从未被编纂成范式或沉淀成理论；这些可能性仍然处于潜伏状态。

Long before psychology used qualitative and quantitative methods to investigate the science of curiosity as a mental state or a personality trait with corresponding behaviors, there was philosophy. And long before neuroscience used neuroimaging and data science to understand the neural circuitry and systems that precondition curiosity, there was philosophy. Indeed, the framework of information seeking that so often defines psychological and neuroscientific studies of curiosity finds its roots here. Philosophy is, in some sense, the Ur-discipline, the source point of reflective engagement with the world. As such, it frequently carries the kernels of contemporary thought. And yet across its long and messy history, philosophy also houses all kinds of other possibilities for thinking differently—possibilities that surfaced here and there, but never got codified into paradigms or sedimented into theories; possibilities that still lie dormant.

在当今的学术界，哲学是一门使用概念分析和逻辑论证来探究事物的本质、知识的本质和价值的本质的学科。好奇心哲学家自然会问，什么是好奇心？它在知识构建中的作用是什么？在什么条件下好奇心有助于或阻碍美好生活？事实上，这样的探究正在进行中。2然而，哲学不仅仅是分析和论证，它也是一门概念创造的学科。从本质上讲，它是一种不同的思考方式。除了在当前的本体论、认识论或伦理框架内探究好奇心之外，哲学还促使人们思考好奇心是如何随着时间的推移而概念化的，以及它可能会以其他方式概念化。这个术语在传统意义上的局限性是什么？它隐藏的投资是什么，经常被常识性用法或意识形态所掩盖？它有什么值得更多关注和更深入分析的地方？除了追求某些方法和研究主题之外，哲学还批判性地评估知识谱系并探索新的思考可能性。这项工作涉及解构现有概念并生成新的，不是维护普遍性，而是让思想接受无休止的更新、替换和变异过程。正如吉尔·德勒兹和菲利克斯·瓜塔里所写，“哲学是形成、发明和制造概念的艺术。” 3这种超越历史资源的发明是本章的研究课题。

In the academy today, philosophy is a discipline that uses conceptual analysis and logical argument to suss out the nature of things, the nature of knowledge, and the nature of value. Philosophers of curiosity might naturally ask then, What is curiosity? What is its role in the construction of knowledge? And under what conditions does curiosity contribute to or detract from a good life? Inquiries like these are in fact underway.2 More than analysis and argumentation, however, philosophy is also a discipline of concept creation. It is, at its core, an attempt to think differently. Beyond plumbing curiosity within current ontological, epistemological, or ethical frameworks, philosophy pushes one to ask how curiosity has been conceptualized over time and how it might be conceptualized otherwise. What are the limits of the term as it has been traditionally conceived? What are its hidden investments, so often obscured through commonsense usage or ideology? What about it deserves greater attention and closer analysis? Beyond pursuing certain methods and topics of inquiry, then, philosophy critically assesses intellectual lineages and explores new possibilities for thought. This work involves deconstructing existing concepts and generating altogether fresh ones, not safeguarding universals, but submitting ideas to the endless process of renewal, replacement, and mutation. As Gilles Deleuze and Félix Guattari write, “Philosophy is the art of forming, inventing, and fabricating concepts.”3 That invention, through and beyond historical resources, is the project of this chapter.

接下来，我们将回顾将好奇心概念化为个人求知的欲望，或者用当代科学术语来说，是获取信息或填补知识空白的驱动力这一漫长的哲学历史。我们花点时间去理解这种传统概念化所允许的东西，以及它所隐藏的东西。然后，我们转向采用一种明确的关系方法，提出了一种新的好奇心概念化，根据这一概念，好奇的动力不是知者 Y 想要了解 X 的愿望，而是一种建立联系的实践，即在 (不) 知者、(不) 知识和 (不) 已知事物的系统之间建立关系。4然后，我们回到哲学史，在过去的理论构建中挖掘这一新概念的痕迹，然后再探索它对心理学和神经科学的影响。最后，我们探讨这种戏剧性的范式转变的潜在回报。如果我们在网络命名法中将好奇心理解为构建或获取节点的个人能力，而不是边缘的能量，会怎么样？这会让什么被看到和注意到、被测试和被扰乱呢？

In what follows, we revisit the long philosophical history of conceptualizing curiosity as an individual desire to know or, in contemporary scientific nomenclature, a drive for information or to fill knowledge gaps. We take a moment to appreciate what this traditional conceptualization has allowed to surface, but also what it has hidden. Turning to take an expressly relational approach, we then propose a new conceptualization of curiosity, according to which the curious impetus is not knower Y’s desire to know X but rather a practice of connecting, of building relations between and among systems of (un)knowers, (un)knowledges, and things (un)known.4 We then dive back into the history of philosophy to excavate inklings of this novel concept in past theoretical constructions before exploring the implications of it for psychology and neuroscience. Ultimately, we explore the potential payoffs of this dramatic paradigm shift. What if, in network nomenclature, we understood curiosity less as an individual capacity to build or acquire nodes, and more as simply the energy of the edge? What would this allow to be seen and noticed, tested and perturbed?

在我们开始之前，先来谈谈方法论。首先，在本章中，我们有意识地进行哲学上的谱系调查。也就是说，我们分析了当前的想法如何植根于先前的想法，以及过去的思想如何为今天的不同思考提供未被充分重视的资源。因此，在接下来的谱系调查中，我们将挖掘过去的资源，为好奇心的现在和未来概念化提供新的资源。其次，在回溯过去的工作中，我们追踪了西方哲学的几种语言（例如希腊语、拉丁语、法语、德语和英语）中的“好奇心”一词，同时也追踪了“连接”、“链接”和“关系”等词。当这些术语同时出现时，就会出现不同的范式。第三，也是最后，我们将网络理解为任何具有网状交叉点和间隙的结构。根据图论的模型，网络由以下部分组成：节点（位置）和边缘（位置之间的关系）。让当代网络感性与过去的关系范式产生共鸣，我们因此将好奇心的概念化视为内在的互联性而非个体化——好奇心的概念化不是节点获取，而是边缘工作。

A few notes on method before we begin. First, in this chapter we consciously undertake a genealogical investigation of the philosophical sort. That is, we analyze how what is currently thought has its roots in prior thought, but also how thoughts of yesteryear hold underappreciated resources for thinking things differently today. As such, in the genealogical investigation to follow, we unearth resources in the past for new present and future conceptualizations of curiosity. Second, in that work of diving back into the past, we track the word curiosity in several languages of Western philosophy (e.g., Greek, Latin, French, German, and English), but also alongside the words “connection,” “link,” and “relation.” Where these terms appear together, a different paradigm lies in wait. Third and finally, we understand a network to be any structure with netlike intersections and interstices. As modeled by graph theory, a network is composed of nodes (loci) and edges (relations between the loci). Allowing contemporary network sensibilities to resonate with past relational paradigms, we therefore attend to conceptualizations of curiosity as inherently interconnective rather than individualizing—conceptualizations of curiosity not as nodal acquisition but as edgework.

好奇心作为节点获取

Curiosity as Nodal Acquisition

几千年来，好奇心一直被主要描述为一种获取信息的个体动力。无论是圣奥古斯丁的“体验欲望”，约翰·洛克的“求知欲望”，西格蒙德·弗洛伊德的“窥视欲”，还是汉斯-格奥尔格·沃斯的“探索动机”，西方思想传统的哲学家和心理学家在很大程度上都是从有机体、其力量和感觉的层面来理解好奇心的。在这个框架内，好奇心是了解 X、理解 X、发现 X、更好地认知 X、用 X 填补信息空白或获得有关 X 的信息的欲望、胃口、冲动、兴趣、动机、感觉或驱动状态。它是个体的，是习得性的，根植于知识者单位和知识单位。这些特征对于各种哲学和科学研究人类知识的本质都是有益和有用的，但它们也有明显的局限性。在本节中，我们将探讨这一传统的可能性和参数。

For millennia, curiosity has been characterized predominantly as an individual impetus to secure pieces of information. Whether it is Saint Augustine’s “lust to experience,” John Locke’s “appetite after knowledge,” Sigmund Freud’s “scopophilic drive,” or Hans-Georg Voss’s “motivation to explore,” philosophers and psychologists of the Western intellectual tradition have largely understood curiosity at the level of the organism, its forces, and its feelings. Within this framework, curiosity is the desire, appetite, impulse, interest, motivation, feeling, or drive state to know X, understand X, find out X, better cognize X, fill an information gap with X, or gain information about X. It is individual and it is acquisitional, rooted in units of knowers and units of knowledge. Such characterizations are informative and useful for a variety of philosophical and scientific investigations into the nature of human knowledge, but they also have distinct limitations. In this section, we explore the possibilities and parameters of this tradition.

在古代和中世纪，好奇心被人们视为一种对新奇或禁忌信息的兴趣，人们对此深表怀疑。人们认为好奇的人会去探寻隐藏的秘密，超出他们应有的视野，从而将自己与精神和社会隔离开来。罗马散文家普鲁塔克和基督教主教奥古斯丁的记述在这方面具有代表性。对普鲁塔克来说，好奇的人——或者用他的术语来说，好管闲事的人——是一个怪人，一个奇怪的人，有点爱管闲事。好管闲事的人的好奇心表现为“渴望学习”和“渴望发现”真正新奇的东西。他们涌入集市、市场和港口，问：“有什么新闻吗？”但是，由于中等新闻很容易获得——只要人们在屋顶上大声喊叫或把新闻散布在他们身上，社交媒体信息流——真正的新闻很难获得。真正新颖的通常是“隐藏的”、“模糊的”和“隐蔽的”，因为它令人不安：肮脏的秘密和谎言。他们几乎不羞于揭露这些。正如普鲁塔克所写，好管闲事的人“不仅剥去身边人的衣裳和衣服，还剥去他们的墙壁；他敞开大门，像一阵刺骨的风一样向前走。” 5好管闲事的人对蛆虫奥秘的探索是无私的，他们不关心自己也不关心他人。好管闲事的人放弃了自己的利益，让自己的灵魂处于肮脏的境地，危及了他们的友谊，破坏了社会联系。为了治疗这种“好奇心病”，普鲁塔克推荐了一系列苦行修行，包括收到信后不打开，不圆房，听到远处有戏剧表演时就朝另一个方向走。信息很简单：放弃单一的秘密，细节中的魔鬼。

In the ancient and medieval periods, curiosity was held in deep suspicion as a largely vacuous interest in novel or forbidden information. The curious person was thought to reach for what was hidden and secret, beyond their proper purview, and thereby isolate themselves from spiritual and social community. The accounts of Plutarch, a Roman essayist, and Augustine, a Christian bishop, are representative in this respect. For Plutarch, the curious person—or in his nomenclature, the busybody—was an oddball, a singular fellow and a bit of an earwig. The busybody’s curiosity manifests as “a desire to learn” and “a passion to find out” what is truly new and novel. They push into the bazaars, marketplaces, and harbors asking, “Is there any news?” But because middling news is easy to come by—insofar as people shout it from the rooftops or splatter it across their social media feeds—real news is hard to get. What remains truly novel is typically “hidden,” “obscure,” and “concealed” because it is troubling: the dirty secrets and the lies. They are hardly timid about sussing these out. As Plutarch writes, the busybody “strips off not only the mantles and tunics of those near him, but also their very walls; he flings the doors wide open and makes his way, like a piercing wind.”5 The busybody’s quest for the maggoty mysteries is pursued without concern for themself or others. Abandoning their own interests and leaving their own soul in seedy squalor, the busybody jeopardizes their friendships and destroys social ties. As an antidote to this “disease” of curiosity, then, Plutarch recommends a suite of ascetic practices, including not opening a letter upon its receipt, not consummating a marriage, and, upon hearing a theatrical performance in the distance, walking in the other direction. The message is simple: abandon the singular secret, the devil in the details.

对于将古代记载基督教化的奥古斯丁来说，好奇的人是罪人，是弱小的兄弟，是需要牧羊人的绵羊。《创世纪》当然以创造和好奇的故事开始。第一个女人夏娃想要吃一棵她禁止吃的树，这棵树代表着她和亚当被禁止获得的知识。出于对善恶的好奇，她吃了——也就是说，她伸手去抓、抓、拉、获得、吞下并吃掉了——禁树上的一块果实，她的眼睛睁开了。通过她，全人类被谴责，从比喻上讲，像蛇一样匍匐着，吃世俗的东西而不是精神的东西。奥古斯丁写道：“因为吃土的人，会洞察深奥而黑暗的东西，但仍然是世俗的。” 6这种现在普遍存在的人类好奇心表现为“对实验和了解”一连串没有真正精神价值的无关紧要的事情的渴望。堕落的人类一头栽进了“令人分心的喧嚣”。7人们经常去剧院，呆呆地看着残缺不全的尸体，沉迷于梦境、神迹和奇迹，用占星术和黑魔法来取悦自己，惊叹于星星，并追求鬼魂。他们不仅捕猎生物，还为了消遣而猎捕无聊的故事和科学细节。他们目光呆滞，专注于蜘蛛或蜥蜴捕捉苍蝇的小戏剧。在这种对知识的迫切需求中，他们与宗教交流中的精神意义隔绝，神圣的智慧，每个人都注定要陷入他们所寻求的知识的空虚和流放之中。

For Augustine, who largely Christianizes the ancient account, the curious person is a sinner, the weaker brother, a sheep in need of a shepherd. Genesis begins, of course, with a story of creation and curiosity. The first woman, Eve, wants to partake of the one tree forbidden to her, representing the knowledge from which she and Adam are prohibited. Curious to know good and evil, she eats—that is, she reaches for, grasps, tugs, acquires, ingests, and consumes—a single piece of fruit from the forbidden tree and her eyes are opened. Through her, all of humanity is condemned, metaphorically, to creep on its belly like a serpent, eating things worldly rather than spiritual. “For one who eats the earth,” Augustine writes, “penetrates things deep and dark but nonetheless temporal and earthly.”6 This now-generalized human curiosity manifests itself as “a lust for experimenting and knowing” a string of insignificant things of no real spiritual worth. Fallen humanity tumbles headfirst into a “buzz of distraction.”7 People frequent the theater, gawk at mangled corpses, obsess over dreams, signs, and wonders, titillate themselves with astrology and the dark arts, marvel at the stars, and court ghosts. They hunt not only creatures but also idle tales and scientific details for sport. Their eyes glaze over, glued to the minor drama of a spider or a lizard catching flies. In this burning need for bits of knowledge, isolated from spiritual meaning in religious communion and divine wisdom, each person is condemned to the very vacuity and exile of the knowledge they seek.

虽然好奇心的超个性化本质及其对孤立细节的兴趣在古代和中世纪时期最为令人担忧，但这些相同的特征在现代时期却得到了最强烈的赞扬。这是早期现代科学和个人的时代，为自由主体和工业革命奠定了基础。现代好奇心寻求的不是新奇或禁忌的信息，而是极其有用的信息。哲学家勒内·笛卡尔、洛克和大卫·休谟都对此提出了类似的看法。笛卡尔将好奇心定义为“理解的渴望”。8灵魂对任何新奇或陌生的事物感到惊奇之后，好奇心会去了解什么对人类有机体和社会的繁荣有用。同样，洛克将好奇心定义为“对知识的渴望”。作为消除我们的无知或填补信息空白的基本工具，好奇心自然会从问“它是什么？”转变为问“它有什么用？” 9最后，休谟将好奇心定义为“对真理的热爱”。他呼应笛卡尔的观点，指出好奇心一旦被“事物的突然性和陌生性”所激发，就会关注“对世界重要且有用”的事物。10因此，在弗朗西斯·培根的精神下，现代的好奇心由独立的认知者表现出来，他们为了自身利益而寻求令人惊讶的信息，而这一过程本身最终服务于社会效用。奇异的好奇对象会激发好奇心的个体实践者去获取最终对社会有用的知识。

While the hyperindividualized nature of curiosity and its interest in orphaned details is of the utmost concern in the ancient and medieval periods, these same characteristics are curiosity’s strongest commendations in the modern period. This is the era of early modern science and the individual, which then sets the stage for the liberal subject and the Industrial Revolution. Rather than novel or forbidden information, modern curiosity seeks eminently useful information. Philosophers René Descartes, Locke, and David Hume all offer similar accounts in this regard. Descartes defines curiosity as a “desire to understand.”8 Following upon a wondrous surprise of the soul at anything new or strange, curiosity moves to understand what is useful for the flourishing of the human organism and society. Likewise, Locke defines curiosity as “an appetite after knowledge.” As the fundamental tool to remove our ignorance—or fill information gaps—curiosity naturally moves from asking “What is it?” to “What is it for?”9 Lastly, Hume defines curiosity as “the love of truth.” Echoing Descartes, he remarks that curiosity, once generated by “the suddenness and strangeness of an appearance,” then focuses on what is “important and useful to the world.”10 In the spirit of Francis Bacon, then, modern curiosity, performed by independent knowers, courts surprising information for its own sake, a process that itself ultimately serves the cause of social utility. Singularly curious objects inspire the individual practitioner of curiosity to gain knowledge of eventual use to society.

好奇心的概念化为一种个人驱动力，目的是发现某个事物，这种驱动力一直延续到现在，正如当代认识论、道德心理学和语言哲学的研究表明的那样。例如，哲学家伊尔汗·伊南和拉尼·沃森分别将好奇心描述为一种个人动机，目的是发现特定的指称物或获得某些知识产品。伊南将好奇心定义为一种有意识的心理状态，可以用一个不言而喻的术语来表达。11对他来说，更简单地说，好奇心包括专注于某个特定的事物，人们可以用手指、眼睛、舌头或从舌头上发出的声音来指向它；而某些东西却超出了人们的知识范围，这是一个人们还无法完全描述或掌握的东西。例如，伊南写道：“当福尔摩斯好奇谁是凶手时，他的主要目标是找到凶手这个单数表示的指称。” 12当最终找到不可言喻术语的指称时，好奇心就得到了满足。同样，对于华生来说，好奇心是一种“获取有价值的认识论商品的动机”。这种动机源于对自己真实或假定的无知的认识，并且必须强大到足以“以某种边际成本”继续下去，涉及一些“小小的牺牲”。要获取的认识论商品必须是有价值的——也就是说，非平凡的——“信息、知识和理解”。因此，根据华生的说法，“蝴蝶保护主义者”并不好奇，而“蝴蝶收藏家”好奇，因为前者没有获取的动机，而后者有。此外，沉迷于名人八卦或满足于“数草叶”的人并不是具有美德好奇心的人，因为这两种兴趣本质上都是微不足道的。13虽然伊南关注的是语言条件，而沃森关注的是美德含义，但他们都将好奇心视为获取可​​定义信息的个人动力。

The conceptualization of curiosity as an individual drive to find out an individual thing continues on into the present, as indicated by contemporary work in epistemology, moral psychology, and philosophy of language. Accounts by philosophers Ilhan Inan and Lani Watson, for example, characterize curiosity as an individual motivation to find out a specific referent or to acquire certain epistemic goods, respectively. Inan defines curiosity as an intentional state of mind expressible by an inostensible term.11 Put more simply, for him, curiosity involves focusing on something specific that one can point to with one’s finger, one’s eye, one’s tongue, or the sounds that roll off of it; and something that is nevertheless beyond one’s knowledge, something one cannot yet fully describe or grasp. For instance, “when [Sherlock] Holmes is curious about who the murderer is,” Inan writes, “his primary goal is to find the referent of the singular representation the murderer.”12 When the referent of the inostensible term is finally found, curiosity is satisfied. Similarly, for Watson, curiosity is a “motivation to acquire worthwhile epistemic goods.” Such motivation arises from an awareness of one’s real or presumed ignorance, and must be strong enough to proceed “at some marginal cost,” involving some “small sacrifice.” The epistemic goods to be acquired must be worthwhile—that is, nontrivial—sorts of “information, knowledge, and understanding.” On Watson’s account therefore, the “butterfly preservationist” is not curious whereas the “butterfly collector” is because the former is not motivated to acquire whereas the latter is. Furthermore, the person obsessed with celebrity gossip or content to “count blades of grass” is not virtuously curious because both interests are essentially trivial.13 While Inan focuses on the linguistic conditions and Watson the virtue implications, both take curiosity to be an individual impetus to acquire definable pieces of information.

纵观哲学史，传统观点认为好奇心是主体 Y 想要了解信息 X 的愿望。那么，好奇心的征婚启事可能是：单一的认知者寻求特定的知识单元。不同哲学论述和时代的差异更多地体现在如何和为什么上，而非谁和什么上。理论家在描述好奇主体获取信息的方法和价值时存在很大分歧。然而，无论信息是新的、被禁止的、有用的、可用语言描述的还是有价值的，也无论信息是通过欲望、胃口、热情、兴趣、意图、动机还是驱动力来寻求的，好奇心都是主体对信息的寻求。因此，这种传统观点阐明了人们好奇的信息类型、人们对这些信息好奇的方式以及人们对这些信息好奇时的状态。然而，由于其个体主义和获取性承诺，好奇心的精确性和解释力受到限制。社区和关系承诺如何改变这种观点？如果好奇心的典范是蝴蝶保护主义者，他们实际上深深地参与了培育——从而理解——维持蝴蝶种群的生态条件？什么样的好奇心观点可以解释知者、知晓方法和知识所处的关系网络？边缘的能量究竟是什么？

Across the history of philosophy, the traditional view has been that curiosity is subject Y’s desire to know information bit X. Curiosity’s personal ad, then, might read: Singular unitary knower seeks specific unit of knowledge. The difference across philosophical accounts and eras appears less in the who and what than in the how and why. Theorists diverge significantly in their description of the method and value of the curious subject’s information acquisition. Whether the information is new, forbidden, useful, linguistically describable, or worthwhile, however, and whether it is sought via desire, appetite, ardor, interest, intention, motivation, or drive, curiosity is a subject’s seeking of information. This traditional view thus illuminates the sorts of information one is curious about, the ways one is curious about that information, and the states in which one finds oneself when one is curious about that information. It is nonetheless limited in its precision and explanatory power by its individualistic and acquisitional commitments. How might communal and relational commitments change that view? What if the paradigm for curiosity were the butterfly conservationists who are in fact deeply involved in cultivating—and thereby understanding—the ecological conditions that sustain butterfly populations? What is a view of curiosity that could account for the networks of relations in which knowers, methods of knowing, and knowledges sit? And what, indeed, is the energy of the edge?

好奇心作为边缘艺术

Curiosity as Edgework

我们都熟悉获取知识的经历——即想要或需要知道某件事，经过一段时间和一些精力投入后，获得该知识。这是一种有效的体验，或者说是一种有效的体验，并非没有乐趣。但我们也熟悉孵化一项探究的经历——即让它成长，将其根深深扎入我们的灵魂（因为没有更好的词来形容），并将其枝叶延伸到我们思考和说的每一件事中，持续数周、数月甚至数年（我们敢说几十年？）。正是通过这种探究，我们爱上了知识景观。我们参观它，在它的星空下睡觉，在它的壁龛里居住，直到它成为我们的一部分，我们也成为它的一部分。这不是匆匆越过篱笆偷几个梨。这不是抢夺和逃跑。这是一种边缘驱动的好奇心，不仅要学习事物属于什么以及如何属于，还要建立迄今为止难以想象的归属线。这是一种与获取无关的好奇心。

We are all familiar with the experience of acquiring knowledge—that is, of wanting or needing to know something and, after some interval of time and some investment of energy, getting that knowledge. It is an effective experience, or an experience of effectiveness, that is not without its pleasures. But we are also familiar with the experience of incubating an inquiry—that is, letting it grow, sinking its roots deep into our souls (for lack of a better word), and stretching its branches into everything we think and say for weeks, months, or even years (dare we say decades?). This is the kind of inquiry through which we come to fall in love with a knowledgescape. We visit it, sleep under its stars, and take up residence in its alcoves until it becomes part of us, and we become part of it. This is no scurry across the fence to poach a few pears. This is no snatch and skedaddle. This is the sort of curiosity that is edge driven, not only learning what and how things belong, but also building heretofore unimaginable lines of belonging. It is inquisitiveness untethered to acquisition.

很久以前，奥古斯丁就将好奇心归结于眼睛——用来观察、搜索和探索的眼睛。后来，笛卡尔将好奇心扩散到血液中，认为“动物精神”会穿梭并让我们的注意力停留在新的感知印象上，而博物学家查尔斯·博内和经验主义者埃蒂安·博诺·德·孔狄亚克则将好奇心重新植根于触觉器官，尤其是人类的手指或大象的鼻子。14直到19 世纪，随着颅相学的出现，好奇心才在大脑中找到了位置。颅相学家 H. Lundie 和 George Combe 将好奇心定位在顶叶的两侧，好奇心在那里不是作为一种智力能力，而是一种“高级”或“情感”情绪。15当然，随着神经科学的发展，当代科学家已经使用fMRI表明，大脑并非只是各个部分的组合，每个部分都专注于一项特定的任务，而是一个信息通道网络，其灵活性决定了其功能。16按照这一模型，虽然某些好奇行为的信号可追溯到海马体或侧顶叶，但好奇心本身必然是扩散的。17它不可能是单一事物、位于某一位置、由某一人为追求某一信息而采取的行动。但如果不是单一事物，那是什么？从关系甚至网络的角度重新思考好奇心意味着什么？重新开始形成和塑造好奇心概念的艺术意味着什么？

Long ago, Augustine traced curiosity to the eyes—the eyes that look, observe, search, and explore. Later, Descartes diffused it in the blood, suggesting that “animal spirits” shuttle about and suspend our attention on novel perceptual impressions, while naturalist Charles Bonnet and empiricist Étienne Bonnot de Condillac rerooted it in the organ of touch, especially the human finger or the elephant’s trunk.14 It was not until the nineteenth century, with the advent of phrenology, that curiosity found its place in the brain. Appearing under the term “marvelousness” or “wonder,” curiosity was located by phrenologists H. Lundie and George Combe on either side of the parietal lobe, where it functioned not as an intellectual faculty but instead as a “superior” or “affective” sentiment.15 Of course, with the development of neuroscience, contemporary scientists have used fMRI to show that the brain is not simply a conglomeration of sections, each devoted to one specific task, but rather it is a network of information channels, the flexibility of which preconditions function.16 On this model, while certain signals of curious behavior are traceable to the hippocampus or lateral parietal lobe, curiosity itself is necessarily diffused.17 It cannot be one thing, located in one place, practiced by one person, in the pursuit of one piece of information. But if not one, then what? What would it mean to rethink curiosity from a relational or even a network perspective? To take up the art of forming and fashioning the concept of curiosity anew?

想象一下，好奇心更具社会性和实践性，而非个体性、智力性和获取性。想象一下，好奇心的目标不是了解 X、找出 X 或认知 X，而是建立联系、构建星座、寻找链接和追随线索。想象一下，好奇心是集体的、相互联系的，在知识者、知识方法和知识之间关系的网络中发挥作用。虽然传统的好奇心观点将其实践定位于收集信息、追寻答案或想象新事物的个人行为，但好奇心的关系和网络观点会明确地将好奇的情感、实践和架构嵌入到深层交织的（生态）系统和（生态）文化中。18从这个角度来看，好奇心不像眼睛，而更像光本身。这至少是一个有趣的建议，但这种概念有历史先例吗？简而言之，是的；这种观点有非常强大的先例。虽然历史上某些对好奇心的批评恰恰谴责它破坏了联系并造成了孤立——回想一下早期现代主义者布莱兹·帕斯卡 (Blaise Pascal) 的文字：“我看到了我的骄傲、好奇心和欲望的深处。我和上帝之间没有任何联系 [融洽关系]”——但总体而言，作为认识者、认识方法和 (不) 已知事物之间联系的一种关系实践，思考好奇心仍然有迹可循。19在这里，我们沿着这条线索，剔除好奇心作为一种联系实践的关键特征。

Imagine a curiosity that is more social and praxiological than it is individual, intellectual, and acquisitional. Imagine a curiosity that aims less to know X, to find out X, or to cognize X than to make connections, build constellations, find links, and follow threads. Imagine a curiosity that is collective and interconnective, functioning within a webbed network of relations between knowers, methods of knowing, and knowledges. While the traditional view of curiosity locates its practice in the individual act of collecting information, tracking down answers, or imagining something new, a relational and network view of curiosity would expressly embed inquisitive affects, practices, and architectures in deeply imbricated (eco)systems and (eco)cultures.18 Curiosity from this vantage point would be less like the eye than the light itself. It is an intriguing suggestion at the very least, but is there historical precedent for such a concept? In short, yes; there is a markedly robust precedence for this view. While certain historical critiques of curiosity precisely castigate it for breaking connection and creating isolation—recall early modernist Blaise Pascal writing, “I see the depths of my pride, curiosity, concupiscence. There is no link [rapport] between me and God”—on the whole, there is nevertheless a steady trace of thinking curiosity as a relational practice of connection between knowers, methods of knowing, and (un)knowns.19 Here we follow that trace, culling critical characteristics of curiosity as a practice of connection.

对于古代思想家来说，好奇心能够产生两种基本联系：1）探究者与内心之间的联系；2）一个探究对象与另一个探究对象之间的联系。普鲁塔克开玩笑说，话匣子——好奇的爱管闲事的人——具有非典型的解剖结构：耳朵和灵魂之间应该有一条管道，但耳朵和舌头之间却有一条。20一条流氓耳咽管直通食道！词语只是通过狂风小路滚进滚出，从未落在灵魂的甜美土壤中发芽结实。普鲁塔克在这里表示管道的词是suntetraino (希腊语sun：一起，一起；tetraino：穿孔)，指的是在事物之间钻一条连接通道或渠道。如果纠正了，好奇心就会重新钻出正确的渠道，尤其是在认知者和自己之间。当普鲁塔克等古人建议“回头凝视”时，他们并不是要建议用一件事物取代另一件事，仿佛要将自我降低为另一个知识对象；相反，他们要求关注我们与自己和我们自己的目标之间的紧张和距离。因此，他们所呼唤的不是知识，而是“注意力”。这个词源于拉丁语tendere，意为在事物之间伸展。21但自我关系并不是好奇心所促成的唯一联系。中世纪教育理论家胡安·路易斯·比夫斯 (Juan Luis Vives) 增加了已知事物之间的关系。对于“好奇心”，他写道：“有些事物……源于对其他事物的发现，就像当一根线的开头被固定住时，会发现它与另一组与正在检查的事物完全不同的东西相连。” 22这就是好奇心的乐趣，手中线的紧绷引领着你向前走。

For ancient thinkers, curiosity has the capacity to produce two essential connections: 1) a connection between the inquirer and their inner selves and 2) a connection between one object of inquiry and another. Plutarch makes good fun when he surmises that the chatterbox—close cousin of the curious busybody—has an atypical anatomy: where a conduit between ear and soul should appear, there is instead one between ear and tongue.20 A rogue eustachian tube straight into the gullet! The words just tumble in and tumble out, via blustery byways, never landing in the sweet earth of the soul to germinate and bear fruit. Plutarch’s word for conduit here is suntetraino (Gk. sun: with, together; tetraino: to perforate), which refers to boring a connective passage or channel between things. When righted, curiosity rebores proper channels, especially between the knower and themself. When the ancients like Plutarch and others recommend “turning back the gaze,” they do not mean to suggest replacing one thing with another, as if to reduce the self to yet another object of knowledge; rather, they enjoin attending to the tension and the distance that separates us from ourselves and our own aims. Their call is not to knowledge, then, but rather to “attention,” from the Latin tendere, meaning to stretch between things.21 But self-relation is not the only connection that curiosity curates. Medieval educational theorist Juan Luis Vives adds the relation between (un)knowns. With “curiosity,” he writes “some things . . . follow from the finding of others, just as when the beginning of a thread is secured, it is found to be connected with another set of things quite different from those which were being examined.”22 This is the pleasure of curiosity, the tautness of a thread in one’s hand, leading one onward.
