同样，一些现代哲学家认为好奇心是一种关系活动，与其说是自我与自我的关系，不如说是自我与客体的关系以及客体相互之间的关系。对托马斯·霍布斯来说，好奇心是对因果关系的兴趣，从结果追溯到所有可能的原因，或从原因追溯到所有可能的结果。23 更为坚定的是，让-雅克·卢梭认为好奇心受已知者与（不）已知者之间现有联系的支配，也受（不）已知者之间现有联系的引导。在《爱弥儿》一书中，卢梭巧妙地区分了仅仅为了给人留下深刻印象的“求知热情”和追求自己内在兴趣或关注的热情。24好奇心是每个人心中的本能，它延伸到与个人探究者福祉“相关”的任何事物。正如弗里德里希·尼采谴责缺乏个人投入的好奇心，坚持认为“所有重大问题都需要伟大的爱”，卢梭也坚持认为好奇心必须源于个人投入才能真实。25然而，由于最终“一切都与我们有关”，或与我们有关，一切都与其他一切有关，以至于“每个单独的对象都带来另一个”，就像维夫斯一样，每件事物都是好奇心的潜在对象。人类认知者需要的是，好奇心从个人联系开始，通过（不）已知与其他（不）已知之间的联系进行，并不断将知识重新与个人关注和社会利益联系起来。“在观察了我们周围的一切之后，我们还能做什么？”卢梭总结道，除了“将我们可以占有的一切转化为我们的用途，并利用我们的好奇心来造福我们自己。” 26

Some modern philosophers, likewise, think curiosity as an activity of relation, not so much of the self’s relation to the self, but of the self’s relation to objects and those objects’ relations to each other. For Thomas Hobbes, curiosity is an interest in causal relations, shuttling from an effect back to all possible causes or from a cause forward to all its possible effects.23 More robustly, Jean-Jacques Rousseau conceives of curiosity as governed by existing connections between knower and (un)known, as well as guided by existing connections between (un)knowns. In Émile, his treatise on education, Rousseau deftly distinguishes between an “ardor for knowledge” that aims to merely impress, and one that aims to pursue what is of inherent interest or concern to oneself.24 Natural to every human heart, curiosity extends to anything and everything that is “connected” to an individual inquirer’s well-being. Much as Friedrich Nietzsche decries a curiosity that lacks personal investment, insisting that “all great problems demand great love,” Rousseau too insists that curiosity must stem from personal investment for it to be authentic.25 Since, however, ultimately “everything concerns us,” or is connected to us, and everything is connected to everything else, such that “each individual object brings forward another,” à la Vives, every single thing is a potential object of curiosity. What is required of the human knower is that curiosity start from a personal connection, proceed via the (un)known’s connection to other (un)knowns, and constantly reconnect knowledge back to personal concern and social good. “What remains for us to do after having observed all that surrounds us?” Rousseau concludes, but “to convert to our use all of it that we can appropriate to ourselves, and to make use of our curiosity for the advantage of our own well-being.”26

在这些古代和现代见解的基础上，19 世纪末和 20 世纪初的实用主义哲学家在思考好奇心时堪称深度典范。鉴于他们致力于将对世界的认识融入对世界的体验式实验中，这也许并不奇怪。威廉·詹姆斯建议通过“激发认知者本性和未知之间的联系”来培养好奇心，无论是通过“个人兴趣”、“好斗冲动”还是“理论好奇心”。27他澄清道：“理论好奇心受到“事物之间的理性关系”的刺激——或者用查尔斯·桑德斯·皮尔士的话来说，是需要“理性解释”的“非常了不起的关系”。28一旦(不) 认知者和 (不) 已知者之间的联系得到启动，就可以建立未知和已知之间的联系。正如詹姆斯令人难忘地说的那样，好奇心在新的事实中找到了“老朋友”；它把新信息与旧信息“编织”在一起，把新的好奇心与以前的好奇心“编织”在一起。29约翰·杜威进一步阐述了这一观点，他首先坚持认为好奇心本身并不是“偶然的孤立拥有”，它也不是通过“聚集”、“积累”或“堆积”不连贯的信息片段来发挥作用的。它既不是节点性的，也不是主要以节点性获取为标志的。相反，好奇心源于“对生活的直接兴趣”。它暗示着，无论一个人目前知道什么，都不是“全部故事”；总是有“更多的东西在后面”，“还有更多。”因此，好奇心是一种冲动，使事物之间的“联系”——最终是联系本身的条件——变得可感知。30因此，务实的认知者会从自我到世界追寻一条线索，发现世界上事物之间的联系，然后将自己重新编织到那个网络、那个世界中。

Building and expanding upon these ancient and modern insights, the pragmatist philosophers of the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries are exemplary in the depth with which they think curiosity in relation. This is perhaps no surprise given their commitment to embedding knowledge of the world in experiential experiments with that world. William James recommends cultivating curiosity by “stirring up connections” between the knower’s nature and the unknown, whether via “personal interest,” “pugnacious impulse,” or “theoretic curiosity.”27 “Theoretic curiosity,” he clarifies, is stimulated by “the rational relations between things”—or in Charles Sanders Peirce’s terms, “the very remarkable relations” that demand “rational explanations.”28 Once the connectedness between the (un)knower and (un)known has been primed, connections between the unknown and known can be built. As James memorably puts it, curiosity finds in new facts “an old friend”; it “knits” new information to old information and fresh curiosities to former curiosities.29 Further developing this account, John Dewey begins by insisting that curiosity itself is not “an accidental isolated possession,” nor does it function by “amassing,” “accumulating,” or “heaping up” disconnected bits of information. It is neither merely nodal nor primarily marked by nodal acquisition. Rather, curiosity springs from “the direct interest of life.” And it carries an inkling that whatever one currently knows is never “the whole story”; there is always “more behind” and “more to come.” As such, curiosity is an impulse to make the “connections” between things—and ultimately the condition of connectedness itself—perceptible.30 The pragmatic knower thus follows a thread from the self to the world, discovers the knits between things in that world, and then knits themselves back into that web, that worlding.

尽管与传统观点及其当前表现形式不一致，但不可否认的是，西方哲学史上散布着一些资源，可以将好奇心视为一种联系的实践和关系的传播者。有趣的是，我们没有观察到时代之间的任何重大鸿沟或描述性叙述中的戏剧性脱节。相反，我们观察到，一个又一个时代，人们对​​产生好奇心和好奇心所产生的关系的理解不断加深。在这个叙述中，至少有四组关系浮出水面：（不）知者与自己的关系、（不）知者与（不）知者的关系、（不）知者与其他（不）知者的关系、（不）知者与（不）知者的关系。这些是好奇心跨越的洞穴和它旋转的辐条。好奇心将面向外部的探究者拉回到与他们的内心世界的关系中。好奇心将探究者引向与他们有根本联系和关注的事物。好奇心随之而来，感受着世界上事物之间的事实和功能关系。好奇心将所学知识重新与知识者和知识社区联系起来，从而使两者得到改善。那么，历史中埋藏着一种新的好奇心范式的材料，即边缘工作。这种关系解释对心理学、神经科学、网络理论和其他领域有何影响？这种范式转变可能带来什么实际结果？

Although inconsistent with the traditional view and its current manifestations, there are undeniably resources, scattered across the history of Western philosophy, for thinking curiosity at the edge, as a practice of connection and a promulgator of relation. Interestingly, we do not observe any significant chasms between eras or dramatic disjunctions in descriptive accounts. Instead, we observe, era after era, a deepening of appreciation for the relations that produce and are produced by curiosity. In this narrative, at least four sets of relations surface: the relation of an (un)knower to themselves, of an (un)knower to an (un)known, of (un)knowns to other (un)knowns, and of (un)knowns to (un)knowers. These are the caverns that curiosity spans and the spokes on which it spins. Curiosity draws the externally facing inquirer back into relation with their internal world. Curiosity draws the inquirer out toward things with which they are fundamentally connected and concerned. Curiosity follows, feeling along the factual and functional relations between things in the world. And curiosity reconnects what is learned back to the knower and the knowing community, such that both are improved in its wake. Buried here in history, then, is the material for a new paradigm of curiosity as edgework. What are the implications of this relational account for psychology, neuroscience, network theory, and beyond? And what might be the practical results of such a paradigm shift?

边缘作业实际操作

Edgework in Action

网络是一种连接结构，其本质是由点和间隙定义的，它既是节点又是边，既是单位又是关系。虽然到目前为止，我们一直对节点和边保持距离，以便更好地阐明传统好奇心理论中对节点获取的过分强调，并接受将好奇心重新概念化为边际工作，但实际上，这两种观点的融合对于理解好奇心至关重要。任何名副其实的好奇心网络解释都是如此。好奇心不是吃豆人游戏，嘴巴四处游走，咀嚼能量球。但它也不仅仅是夏洛特网的表演，局限于情感归属和交流的网络。但如何才能最好地平衡节点获取和边缘工作？它们是如何交织在一起的？如何才能最好地接受它们的连续性，而不是否认或否定它们？如果没有（不）知者、（不）知和（不）知的结缔组织，节点创建和成长的时刻就会脱离语境，很容易被误解为单一收益。传统观点不仅过分强调节点获取是好奇心的主要标志，而且还将边缘定位在欲望中，延伸到个人和信息之间。我们在这里挖掘的解释优先考虑好奇心的边缘工作，它将节点定位为始终已经由多个网络中的其他节点和边缘共同构成和连接。这样的叙述建立在这些联系之上，而不是破坏这些联系。在词语和事物的漩涡中，这样的叙述将关系置于最前沿，无论是（不）知者、（不）知者还是（不）知者之间。

As connective architectures, inherently defined by pinpoints and interstices, networks are nothing if not nodes and edges, units and relations, at once. While we have held nodes and edges at arm’s length up to this point, so as to better illuminate the overemphasis on nodal acquisition in traditional accounts of curiosity and entertain the reconceptualization of curiosity as edgework, realistically a blend of these two viewpoints is required for any network account of curiosity worthy of the name. Curiosity is no game of Pac-Man, with its traveling mouth munching power pellets. But nor is it merely a performance of Charlotte’s web, confined to nets of affective belonging and communications. But how are nodal acquisition and edgework best balanced? How are they imbricated? How can their contiguous natures be best embraced rather than denied or disavowed? Without the connective tissue of (un)knowers, (un)knowledges, and (un)knowns, the moments of nodal creation and growth are decontextualized, and easily misunderstood as unitary gains. The traditional view not only overemphasizes nodal acquisition as the primary marker of curiosity but also locates the edge in desire, stretched between individual and information. The account we have excavated here privileges the edgework of curiosity, and it locates the node as always already coconstituted and connected by other nodes and edges in multiple networks. Such an account builds upon rather than breaks those connections. Standing in a swirl of words and things, such an account positions relations at the forefront, whether between (un)knowers, (un)knowledges, or (un)knowns.

在最后一节中，我们将通过两种不同的哲学体系来阐明好奇心的网络范式，一个是当代的，另一个是古代的：分别是米歇尔·福柯的作品和土著哲学传统。它们各自以自己的方式阐明了好奇心的潜在意义，好奇心被重新概念化为一种联系实践，在一个复杂的重叠网络系统中。

In this final section, we elucidate this network paradigm for curiosity through two different philosophical systems, one contemporary and the other ancient: the work of Michel Foucault and the tradition of Indigenous philosophy, respectively. Each in their own way illuminates the potential significance of curiosity reconceptualized as a practice of connection, within a complex system of overlapping networks.

福柯是二十世纪的一位权力思想家，他研究的是抵抗既定思维方式和行为方式的力量。对他来说，好奇心是这种抵抗的核心，因为它重新设想并改造了继承下来的道路。31 福柯沉思于人们对大众媒体的长期怀疑——它是一种反乌托邦的细节洪流，使人头脑迟钝，意志消沉——相反，他强调信息的扩散及其对好奇心的内在重要性。无论信息本身的价值如何，信息网络的指数级增长对于思考、行动和成为其他事物的批判能力至关重要。简而言之，信息网络是好奇心的先决条件。“我梦想着一个充满好奇心的新时代，”他写道。“我们有技术手段；有欲望；有无限的东西去了解；有能力做这种工作的人是存在的。那么我们的问题是什么？太少了：沟通渠道太窄，几乎是垄断性的，不够充分。” 32对于福柯来说，好奇心首先是一种立场；它是对当下的热情，是对长期形成的价值观和结构的不敬；它是准备接受惊喜和尝试不同观点的决心。要让好奇心发挥作用，必须打破限制信息的锁链，并诞生新的信息渠道来取代它们。我们需要的是桥梁的蓬勃发展，边缘工作的爆炸式增长。“我们必须增加来回移动的可能性”，沿着更加分化的网络。33只有通过这种增长模式——增加链接、关系和连接——才能构想出新的好奇配置，建立新的架构，并将新的亲和力缝合在一起。好奇心是穿越网络的流浪者，是一次随机游走，是一次跨越网格的突进，它有能力颠覆一切。

Foucault is a twentieth-century thinker of power and, specifically, the power to resist established ways of thinking and doing. For him, curiosity is central to that resistance insofar as it reenvisions and revamps inherited pathways.31 Musing on the perennial suspicion of mass media—as a dystopian deluge of details that dulls the mind and deadens the will—Foucault instead insists upon the proliferation of information and its inherent importance for curiosity. The exponential growth of information networks, whatever the value of the information itself, is crucial for the critical capacity to think, do, and be otherwise. Put quite simply, information networks precondition curiosity. “I dream of a new age of curiosity,” he writes. “We have the technical means; the desire is there; there is an infinity of things to know; the people capable of doing such work exist. So what is our problem? Too little: channels of communication that are too narrow, almost monopolistic, inadequate.”32 For Foucault, curiosity is a stance more than anything else; it is a passion for the present, and an irreverence for long-sedimented values and structures; and it is a readiness to be surprised and a determination to try a different point of view. For curiosity to function, the chains that constrain information must be broken and new information channels must be born in their place. What is needed is a burgeoning of bridges, an explosion of edgework. “We must increase the possibility of movement backward and forward,” along ever more differentiating networks.33 It is only via this growth pattern—of multiplying links, relations, and connections—that newly curious configurations can be conceived, new architectures erected, and new affinities sewn together. Curiosity is a rogue shuttling across networks, a randomized walk, a lunging across lattices that has the capacity to upend it all.

对于福柯来说，这种好奇心的工作不仅仅是智力或观念性的。他从不喜欢孤立地谈论权力或知识，而是总是谈论权力-知识，连字符表示信息始终是物质的，而具体化始终是理论的。蓬勃发展的信息网络也是快速增殖的可能性网络，可以为情感和行动、权力的沉淀和抵抗行为提供可能性。在最近的一次采访中，福柯用网络术语讨论了这种活生生的抵抗。酷儿人群从顺性别异性恋规范的世界继承了一套实践，包括既定的说话、思考、感受和性关系和恋爱关系的方式。也就是说，有一些老套的道路，深深刻在网络架构中，通常定义了男人和女人的浪漫传奇。面对这些既定的网络，酷儿人群的任务是“逃离……”酷儿们必须“打破这些现成的公式”，并“发明”一些仍然“不可能”的东西：“情感强度”和“生活方式”，这些生活方式跨越了继承下来的公式和制度化的模式。也就是说，酷儿生活需要重新配置网络，重新设计图表的运行方式。要做到这一点，酷儿们必须以“倾斜”的方向思考和行动，不断在社交网络中创造“对角线”。在这些新模式中移动需要他们“发明……他们必须创造新的意义形式和意义来源；他们必须讲述新的故事。最终，鉴于“现有的东西远不能填满所有可能的空间”，更多的信息渠道的产生为抵抗和重构创造了更多的机会。34有了更多的面料，就可以有更多的制作。

For Foucault, this work of curiosity is not simply intellectual or ideational in nature. He prefers never to speak of power or knowledge in isolation but instead always of power-knowledge, the hyphen signifying that information is always material and the embodied is always theoretical. Burgeoning information networks are also fast-proliferating webs of possibility for affects and actions, sedimentations of power and acts of resistance. In a late interview, Foucault discusses this lived resistance in network nomenclature. Queer people inherit a set of practices from the cisheteronormative world that includes settled ways of speaking, thinking, feeling, and relating both sexually and romantically. That is, there are well-worn pathways, deeply etched network architectures that typically define the romantic sagas of men and women. In the face of those established networks, the task of queer people is to “escape . . . [these] readymade formulas” and “invent” something still “improbable”: “affective intensities” and “way[s] of life” that traverse inherited formulas and institutionalized patterns. That is, queer life requires reconfiguring networks, revamping the ways a graph is walked. To do so, queer people have to think and move in a “slantwise” direction, constantly creating “diagonal lines” in the social network. Moving in these new patterns requires that they “invent . . . the meaning of [that] movement.” They must generate fresh forms of signification and sources of significance; they have to tell new stories. Ultimately, given that “what exists is far from filling all possible spaces,” the generation of more channels of information creates more chances for resistance and reconfiguration.34 With more fabric, there can be more fabrication.

福柯认为，信息网络是思考、做事和存在方式的先决条件，这一假设在土著哲学中有着古老、丰富且至今仍强有力的先例。土著哲学植根于“一切存在都与其他一切相连”的智慧，强调庞大而复杂的关系网络系统。西方哲学，尤其是后启蒙运动时期的哲学，通常强调知者和已知者的个体节点，而土著哲学则始终致力于边缘思维。英语中 70% 是名词，而波塔瓦托米语中 70% 是动词，这并非无关紧要。35或者西方定居者将土地概念化为私有财产和商品资本，而土著人民则将其理解为更大礼物经济中的结缔组织。零碎和一块一块的精神差异再明显不过了。在土著的本体论认识论中，人们总是通过与其他认知者的亲密关系来认识，这不仅包括社区成员，也包括地球本身的所有组成部分。在《编织甜草》一书中，波塔瓦托米植物学家罗宾·沃尔·金默勒讲述了她自己的土著好奇心的故事。从小被“鞋盒里的种子和一堆堆压制的叶子”包围着，她知道是植物选择了她。36在大学里，她主修植物学，很快就学会了储存分类名称和功能事实，同时让她关注能量关系的能力被废弃了。直到重新与土著社区——特别是土著科学家——建立联系时，她才想起“亲密关系给了我们一种不同的看待事物的方式”。37现在，她的学术研究和推广工作都专注于尊重这种科学和社会智慧的光芒。

The Foucauldian assumption that networks of information precondition ways of thinking, doing, and being has an ancient, rich, and still robust precedent in Indigenous philosophy. Rooted in the wisdom that everything that exists is connected to everything else, Indigenous philosophy foregrounds the vast and complex system of relational networks. While Western philosophy, especially post-Enlightenment, has typically emphasized the individual nodes of knowers and knowns, Indigenous philosophy has consistently contributed to a thinking of the edge. It is not insignificant that the English language is 70 percent nouns, while Potawatomi is 70 percent verbs.35 Or that Western settlers conceptualize land as private property and commodity capital, while Indigenous peoples understand it as a connective tissue in a larger gift economy. The difference in ethos between piecemeal and of a piece with could not be more pronounced. In an Indigenous onto-epistemology, one is always coming to know in intimate relationship with other knowers, including not only community members, but also all the components of the earth itself. In Braiding Sweetgrass, Potawatomi botanist Robin Wall Kimmerer tells the story of her own Indigenous curiosity. Growing up surrounded by “shoeboxes of seeds and piles of pressed leaves,” she knew the plants had chosen her.36 Declaring a botany major in college, she soon learned to stockpile taxonomic names and functional facts, all while letting her capacities to attend to energetic relationships fall into disuse. It was not until rekindling her connections with Indigenous communities—and specifically Indigenous scientists—that she remembered how “intimacy gives us a different way of seeing.”37 Her scholarship and outreach are now focused on honoring this ray of scientific and social wisdom.

土著哲学最独特的地方或许在于它将关系宇宙论与关系认识论交织在一起。这种世界观的核心是“世界在任何一件事物中永恒的融合”，卡尔·米卡写道，这样“一件事物永远不会孤单，万物都在积极地建构和组成它。”从深层整体论的角度来看，存在的形而上学本质上是零散的，谈论了解任何一件事都是“最无用的”。38正如存在总是已经嵌入在相邻的存在物中一样，知识也总是已经嵌入在局部框架中。因此，针对殖民知识体系的去本地化和抽象化，布赖恩·伯克哈特主张恢复“亲密的认识亲属关系”。39这种关系不再静态地强调获取真理，而是注重意义建构的动态，传统上通过仪式和讲故事来支持。在这样的环境中，社区中的个人和与身体结合在一起的心灵是深刻理解的先决条件。正如托马斯·诺顿-史密斯所表达的，在土著哲学中，“关联性是一种世界秩序原则”。因此，知识不是严格意义上的命题性的，而是程序性的；它关心的不是知道什么，而是知道如何。它的智慧在于“分享”而不是“陈述”。因此，提出问题就涉及通过“生活”和“体现”来寻找现有的模式和新出现的联系。40好奇心不可避免地会在关系中产生和满足。

What is perhaps most distinctive about Indigenous philosophy is its imbrication of a relational cosmology with a relational epistemology. At the heart of this worldview is “the eternal convergence of the world within any one thing,” writes Carl Mika, such that “one thing is never alone and all things actively construct and compose it.” From this perspective of deep holism, a metaphysics of presence is inherently fragmentary and talk of knowing any one thing is “minimally useful.”38 Just as existence is always already embedded within contiguous existants, knowledge is always already embedded within local frames. Against a colonial knowledge system of delocalization and abstraction, then, Brian Burkhart argues for a restoration of “intimate knowing kinship relationships.”39 Such relationships dispense with a static emphasis on truth acquisition and focus instead on the dynamics of meaning making, traditionally supported through ceremony and storytelling. In such settings, it is the individual in the community and the mind united with the body that precondition deep understanding. As Thomas Norton-Smith expresses it, in Indigenous philosophy “relatedness [is] a world-ordering principle.” As such, knowledge is not properly propositional but instead procedural; it is less concerned with knowing what than with knowing how. And its wisdom lies in “sharing” more than “stating.” Asking questions, then, involves seeking out existing patterns and emerging connections through what is “lived” and what is “embodied.”40 Curiosity inescapably arises and is satisfied in relation.

尽管西方哲学中对好奇心的传统解释通常强调其在个体、独立认知者节点式知识获取中的作用，但网络方法必然会将节点淹没在网络中，并将注意力重新平衡在边缘能量上。虽然我们已经追溯了西方哲学中将好奇心视为一种联系实践或边缘工作的未被充分重视的历史，但我们也通过在福柯的政治哲学和土著哲学的认识论中考虑好奇心的作用来深化这一解释。不过，仍有不止一条研究线索可以探索。例如，在福柯和土著解释中，信息网络与社交网络、思维网络与物种网络之间究竟存在怎样的相互作用？好奇心在社会变革和环境治愈中分别扮演着什么角色？更广泛地说，好奇心的网络重构如何不仅挑战当代的好奇心哲学，而且挑战心理学和神经科学中关于好奇心的最新解释？

Although traditional accounts of curiosity in Western philosophy typically stress its function in the nodal acquisition of knowledge by individual, independent knowers, a network approach necessarily submerges the node in the network and rebalances attention on the energy of the edge. While we have traced an underappreciated history of thinking curiosity as a practice of connection, or as edgework, across Western philosophy, we have also deepened that account by considering it in action within the political philosophy of Foucault and the epistemology of Indigenous philosophy. Still, more than one line of inquiry remains open. Within the Foucauldian and Indigenous accounts, for example, what is the precise interplay between information networks and social networks, or thought networks and species networks? And what is curiosity’s role in social change and environmental healing, respectively? More broadly, how does a network reconfiguration of curiosity challenge not only contemporary philosophies of curiosity but also recent accounts of curiosity in psychology and neuroscience?

* * *

* * *

回想一下，虽然心理学将好奇心视为一种心理状态或一种性格特征以及相应的行为，但神经科学旨在确定好奇心的神经基础。在这两个领域的当代论述中，好奇心通常被理解为有机体获取和积累知识的动机。这种动机依次被描述为填补信息空白的需要，或获取生存和繁荣所需信息的进化能力。在许多情况下，这种好奇心是通过分配的操作任务或回答琐碎问题来测试的。将好奇心重新概念化为一种认识论联系的实践，将好奇的主体本质上嵌入关系中，这促使人们不仅在哲学上，而且在社会心理学和认知神经科学中对好奇心进行深入分析。在这个框架内，好奇心不再是一种抽象的情感、状态或特征，而是一种始终在运动中的实践，贯穿信息和社会网络。与一个旨在个性化和隔离（无论是询问者还是信息）的理论框架相比，关系网络方法引发了对生态效度的重新投资，在现场思考和重新思考好奇心。这种观点是有前景的，因为它重新根植于节点边缘关系中的好奇心分析，无论是通过神经科学、心理学和哲学，还是它们之间的跨学科对话来考虑。

Recall that while psychology focuses on curiosity as a mental state or a personality trait with corresponding behaviors, neuroscience aims to identify the neural substrates of curiosity. Within contemporary accounts in both fields, curiosity is typically understood as an organism’s motivation to acquire and accumulate knowledge. This motivation is characterized, by turns, as the need to fill a gnawing information gap or as the evolutionary capacity to secure information necessary for survival and flourishing. In many cases, such curiosity is tested through assigned tasks of manipulation or answers to trivia questions. Reconceptualizing curiosity as a practice of epistemic connection and the curious subject as essentially embedded in relations prompts a deepening analysis of curiosity not only in philosophy but also in social psychology and cognitive neuroscience. Within this frame, curiosity is less of an abstract affect, or state or trait, and more of a practice, always in motion, stretched across informational and social networks. Against a theoretical framework that functions to individualize and isolate—whether the inquirer or the information—a relational, network approach invites a renewed investment in ecological validity, thinking and rethinking curiosity in situ. Such a perspective is promising insofar as it reroots an analysis of curiosity in the node-edge relation, whether considered via neuroscience, psychology, and philosophy, or transdisciplinary conversations between them.

让我们回到医生兼自然历史学家奥劳斯·沃米乌斯。他是一位无畏的调查者，他走遍全球，收集——事实上是获得了——数不清的文物。这里有一个龟壳，那里有一只犰狳和麋鹿角，一个村庄的披肩和另一个村庄的盔甲。从硬币和化石到原创艺术品和土著文物，他把所有东西都带回了哥本哈根。在那里，他建造了沃米博物馆，这是一个在十七世纪几乎无可匹敌的珍奇柜。很容易把奥勒·沃米乌斯想象成一个孤独的珍奇者，他的收藏品就是一堆珍奇物品。但这些物品都是从关系、社会系统和生态网络中抽取出来的，在这些网络中，它们既扮演着物质角色，也扮演着象征角色。不仅是这些古玩像海星一样棱角分明，但奥勒·沃姆自己的好奇心也是殖民机器中的一个齿轮，他的兴趣就像帝国自然历史的许多手臂和腿。好奇心和古玩实际上从来都不是孤独的。但这引出了一个问题，一个人如何尊重（或贬低）他的好奇心和古玩之间相互嵌入的关系？他对哪些棱角有感觉？他对哪些棱角保持忠诚？沃姆博物馆脱离了它所赋予意义和形态的殖民机器会是什么样子？奥勒·沃姆本人并不是一个隐居者。他经常和妻子多萝西（她发明了切线一词）和他的宠物海雀（一种长得像企鹅的动物）在一起，是黑死病期间留在哥本哈根照顾病人的那种人——即使以自己的生命为代价。什么是建立在切线归属基础上的好奇心——它赋予了我们的生活和见解彻底的相互依存关系？

Let us return for a moment to physician and natural historian Olaus Wormius. The intrepid investigator that he was, he traipsed around the globe and collected—indeed acquired—untold troves of artifacts. A tortoise shell here, an armadillo and elk horn there, shawls from one village and armor from another. From coins and fossils to original artwork and Indigenous artifacts, he brought everything back to Copenhagen. There he crafted his Museum Wormianum, a cabinet of curiosities hardly rivaled in the seventeenth century. It is easy to think of Ole Worm as a solitary curiosus and his collection as a stockpile of curios. But each of these objects was extracted from a network of relations, social systems, and ecologies in which they played a material as much as a symbolic role. Not only were these curios deeply edged, like starfish, but Ole Worm’s own curiosity was also a cog in the colonial machinery, his interests like so many arms and legs of an imperial natural history. Curiosity and curios are never in fact solitary. But this begs the question, How does one honor (or dishonor) the relations in which one’s curiosity and curios are embedded? What edges does one feel for? And to which does one sustain fealty? What might the Museum Wormianum look like apart from the colonial apparatus in which it took meaning and shape? Ole Worm himself was no recluse. Often accompanied by his wife, Dorothy (who invented the term tangent) and his pet auk (a penguin look-alike), he was the sort of person who remained in Copenhagen during the Black Plague to care for the sick—even at the cost of his own life. What is a curiosity grounded in tangential belonging—one that grants the radical interdependence of our lives and our insights?

当一个人好奇时，他如何捕捉和编织一条线？从儿童故事到成人科幻小说，英国文学中一直存在着一种预感，即事实上整个世界都是由线连接在一起的。如果我们能看到它就好了！我们可以像《公主与妖精》中的艾琳那样，将一根线放在我们的手指和拇指之间，走进世界，追随它，无论它通向何方，最终找到存在、真理和归属的密码。或者像《变形人》中的马克一样，我们可以拉动悬挂在我们世界上不同长度和颜色的线，从中获得不同种类的力量，仿佛事物相互联系的方式是宇宙能量和洞察力的源头。作家亨利·詹姆斯在《小说的艺术》中令人印象深刻地观察到：“体验永远不会受到限制，也永远不会完整；它是一种巨大的感性，一种巨大的蜘蛛网，由最细的丝线组成。” 41小说创作——或者通过经验来创造意义——是一种穿线工作。人们如何追随这些线？人们用什么力量来编织它们，以编织出奇妙的生活结构？边缘工作邀请我们以一种节点获取永远无法做到的方式提出这些问题。

When one is curious, how does one catch and craft a thread? It is a long-standing hunch in English literature, from children’s tales to adult science fiction, that in fact all the world is threaded together. If only we could see it! We might, as Irene does in The Princess and the Goblin, position a thread between our finger and thumb, and journey out into the world, following it wherever it may lead, and ultimately find the cipher of being, truth, and belonging. Or like Mark in The Changeling, we might pull on the threads of varying lengths and colors that hang about our world and, from them, gain different kinds of power, as if the way in which things belong together were a source point for cosmic energy and insight. Writer Henry James, in “The Art of Fiction,” memorably observes, “Experience is never limited and it is never complete; it is an immense sensibility, a kind of huge spider-web, of the finest silken threads.”41 The work of fiction—or of crafting sense through experience—is a work of threading. How does one follow the threads? And by what force does one weave them in and out so as to craft the fabric of a curious life? Edgework invites us to ask these questions in a way that nodal acquisition never could.

中世纪末期，哲学家兼神学家德西德里乌斯·伊拉斯谟对狂热探索自然奥秘的不敬的好奇心深感悲哀；他尤其对天文学的傲慢感到恼火，称“测量星星”纯粹是“疯狂”。42到20 世纪末然而，20 世纪情况发生了逆转。哲学家兼经济学家亚当·斯密在其《天文学史》一书中不仅赞扬了对外星遗址进行好奇心的实践，还指出“好奇的注意力……努力将一件事与另一件事联系起来” 。43我们不必转向头顶的星星网络，而是转向我们体内的神经元网络和贯穿我们的想法。我们将研究这些联系可能教会我们什么关于好奇心结构的知识。因此，在下一章中，我们将把好奇心视为知识网络增长的一种实践，而不是将其作为知识获取的原则。

At the close of the medieval period, philosopher and theologian Desiderius Erasmus bemoaned the irreverent curiosity that feverishly ferrets out the secrets of nature; especially galled by the hubris of astronomy, he called the “measure of the stars” sheer “madness.”42 By the late twentieth century, however, the tables had turned. In his History of Astronomy, philosopher and economist Adam Smith not only praised the practice of a curiosity trained on extraterrestrial sites but also remarked that “curious attention . . . labors to connect one thing to another.”43 Without having to turn to the network of stars overhead, we turn to the network of neurons within us and the notions that traverse us. And we investigate what those connections might teach us about the architectures that characterize curious minds. In the next chapter, we therefore explore curiosity less as a principle of knowledge acquisition than as a practice of knowledge network growth.

3

3

网络范式

The Network Paradigm

好奇心并非偶然产生的孤立现象；它是经验是不断移动、变化的事物的必然结果，涉及与其他事物的各种联系。好奇心只是使这些情况变得可感知的倾向。

Curiosity is not an accidental isolated possession; it is a necessary consequence of the fact that an experience is a moving, changing thing, involving all kinds of connections with other things. Curiosity is but the tendency to make these conditions perceptible.

—约翰·杜威，《民主与教育》（1916年）

—John Dewey, Democracy and Education (1916)

当我们从丰富的历史记载中抬起头来时，我们重新与周围的环境融为一体。我们在哪里？啊，是的。在哥本哈根，看着 Ole Worm 弯腰为 Wormianum 博物馆捡起一件文物。我们小心翼翼地伸开腿，从漆黑的书页深处退回到我们头脑中新鲜而活生生的组织中。从这个最熟悉的有利位置，我们看向世界。我们发现——奇怪的是——时钟滴答得比以前更响，空气比以前更有兴趣弯曲我们手臂上的小毛发，透过窗户的光线比以前更加多彩。颜色。光的颜色。光的颜色发生了许多变化。

As we look up from the rich annals of history, we reengage with our surroundings. Where were we? Ah yes. In Copenhagen, watching Ole Worm stoop to pick up an artifact for the Museum Wormianum. Stretching our legs gingerly, we retreat from the deep recesses of darkened pages into the fresh living tissue of our minds. From this most familiar of vantage points, we look out at the world. We find—oddly—that the clock ticks more loudly than before, the air takes interest in bending the little hairs on our arms more curiously than before, and the light streams through the window more colorfully than before. Colors. The colors of light. Many changes in the colors of light.

刚才的同一种光线，现在看起来怎么会如此不同？科学家兼作家约翰·沃尔夫冈·冯·歌德在 1810 年出版的《色彩理论》中对此进行了深刻的阐述，作曲家路德维希·范·贝多芬也承认，这部著作与歌德其他“平淡无奇”的作品不同，具有“重要意义”。1在这篇论文中，歌德试图追溯“色彩现象的最初来源，追溯它们出现和存在的环境”。在书的最后，他指出，色彩策展人和保护主义者（科学家）在与哲学家同居后，刚刚完成的探索，获得了与世界不同的关系。“自然研究者不能被要求成为哲学家，但人们期望他已经养成了哲学思考的习惯，从本质上将自己与世界区分开来，以便在更高的意义上再次与世界联系起来。” 2我们成功地从好奇心的探究中解脱出单一的认知者，获得单一的知识，从而使自己与世界区分开来。这样一来，我们就获得了一个连接棱镜，一种感知和测量的工具，将我们自己与周围的世界以不同的方式联系起来。我们把棱镜放在眼前，踮起脚尖站在我们视野的边缘，……我们好奇的思想之光以各种颜色向世界相邻的球体的光线弯曲。如果好奇的思想是连接的，那么好奇心的科学就一定是连接的科学。而且不是单一的连接，而是复数的连接……是多彩的连接。

How does the same light, here just a moment ago, look so different now? Scientist and writer Johann Wolfgang von Goethe offers a thoughtful account in his 1810 Theory of Colours, which composer Ludwig van Beethoven kindly admits to be “important,” unlike his other “insipid” writings.1 In the treatise, Goethe sought to trace “the phenomena of colours to their first sources, to the circumstances under which they appear and are.” Toward the end of the book, he notes that the color curator and conservationist (the scientist), after cohabiting with a philosopher as we have just done, acquires a different relationship with the world. “The investigator of nature cannot be required to be a philosopher, but it is expected that he should so far have attained the habit of philosophizing, as to distinguish himself essentially from the world, in order to associate himself with it again in a higher sense.”2 We have distinguished ourselves from the world in successfully extricating the unitary knower, acquiring unitary knowledges, from our inquiry into curiosity. In so doing, we have gained a connective prism, an instrument of perception and measurement, linking ourselves differently to the world around us. Holding the prism to our eyes, we stand tiptoe at the edge of our seeing orbs, . . . the light of our curious thoughts bending in colors toward and into the light of the world’s adjoining sphere. If curious thought is connective, then a science of curiosity must be a science of connection. And not of a single connection but instead of connection plural . . . of many-colored connections.

我们以全新的视角重新审视好奇心科学的基础。联系意味着什么？我们在自然界中哪里看到联系？过去是如何研究这些联系的？哪些仪器、模型和理论被证明是有用的？是否存在一门可以准确地称为联系科学的科学学科？如果存在，那么这门学科在好奇心研究中会很有用吗？让我们从头开始，一个联系将两件事联系在一起。一旦抓住，这个小小的人工制品就把奥勒的食指和他对生的拇指连接起来了，他和懒猴和狐猴有相同的拇指，但和树上毛茸茸的金色狮子狮却没有。这是我们在寻找的那种联系吗？是通过触摸连接的，就像雪落在地上一样，还是通过物理接触连接的，就像我背靠在树根上，看着风吹动树叶，树叶吹动松鼠一样？或者我们是在寻找一种像绳索或细绳一样的束缚连接，或者是一种像管道或静脉一样的传导连接？奥勒拇指的传感垫位于远端指骨的骨质基底之上，远端指骨通过副韧带与近端指骨相连。韧带将两块骨头绑在一起并传导力量，从而确保远端指骨不会像陀螺一样在我们转动拇指时旋转。幸运。这是我们正在寻找的那种连接吗？或者我们是在寻找一种就像脐带将给予者和接受者连接起来以维持生命一样，或者可能是一种产生联系的方式，就像脊髓或腹侧神经索引起感官刺激一样？沿着 Ole 的远端指骨，有适当的掌侧指神经，将物品的触觉特征传递到大脑，通过考虑、比较和对比的心理操纵，物品被放置在他更广泛的收藏中。新旧事物之间的联系，反之亦然，产生了理解并产生了实现。将一个想法与另一个想法、一个概念与另一个概念联系起来，不仅改变了 Ole 对每个物品的单独看法，也改变了他对生命之树更广泛结构的看法。

With new eyes, we revisit the foundations of a science of curiosity. What does it mean to connect? Where do we see connections in Nature? How have they been studied in the past? What instruments, models, and theories have proven useful? Does there exist a scientific discipline that can accurately be called a science of connection? If so, might that discipline prove useful in the study of curiosity? Let’s start at the beginning, where a single connection links two things. Once grasped, the diminutive artifact connects Ole’s pointer finger with his opposable thumb, which he shares with the loris and lemur, but not with leontopithecus, that fluffy golden lion of the trees. Is this the sort of connection we are looking for? One that connects by touch, like snow resting on the ground, or one that connects by physical abutment, like my back leaning against the base of a tree as I watch the wind tussle the leaves and the leaves tussle the squirrels? Or do we seek a connection that tethers, like a rope or string, or perhaps a connection that conducts, like a duct or vein? The sensing pad of Ole’s thumb sits atop the bony substrate of the distal phalanx, which connects to the proximal phalanx by the collateral ligament. The ligament tethers the two bones to one another and conducts force, thereby ensuring that the distal phalanx never spins like a top as we twiddle our thumbs. Lucky. Is this the sort of connection we are looking for? Or do we seek a connection that generates, like an umbilical cord linking the giver to the receiver to support life, or perhaps a connection that engenders, like a spinal or ventral nerve cord that gives rise to the tickle of senses? Along Ole’s distal phalanx runs the proper volar digital nerve that transmits the artifact’s tactile features up to the brain, where the item is placed within his broader collection by the mental manipulations of consideration, comparison, and contrast. The connection of the new to the old, and vice versa, generates understanding and engenders realization. Connecting one idea to another, one concept to another, changes not just how Ole thinks about each item separately but also how he thinks about the broader structure of the tree of life.

接触或物理接触的连接，即束缚或传导，产生或引发，可以将两件事联系起来。但两个就足以说明好奇心的连接吗？还是我们需要了解如何连接两个以上？两个就足以说明生与死、光明与黑暗，更普遍地说，足以说明任何具有双重端点的线。一个连续体、一对对立面、黑白二元或简单的边界，都只需要一个二元连接。当我们考虑集合时，我们开始遇到麻烦。我们如何解析三种粒子（电子、质子和中子）或三条公设（牛顿运动定律）、四种粒子（规范玻色子）或四条公设（麦克斯韦电磁方程式）、五种柏拉图立体（四面体、立方体、八面体、十二面体和二十面体）或六个夸克（上、下、顶、底、奇异和粲）之间的联系概念。这种归属、社区或家族相似性的联系概念是什么？正如英国奥地利哲学家路德维希·维特根斯坦所说？如果我们从物理学的抽象转向生物学的具体性，也许问题（及其解决方案）将变得更加明显。让我们考虑一个头、两只耳朵、三个筛窦、四个附属物、五根手指……啊，是的，Ole 的传感垫，每个都位于远端指骨的骨质基底上。这五个连接在一起：一只手，让他能够抓住文物。手掌充当集合中所有元素之间的通用、无差别连接器，而不仅仅是元素对之间的连接器。这是一种不同类型的连接，一种集合类型的连接，我们作为科学家使用不同的词来表示它。而二元关系通常被称为在科学中，集合关系通常被称为超边。在我们的记事本中，我们将超边画成一个斑点状的轮廓，延伸并环绕集合中的每个元素，在视觉上让人联想到变形虫伸出手指状原生质突起的身体轮廓，或幼儿圆润的手的弯曲轮廓，胖乎乎的指骨伸展开来，以便在粉色建筑纸上描绘。边和超边都是单一的，每个都反映单个连接中的单一关系类型。

Connections of touch or physical abutment, that tether or conduct, to generate or engender, can link two things. But is two enough for a connectional account of curiosity? Or do we need to understand how to connect more than two? Two is enough for life and death, for light and dark, and more generally for any line with dual ends. A continuum, a pair of opposites, black-and-white binaries or simple boundaries, all need only a dyadic connection. Where we start running into trouble is when we think about sets. How do we parse the notion of connection among three particles (electrons, protons, and neutrons) or three postulates (Newton’s laws of motion), among four particles (gauge bosons) or four postulates (Maxwell’s equations of electromagnetism), among five Platonic solids (tetrahedron, cube, octahedron, dodecahedron, and icosahedron) or six quarks (up, down, top, bottom, strange, and charm). What is this connectional notion of belonging, of community, or of family resemblance, as Austrian British philosopher Ludwig Wittgenstein might have put it? Perhaps the problem (and its solution) will become more evident if we move from the abstraction of physics to the tangibility of biology. Let’s consider one head, two ears, three ethmoid sinuses, four appendages, five fingers . . . Ah yes, Ole’s sensing pads, each sitting atop its own bony substrate of a distal phalanx. These five are connected as one: a hand that allows him to grasp the artifact. The palm serves as a generic, indiscriminate connector among all elements of the set, not simply among element pairs. Here then is a different sort of connection, a set-type connection, for which we as scientists use a different word. Whereas a dyadic relation is typically referred to as an edge in science, a set relation is typically referred to as a hyperedge. In our notepads, we draw a hyperedge as a blob-like outline that reaches and encircles each element of the set, visually reminiscent of the bodily outline of an amoeba extending fingerlike projections of protoplasm or the bowed outline of a toddler’s rounded hand with pudgy phalanges spread out so as to be traced on pink construction paper. Both the edge and the hyperedge are unitary, each reflecting a single type of relation in a single connection.

二元或多元联系使我们能够理解任意数量事物之间的单一关系。但是，无论多大或多管齐下，单一联系是否足以解释好奇心？或者我们需要了解如何将联系相互联系起来？作为一个简单的思想实验，想象一个三角形。在自然界中，我们在山毛榉坚果、延龄草、三叶草、紫露草花、酢浆草叶、角叶蛾、三角叶、中心硅藻、山影、黄瓜肉、尾鳍和兰花中看到这些形状。从自然到思想，我们可以将三角形分解为其组成元素：三根梁通过铰链在接头处连接以形成三角形框架。通过将形状转换为框架，我们获得了更基本的结构，使我们能够以不同的方式思考概念及其联系。例如，考虑将光的概念拼接在一起的三角形框架。三角形框架顶部的交界处是绿光，左下角的交界处是橙光，右下角的交界处是紫光。框架连接绿光和橙光的边反映了“共享黄光”的关系。连接橙光和紫光的边反映了“共享红光”的关系。连接紫光和绿光的边反映了“共享蓝光”的关系。总之，我们有三个不同的概念和三个不同的边，我们从经验中知道这些成分形成了一个三角形。

Connections of a dyadic or multiadic linkage allow us to understand a single relation among any number of things. But is a single connection—no matter how large or multipronged—enough for a connectional account of curiosity? Or do we need to understand how to link connections to one another? As a simple thought experiment, imagine a triangular shape. In nature, we see these shapes in beech nuts, trillium, trefoil, spiderwort flowers, oxalis leaves, the angle shades moth, deltoid leaves, centric diatoms, mountain silhouettes, cucumber flesh, tail fins, and orchid blossoms. Moving from nature to mind, we can decompose the triangular shape into its compositional elements: three beams connected at the joints by hinges to form a triangular frame. By transforming the shape into a frame, we obtain a more elemental structure that allows us to think differently about concepts and their linkages. Consider, for example, a triangular frame stitching together the concepts of light. At the top junction of the triangular frame sits green light, at the bottom-left junction sits orange light, and at the bottom-right junction sits purple light. The edge of the frame connecting green to orange light reflects the relation “shares yellow light.” The edge connecting orange to purple light reflects the relation “shares red light.” And the edge connecting purple to green light reflects the relation “shares blue light.” In all, we have three distinct concepts and three distinct edges, and we know from experience that these ingredients form the shape of a triangle.

现在再次想象三角形框架，但这次缺少一条边。在自然界中，我们在分叉的树枝、分叉的小路、分叉的容器、分裂的纤维、飞舞的线团或分叉的河流中看到这种结构。从自然到心灵，我们可能会在关系中看到这种结构三个概念之间，其中两个概念可能相关，也可能不相关，这取决于上下文。例如，红色的概念通过“共同的颜色”关系与血液的概念相关联，血液的概念通过“与力量和活力的共同关联”关系与健康的概念相关联。然而，正如中世纪冒险故事的狂热读者所知，红色和健康可能相互关联，也可能不相互关联，这取决于上下文。当血液的红色留在体内时，我们将红色与健康联系起来，就像行动的潮红或不行动的脸红。相反，当血液的红色突破到体外时，我们将红色与死亡联系起来，就像致命的伤口一样。楔形与三角形不同，它在这里提供了上下文灵活性的潜力，以及储存能量和可能性的弹簧；就像叉骨（叉骨：鸟的融合锁骨）一样，楔形捕捉了概念收缩的向下推力只会在向上推力时弹回，在思维概念扩展中张开翅膀飞翔。请注意，楔形也可能表示第三个环节不存在或尚不为人所知。

Now imagine the triangular frame again, but this time with one edge missing. In nature, we see this structure in a branching twig, a forking path, a bifurcating vessel, a splitting fiber, a flying skein, or a diverging river. Moving from nature to mind, we might see this structure in the relations among three concepts, two of which may or may not be related depending on the context. For instance, the concept of red is linked to the concept of blood by the relation “shared color,” and the concept of blood is linked to the concept of health by the relation “shared association with strength and vitality.” Yet as avid readers of medieval adventure stories know, red and health may or may not be associated with one another depending on the context. When the red of the blood remains inside the body, we associate red with health, as in the flush of action or the blush of inaction. In contrast, when the red of the blood breaks through to the outside of the body, we associate red with death, as in a mortal wound. The wedge shape, unlike the triangle, here provides the potential for contextual flexibility as much as for stored energy and the spring of possibility; like the wishbone (furcula: fused clavicles of a bird), the wedge shape captures the energy of the downward thrust of conceptual contraction only to spring back in the upstroke, lifting the wings for flight in the conceptual expansion of the mind. Note that the wedge shape could also indicate that the third link does not exist or is simply not yet known.

三角形和楔形是连接图案的两个常见例子。当我们好奇时，我们可能会在概念中寻找（或找到）三角形，或者寻找（或找到）楔形。或者，我们可能会通过在飞线的尾线之间添加一条新边来填补明显的信息空白，从而将楔形转变为三角形。但我们的思维是否必须局限于只在三元图案中进行交易？难道我们不能想象矩形、五边形或六边形框架吗？或者七边形、八边形、九边形和十边形框架？是的，我们可以。我们还可以想象每个框架都删除了一条或多条边。或者我们可以想象每个框架在非相邻连接点之间添加一条或多条边，迭代地将多边形转变为在风中飘扬的阿尼希那比捕梦网。随着我们的成长、发展和学习，我们似乎很自然地会建立起不仅一种概念之间联系的形式，而是多种形式——有些是缝合在一起的，有些是孤立的，有些是社会上疏远的，等待时间和自由来拉近距离。在我们生活的某些领域，也许我们在全面正规教育的支持下建立网格，然后限制我们对一门严格学科的知识，就像在网球拍面的网眼上放一个光滑的边缘一样。在我们生活的其他领域，也许我们建立的几何拼贴和镶嵌的混合体让人联想到准晶体（p 型、f 型或二十面体），不断填充我们可用的概念空间，但缺乏平移对称性。然而，在我们一生中的大部分时间里，我们所建造的建筑可能都远离网格、网状和镶嵌图案，而更类似于河流网络、真菌菌丝体、树枝状乔木和香茅根茎。我们如何开始理解特定的思维流如何构成思维的河流网络？为什么一个思维的网络与另一个思维的网络不同以及如何不同？我们如何解剖、检测、辨别、发现和描述我们在与世界进行好奇交流时建立的连接模式？

Triangles and wedges are two common examples of connectional motifs. When we are curious, we may seek (or find) triangles among concepts, or we may seek (or find) wedges. Or perhaps we may seek to transform a wedge into a triangle by filling the apparent information gap by adding a new edge between the trailing lines of the flying skein. But need our minds be constrained to only trade in triadic motifs? Could we not imagine rectangular, pentagonal, or hexagonal frames? Or heptagonal, octagonal, nonagonal, and decagonal frames? Yes, we could. We could also imagine each of those frames with one or more edges removed. Or we could imagine each of those frames with one or more edges added between nonadjacent junctions, iteratively transforming the polygon into an Anishinaabe dreamcatcher waving in the wind. As we grow, develop, and learn, it seems natural that we might build not just one shape of connections between concepts but instead many shapes—some stitched together, some isolated, and some socially distanced waiting for the time and freedom to draw closer. In some areas of our lives, perhaps we build in grids under the auspices of a comprehensive formal education and then circumscribe our knowledge of a rigorous discipline as if placing a smooth rim about the string mesh of a tennis racquet face. In other areas of our lives, perhaps we build in mixtures of geometric tiling and tessellation reminiscent of quasicrystals (p-type, f-type, or icosahedrite), continuously filling our available conceptual space, but in a way that lacks translational symmetry. Probably in most of our lives, though, we build in architectures far from grids, meshes, and tessellations, and more akin to river networks, the mycelium of fungi, dendritic arbors, and the rhizomes of sweetgrass. How do we begin to understand how a particular flow of thought makes the river network of a mind? Why and how does the network of one mind differ from that of another? How do we dissect, detect, discern, discover, and describe the connectional patterns we build as we lay down edgework in curious communion with our world?

绘画网络

Painting Networks

在罗伯特·麦克法兰的《地标》 ——一本关于语言和景观的精彩书籍中，他回忆起邀请他的导师、英国作家、纪录片制作人和环保主义者罗杰·迪肯到剑桥大学就他在英国水道方面的工作发表演讲。麦克法兰回忆说，罗杰并没有像典型的牛津剑桥研讨会那样，对严谨的逻辑有所期待。水——这是罗杰的主题——“并不严谨，罗杰也没有”，麦克法兰观察到，就好像水的蓝色绝对不是剑桥的蓝色。“对罗杰来说，水在文化中流动得又快又疯狂：它千变万化，是‘滑动形状’……所以这就是他追随它的方式，既马虎又井井有条，从这里的一个词转到那里的一个想法，追寻水的影响，速度太快了，他的笔记或观众都无法跟上，加入他的……通过看不见的隧道和排水网络，罗杰的思维追随他好奇的对象（水），通过他说话的方式（流动、隧穿和排水）描绘出它的网络结构（水道）。就好像水在罗杰话语的液面上看到了自己清秀的面容。这种反思让人想起古代和中世纪修辞学中的导管概念：“人们在作品中移动的‘路线’，以各个部分的‘模式’或‘颜色’为标志的路径，……作品的基本方向，像渡槽中的水一样，流经途中遇到的任何建筑类型，”著名的中世纪修辞学和美学学者玛丽·卡拉瑟斯写道。“事实上，导管强调运动，即思考的思维在作品中的行为。” 4我们当代的导管是什么？我们通过什么路线、小路和渡槽移动，以什么方式和颜色移动？无论是在独处还是在社会中，思维如何追踪和追踪知识的网络结构？我们追踪的那些结构是什么？对于河流网络，我们可以在一张二维的纸上画出通道线或航程脉络。但是，我们如何以及在什么物质上描绘思维网络呢？

In Robert Macfarlane’s Landmarks, a marvelous book about language and landscape, he recalls inviting his mentor, Roger Deakin, an English writer, documentarian, and environmentalist, to give a lecture at the University of Cambridge regarding his work on UK waterways. Macfarlane recalls Roger departing from the expectation of rigorous logic that is characteristic of the typical Oxbridge seminar. Water—which was Roger’s subject—“doesn’t do rigor in that sense, and neither did Roger,” Macfarlane observes, as if the blue of water were definitively not the blue of Cambridge. “For Roger, water flowed fast and wildly through culture: it was protean, it was ‘slip-shape’ . . . and so that was how he followed it, slipshod and shipshape at once, moving from a word here to an idea there, pursuing water’s influence, too fast for his notes or audience to keep up with, joining his . . . watery subjects by means of an invisible network of tunnels and drains.”3 Roger’s mind followed his subject of curiosity (water) by tracing out its network architecture (waterways) in the way he spoke (flowing, tunneling, and draining). It’s as if water saw its own comely face reflected in the liquid surface of Roger’s words. This type of reflection is reminiscent of the notion of ductus in ancient and medieval rhetoric: “the ‘route’ in which one moves through a composition, a path marked by the ‘modes’ or ‘colors’ of its varying parts, . . . the basic direction of a work, which flows along, like water in an aqueduct, through whatever kinds of construction it encounters on its way,” writes Mary Carruthers, a notable scholar of medieval rhetoric and aesthetics. “Indeed, ductus insists upon movement, the conduct of a thinking mind on its way through a composition.”4 What is our contemporary ductus? Through what routes, paths, and aqueducts do we move, and in what modes and colors? How does the mind track and trace through the network structures of knowledge, either in solitude or in society? And what are those architectures that we trace? For river networks, we can draw lines of passage or paint veins of voyage on a two-dimensional bit of paper. But how, and upon what substance, do we paint the networks of the mind?

在寻求答案时，我们自然会求助于连接的形式科学。网络科学是研究由以下部分组成的系统：网络科学是一门相对年轻的研究领域，它于 2000 年左右成立了第一所正式研究所，大约十年后开设了第一批本科和研究生学位。网络科学对全球研究资助机构的使命至关重要，它在极短的时间内确保了生物学、生态学、神经科学、社会科学、技术和工程等领域的根本性进步。每项研究都从还原论方法开始，即描述系统的单元（称为网络节点）和这些单元之间的关系（称为网络边缘）。然后，我们脱下还原论者的帽子（我总是想象它是一顶无檐便帽——戴着它数豆子），戴上建构论者的帽子（当然，是夏洛克·福尔摩斯的猎鹿帽——戴着它用编织的花呢连接线索）。穿戴整齐后，我们拿起调色板和画笔，在网络科学家的典型画布上作画：由 N 行和 N 列组成的表格中纵横交错的纤维，其中 N 是系统中的单元数。在第 i 行和第 j 列的交叉点处有一个数字，表示单元 i 与单元 j 的连接强度。要知道要填充哪些交叉点以及用什么数字，我们将目光转向真实系统，注意每个身份点和每个连接点，然后再转回画布，尝试准确描绘。就像任何绘画一样，我们绘制的描绘并不像真实系统那样生动活泼，而是代表和编码。在绘制网络时，我们构建了一个摘要或模型，以期从中获得理解。

In seeking answers, we naturally turn to the formal science of connection. Network science is the study of systems that are composed of many units linked in complex patterns of connection. It provides a mathematical language in which to describe the architecture of those patterns and to explain the functions supported by that architecture.5 A relatively young field of inquiry, network science saw its first formal institutes around the year 2000, and its first undergraduate and graduate degrees about ten years later. Of critical importance to the missions of research funding bodies across the world, network science has—in a remarkably short time—secured fundamental advances in biology, ecology, neuroscience, social science, technology, and engineering, among others. Each investigation begins with the reductionist approach of delineating the units of the system, which are referred to as network nodes, and the relations between those units, which are referred to as network edges. Then we doff the reductionist’s hat (which I always envision as a beanie—in which one counts beans) and don the constructionist’s hat (naturally, Sherlock Holmes’s deerstalker—in which one connects clues in woven tweed). Appropriately attired, we take up our palette and brushes to paint upon the network scientist’s typical canvas: the crisscrossing fibers of a table composed of N rows and N columns, where N is the number of units in the system. At the intersection of the i-th row and j-th column sits a number indicating the strength with which unit i is connected to unit j. To know which intersections to fill and with what numbers, we turn our eyes to the real system, notice each point of identity and each stroke of connection, and then turn back to the canvas to attempt an accurate portrayal. Like any painting, the depiction we produce does not live and breathe as the true system might but instead it represents and it encodes. In painting the network, we construct a summary or model from which we seek to derive understanding.

理解源自对网络架构的仔细研究，而每个系统都有自己的架构。我们假设在周围世界中可以观察到的不同连接模式的数量由表格可以填充的独特方式的数量决定。作为一个简单的第一个例子，让我们考虑一下知识系统。想象一下世界上所有的知识点；这个数字是 N，即行数——或者等价地，列数。现在想象一下这些知识片段可以以多种方式相互关联——表格中元素的颜色有很多种。随着我们考虑到思维的特质和时代的独特性，随着未知在发现过程中变成已知，或者已知在证伪或遗忘过程中变成未知，这些方式的基数会增长、复合和倍增。可能性似乎无穷无尽。我们如何将这些可能性整理成原则？或者将表现型归类？或者将模式编入卡片？网络科学提供了一组统计指标，我们可以使用这些指标定量而准确地描述任何观察到的连接模式。这些指标不仅使我们能够说出，例如，埃菲尔铁塔的铁格子结构与普通输电塔的钢格子结构不同，而且还能说出这种差异的方式和程度。类似地，这样的衡量标准可以让我们描述思想之间的运动模式，比如小说家乔治·佩雷克 (Georges Perec) 的《生活：用户手册》的故事情节，其中追踪了骑士在西蒙-克鲁贝利尔街 11 号一栋公寓楼的十乘十网格（十层，每层十个房间）中的巡回（棋盘上骑士的移动），……或者像小说家胡利奥·科塔萨尔 (Julio Cortázar) 的《跳房子》的叙事一样，可以按第一顺序阅读（第 1 章至第 56 章，按数字顺序阅读），也可以按第二顺序阅读（第 73-1-2-116-3-84-4-71-5-81-74-6-7-8-93-68等等）。无论感兴趣的网络主要是可以发生过程的结构（平衡力量以达到高度、维持刚性和保持稳定性的格构塔）还是结构上过程的结果（通过人物、事件和地点的概念空间构建的故事的连接组织），其架构都是可测量、可计算和可制表的。

Understanding arises from a careful study of the network’s architecture, which is peculiar to each system. The number of different connection patterns that we could hypothetically observe in the world around us is given by the number of unique ways in which the table can be filled. As a simple first example, let’s consider the system of knowledge. Imagine all the bits of knowledge in the world; that number is N, the tally of rows—or equivalently, the count of columns. Now imagine the many ways in which those bits of knowledge could be related to one another—the many ways to color in the elements of the table. The cardinality of these ways grows, compounds, and multiplies as we consider the idiosyncrasies of minds and the distinctiveness of times, as unknowns become knowns in the process of discovery, or knowns become unknowns in the processes of falsification or forgetting. The possibilities feel boundless. How do we wrangle those possibilities into principles? Or categorize phenotypes into classes? Or catalog patterns onto cards? Network science offers a set of statistical measures that we can use to quantitatively and precisely describe any observed connectivity pattern. Such measures allow us not only to state, for instance, that the iron lattice architecture of the Eiffel Tower is different from the steel lattice architecture of a common transmission tower but also to state the manner and extent of that difference. Similarly, such measures allow one to describe the patterns of movement among ideas, such as in the storyline of novelist Georges Perec’s Life: A User’s Manual, which traces a knight’s tour (the movement of a knight on a chessboard) across the ten-by-ten grid (ten floors, with ten rooms per floor) of an apartment building on 11 rue Simon-Crubellier, . . . or as in the narrative of novelist Julio Cortázar’s Hopscotch, either read in the first order (chapters 1 through 56 in numerical sequence) or the second (chapters 73-1-2-116-3-84-4-71-5-81-74-6-7-8-93-68 and so on). Whether the network of interest is primarily a structure upon which a process can occur (a lattice tower balancing forces to attain height, sustain rigidity, and retain stability) or the outcome of a process upon a structure (the connective tissue of a story constructed by a walk through a conceptual space of characters, events, and locations), its architecture is measurable, calculable, and tabulatable.

一个特别值得研究的网络特征是局部聚类。在简单网络中，边要么存在（表中为 1），要么不存在（表中为 0），聚类系数可以定义为连接三角形的数量（三个节点和三个边）与连接三元组的数量（三个节点和两个边）之比。直观地看，二维三角网格具有较高的聚类系数（许多三角形），而轮辐式结构或星形具有较低的聚类系数（零个三角形）。三角形的有效闭合支持可能沿着网络边缘流动的内容、电流或食物的汇合。要了解其工作原理，让我们来看看塞维利亚主教和学者伊西多尔的《词源学》的副本，该书于 12 世纪第三季度出版，现藏于法国杜埃市立图书馆。6这本书图文并茂，以一首写在三角网格上的宗教诗歌开篇。页面被切成八个方框；四个方框从上到下横跨页面左侧，相邻的四个方框横跨页面右侧。每个方框的中心都有八个管子，它们向外放射状延伸，将方框分成三角形。诗中的单词写在每一根内管和外框周围，用相交的短语填满整个三角形网格，从而引导读者从多个方向跟随作者的思路。（这是一场选择你自己的冒险。）三角形使我们能够沿着许多不同的短语路径到达任何给定的交叉点，根据我们选择的遍历方式，为我们带来不同的上下文。（这首诗的几何形状与梵蒂冈图书馆中另一首诗的几何形状相似，属于从古代到今天的迷宫诗的广泛类型。）7在这里，三角形引导着思想的实现。但我们不必止步于抽象。确实，三角形与思维的上层有关，但它们也与整个思维有关深入到底层生物学的最深处。在这里，在骨幕后面脉动的细胞黑暗潮湿的空间中，三角形引导着大脑的发育。沿着大脑中信息传输的物理路径，三角形允许替代路线，并被认为支持灵活高效地传播人类认知、感知和行动所需的信息。8

One network feature that is particularly interesting to study is local clustering. In a simple network where edges either exist (a one in the table) or do not exist (a zero in the table), the clustering coefficient can be defined as the ratio of the number of connected triangles (three nodes and three edges) to the number of connected triples (three nodes and two edges). Intuitively, a triangular mesh in two dimensions has a high clustering coefficient (many triangles) whereas a hub-and-spoke architecture or star has a low clustering coefficient (zero triangles). The effective closure of triangles supports the confluence of content, current, or comestibles that may be traveling along the network edges. To see how this works, let’s examine a copy of prelate and scholar Isidore of Seville’s Etymologiarum, from the third quarter of the twelfth century, housed in the Bibliothèque Municipale in Douai, France.6 Richly illuminated, the book opens with a religious poem written on a triangular grid. The page is cut into eight square frames; four span the left side of the page from top to bottom and an adjoining four span the right side of the page. In the center of each square originate eight tubes that emanate radially outward, octisecting the square into triangles. The words of the poem are written around each bit of inner tubing and outer framing, filling the full triangular grid with intersecting phrases, thus inviting the reader to follow the writer’s thoughts in a plethora of directions. (An adventure of the choose-your-own-ductus variety.) The triangles allow us to arrive at any given junction along many different paths of phrase, bringing with us different contexts depending on the traversal we have chosen. (The geometry of this piece is similar to that of another in the Vatican library and falls under the broad genre of labyrinth poems, which spans from ancient times to today.)7 Here, triangles guide the fruition of the mind. But we need not stop at the abstract. True, triangles are relevant to the upper echelons of the mind, but they are also relevant all the way down to the deepest recesses of the underlying biology. Here, in the dark wetter spaces of cells pulsing behind their curtain of bone, triangles guide the fruition of the brain. Along the physical paths by which information is transmitted in the brain, triangles allow for alternate routes, and are thought to support flexible and efficient propagation of the information necessary for human cognition, perception, and action.8

第二个特别值得研究的网络特征是最短路径。在刚刚描述的中世纪诗歌中，从左上角（初始节点）到右下角（目标节点）的最短路径需要我们遍历八个短语（边）；当然，按照设计，可以从初始节点开始到目标节点结束，可以遍历许多更长的路径，但这里我们关注最短的路径。如果我们枚举所有可能的初始节点和最终节点对，计算每个节点之间的最短路径，然后取结果数字的平均值，我们将获得平均最短路径长度。最短路径长度通常较小的网络往往通过一些充当捷径的边来实现这一点，这些捷径将网络中彼此基本不相连的不同部分连接起来。捷径可以支持血管网络中营养物质的有效运输和分配、社交网络中人们之间思想的快速共享或概念网络中思想之间思想的快速跳跃。作为这种跨越的一个简单例子，我们想起五代诗人许隐，他将“弥色”（一种青瓷色）描述为“雕月光染山涧”。9要将月球与地球联系起来，需要一条概念上的捷径，跨越两者之间 238,900 英里的距离，然而这可以通过追踪一束月光在头脑中开辟一条捷径。同样，要将光与染料联系起来，需要一条概念捷径，跨越光子（光的元素）和 50 个原子串（染料分子的典型大小）之间巨大的空间尺度差异，但可以通过注意光吸收和光反射之间的密切关系在头脑中开辟这条捷径。跳跃是网络景观中的一条捷径，它使两个想法比它们原本可能出现的更接近。因此，直观地说，捷径引导着思维的跳跃。但我们也不必停留在抽象层面。捷径与底层生物学同样相关，它们在那里引导大脑的生理跳跃。连接不同大脑区域的物理线路导致平均路径长度较短，被认为是高速公路，不同类型的信息可以沿着这些高速公路跳跃到相关的局部区域进行整合和处理。10可能是大脑中的这些物理捷径让我们能够抓住溪流，将其从河床上提起，并将其抛向月球？

A second network feature that is particularly interesting to study is the shortest path. In the medieval poem just described, the shortest path from the upper-left corner (initial node) to the lower-right corner (target node) requires us to traverse eight phrases (edges); there are, of course by design, many longer paths that could be traversed starting at the initial node and ending at the target node, but here we focus on the shortest. If we were to enumerate all possible pairs of initial and final nodes, calculate the shortest path between each of them, and then take the mean of the resultant numbers, we would obtain the average shortest path length. Networks with generally small shortest path lengths tend to do so by having a few edges that serve as shortcuts, connecting disparate sectors of the network that are otherwise largely disconnected from one another. The shortcuts can support the effective transport and distribution of nutrients in vasculature networks, the swift sharing of ideas between people in social networks, or the rapid leaping of the mind between ideas in concept networks. As a simple example of such a leap, we think of Xu Yin, the Five Dynasties poet, describing mi se (a jade green celadon color) as “carving the light from the moon to dye the mountain stream.”9 To link the moon to the earth requires a conceptual shortcut across the vast 238,900 miles between them, yet that shortcut can be made in the mind by tracing a ray of moonlight. Similarly, to link light to dye requires a conceptual shortcut across the vast difference in spatial scales between a photon (the element of light) and a string of fifty atoms (the typical size of a dye molecule), yet that shortcut can be made in the mind by noticing the close relation between light absorbed and light reflected. The leap is a shortcut in the network landscape that brings two ideas closer than they might otherwise appear. Here then, intuitively, shortcuts guide the leaping of the mind. But again we need not stop at the abstract. Shortcuts are just as relevant to the underlying biology, where they serve to guide the physiological leaping of the brain. The physical wires that connect distinct brain areas, resulting in a short average path length, are thought of as highways along which quite distinct types of information can leap to the relevant local regions for integration and processing.10 Might it be these physical shortcuts in the brain that allow us to grasp the stream, lift it from its bed, and fling it about the moon?

思维网络

Thinking Networks

思维的跳跃、弹跳和跳跃，以及支持它的神经活动，与我们的好奇心和对各种问题的追求息息相关。但要利用网络科学来理解跳跃的好奇心，我们必须首先选择思维的单位。一个想法有多大？一个概念有多广阔或狭小？我们在这里跳跃的石头有多大？南·谢泼德（Nan Shepherd）是 20 世纪初至中期的苏格兰自然作家和诗人，她在《小鹿》中观察了“那个想法像一只受惊的小鹿一样跳跃而来 / 迷失在树林的掩护中”的经历，并讲述了她的追求“希望我能再次遇到 / 那个美丽想法的金色闪光”。11在这里，一个思维单位被描绘成小巧、精致、脆弱、新颖和自由的。然而，谢泼德对心灵物理运动的欣赏延伸到了其他思维单位，这些思维单位被描绘成大、强壮、有弹性、古老和扎实的。在《冬日的枝条》中，她将思想比作树枝，指出木质的枝条“在浩瀚的天空中颤抖着跃起”，就像“人类的思想/从大地的滋养中跃起一样。” 12是的，有些思想看起来很小，有些则似乎如果我们选择小的思维单位而不是大的思维单位，那么心智网络是否更容易或更不容易被网络科学描绘出来？

The bounding, springing, and vaulting of thought—and the neural activity that supports it—is germane to our curiosity, and to our pursuit of various lines of questioning. But to use network science to understand that leaping curiosity, we must first choose the units of thought. How large is a thought? How expansive or diminutive is a concept? What size stones are we leaping among here? In “Fawn,” Nan Shepherd, Scottish nature writer and poet from the early to mid-1900s, observed her experiences when “that thought came leaping like a startled fawn / to lose itself in cover of the wood,” and recounted her pursuit “if haply I might meet / the golden flash of that fair thought again.”11 Here a unit of thought is depicted as small, delicate, vulnerable, new, and free. Yet Shepherd’s appreciation of the physical movement of the mind extends to other units of thought, portrayed as large, strong, resilient, old, and grounded. In “Winter Branches,” she likens thought to the boughs of a tree, noting the way the woody arms “leap up quivering in the vastness” of the sky just as “the thought of humans / leaping from earth’s nurture.”12 Yes, some thoughts seem small and others seem large. Are the networks of the mind more or less easily painted by network science if we choose small versus large units of thought?

文献中现有的证据表明，网络科学可以灵活地应用于各种系统尺度，而不需要将任何一个尺度置于其他尺度之上。例如，在早期历史中，网络科学被用于构建社会群体的表征，以了解社会互动模式，量化单个个体对集体行为的影响，并预测投票模式或政治动荡等社会文化现象。13在这些努力中，分析单位可以从小到大：从人的部分（例如，驱动社会行为的大脑区域）到整个人（例如，具有特定身份的智能代理），然后到许多人组成的群体（例如，政党、社区或国家）。14网络科学在分析单位之间的灵活性也体现在它被用于研究所谓的好奇心器官：人类大脑的方式上。15大脑的网络表征通常从将组织细分为小到细胞或大到脑叶的部分开始。选择每个地块是因为它执行一项功能，并且地块的边界是根据解剖标记（组织的结构方式）或功能标记（信号的结构方式）选择的。16然后，使用硬连线连接或同步活动的估计值将这些地块相互连接起来。17在定义地块的不同空间尺度上，所得到的模式可以追踪一个人对经验、创造力和信息寻求行为的开放性。18从本质上讲，社会和大脑都是多尺度网络系统，它们——就像思想一样——可以具有在不同尺度上定义的有意义的单元。

The current evidence in the literature suggests that network science can be flexibly applied across a range of system scales and need not privilege any one scale above others. In its early history, for example, network science was used to build representations of social groups in an effort to understand patterns of social interactions, quantify the influence of a single individual on collective behavior, and predict sociocultural phenomena such as voting patterns or political tumult.13 Across these efforts, the unit of analysis could vary from small to large: from parts of a person (e.g., brain areas driving social behaviors), to the person as a whole (e.g., an intelligent agent with a particular identity), and then on to groups of many persons (e.g., parties, communities, or countries).14 The flexibility of network science across units of analysis is also evident in the way it has been used to study the supposed organ of curiosity: the human brain.15 Network representations of the brain typically begin with a subdivision of the tissue into parcels as small as cells or as large as lobes. Each parcel is chosen because it performs a function, and the parcels’ boundaries are chosen according to anatomical markers (the way the tissue is structured) or functional markers (the way the signals are structured).16 These parcels are then connected with one another using estimates of hardwired connections or of synchronous activity.17 Across different spatial scales at which parcels are defined, the resultant patterns track a person’s openness to experience, creativity, and information-seeking behaviors.18 In essence then, both society and the brain are multiscale network systems, which—like thought—can have meaningful units defined at different scales.

尽管网络科学可以接受思想的多尺度性质，但它仍然需要对每个节点进行精确、可量化的定义。思想是什么？是小（“三英尺高”），中等（“一个人的门厅壁橱大小”），还是大（“宏伟壮观，倾盆大雨，傲视群雄，拳头紧握的希望爆发，数百把大提琴”）？19哎——就像小鹿在数百棵树（或大提琴？）中跳跃，树枝（或弓？）随时待命，它是难以捉摸的。也许相反我们应该考虑思想在知识中更具体的成果。什么是知识？虽然《牛津英语词典》将知识笼统地解释为“已知事物的总和”，但丹尼尔·韦伯斯特 1828 年出版的《英语词典》更具体地指出，知识是“对存在事物或真理和事实的清晰而确定的感知；对我们想法之间的联系和一致、不同意和矛盾的感知。” 20那么，知识就是由通过关系连接起来的想法组成的网络。想法和思想不同吗？也许，通过考虑我们用来分享和保存知识的精确符号：语言符号，我们会获得更多的关注。语言由比“想法”和“思想”更精确定义的单位组成。这些单位存在于不同的时间尺度上，包括音素（短）、音节（中）和超音节对象（长），每个对象都由大脑的不同区域表示和处理。21在最精细的音素层面上，音素对会以特定的概率并排出现，概率集定义了语言的网络架构。22在更粗略的音系词形或词素层面上，如果词素在成人词汇中是音系相邻的，则可以通过链接词素来构建网络表示。23这种网络结构被认为使我们能够快速有效地从个人心理词汇中检索词形。24

Although network science can embrace the multiscale nature of thought, it still requires a precise, quantifiable definition of each node. What is a thought, whether small (“three feet tall”), medium (“the size of one’s hall closet”), or large (“with grandeur, and drenching, barrel-scorning cataracts, and detonations of fist-clenched hope, and hundreds of cellos”)?19 Ack—like the fawn bounding away through hundreds of trees (or cellos?), boughs (or bows?) at the ready, it is elusive. Perhaps instead we should consider the more concrete fruition of thought in knowledge. What is knowledge? While the Oxford English Dictionary provides a quite general account of knowledge as “the sum of what is known,” Daniel Webster’s 1828 Dictionary of the English Language more specifically claims that knowledge is “a clear and certain perception of that which exists, or of truth and fact; the perception of the connection and agreement, or disagreement and repugnancy of our ideas.”20 Knowledge then is a network composed of ideas connected by relationships. Are ideas different from thoughts? Perhaps we will gain yet more traction by considering the precise symbols with which we share and save knowledge: the symbols of language. Language is composed of units that can be defined more precisely than “ideas” and “thoughts.” Those units exist over different temporal scales including phonemes (short), syllables (middling), and suprasyllabic objects (long), each of which are represented and processed in different areas of the brain.21 At the finest level of phonemes, pairs of phonemes are found beside one another with some specific probability, and the set of probabilities defines a network architecture for the language.22 At the coarser level of phonological word forms, or lexemes, one can similarly construct a network representation by linking lexemes, if they are phonological neighbors of each other in the adult lexicon.23 The structure of this network is thought to allow us to swiftly and efficiently retrieve word forms from our personal mental lexicons.24

从音素和词素转向更大的语言单位，我们来到了语义网络，它代表概念（节点）和概念含义之间的关系（边）。25例如，大提琴（节点）通过具体关系“由木头制成”（边）与树木（节点）相连，也通过更抽象的关系“琴身结实”、“喜欢被演奏”和“枝条弯曲（树枝？）”相连。早期的研究认为语义网络是分叉结构，没有任何三角形；节点之间的连接仅由类包含关系决定，例如概念“树”分支到特定树种的较小概念。26但后来的研究断言，这种严格的、分层的分支结构可能无法解释大多数概念。27 如今，越来越多的数据支持了这样一种观点：语义网络并非特别像分叉网络，而是具有小世界组织（局部聚类伴随着一些捷径）和无标度组织（大多数节点具有少量连接，少数节点具有许多连接）。28这种聚类和连接异质性的组合被认为会影响我们形成和搜索语义记忆的方式。29 （啊，就是这个！）值得注意的是，不同类型的语义网络可以用不同的关系来构建。网络中的因果链接可以实现因果推理、因果推理和因果感知，而简单相似性的链接可以反映语言中同义词的结构。30

Moving from phonemes and lexemes to larger linguistic units, we come to semantic networks, which represent concepts (nodes) and relations between the concepts’ meanings (edges).25 For example, cellos (node) are connected to trees (node) by the concrete relation “is made of wood” (edge) as well as by the more abstract relations “has a sound body,” “enjoys being played upon,” and “is branched with bows (boughs?).” Early efforts argued that semantic networks were forking structures, without any triangles; connections among nodes were simply determined by class-inclusion relations such as the concept “tree” branching into the smaller concepts of specific tree species.26 But later work asserted that such a strict, hierarchically branching structure might not account for a majority of concepts.27 Today, data continue to mount supporting the notion that semantic networks are not particularly fork-like but instead have a small-world organization (local clustering accompanied by a few shortcuts) and a scale-free organization (most nodes having few connections and a few nodes having many connections).28 This combination of clustering and connectional heterogeneity is thought to impact how we form and search through our semantic memories.29 (Ah, there it is!) Notably, distinct types of semantic networks can be built with different relations. Causal links in the network can enable causal inference, causal reasoning, and causal perception, whereas links of simple similarity can reflect the structure of synonyms in a language.30

重要的是，由于每个人的经历不同，我们对单词之间的相似性或不相似性的评价也会略有不同；实际上，我们每个人的心理网络可能也不同。为了探究人们对相似性的不同看法，可以通过实验建立网络，实验中每个人类志愿者列出一系列单词，其中每个单词在含义上与下一个单词相关。31这些实验被称为词语联想或自由联想任务，你可能已经在英国作家 TH 怀特的一部鲜为人知的作品中见过它们，怀特最著名的作品可能是亚瑟王小说《石中剑》和《永恒之王》。在怀特后来的小说《玛莎姆夫人的安息》中，教授——一个好奇的角色——根本不记得自己要做什么，所以他用词语联想任务来解开谜团：

Importantly, because each of us has different experiences, we can each have slightly different appreciations for the similarities or dissimilarities between words; in effect, we may each have different mental networks. To probe people’s distinct perceptions of similarity, networks can be built from experiments in which each human volunteer lists a sequence of words where each word is related to the next by meaning.31 These experiments are referred to as word association or free association tasks, and you may have already met them in a lesser-known work of the English author T. H. White, perhaps best known for his Arthurian novels Sword and the Stone and The Once and Future King. In White’s later novel Mistress Masham’s Repose, the professor—a curious character—simply cannot remember what he was about to do, so he uses a word association task to solve the mystery:

一个小时后，教授试着挠头，发现帽子挡住了他的路，他很奇怪自己为什么要戴上它。他通过自由暗示和自我分析，尝试了几次来解决问题，最后决定他戴上它是因为要出去。于是他走出去，看着天空。天空似乎没有任何信息给他。于是他又进去，找到一张纸，在上面写下他集中精力思考帽子时想到的第一个词。这是tripharium。他把它撕碎了。然后又试了一次，得到了ratto，他认为这可能与汉诺主教和老鼠有关。于是他试了汉诺，得到了Windup，试了windup，得到了cape，试了cape，得到了ulster。他发现他戴着他的阿尔斯特，很高兴。接下来是一次漫长的旅行，游览了爱尔兰各省、四大大师年鉴等等，这让他回到了三叉戟。他试了一下，得到了 Bloaters，他现在完全把它和瑞典联系起来了，绕了哥德堡、斯威登堡、布莱克和古斯塔夫·阿道夫一圈，突然想起他已经承诺要找到玛丽亚。于是，他更加小心地把深绿色的礼帽顶在头上，然后小跑着去履行他的职责。32

An hour later the professor tried to scratch his head, found that the hat was in his way, and wondered why he had put it on. He made several attempts to solve his problem, by free suggestion and self-analysis, finally deciding that he had put it on because he was going out. He therefore went out, and looked at the sky. It did not seem to have any message for him. So he went in again, found a piece of paper, and wrote on it the first word which occurred to him while concentrating on hats. This was tripharium. He tore it up. And tried again, getting ratto, which he thought was probably something to do with Bishop Hanno and the rats. So he tried Hanno and got Windup, tried windup and got cape, tried cape and got ulster. He discovered that he was wearing his ulster, and was delighted. This was followed by a longish tour through the provinces of Ireland, the Annals of the Four Masters, and so forth, which brought him back to tripharium. He tried this, and got Bloaters, which he connected by now entirely with Sweden, took a short circuit through Gothenburg, Swedenborg, Blake, and Gustavus Adolphus, and suddenly remembered that he was pledged to find Maria. So he balanced the bottle-green bowler still more carefully upon his head, and trotted off to do his duty.32

词语联想任务不仅可以让我们想起我们当前的生活目标（就像教授所做的那样），还可以为科学家提供我们词语世界的网络地图：哪些词语生活在山谷中，与许多其他词语相邻（并连接），哪些词语生活在山顶上，与大多数其他词语隔绝（并断开连接）。除了表明某些词语在特定人的头脑中有多大联系外，网络图还提供了有关概念空间距离的信息：哪些词语居住在科罗拉多州的博尔德，而不是佛罗里达州的迈阿密，哪些词语居住在伦敦而不是利马。

Not only can the word association task remind us of our current purpose in life (as it did for the professor) but it can also provide scientists with a network map of our word-world: which words live in the valleys, adjacent (and connected) to many others, and which words live upon the hilltops, secluded (and disconnected) from most others. In addition to evincing how connected certain words are in a given person’s mind, the network map supplies information about distances in conceptual space: which words have their abodes in Boulder, Colorado, versus Miami, Florida, and which spend their days in London versus Lima.

当我们从音素到词素再到单词时，我们稳步走向更大的语言和思想单位。自然而然，在单词之后我们来到了句子。虽然奥勒·沃姆可能更喜欢前者（把物品分成“矿物质”、“木质素”和“萨利亚”），但我觉得弗吉尼亚·伍尔夫可能会邀请我们在后者中停留一会儿。对她来说，句子是超越时间的单位（“比圣诞假期更长久”），但值得标注日期（“1928 年 8 月”）。33它们是保持生命平衡的单位：一个句子可以扼杀一个思想（“它重重地掉到地上——死了”），也可以创造一个思想（“爆炸并催生出各种其他的想法”）。34它们是构成思想本质的单位：当在纸上遇到新朋友时，伍尔夫会首先“熟悉她的句子”，就像衡量作者的步态以确定他们是否是好的步行伙伴一样；她会“在我的舌头上滚动一两句话”，就像在吮吸黑加仑糖来评估其味道的深度和真实性一样。35句子可以“如此刻板，以至于它们像铃铛一样响亮”，也可以如此“不加掩饰”，以至于它们表现出“庄严而难忘的美”，就像一队“略带面纱”的身体，其轮廓是仍然可见。36无论如何，它们都留下了印记：“句子像水滴一样从窗玻璃上滚落下来，一滴接一滴，但当它们到达底部时，窗玻璃就被弄脏了。” 37每一个都可能包含“微小的信号，通过这些信号，一个短语被用来暗示、转变、生活”，然后“随着短语连接短语，一个接一个的括号涌入它的支流，我们感受到了整个游泳的溪流。” 38在这里我们再次遇到了心灵的河流。“品质，”伍尔夫写道，“不在于故事，而在于故事之上，不在于事物本身，而在于它们的排列。” 39事物的排列就是网络，是单元连接的方式，是思想的结构。我们在网络中写作。我们在网络中说话。我们在网络中思考。

As we move from phonemes to lexemes to words, we steadily walk toward larger units of language and thought. Naturally, after words we come to sentences. While Ole Worm may have preferred the former (binning items into “mineralia,” “ligna,” and “salia”), I feel as if Virginia Woolf might have invited us to stay awhile in the latter. To her, sentences are the units that defy time (“outlast the Christmas holidays”) and yet deserve to be dated (“August, 1928”).33 They are the units that hold life in the balance: a sentence can either kill a mind (“it falls plump to the ground—dead”) or create a mind (“explodes and gives birth to all kinds of other ideas”).34 They are the units that comprise the essence of a mind: when meeting someone new on the page, Woolf will first “get the hang of her sentences” as if gauging the author’s gait to determine whether they would be good walking companions; she will roll “a sentence or two on my tongue” as if critically sucking a blackcurrant candy to evaluate the depth and verity of its flavor.35 Sentences can either be “so stereotyped that they chime like bells,” or so “undraped” that they evince “a stately and memorable beauty” as a procession of “slightly veiled” bodies whose contours are still visible.36 Either way, they leave their mark: “sentences roll like drops down a pane, drop collecting drop, but when they reach the bottom, the pane is smeared.”37 Each may contain “minute signals by which a phrase is made to hint, to turn, to live,” and then “as phrase joins phrase and one parenthesis after another pours in its tributary, we have a sense of the whole swimming stream.”38 Here again we meet the river of the mind. “The quality,” Woolf pens, “is not in the story but above it, not in the things themselves but in their arrangement.”39 The arrangement of things is the network, the manner in which units are connected, the fabric of ideas. We write in networks. We speak in networks. We think in networks.

构建网络

Building Networks

我们头脑中的网络是如何形成的？与小精灵不同，它们不会自动出现。相反，它们是随着我们采取的每一个好奇行动而建立起来的。所获得节点的本质取决于所寻求的信息，而所构建网络的架构则取决于寻求的方式。我们每个人寻求的信息可能都不同，而且在我们的一生中也各不相同。在幼儿中，寻求信息可能意味着对“明亮、生动、令人吃惊”的物体高度关注和集中注意力，而在老年人中，寻求信息自然伴随着自愿运动（眼睛或身体），以获取更多知识。40人们可能会想象婴儿痴迷于棉球，球外面有五颜六色的天鹅绒补丁，上面有各种各样的丝带，丝带用防牙齿缝线缝制而成，人们可能会将这种狭隘的视野与研究生进入剑桥大学三一学院雷恩图书馆寻找一本关于“神经元、网络和星云”的权威书籍的视野进行对比。41除了寻求的信息之外，好奇行为还可以通过寻求的方式进行表征。这些好奇行为（或统称为这种实践）可能因人而异，可能随着年龄和认知发展而变化，并且可能受到压力和社会经济背景以及先前经验的影响。42直观地讲，好奇实践可能是不耐烦或忍耐。它可能涉及寻找完全未知或模糊熟悉的信息。它可能涉及收集新信息并将其像琐事一样单独记录，或者它可能涉及确定信息之间的联系以使其适合现有的知识体系。虽然这些好奇心的方式是直观的，但它们感觉很模糊。网络科学能让我们更准确地定义它们吗？我们能否将好奇心的实践分为几类，写下它们的性质的数学公式，并为它们的过程形成生成模型？每种实践可能建立什么样的网络？

How do the networks in our mind come to be? Unlike pixies, they cannot just appear of their own accord. Instead, they are built, with every curious action we take. The essence of the nodes gained is determined by the information sought, and the architecture of the network built is determined by the manner of seeking. We may each seek different information, and differently so across our life spans. In young children, information seeking can amount to a heightened attention and focus on objects that are “bright, vivid, startling,” while in older adults, information seeking is naturally accompanied by voluntary movements (of the eye or body) to gain more knowledge.40 One might envision the infant obsessed with the cotton-stuffed ball with colorful velvet patches on the outside and a rich smattering of various sorts of ribbons attached with teeth-resistant stitching, and one might contrast this parochial vision with that of a graduate student entering the Wren Library at Trinity College, Cambridge, seeking a definitive tome on “neurons, networks, and nebulae.”41 Apart from the information sought, curious actions can be characterized by the manner of seeking. These actions—or collectively this practice—of curiosity can differ across individuals, may change with age and cognitive development, and is likely impacted by stress and socioeconomic background as well as prior experience.42 Intuitively, the practice of curiosity could be impatient or enduring. It could involve seeking completely unknown or vaguely familiar information. It could involve gathering the new information and keeping it logged separately like bits of trivia, or it could involve determining the links between bits of information to fit them into one’s existing body of knowledge. While these manners of curiosity are intuitive, they feel nebulous. Might network science allow us to define them more precisely? Could we categorize the practices of curiosity into classes, write down mathematical formulations for their nature, and form generative models for their processes? What sorts of networks might each practice build?

发展实践科学要求我们了解知识的网络结构，以及知识如何在一个人或整个文化中发展。我们需要一部电影来代替一张图片。我们需要一个动力学方程来代替一个数字。我们需要一系列网络来代替一个网络，每个网络都代表给定时间点的系统。如今，许多自然和社会系统都开发了这种网络增长模型，每个模型都为节点的添加和边的放置制定了简单的规则。例如，社会联系的优先连接模型从连接两个节点的一条边开始，然后通过将新节点链接到一定数量的现有节点，迭代地将单个节点添加到网络，并优先选择已经高度连接的节点。43这个过程自然符合众所周知的社会动态，即已经受欢迎的人往往会在未来变得更受欢迎。在很长一段时间内，这种增长模式往往会形成无标度组织的网络，其中大多数节点的连接很少，而少数节点的连接很多。优先依恋模型可以为好奇心的实践提供哪些预测？如果我们的思维网络以同样的趋势增长，我们会发现我们添加的每个新信息节点往往与已经连接良好的节点相关；换句话说，我们对这些热门节点（我们认为最有趣的话题）的了解往往会随着我们学习新的关联、相同和差异的新维度以及新的相似性而增长，这些新维度总是将我们从不同的空间引导回我们的核心兴趣。由此产生的结构包含知识和无知的口袋；前者的枢纽在我们的脑海中映射出许多连接，而后者的节点则很少。因此，优先依恋模型对于那些培养明确激情的思想者来说特别有用，这些激情总是吸引、呼唤和强迫他们的注意力。

Developing a science of practice invites us to understand the network architecture of knowledge and how it might grow in a single person or across a culture. In place of a picture, we need a movie. In place of a number, we need an equation of dynamics. In place of one network, we need a series of networks, each representing the system at a given point in time. Such network growth models have now been developed for many systems in nature and society, each laying down simple rules for the addition of nodes and the placement of edges. For example, the preferential attachment model of social connection begins with a single edge connecting two nodes and then iteratively adds a single node to the network by linking the new node to some number of existing nodes, with a preference for nodes that are already highly connected.43 The process naturally aligns with the well-known social dynamics in which already popular people tend to become more popular in the future. Over long periods of time, this growth model tends to form networks with a scale-free organization, whereby most nodes have few connections and a few nodes have many connections. What predictions might a preferential attachment model offer for the practice of curiosity? If the networks of our minds grow with these same tendencies, we would find that each new node of information we add tends to be related to an already well-connected node; in other words, our knowledge of these popular nodes—the topics that we find most intriguing—tends to grow as we learn new associations, new dimensions of sameness and difference, and new likenesses that always lead us from diverse spaces back to our core interests. The resultant structure has pockets of knowledge and ignorance; the hubs of the former have many connections mapped out in our minds, and the nodes of the latter have few. The preferential attachment model, then, is a particularly useful one for the thinker who cultivates well-defined passions that always draw, call, and compel their attention.

从大规模的主题单位转向小规模的语言单位，我们要问，网络增长模型是否也适用于解释单词的习得和单词与单词之间的关系？在一个简单的语义网络增长模型中，新词以区分现有节点的连接模式的方式添加到网络中；该模型将任何新概念往往是旧概念的变体这一直觉付诸实践。44 它的存在、本质和性质都由其相关点和不相关点构成。因此，学习和成长是一个意义分化的过程，新事物的规范同时改变了我们对旧事物的理解。这种分化模型产生了小世界和无标度架构，与在真实的单词关联和同义词网络中观察到的架构一致。有趣的是，该模型还提出了一种机制，用于研究学习历史（单词习得的年龄或单词使用频率）对人类执行需要语义处理的实验室任务的方式的影响。同样，科学家们也曾研究过人类如何发展特定类型的语义网络，比如词语联想任务所显示的语义网络。有证据表明，优先依附模型结合了词频、音位邻居的数量以及新词与学习环境中的单词的关联性，可以合理地拟合从幼儿词汇量增长过程中获得的数据。45 人们通常认为，这种模型适用于各种各样的人。然而，确定如何调整这些模型以解释人与人之间的差异也很有趣。人类构建语义网络的不同方式是否部分源于他们性格或大脑回路的差异，或者解释了他们创造力的差异？46一个人的社会特权会支持（或劣势会限制）他构建语义网络的方式吗？在给定网络中或在给定时间内，哪些其他类型的限制可能会决定哪些边是可以放置的，哪些边是不可能放置的？

Moving from the large-scale unit of a topic to the smaller-scale units of language, we ask, Are network growth models also relevant for explaining the acquisition of words and word-to-word relations? In one simple model for the growth of semantic networks, new words are added to the network in such a way as to differentiate the connectivity pattern of an existing node; this model operationalizes the intuition that any new concept tends to be a variation on an old one.44 Its being, its essence, its nature are as framed by its points of relatedness as by its points of unrelatedness.
