知识网络在不断发展。每次发现，我们都会添加一个新节点（一个想法、一个模型、一个理论或一些证据），并将其与网络其余部分的一条边（关系、依赖或支持）连接起来。在不同的学科中，知识网络由一组特定的思想家和历史上发展起来的思想体系以不同的方式形式化。这些特定的起源加上研究主题本身的性质，可以共同导致每个领域特有的不同网络架构。哲学家、医生和海洋生物学家恩斯特·海克尔在 19 世纪 70 年代绘制了精美的放射虫（海洋原生动物；他命名了近 150 个新物种）、海绵动物（海绵）和环节动物（节肢动物），这幅画作为我们脑海中的一幅有用的画面。13尤其是放射虫，它们在 0.1-0.2 毫米的复杂矿物骨架中表现出令人难以置信的复杂网络结构，这些骨架通常由二氧化硅组成。Sphaerozoum variabile的细长骨针可能让人想起历史的长尾，通过一系列事件追踪生命的线性发展。14 Orosphaera huxleyii的规则网格可能让人想起线性代数中数学概念之间高度结构化的依赖关系。15 Octopyle stenozona的海绵状环可能让人想起幼儿早期词汇的结构，因为他们学会以一种说明的方式谈论他们的世界他们的理解中存在着许多小漏洞。16不同知识领域的多样化网络结构反映了我们世界的多样化网络结构。

Knowledge networks are constantly evolving. With each discovery, we add a new node (an idea, a model, a theory, or a bit of evidence) and connect it with an edge (of relation, of dependence, or of support) to the rest of the network. In distinct academic disciplines, knowledge networks have been formalized differently, by a specific set of thinkers and historically developed systems of thought. These specific origins coupled with the nature of the subject of inquiry itself can together lead to different network architectures characteristic of each field. A helpful mental picture can be found in philosopher, physician, and marine biologist Ernst Haeckel’s exquisite drawings of radiolaria (sea protozoa; nearly 150 new species of which he named), poriferans (sea sponges), and annelids (segmented worms) in the 1870s.13 The radiolaria, in particular, evince incredibly intricate network architectures in their 0.1–0.2 millimeter elaborate mineral skeletons, typically composed of silica. The spindly spicula of Sphaerozoum variabile may remind one of the lengthy tails of history, tracking the linear progression of lives through a series of events.14 The regular mesh of Orosphaera huxleyii may remind one of the highly structured dependencies between mathematical notions in linear algebra.15 And the cavernous loops of Octopyle stenozona may remind one of the structure of early vocabulary in toddlers as they learn to speak about their world in a way that illustrates the existence of many small holes in their understanding.16 The diverse network structures of different areas of knowledge mirror the diverse network structures of our world.

行走在知识网络上

Walking on Knowledge Networks

除了集体知识的正式领域之外，考虑一下我们每个人头脑中的知识网络也是很有意思的。这个个人网络不断地以我们每个人特有的方式和方向发展和成长。好奇心在已知和未知的间隙中、在知识网络的现实性和潜在性的边界上蓬勃发展。我们沿着连接信息片段的链接行走，然后站在虚空处大声呼喊。正如诗人沃尔特·惠特曼所说，我们“思考宇宙的裂口和未来”。17当我们找到或发现完全或部分填补空白的知识时，我们就在知识网络中建立了一个新的支架。

Beyond the formal areas of collective knowledge, it is of interest to consider the knowledge network inside each of our heads. That individual network is constantly evolving and growing in manners and directions that are idiosyncratic to each of us. Curiosity flourishes at the interstices of the knowns and unknowns, at the boundary between the actuality and potentiality of knowledge networks. We walk along the links that connect bits of information, and then stand at the void and shout across. With poet Walt Whitman, we “think a thought of the clef of the universe, and of the future.”17 When we find or discover knowledge that fully or partially fills the void, we have built a new bit of scaffold in our knowledge network.

这种行走、呼喊和填充在日常生活中是如何发生的？最近，我们有幸与通讯科学家戴维·莱登-斯塔利合作，他着手观察人类在集体知识网络上行走，从而建立个人精神网络。18我们选择了在线百科全书维基百科的集体知识网络，因为它相对容易踏入，可以从每个人自己的客厅（或卧室……或浴室！）访问。在这项研究中，志愿者参与者每天浏览维基百科十五分钟，持续二十一天。在他们浏览时，参与者同意安装在他们电脑上的一款软件向我们发送有关他们访问了哪些网站、访问顺序和访问时间的信息。然后，通过将每个维基百科页面视为网络中的一个节点，并将从一个页面到另一个页面的转换概念化为沿着连接它们的边的一步来分析数据。长步是内容不同的页面之间的步数，短步是内容相似的页面之间的步数。每个人采取的步骤顺序都反映了他们独特的好奇心风格、他们搜索动作的动觉以及他们知识网络的构建。

How does this walking, shouting, and filling happen in everyday life? Recently we had the privilege of collaborating with communications scientist David Lydon-Staley, who set out to watch humans walk on collective knowledge networks, thereby building personal mental webs.18 We chose the collective knowledge network of the online encyclopedia Wikipedia as it was relatively easy to step upon, being accessible from each person’s own living room (or bedroom . . . or bathroom for that matter!). In this study, volunteer participants browsed Wikipedia for fifteen minutes a day for twenty-one days. While they browsed, a piece of software—which participants had agreed to install on their computers—sent us information about which sites they visited, in what order, and for how long. The data were then analyzed by treating each Wikipedia page as a node in a network and by conceptualizing the transition from one page to another as a step along the edge connecting them. Long steps were those taken between pages with dissimilar content, and short steps were those taken between pages with similar content. The sequence of steps that each person took reflected their characteristic style of curiosity, the kinesthetics of their searching movement, and the building of their knowledge networks.

在收集的大量数据中，我们清楚地看到了两种好奇心原型的迹象，即好管闲事者和猎人，以及两者之间的一系列风格变化。19回想一下，猎人“希望有几百个帮手和训练有素的猎犬，以便他们能够深入人类灵魂的历史，围捕猎物”，有针对性地搜索信息；相比之下，好管闲事者“到处乱窜，随意漫游，随心所欲。” 20猎人和好管闲事者的这些运动特征应该自然而然地导致创建不同的个性化知识网络。与这一预期一致，我们发现，更像猎人的参与者会沿着高聚类网络散步，这意味着他们会在三个或更多高度相似的页面集合之间导航，在当地社区迈出小步。相比之下，更爱管闲事的参与者会沿着低聚类和长路径的网络行走，这意味着他们在高度不同的页面之间导航，迈出跨越许多不同社区的长步。有趣的是，参与者每周都在爱管闲事者和猎人之间移动，有时比有时更像爱管闲事的人（或猎人）。

In the many hours of data collected, we saw clear evidence for two of the archetypal styles of curiosity, the busybody and hunter, and a continuum of stylistic variation between them.19 Recall that the hunter “wishes [they] had a few hundred helpers and good, well-trained hounds that [they] could drive into the history of the human soul to round up [their] game” in a targeted search for information; in contrast, the busybody “frisk[s] about, and rove[s] about, at random, wherever they please.”20 These kinesthetic signatures of the hunter and busybody should naturally lead to the creation of different individualized knowledge networks. Consistent with this expectation, we found that the more hunter-like participants took walks that traced out networks with high clustering, meaning that they navigated among sets of three or more highly similar pages, taking short steps in a local neighborhood. In contrast, the more busybody-like participants took walks that traced out networks with low clustering and long path length, meaning that they navigated among highly dissimilar pages, taking long steps spanning many distinct neighborhoods. Intriguingly, participants moved somewhat along the continuum between busybody and hunter from week to week, being more busybody-like (or hunter-like) at some times than at others.

有趣的是，一种性格特征解释了爱管闲事者和猎手们不同的网络构建实践：他们对信息剥夺的敏感性。这一观察是通过在单独的测试环节中收集的数据实现的。参与者完成了心理学家实验室的一份量表，通过确定以下陈述对他们的特征的程度来衡量他们的剥夺敏感性：“思考困难的概念问题的解决方案会让我彻夜难眠”；“我可以花几个小时解决一个问题，因为如果不知道答案我就无法休息”；“如果我不能找出问题的答案，我会感到沮丧，所以我会更加努力地去解决它”；“我会不懈地努力解决我认为必须解决的问题”；“没有我需要的所有信息让我很沮丧。” 21剥夺敏感性高的人在遇到新信息并认识到知识上的差距时，会有一种消除未知的动力。与这一特征一致，我们发现剥夺敏感性高的人是猎手，而剥夺敏感性低的人剥夺敏感性的人是好管闲事的人。换句话说，剥夺敏感性的个体差异导致了具有不同架构的知识网络的产生。

Interestingly, a personality trait explained the different network building practices of the busybodies and hunters: their sensitivity to information deprivation. This observation was made possible by data collected in a separate testing session. The participants had completed a scale from the psychologist’s laboratory, measuring their deprivation sensitivity by determining the degree to which the following statements characterized them: “Thinking about solutions to difficult conceptual problems can keep me awake at night”; “I can spend hours on a single problem because I just can’t rest without knowing the answer”; “I feel frustrated if I can’t figure out the solution to a problem so I work even harder to solve it”; “I work relentlessly at problems that I feel must be solved”; and “It frustrates me not having all the information I need.”21 Individuals high in deprivation sensitivity have a drive to eliminate the unknown as they encounter new information and recognize gaps in their knowledge. Consistent with this trait, we found that individuals high in deprivation sensitivity were hunters, while those low in deprivation sensitivity were busybodies. In other words, individual differences in deprivation sensitivity led to the creation of knowledge networks with distinct architectures.

人们不禁想知道，Ole Worm 会如何在维基百科这样的在线知识空间中搜寻，以及他会以什么样的真实反应来满足心理学家的剥夺敏感度量表。他是一种什么样的好奇心？他是否像猎人一样开始寻找某种特定的稀有物品？他是否像爱管闲事的人一样带着睁开双眼，耳朵向前倾，双臂挥动？他是否跨越经度跳舞，跨越纬度跳迪斯科？在十七世纪的丹麦，这些标志性的动作方式给人一种描述性和隐喻性的感觉，就像抽象的副词：狩猎、忙碌、跳舞。然而，在现代数字时代，它们变得具体，甚至有形。它们变得具体，因为随着思想在在线知识空间中移动（和鼠标点击），每次行走的步长都可以测量，每次跳跃的弧度都可以绘制，每支舞蹈的编排都可以用符号符号写出来。它们变得有形，因为科学家们在其领域前沿开发的知识不仅在思想上行走、跳跃和跳舞，而且在身体上——在伴随我们解释的手势、姿势和步调中，无论是在舞台上、在会议桌旁，还是在教室课桌之间。对一些人来说，舞蹈甚至变得有利可图。一年一度的国际舞蹈博士竞赛由美国科学促进会和《科学》杂志主办，后者是发表前沿和有影响力的发现的主要渠道之一。该竞赛要求生物学、化学、物理学和社会科学领域的科学家以舞蹈形式解释他们的博士研究。在这里，相互矛盾的数据的刺耳不和谐音和简单理论的丰富和声与说唱的精确性、古典交响乐的秩序或大片配乐的欢快融为一体；概念关系和相互依存的命题成为芭蕾舞、嘻哈舞或现代舞的动作主题。我们在科学发现过程中的思维运动成为我们身体的运动。

One cannot help but wonder how Ole Worm would have scavenged in an online knowledge space like Wikipedia, and with what authentic responses he would have met the psychologists’ deprivation sensitivity scale. What kind of curious was he? Did he set off in a hunter-like search for a specific rare item? Did he roam the world in a busybody-like search with eyes open, ears bent forward, and arms flapping? Did he dance across longitudes and disco over latitudes? In seventeenth-century Denmark, these signature manners of movement feel descriptive and metaphorical, in the sense of abstract adverbs: huntingly, busybodyingly, dancingly. Yet in the modern digital age, they become concrete and even corporeal. They become concrete insofar as the step size of each walk can be measured, the arc of each leap can be mapped, and the choreography of each dance can be written out in symbolic notation as a mind moves (and a mouse clicks) in an online knowledge space. And they become corporeal insofar as the knowledge developed by scientists at the edge of their field is walked, leaped, and danced not just in mind but also in body—in the gesticulations, stance, and pacing that accompany our explanations, whether across the stage, around the conference table, or between the classroom desks. For some, the dance even becomes lucrative. The annual international competition Dance Your PhD is run by the American Association for the Advancement of Science and Science magazine, one of the premier outlets to publish cutting-edge and impactful discoveries. The contest challenges scientists working in biology, chemistry, physics, and social sciences to explain their PhD research in interpretive dance. Here the jarring discords of conflicting data and rich harmonies of simple theories blend in the precision of rap, the order of classical symphonies, or the euphoria of blockbuster soundtracks; the conceptual relations and interdependent propositions become movement motifs in ballet, hip-hop, or contemporary dance. The movements of our minds in the process of scientific discovery become the movements of our bodies.

学习知识网络

Learning Knowledge Networks

当我们人类寻找信息时，我们每个人都以不同的方式寻找信息，从而构建出完全不同的知识网络。但假设我们不处于自我激励的浏览状态。相反，我们处于大多数教室和机构会议空间的状态，被灌输我们期望学习的信息。当呈现连续不断的信息流时，人类如何学习知识网络信息？答案可以简单地用我们之前讲过的一个故事来描述。回想一下罗伯特·麦克法兰邀请他的导师罗杰·迪肯到剑桥大学演讲，罗杰的演讲结构反映了演讲主题的结构。22罗杰谈到了水道，并发表了一场水上演讲，其中的主题沿着一条看不见的隧道和排水沟网络蜿蜒曲折地连接起来。这个故事说明了知识网络可以通过例子来学习——一个人如何在它们上面行走的例子。当演讲者从一个话题走到另一个话题时，他们会描绘出一个网络，听众可以看到、吸收，并且——如果他们愿意的话——拥有它。

When we as humans seek information, we each seek it differently, thereby constructing fundamentally different networks of knowledge. But suppose that we are not in the state of self-motivated browsing. Instead, we are in the state of most classrooms and institutional meeting spaces, being fed information that we are expected to learn. How does a human learn a knowledge network when presented with a continuous stream of information? The answer can be simply portrayed in a story we told earlier. Recall Robert Macfarlane inviting his mentor, Roger Deakin, to give a talk at the University of Cambridge, and how Roger had provided a lecture whose structure mirrored the structure of the lecture’s topic.22 Roger spoke on waterways, and gave a talk that was watery, in which the topics were connected in a circuitous meander, along an invisible network of tunnels and drains. The story illustrates the point that knowledge networks can be learned by example—the example of how one walks upon them. As a speaker walks from topic to topic, they trace out a network that the listener then sees, ingests, and—if they so choose—owns.

整个过程引发了许多有趣的问题。假设在一个美丽的秋日星期五的早晨，我作为宾夕法尼亚大学的生物工程学教授，计划讲授线性代数、好奇心甚至神经科学。我必须选择一组思想传达给全班，这些思想以异质的方式相互关联，形成一个网络。但我无法在一瞬间将网络交给学生。因为时间是一维和单向的，所以我必须线性地翻译这些信息，先讲一个话题，再讲下一个话题，先讲一个词，再讲下一个词。我应该如何创建这个信息序列——一组串在思想上的珠子——以最大限度地提高学习效果？换句话说，我如何将我脑海中的网络（可能是一个高维对象）映射到时间中遍历的一维概念串中，以便听众的大脑能够最佳地重建网络的形状？

The whole process raises many fascinating questions. Suppose that on a lovely autumnal Friday morning I, as a professor of bioengineering at the University of Pennsylvania, am scheduled to give a lecture on linear algebra, or perhaps curiosity, or even neuroscience. I must choose a set of ideas to transmit to the class, and those ideas are related to one another in a heterogeneous manner, making a network. But I cannot hand the students a network in a single instant in time. Because time is one-dimensional and unidirectional, I must translate that information linearly, passing through one topic before the next, speaking one word before the next. How should I create this information sequence—a set of beads on a string of thought—in a way that maximizes learning? In other words, how do I map the network in my mind (which is potentially a high-dimensional object) into a one-dimensional string of concepts traversed in time such that the mind of the listener can optimally reconstruct the network’s shape?

映射和重构过程有点像魔术，但人类已经学会了轻松地完成这两个过程：每次交流时，我们都在映射，每次聆听时，我们都在重构。我们怎么做到的？让我们关注重构过程。听众或读者的大脑不断体验着传入的数据流，并从该数据流中推断出概念对之间的依赖关系。通过在较长时间内进行这些推断，听众或读者最终可以推断出概念之间成对依赖关系的整个模式。推断这些模式的能力不仅与听讲座或读书有关。事实上，它是一种这使得人类能够学习语言、区分视觉事件、解析音调组合、解析空间场景、推断社交网络以及感知不同的概念。23我们经常这样做，也很容易做到。但承认存在并不意味着解释了过程。要了解我们如何做到这一点，我们必须设计精心控制的实验室实验并使用科学推理工具。

The mapping and reconstruction processes feel a bit like magic, but somehow humans have learned to perform both easily: every time we communicate, we are mapping, and every time we listen, we are reconstructing. How do we do it? Let’s focus on the reconstruction process. The brain of the listener or reader is continually experiencing an incoming stream of data, and from that stream is inferring dependencies between pairs of concepts. By making these inferences over extended periods of time, the listener or reader can eventually infer the whole pattern of pairwise dependencies between concepts. The capacity to infer these patterns is not just relevant to listening to a lecture or reading a book. It is in fact the capacity that allows humans to learn language, segment visual events, parse tonal groupings, parse spatial scenes, infer social networks, and perceive distinct concepts.23 So we do it, both commonly and easily. But an acknowledgment of existence is not an explanation of process. To understand how we do it, we must design carefully controlled laboratory experiments and use the tools of scientific inference.

建立网络学习实验室

Building a Laboratory for Network Learning

我们能否测量人类如何感知连续信息流背后的（可能高维的）网络拓扑？想象一下，我们站在白板前，在上面画一个网络。我们让网络中的每个节点代表一个项目：一个概念、一个事件、一个按键或图片。我们让网络中的每个边表示两个项目之间允许的时间转换；也就是说，如果节点i和j之间有边，则允许项目j在流中直接跟在项目i后面。接下来我们想象在网络上散步。例如，我们可以想象缩小到非常小（像爱丽丝梦游仙境一样），这样我们就可以物理地踩到每个圆形节点并穿过每个线性边缘（不要往下看！）。或者我们可以简单地用手指在白板表面上沿着边缘穿过节点描绘出一条步行路线。每当我们用手指或小小的身体到达一个节点时，我们都会写下该节点代表的项目。该过程使我们能够创建遵循网络结构的项目字符串。

Can we measure how humans perceive the (potentially high-dimensional) network topology behind a continuous stream of information? Imagine that we stand before a whiteboard upon which we draw a network. We let each node in the network represent an item: a concept, an event, a keypress, or a picture. We let each edge in the network indicate an allowable temporal transition between two items; that is, if nodes i and j have an edge between them, then item j is allowed to directly follow item i in the stream. Next we imagine taking a walk on the network. For example, we could imagine shrinking down to very small (like Alice in Wonderland) so that we could physically step on each circular node and walk across each linear edge (don’t look down!). Or we could simply use our finger to trace out a walk on the surface of the whiteboard, along edges, through nodes. Every time we reach a node, with our finger or with our tiny body, we write down the item that the node represents. The process allows us to create a string of items that obeys the structure of the network.

现在想象一下，在一个单独的房间里坐着一位刚刚同意参与我们研究的人类志愿者。我们向他们展示了我们刚刚创建的一串项目。对于字符串中的每个项目，我们都要求他们执行一个简单的任务（例如，按下笔记本电脑键盘上的按钮），以便我们记录他们的反应时间。引发人类反应的简单任务至关重要，因为志愿者的反应时间反映了他们对网络中该边缘的学习程度。如果他们反应迅速，那么他们已经很好地学习了网络中的那个边缘；如果他们反应缓慢，那么他们就没有很好地学习网络中的那个边缘。这种设置使我们能够确定学习网络每个部分需要多长时间，并询问某些网络是否比其他网络更容易学习。换句话说，我们可以问人类是否更容易学习具有纺锤体的网络（如Sphaerozoum variabile），或具有网状结构的网络（如Orosphaera huxleyii），或具有环状结构的网络（如Octopyle stenozona）。

Now imagine that in a separate room sits a human volunteer who has just agreed to participate in our study. We show them the string of items that we have just created. At each item in the string, we ask them to perform a simple task (e.g., press a button on a laptop keyboard) so that we can record their reaction time. The simple task that induces a human response is crucial because the volunteer’s reaction time reflects how well they have learned that edge in the network. If they respond quickly, then they have learned that edge in the network well; if they respond slowly, then they have not learned that edge in the network well. This setup allows us to determine how long it takes to learn each part of the network and ask whether some networks are easier to learn than others. In other words, we can ask whether humans can more easily learn networks with spindles like Sphaerozoum variabile, or those with meshwork like Orosphaera huxleyii, or those with loops like Octopyle stenozona.

在描述最近的发现之前，有必要回顾一下之前已知的关于此类任务引发的人类认知过程的知识。我们知道，人类对转换概率很敏感。例如，假设一个人在环境中看到项目 A 转换到项目 B 的概率约为 75%，而看到项目 A 转换到项目 C 的概率约为 25%。那么当他们下次看到 A 时，他们对 B 的期望将比对 C 的期望高出三倍。由于这个人对 B 的期望更高，因此他们对 B 的反应时间也将比对 C 的反应时间快得多。他们对 C 的反应时间。这一事实的必然结果是，如果一个人生活在 A 导致十种可能结果的环境中，由于不确定性很大，他通常会反应迟缓；相反，如果一个人生活在 A 只导致一种可能结果的环境中，由于完全确定，他通常会反应很快。事实上，通过将人们置于不同的局部环境中，我们可以看到，每个额外的结果都会使不确定性发生固定的改变，不确定性每增加一个单位，人类的反应时间平均会减少三十二毫秒。换句话说，人们每三十二毫秒处理一比特信息。24更具体地说，它是血液从心脏流到脚趾再流回所需时间的 0.07%（或者如果你喜欢用天文尺度来表示，则是光传播约九千六百米所需的时间，而这又约为从地球到太空距离的十分之一）。

Before describing recent discoveries, it is useful to recount what had previously been known about the human cognitive processes that are elicited by such a task. What we had known is that humans are sensitive to transition probabilities. For example, consider a person who sees item A transition to item B approximately 75 percent of the time in their environment, whereas they see item A transition to item C approximately 25 percent of the time in their environment. Then when they next see A, they will expect B three times more than they expect C. Because the person is expecting B more, their reaction time to it will also be much faster than their reaction time to C. A corollary to this fact is that a person who lives in an environment where A leads to ten possible outcomes will generally respond slowly due to great uncertainty; in contrast, a person who lives in an environment where A only ever leads to one possible outcome will generally respond quite quickly due to full certainty. Indeed, by placing people in different local environments, we can see that each additional outcome changes the uncertainty by a fixed amount, and every unit increase in uncertainty costs a human an average of thirty-two milliseconds in reaction time. In other words, people process one bit of information every thirty-two milliseconds.24 To put this number in more concrete terms, it is 0.07 percent of the time it takes blood to move from your heart to your toe and back again (or if you prefer astronomical scales, the time it takes light to travel approximately ninety-six hundred meters, which in turn is about one-tenth of the way from the earth to space).

为了了解人类如何学习网络结构，我们可以保持局部环境不变（例如，每个节点都连接到其他四个节点，每个项目都有四个结果），同时改变边缘的全局模式（例如，偏向纺锤状、网状或环状）。我们与心理学家 Elisabeth Karuza 和神经科学家 Ari Kahn 一起，通过在这些不同的网络上行走，创建了不同的项目串。然后，我们向志愿者展示每个字符串，同时测量他们对序列中每个元素的反应时间。我们发现了什么？人类似乎对网络中的集群很敏感；他们很快就能检测到一组项目的存在，在这些项目中，他们会看到许多转换——因为在我们的网络中，这组节点是紧密相连的。我们可以说人类对这些集群很敏感，因为他们对集群内部的边缘反应迅速，而对集群之间的转换感到惊讶（并且反应缓慢）。25有趣的是，人类对网络中的层次结构也很敏感，对簇之间或簇边界的转换比对簇内深处的转换更感到惊讶。26我们可以看出人类对这种层次结构很敏感，因为他们对位于网络簇内部深处的节点所代表的项目反应更快，而对位于网络簇外围的节点所代表的项目反应更慢。

To understand how people learn the structure of a network, we can keep the local environments fixed (e.g., each node is connected to four other nodes, and every item has exactly four outcomes) while altering the global pattern of edges (e.g., favoring spindles, meshwork, or loops). Together with psychologist Elisabeth Karuza and neuroscientist Ari Kahn, we created distinct strings of items by walking on these distinct networks. We then showed each string to a volunteer while measuring their reaction time to each element in the sequence. What did we find? Humans appear to be sensitive to clusters in the network; they quickly detect the presence of a set of items among which they see many transitions—because in our network, that set of nodes was densely interconnected. We can tell that humans are sensitive to these clusters because they respond quickly to edges inside the clusters, while being surprised (and responding slowly) to transitions between clusters.25 Interestingly, humans are also sensitive to hierarchy in the network, being more surprised by transitions between or at the boundaries of clusters than transitions deep within a cluster.26 We can tell that humans are sensitive to this hierarchy because they respond more quickly to items represented by nodes located deep inside the network’s clusters, and they respond more slowly to items represented by nodes located at the periphery of the network’s clusters.

此类实验提供了令人信服的证据，表明人类学习网络的某些部分比其他部分更好或更快。但人类是否对整个网络的结构有偏好？有些网络总体上比其他网络更容易学习吗？有趣的是，人类确实对整个网络的整体拓扑结构很敏感；他们对从聚类或模块化网络中获取的项目序列反应最快，而对从随机或完全无序网络中获取的项目序列反应最慢。换句话说，当信息以模块化方式呈现时，人类似乎更容易学习，这可能对最佳地组织课堂讲座、写作或动手任务有影响。27总的来说，这些发现表明人类可以从连续的信息流中学习（可能高维的）网络结构。但如何做到呢？

Experiments of this ilk provide compelling evidence that humans learn some portions of a network better or more swiftly than others. But do humans have a preference for the structure of the entire network? Are some networks overall easier to learn than others? Fascinatingly, humans are indeed sensitive to the overall topology of the full network; they respond most quickly to sequences of items taken from clustered or modular networks, and they respond most slowly to sequences of items taken from random or completely disordered networks. In other words, humans seem to find it easier to learn when information is presented in a modular fashion, which may have implications for optimally organizing a classroom lecture, a piece of writing, or a hands-on task.27 Collectively, these findings demonstrate that humans can learn a (potentially high-dimensional) network structure from a continuous stream of information. But how?

人们在想什么？

What Are People Thinking?

准确理解大脑中发生了什么来解释某种行为或形成某种想法是非常困难的。剑桥大学教授亚瑟·C·本森在维多利亚时代的英国艺术评论家约翰·拉斯金的传记中很好地阐述了这一点，他写道：

Understanding precisely what happens in the mind to explain a particular behavior or form a particular thought is notoriously difficult. Cambridge don Arthur C. Benson put it well in his biography of English art critic John Ruskin of the Victorian era when he wrote,

你知道，我们大多数人在闲暇时，或者在正式工作时，都会陷入沉思，思绪如泉涌，可能是平静的，也可能是激烈的，从头脑中涌出。假设你突然在沉思中停下来。试着用语言写下你一直在想的，以及你的想法。你会发现这简直是荒谬的不可能。一半的想法没有用任何语言来包装自己，一件事引出了另一件事，通常是通过一些表面形式的微不足道的相似性。整个事情都是难以捉摸的，难以捉摸的，无法挽回的。28

You know how most of us in idle moments, or perhaps even more in moments when we are officially supposed to be occupied, lapse into a reverie, in which a stream of thought—it may be placid, it may be vehement—sweeps through the brain from the flushed reservoir of the mind. Suppose you check yourself suddenly in one of these reveries. Try to put down in words what you have been thinking of, and as you thought it. You will find it to be ludicrously impossible. Half the thoughts have passed without clothing themselves in any vesture of word, one thing has suggested another, often enough by some trivial similarity of superficial form. The whole thing is evasive, elusive, irrecoverable.28

啊，那些未经修饰的想法——它们总是偷走我们最好的想法的罪魁祸首，拒绝从任何地方带回任何消息。29但更严重的是，如果我们试图用文字记录下人们在从连续的信息流（比如从讲座、书籍、独白或其他一些时间延长的体验）中学习网络时所想的东西，会怎么样？

Ack, those unclothed thoughts—they are always the culprits spiriting away our best ideas, refusing to bring back any news from nowhere.29 But more seriously, what if we were to try to put down in words what people are thinking of as they learn a network from a continuous stream of information, such as from a lecture, a book, a monologue, or some other temporally extended experience?

也许我们可以从弗吉尼亚·伍尔夫那里得到一些启发，她在《为什么？》一文中写道，有一天，她“出于友谊的尊重，或者为了获取信息而拼命地”决定去听一场讲座。她回忆道：“一口大钟显出阴郁的面容，当整点敲响时，一个看起来焦躁不安的男人大步走来，他的脸上充满了紧张、虚荣，或者可能是因为他的工作令人沮丧和不可能，所以他脸上没有一点普通人性的痕迹。”真可怕。

Perhaps we can gain some insights from Virginia Woolf, who writes in her essay “Why?” of a date on which “in deference to friendship, or in a desperate attempt to acquire information,” she had decided to attend a lecture. She recalls, “A large clock displayed its cheerless face, and when the hour struck in strode a harried-looking man, a man from whose face nervousness, vanity, or perhaps the depressing and impossible nature of his task had removed all traces of ordinary humanity.” Grim.

[然后]他清了清嗓子，开始讲课。现在，人的声音是一种具有多种力量的工具；它可以使人着迷，也可以使人安抚；它可以使人愤怒，也可以使人绝望；但当它讲课时，它几乎总是令人厌烦。他说的话很有道理；其中有学问、论据和道理；但随着声音的继续，注意力分散了。钟面似乎苍白得异常；手……移动得如此缓慢。它们让人想起一只熬过冬天的三条腿的苍蝇的痛苦历程。平均有多少只苍蝇能在英国的冬天存活下来，当这种昆虫醒来发现自己正在听关于法国大革命的讲座时，它会有什么想法？这个问题是致命的。一个环节丢失了——一个段落被删去了。要求讲师重复他的话是没有用的；他以顽强的毅力继续讲下去。人们在寻找法国大革命的起源——也是苍蝇的想法。现在，出现了一段平淡的演讲，可以看到微小的物体在两三英里外飞来。“跳！”我们恳求他——徒劳无功。他没有跳。他开了个玩笑。然后声音又继续下去；然后似乎窗户需要清洗；然后一个女人打了个喷嚏；然后声音加快了；然后是总结；然后——感谢上帝！——讲座结束了。

[Then] he cleared his throat and the lecture began. Now the human voice is an instrument of varied power; it can enchant and it can soothe; it can rage and it can despair; but when it lectures it almost always bores. What he said was sensible enough; there was learning in it and argument and reason; but as the voice went on attention wandered. The face of the clock seemed abnormally pale; the hands . . . moved so slowly. They reminded one of the painful progress of a three-legged fly that has survived the winter. How many flies on average survive the English winter, and what would be the thoughts of such an insect on waking to find itself being lectured on the French Revolution? The inquiry was fatal. A link had been lost—a paragraph dropped. It was useless to ask the lecturer to repeat his words; on he plodded with dogged pertinacity. The origin of the French Revolution was being sought for—also the thoughts of flies. Now there came one of those flat stretches of discourse when minute objects can be seen coming for two or three miles ahead. “Skip!” we entreated him—vainly. He did not skip. There was a joke. Then the voice went on again; then it seemed that the windows wanted washing; then a woman sneezed; then the voice quickened; then there was a peroration; and then—thank Heaven!—the lecture was over.

显然，人们在听讲座时想到的是“鼻子和下巴、女人打喷嚏和苍蝇的寿命”。30当一个人的思维反复无常、丢失链接、漏掉句子、遗漏整段内容时，他如何能够准确地描绘出连续信息流背后的网络？一种力量将思想向外拉，专注于讲师的话语，而另一种力量将思想向内拉，专注于内心涌现的许多问题、序言、笔记、抗议、漫谈、信念、脚注和后记。我们能否写下一个平衡这两种力量的数学模型？就像跷跷板的运动方程，还是拔河比赛中推拉的权衡？

Apparently, what people are thinking of as they listen to a lecture is “noses and chins, women sneezing and the longevity of flies.”30 How can a person gather an accurate picture of the network underlying a continuous stream of information when their mind ricochets about, losing links, missing sentences, and dropping whole paragraphs? One force draws the mind outward to concentrate on the lecturer’s words, while another force draws the mind inward to concentrate on the many questions, preambles, notes, remonstrances, rambles, convictions, footnotes, and postambles bubbling up inside. Could we write down a mathematical model that balances these two forces? Like the equations of motion for a seesaw, or like the trade-off of pushes and pulls in a tug-of-war?

为了回答这些问题，我们有幸与物理学家克里斯托弗·林恩合作，他从统计物理学的分支领域中汲取灵感，认为人类思维遵循自由能原理。31在这种背景下，该原理规定，人的思维会寻求平衡两种压力：最大限度地提高其网络世界模型的准确性的压力，以及最小化构建该模型所需的计算复杂性的压力。32 最大限度地提高准确性和最小化复杂性这两个要求是相互对立的，就像光明与黑暗一样。一个最准确的世界模型需要最大的复杂性，而一个最小复杂性模型则需要产生最小的准确性。在网络学习中，最大复杂性模型将提供对网络的完美准确了解。伍尔夫会细细品味每一个环节，捕捉每一个段落，而且她会通过完美控制自己的注意力来做到这一点。相比之下，最小复杂性模型会让人类相信网络是完全相连的；换句话说，任何事件都可能导致任何其他事件，并且每个项目都与其他项目有同等的相关性。伍尔夫会把注意力分散，更多地考虑苍蝇，而很少考虑法国大革命；她对讲座的瞥见会感觉像是具有同等程度的不相关性的随机信息。“三条腿的苍蝇在法国大革命中扮演了关键角色吗？”那天晚上晚些时候她可能会问自己。

To answer these questions, we had the privilege of collaborating with physicist Christopher Lynn, who drew from the subfield of statistical physics to posit that the human mind works upon the free energy principle.31 When applied in this context, the principle stipulates that a person’s mind seeks to balance two pressures: the pressure to maximize the accuracy of their network model of the world, and the pressure to minimize the computational complexity needed to build that model.32 The two requirements of maximizing accuracy and minimizing complexity are mutually antagonist, like light and dark. A maximally accurate model of the world would require maximal complexity, whereas a minimal complexity model would produce minimal accuracy. In network learning, the maximal complexity model would provide a perfectly accurate knowledge of the network. Woolf would have savored every link and caught every paragraph, and she would have done so by perfectly controlling her attention. In contrast, a minimal complexity model would lead the human to believe the network is all-to-all connected; in other words, any event could cause any other event, and every item is equally related to any other item. Woolf would have thought much of flies and little of the French Revolution in letting her attention wander; her glimpses of the lecture would feel like random bits of information with equal amounts of dys-relation. “Did a three-legged fly play a key role in the French Revolution?” she might ask herself later that evening.

每个人都必须在这种准确性与复杂性的权衡中寻找自己的平衡点——完美记忆与昂贵的脑力劳动之间的平衡。人类似乎通过模糊的时间整合过程来实现这种平衡；在他们的头脑中，他们不仅将序列中紧挨着出现的两个项目联系起来，还将在更宽的时间窗口中出现的一组更大的项目联系起来。我们可以将其与视觉艺术作品的感知进行类比。大脑不是专注于乔治·皮埃尔·修拉或文森特·梵高的点彩画中的每个彩色点，而是局部涂抹颜色点以获得格式塔感知。同样，大脑涂抹时间点以从连续的信息流中获得对网络整体结构的感知。正如柏拉图在洞穴寓言中所假设的那样，人类无法感知到他们周围的真实世界。33相反，他们就像透过玻璃看东西一样模糊，感知到他们世界的不准确、模糊的画面。然而，重要的是（与柏拉图相反），这种有偏见的感知过程强调了概念类别与网络中其他显著的建筑主题之间的界限，使人类能够更充分地欣赏他们世界的大规模结构。

Each human must strike their own balance in this accuracy-complexity trade-off—a balance between perfect memory and expensive mental effort. Humans appear to enact this balance through a process of fuzzy temporal integration; in their mind, they connect not just two items that appear right next to each other in the sequence but rather a larger set of items that appear near to one another in a wider temporal window. A useful analogy can be made to the perception of a piece of visual art. Instead of focusing on each colored dot in a pointillist painting from Georges-Pierre Seurat or Vincent van Gogh, the mind locally smears the points of color to obtain a Gestalt perception. Similarly, the mind smears points of time to attain a perception of the global structure of a network from a continuous stream of information. As Plato had postulated in his allegory of the cave, humans do not perceive the true world around them.33 Instead, they see as through a glass darkly, perceiving an inaccurate, smeared picture of their world. Importantly (and contra Plato), though, that biased perceptual process accentuates the boundaries between conceptual categories and other salient architectural motifs in the network, allowing humans to more fully appreciate the large-scale structure of their world.

模糊时间整合模型是网络学习的关键候选机制，它使我们能够构建行走的结构，并从中好奇地踏入未知空间。在科学探究的下一步中，我们不仅仅是简单地假设一个模型，而是通过从数据中估计模型参数，验证模型的机制，并成功地利用该理论预测人类在新环境中的行为。34但即使在通过这些方式证实了模型的实用性和真实性之后，问题仍然是我们从网络学习实验室得出的结论是否真正解释了人类每天相互交流知识的过程。实验室实验是高度结构化的，以控制尽可能多的潜在混杂变量。然而，在创建一个干净的实验的过程中，我们冒着研究只存在于实验室中的过程的风险。我们如何确认我们的推论与现实世界相关？

The model of fuzzy temporal integration is a key candidate mechanism for network learning, allowing us to build the structures upon which we walk and from which we step out curiously into unknown spaces. In the next steps of scientific inquiry, we move beyond simply positing a model by estimating the model parameters from data, validating the model’s mechanisms, and successfully using the theory to make a prediction about human behavior in a new environment.34 But even after confirming the model’s utility and verity in these ways, the question remains whether the conclusions we draw from the network learning laboratory truly explain the everyday processes whereby we humans communicate knowledge to one another. Laboratory experiments are highly structured so as to control as many of the potential confounding variables as possible. Yet in the process of creating a clean experiment, we risk studying a process that only exists in the laboratory. How do we confirm that our inferences relate to the real world?

现实网络中的信息处理

Information Processing in Real Networks

我们究竟如何从经验中构建知识，是思想家们几千年来一直在努力解决的问题。约瑟夫·格兰维尔在他的著作《教条主义的虚荣》中很好地阐述了这一点，他写道：

Exactly how we build knowledge from our experiences is a question that thinkers have wrestled with for millennia. Joseph Glanvill put it well in his book The Vanity of Dogmatizing when he wrote,

但是灵魂是如何、通过什么技巧读出物质中的这种图像或笔触……表示这种物体的？我们在胚胎状态中学会了这种字母表吗？为什么我们没有意识到任何这种先天的理解？……通过各种运动，我们应该拼出图形、距离、大小、颜色，以及它们不相似的事物，我们将其归因于一些秘密的推论。35

But how is it, and by what art, doth the soul read that such an image or stroke in matter . . . signifies such an object? Did we learn such an Alphabet in our Embryo-state? And how comes it to pass, that we are not aware of any such congenite apprehensions? . . . That by diversity of motions we should spell out figures, distances, magnitudes, colours, things not resembled by them, we attribute to some secret deductions.35

当我们在人类通信系统中看到符号、符号集和符号串时，我们的灵魂如何解读它们共同所代表的含义，特别是当我们的感知总是有偏见的时候？

When we see symbols, sets of symbols, and strings of symbols in our human communication systems, how does our soul read what they collectively signify, particularly if our perceptions are always biased?

要回答这个问题，让我们考虑一下人类用来交流的系统。我们通过语言和音乐、社交网络和正式的知识库进行交流。每个通信系统都是一个网络。语言网络由根据语义关系或句子内接近度相互连接的概念组成。音乐网络由音符组成，音符通过乐曲内的时间接近度相互连接。万维网由通过超链接连接到其他站点的网站组成。科学知识网络由通过参考或引文连接到其他论文的科学论文组成。社会系统是由通过友谊、熟人或其他形式的同事关系与其他知识者联系在一起的知识者组成的信息网络。总的来说，这些网络使我们能够彼此共享信息，从而体现了我们交流的结构。

To answer this question, let’s consider the systems that humans use to communicate. We communicate using language and music, through social networks and within formal repositories of knowledge. Each communication system is a network. Language networks are formed by concepts that are connected to other concepts according to their semantic relationships or according to their proximity within a sentence. Music networks are formed by notes that are connected to one another by their temporal proximity within the piece. The World Wide Web is composed of sites that are connected to other sites by hyperlinks. Scientific knowledge networks are composed of scientific papers that are connected to other papers by references or citations. Social systems are information networks composed of knowers who are connected to other knowers by friendship, acquaintance, or other forms of collegiality. Collectively, these networks allow us to share information with one another and thus evince the structure of our communication.

我们再次与 Lynn 合作，着手了解这些通信系统所展示的架构类型，并探究这些架构是否对人类感知偏见敏感或具有弹性。在语言网络家族中，我们研究了威廉·莎士比亚、荷马、柏拉图、简·奥斯汀、威廉·布莱克的名词转换，在语义网络家族中，我们研究了维克多·雨果的《悲惨世界》中人物共现的情况和彼得·罗杰的《同义词典》中的词语相似性。在音乐网络家族中，我们研究了迈克尔·杰克逊的《颤栗》、披头士的《艰难的一天之夜》、皇后乐队的《波西米亚狂想曲》和托托的《非洲》中的音符转换，以及沃尔夫冈·阿马德乌斯·莫扎特的第 11 号奏鸣曲、路德维希·范·贝多芬的第 23 号奏鸣曲、弗里德里克·肖邦的夜曲第 9 号第 2 首、约翰·塞巴斯蒂安·巴赫的《平均律钢琴曲集》中第 13 号前奏曲和赋格曲，以及约翰内斯·勃拉姆斯的叙事曲第 10 号第 1 1. 我们还包括科学中的引文网络、万维网上的站点网络以及 Facebook 好友和其他社交媒体渠道中编码的社交关系。这些样本可用于抽样每个家庭，我们将它们结合起来，以获得有关跨通信系统的差异和共同点的见解。

Collaborating again with Lynn, we set out to understand what types of architectures these communication systems display, and to ask whether those architectures are sensitive to or resilient against our human biases in perception. In the family of language networks, we studied noun transitions in William Shakespeare, Homer, Plato, Jane Austen, William Blake, Miguel de Cervantes, and Whitman, while in the family of semantic networks we studied character co-occurrences in Victor Hugo’s Les Misérables and word similarities in Peter Roget’s Thesaurus. In the family of music networks, we studied note transitions in Michael Jackson’s “Thriller,” the Beatles’ “Hard Day’s Night,” Queen’s “Bohemian Rhapsody,” and Toto’s “Africa,” alongside Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart’s Sonata no. 11, Ludwig van Beethoven’s Sonata no. 23, Frédéric Chopin’s Nocturne opus 9, no. 2, Johann Sebastian Bach’s Prelude and Fugue no. 13 from the Well-Tempered Clavier, and Johannes Brahms’s Ballade opus 10, no. 1. We also included citation networks in science, site networks in the World Wide Web, and social relationships encoded in Facebook friends and other social media outlets. These exemplars serve to sample each family, and together we used them to obtain insights regarding differences and commonalities across communication systems.

网络中保存的信息量反映在节点的连接方式上。节点的所谓度就是从节点发出的边的数量。网络在密集连接的中心节点（高度）数量上有所不同，这些节点通常位于大型模块中；它们在稀疏连接的节点（低度）数量上也有所不同，这些节点通常位于小型模块中。具有广泛连接度范围的网络被认为具有高熵；它们包含的信息比通常预期的相同大小的随机网络多得多。在短时间内保存和传输大量信息的能力对于为人类通信而设计的系统尤为重要。在跨通信系统进行比较时，语言网络显示出最大的熵，而音乐网络显示出最小的熵。这些差异表明现实世界的网络存在于一个范围内，一些家族比其他家族编码和传输的信息多得多。

The amount of information held in the network is reflected in how the nodes are connected. The so-called degree of a node is the number of edges emanating from it. Networks differ in the number of densely connected hub nodes (high degree) often found in large modules; they also differ in the number of sparsely connected nodes (low degree) often found in small modules. Networks that have a broad range of connectivity degree are said to have high entropy; they pack in much more information than is typically expected in a random network of the same size. The capacity to hold and transmit large amounts of information in short amounts of time is particularly important for systems designed for human communication. In comparing across communication systems, language networks stand out as displaying the greatest entropy, whereas music networks display the least. These differences suggest that real-world networks exist along a spectrum, with some families encoding and transmitting much more information than others.

值得注意的是，每种网络类型都表现出模块化架构，由越来越小的模块组成的大模块层次结构扩展。36当我们回想起模块化网络正是人类容易学习的网络时，模块化结构在人类通信系统中的普遍性就显得尤为有趣。37为什么模块化网络容易学习吗？它们的聚类特性将真实网络结构与人类通过模糊时间整合的偏差过程所感知的结构之间的差异最小化。当我们再次思考视觉艺术时，某些网络结构或多或少对人类感知过程具有弹性的想法可能非常直观。假设你站在杰克逊·波洛克和修拉的画作前；你眼睛的空间模糊将提炼出后者的格式塔感知，但只会是前者的混乱赝品。同样，具有某些结构的网络可以通过我们模糊的感知展现其本质，而其他网络则严重扭曲。人类之间的最佳通信系统应该自然地以最小化对感知信息的扭曲的方式构建。令人惊讶的是，人类通信系统就是这样做的。

Notably, each of these network types displays modular architecture, expanded in a hierarchy of large modules composed of smaller and smaller modules.36 The pervasiveness of modular structure in human communication systems is particularly interesting when we recall that modular networks are precisely those that humans find easy to learn.37 And why might modular networks be easy to learn? Their clustered nature minimizes the divergence between the true network structure and the structure that a human perceives through the biased process of fuzzy temporal integration. The idea that some network structures are more or less resilient to human perceptual processes can be quite intuitive when we think again of visual art. Suppose that you stood before a Jackson Pollock versus a Seurat painting; the spatial smearing of your eyes will distill the Gestalt perception of the latter, but only a messy counterfeit of the former. Similarly, networks with certain structures can have their nature shine through our cloudy perception, while others are severely distorted. An optimal communication system among humans should naturally be structured in a way that minimizes the distortion imposed on the perceived information. And amazingly, human communication systems do just that.

但为什么呢？在过去的两千年里，人类是否优先创建了具有他们最容易理解的架构的网络？还是人类的感知过程已经进化到尽量减少对我们周围世界中真实网络的扭曲？由人工过程（无论是否智能）构建的网络与人类构建的网络是否不同？知识是否会随着时间的推移而发展，以更紧密地匹配人类的网络构建偏好，反之亦然？抛开人类感知和网络结构如何以及为何变得如此一致的问题，有趣的是，这种一致性是否提供了对人类好奇心的洞察。我们对网络空间的共同感知是否让我们知道在哪里可以找到新信息，在哪里可以进入未知的空间？

But why? Over the past two millennia, have humans preferentially created networks to have architectures that they can most easily understand? Or have human perceptual processes evolved to minimize the distortion of the true networks existing in the world around us? Are networks made by artificial processes (whether intelligent or not) constructed differently from those made by humans? Does knowledge evolve over time to more closely match human network building preferences or vice versa? Laying aside the question of how and why human perception and network structures have become so aligned, it is interesting to ask whether that alignment provides insights into human curiosity. Do our shared perceptions of network spaces allow us to know where to walk for new information and where to strike out into the space of the unknown?

了解网络或网络背后的原理？

Understanding Networks or the Principles behind Networks?

如果存储知识的网络和用于交流知识的网络具有某种共同的结构，那么人类可能不仅学习网络本身，还学习该架构的共同原则。如果我们学习了网络支架跨越知识空间的共同原则或规则，那么我们可能能够做出准确的关于新知识可能存在于何处或新知识可能如何构建的预测。哲学家伊曼纽尔康德的《纯粹理性批判》中有一段话提出了类似的观点，尽管没有网络表现型：“我们的理性不是一个无限延伸的平面，我们只是一般地知道它的极限；而是必须比作一个球体，它的半径可以根据其表面弧的曲率确定——也就是说，根据先验综合命题的性质——并且我们同样可以确定它的体积和极限。” 38也许网络的局部结构中有足够的信息来确定它在知识空间遥远区域的位置和跨度，就像球体的局部曲率中有足够的信息来确定其体积和物理空间的极限一样。

If networks that house knowledge and those used to communicate knowledge have some shared structure, then perhaps humans learn not just the network itself but also the shared principles of that architecture. And if we learn those shared principles or rules by which the network scaffold spans the space of knowledge, then perhaps we are able to make accurate predictions about where new knowledge might exist or how new knowledge might be structured. A passage from philosopher Immanuel Kant’s Critique of Pure Reason suggests something similar, albeit devoid of the network phenotype: “Our reason is not a plane indefinitely far extended, the limits of which we know in a general way only; but must rather be compared to a sphere, the radius of which can be determined from the curvature of the arc of its surface—that is to say, from the nature of synthetic a priori propositions—and whereby we can likewise specify with certainty its volume and its limits.”38 Perhaps there is enough information in the local structure of a network to determine its placement and span in far-distant areas of knowledge space, just as there is enough information in the local curvature of a sphere to determine its volume and its limits in physical space.

有哪些证据表明人类对知识片段之间关联的原理有着共同的理解？从人们如何理解彼此截然不同的概念集，可以发现对知识整体结构的共同认知的曙光。考虑一下，不同的概念是知识网络中彼此相距很远的概念，而相似的概念是知识网络中彼此相近的概念。直观地看，人类似乎很容易评估网络上彼此接近的概念的相似性。但是一旦概念彼此相距很远，评估它们的相似性可能会变得更加困难。直觉，无论对错，都与我们对物理距离的感知一致。我们可以很容易地得出结论，一个球离我们的鞋子有一英尺远，但我们发现更难预测远处的山与附近的云有多远。我们预测物体之间距离的准确性会随着距离的增加而降低。

What evidence exists to suggest that humans share an understanding of the principles whereby bits of knowledge are related? Glimmers of a shared perception of the global structure of knowledge can be found in how people understand sets of concepts that are markedly dissimilar from one another. Consider that dissimilar concepts are those that exist far away from each other in a knowledge network, whereas similar concepts are those that exist close by on a knowledge network. Intuitively, it would seem easy for humans to assess the similarity of concepts that are near to one another on the network. But once concepts are far from one another, it might be more difficult to assess their similarity. The intuition, whether right or wrong, is consistent with our perceptions of physical distances. We can quite easily conclude that a ball is one foot away from our shoe, but we find it more difficult to predict how far away a distant mountain is from a nearby cloud. The accuracy with which we predict distances between objects decreases as the distance increases.

最近，Danielle Navarro 和 Andrew Perfors（两位出色的科学家，恰好也是跨性别者）与同事 Simon De Deyne 和 Gert Storms 合作，设计了一组实验，以了解人类如何评估大概念空间中的距离。39他们首先整理了 12,428 个荷兰语单词，这些单词在普通人的词汇中很常见。然后，他们从这个集合中选择了 300 个名词，这些名词具有大致相同的词频和具体性，而且重要的是，这些名词是语义上不相关。他们向成年志愿者展示了 100 组不同的 3 个不同的词，如“hedge”、“belly button”和“peacock”，并要求参与者指出这 3 个不相关的词中哪 2 个最相关。你会如何回答？ 我问自己同样的问题。我应该选择“hedge”和“belly button”吗，因为它们都可以是空心的？40或者选择“peacock”和“hedge”，因为孔雀用它那美丽的尾巴来规避风险？或者选择“belly button”和“peacock”，因为...... 嗯，真的没有什么好的理由。人们可能会理性地预期，由于这些词不相关，每个参与者会随机选择不同的一对。令人震惊的是，就像我们有第六感一样，人类实际上会从 3 个不相关的词中选择相同的一对。为什么？

Recently, Danielle Navarro and Andrew Perfors—two fantastic scientists who also just happen to be transgender—collaborated with colleagues Simon De Deyne and Gert Storms to devise a set of experiments to understand how humans assess distances over large conceptual spaces.39 They began by collating 12,428 Dutch words common to the layperson’s vocabulary. Within that set, they then chose 300 nouns that had approximately the same word frequency and concreteness, and that—importantly—were not related semantically. They showed adult volunteers the 100 different sets of 3 dissimilar words like “hedge,” “belly button,” and “peacock,” and asked the participants to indicate which 2 of the 3 unrelated words were most related. How might you respond? I ask myself the same question. Should I choose “hedge” and “belly button” because both can be holloways?40 Or “peacock” and “hedge” because a peacock hedges its bets behind the fabulous tail? Or “belly button” and “peacock” because . . . Well, there really is just no good reason. One might rationally expect that since the words were unrelated, each participant would choose a different pair at random. Shockingly, and almost as if we had a sixth sense, humans in fact consistently pick the same pair from the 3 unrelated words. Why?

该团队继续进行了几个实验，以表明人类似乎从一个单词开始，然后在网络中心理激活该单词的邻居，然后是次近的邻居，然后是次近的邻居，依此类推，这是一个扩散的心理激活过程。为了在心理上了解这种情况是如何发生的，想象一下你站在一个三维迷宫上方，你将一桶紫色油漆倒进迷宫的一角，然后是一桶蓝色油漆，然后是绿色，然后是黄色、橙色和红色。你看着彩虹在通道中流动。41但由于迷宫的复杂性，你看不到色彩的波浪，而是锯齿状的进展：在迷宫的某个部分，彩虹可能已经扩散到远处的角落，因为它沿着一条短直线行进，而在迷宫的另一个部分，彩虹可能仍然靠近倾倒的角落，停留在一条盘绕的迂回路径上。正如油漆到达迷宫中每个点的时间取决于迷宫的结构，知识网络中的每个单词也会在不同的时间被激活，具体取决于网络的结构。扩散激活过程使人类能够准确估计距离，从而始终如一地选择哪一对单词最相关，尽管它们在网络上相距甚远。

The team went on to use several more experiments to show that humans appear to start with a word, and mentally activate the neighbors of that word in the network, and then the next-nearest neighbors, and then the next-next-nearest neighbors, and so on, in a spreading mental activation process. To gain a mental picture of how this happens, imagine that you are standing above a three-dimensional maze, and you pour a bucket of purple paint into one corner of the maze, then a bucket of blue, then green, and then yellow, orange, and red. You watch as the rainbow flows through the channels.41 But because of the maze’s complexity, you do not see a wave of color but instead a jagged progression: in one section of the maze, the rainbow might have spread to the far corner because it was traveling along a short straight path, whereas in another section of the maze, the rainbow might still be close to the pouring corner, stuck in a coiled circuitous path. Just as the paint reaches each spot in the maze at a different time depending on the maze’s structure, so every word in a knowledge network is activated at a different time depending on the network’s structure. The spreading activation process allows humans to accurately estimate distances and hence consistently choose which pair of words is most related despite the fact that they are far from one another on the network.

准确、快速、共享地估计概念之间的距离表明，人类可能做的不仅仅是学习网络本身。相反，人类可能会学习网络架构的一般原理：它的形状、它的体积和它的极限。我们学习什么空间是什么样的，地形是什么样的，地势表现了什么。我们学会了在 X 菲尔德的学术研究中期待多洛米蒂山脉的山丘，在 Y 菲尔德的学术研究中期待中西部的草原，在 Z 菲尔德的学术研究中期待后退的冰川路径的湖泊。也许正是这种学习让我们感受到尖锐猜测的牵引力，隐约感觉到那块岩石表面的角落里存在着某种美丽而精确的东西，预感拼图的下一块看起来应该是这样的，而不是那样的。这样的牵引力、隐约感觉和预感可能有助于引导我们的好奇心。当我们的猜测正确时，我们会感到一丝满足的快乐，而当猜测不正确时，我们会感到一阵着迷的惊讶。

The accurate, swift, and shared estimation of distances between concepts suggests that humans might do much more than simply learn a network itself. Rather, humans might learn the generic principles of the network’s architecture: its shape, its volume, and its limits. We learn what the space is like, what the terrain entails, and what the topography evinces. We learn to expect hills in the Dolomites of X field’s scholarship, prairies in the Midwest of Y field’s scholarship, and lakes in the receding glacier paths of Z field’s scholarship. Perhaps it is this type of learning from which we feel that tug of a pointed guess, the inkling that something beautifully precise exists around the corner of that rock face, the hunch that the next piece of the puzzle should look something like this but not like that. Such tugs, inklings, and hunches may serve to guide our curiosity. We gather a bit of contented happiness when our guess is right and a jolt of enthralled surprise when it is not.

走同一条路，走不同一条路

Walking Samely, Walking Differently

因此，人类对知识网络结构有着共同的理解，并能准确地估计概念之间的距离，这是网络上一系列的心理步骤。这些共同的概念是道路的终点吗？还是它们可能会被独特的概念所补充？自然语言处理和计算科学的最新进展为我们提供了回答这些问题的新工具。在此过程中，它们促进了对知识网络结构的更深入理解，以及我们每个人都可以用它来进行好奇思考的方式。

So humans share an understanding of the network structure of knowledge and can accurately estimate distances between concepts as a series of mental steps on the network. Are these shared conceptions the end of the road? Or might they be complemented by idiosyncratic conceptions? Recent advances in natural language processing and computational science give us new tools to answer these questions. In doing so, they have facilitated an even deeper understanding of the network structure of knowledge and the ways in which we can each use it to think curiously.

早期研究始于构建有限语义网络。研究人员会要求参与者执行一个简单的词语联想任务。正如前一章中通过 TH White 的《玛莎姆夫人的安息》中教授的轶事所描述的那样，首先向参与者展示实验者选择的一个单词，然后要求他们说出他们脑海中浮现的第一个或多个单词。通过整理许多参与者的回答，研究人员可以估计单词之间的平均距离。但更有趣的是，通过要求参与者制作这样的列表，或制作叙述或故事，科学家可以开始了解产生的语义网络结构与心理健康或疾病之间的关系。42然而，从许多个体获取词语联想网络的过程非常缓慢，需要替代方法来扩大调查范围。一个重要的另一种互补方法是从书面语料库构建语义网络，例如通过连接句法上相互依赖的单词或句子中相隔五到十个单词的单词。43后一种程序建立在这样一个事实之上：在观察到一个人是其交往伙伴的某种组合的情况下，句子一部分中单词的共现暗示了语义相关性。因此，任何作者的故事、博客、文章或书籍都可以建模为词语共现网络。44事实上，这种方法还可以扩展到大型语料库中的许多作者，以研究语义网络在数年、数十年、数百年和数千年中是如何演变的。

Early studies began by building finite semantic networks. Investigators would ask participants to perform a simple word association task. As described in an earlier chapter via an anecdote about the professor in T. H. White’s Mistress Masham’s Repose, participants were first shown a word chosen by the experimenter, and then asked to speak the first one or more words that came into their minds. By collating responses from many participants, investigators could estimate the average distances between words. But even more intriguingly, by asking participants to produce such lists, or to produce narratives or stories, scientists could begin to understand the relationships between the produced semantic network structure and mental health or illness.42 The process of acquiring word association networks from many individuals is painstakingly slow, however, and alternative approaches were needed to scale the investigations. An important complementary approach is to build a semantic network from a written corpus, such as by connecting words that are syntactically dependent on one another or appear within five to ten words from one another in a sentence.43 The latter procedure builds upon the fact that the co-occurrence of words in a portion of a sentence is suggestive of semantic relatedness under the observation that one is some combination of the company one keeps. Any author’s stories, blogs, articles, or books can hence be modeled as word co-occurrence networks.44 In fact, the approach can also be extended to many authors in large corpora to study how semantic networks have evolved over years, decades, centuries, and millennia.

词语联想和词语共现网络虽然功能强大，但并不能直接测量意义的相似性，只能间接测量。最新的进展提供了全自动（简单、快速）和直接的意义评估，它使用机器学习方法来推断大型书面语料库中的潜在结构。一个广泛使用的例子是谷歌的 Word2Vec 算法，它将单词的含义提炼到 N 维概念空间中的单个位置。45正如每个人在地球上的位置可以用两个坐标（纬度和经度）指定一样，每个单词在概念空间中的位置可以用 N 个坐标指定，其中 N 是多个独立的概念特征。Word2Vec 算法学习该概念空间的性质（意义的性质）以及单词在其中的位置（它们各自的含义）。然后可以计算出概念含义之间的距离，就像你和朋友之间的距离可以通过你们在地球上各自位置之间的测地线距离来计算一样。考虑到单词的位置和单词之间的距离，我们可以更全面地开始研究人类在知识网络上以相同或不同的方式行走的方式。

While powerful, word association and word co-occurrence networks do not provide direct measurements of similarity in meaning but instead only indirect. The most recent advance that offers a fully automatic (easy, fast) and direct assessment of meaning uses machine learning methods to infer latent structures in a large written corpus. A widely used example is Google’s Word2Vec algorithm, which distills a word’s meaning into a single location in an N-dimensional space of concepts.45 Just as each person’s location on the earth can be specified by two coordinates (latitude and longitude), each word’s location in conceptual space can be specified by N coordinates, where N is a number of independent concept features. The Word2Vec algorithm learns the nature of that conceptual space (the nature of meaning) and the location of words within it (their respective meanings). Then distances between the meanings of concepts can be calculated, just as the distance between you and a friend can be calculated by the geodesic distance between your respective locations on the earth. Given the location of words and the distances between words, we can more fully begin to study the ways in which humans walk samely or differently on knowledge networks.

我们沿着意义路径穿越知识空间的本质可以根据我们的环境、文化、目标、个性和心理状态而改变、适应和重塑。我们每天浏览网页时的方式都不一样。46 我们在为课堂作业、书籍、期刊文章、博客文章或只是一封电子邮件从草稿到草稿时写作的方式也不同。我们在为新概念寻找新概念时的方式也不同。在教科书和其他资源的各个章节中，我们都能遇到它们。我们甚至在不同的心理健康状态下也会采取不同的行动，无论是短暂的轻度抑郁状态还是更持久的精神病状态。47在前者中，我们可能会迈出更短的步伐；在后者中，我们可能会在底层知识网络上迈出更长的步伐，看到别人看不到的联系。以不同的方式行事是我们所有人都拥有的特权，我们可以选择每天重新协商。我们有机会调整我们的反应以适应不断变化的内部和外部世界，有时激励我们成为猎人，有时激励我们成为舞者。

The nature of our walk through knowledge space, along the paths of meaning, can change, adapt, and remodel according to our environment, culture, goals, personality, and mental state. We walk differently through web pages as we browse from day to day.46 We write differently as we move from draft to draft, for a class project, a book, a journal article, a blog post, or simply an email. We walk differently through new concepts as we encounter them from chapter to chapter in textbooks and other resources. We even walk differently in different states of mental health, whether through transient states of mild depression or through more permanent states of psychosis.47 In the former, we may take shorter steps; in the latter, we may take longer steps on the underlying knowledge network, seeing connections where others do not. Walking differently is a privilege that we all have, and one that we can choose to negotiate anew each day. We have the opportunity to adapt our responses to a changing internal and external world that sometimes inspires us to be hunters, and other times inspires us to be dancers.

* * *

* * *

而在个人行走中，我们不仅经常使用特有的步长和方向，还有步态、双手摆动、呼吸节奏、单词的强调、辅音或元音间隙的和谐音。48当我们穿越知识空间时，我们的动作和声音点缀着风景，从这些标点符号中产生了我们行走的节奏。我们的标点符号是一个指纹，一种存在方式，一种时间的流逝。49努力的破折号，攀登的冒号，进一步向顶峰迈进的分号，或者转身走另一条路的逗号。在下一个山顶之前停下来喘口气的时间。旋转身体、张开双臂、面朝天空的问号，问“为什么？”并乞求大自然解释自己。冲刺最后几米以越过边缘窥视下一个山谷的感叹号。无论我们是用整个身体来点缀，还是用外部附属物或内部器官的运动来点缀，我们清晰地穿越思想的路径都属于我们，也只属于我们。也许正是我们个人的能力，用挥动的手点缀空气，用流动的双脚来安排石头，这解释了为什么我们中的一些人看到树林间的空隙，而其他人看到灌木丛下的洞穴，每个人都在自己的时间里走出小路，进入充满好奇未知的空间。

And in that personal walk, we often use not only a characteristic step length and direction but also a gait, a swinging of the hands, a rhythm of the breath, an emphasis on a word, a euphony of consonant strings or vowel chasms.48 The movements and sounds we make punctuate the landscape as we traverse the space of knowledge, and from that punctuation arises the cadence of our walk. Our punctuation is a fingerprint, a way of being, a passing through time.49 The em dash of effort, the colon of climbing, the semicolons of pressing further to the peak, or perhaps the commas of turning about to walk a different path. The periods of pausing for breath before the next summit. The question mark of spinning one’s body with arms flung out and face turned to the sky, asking, “Why?” and begging Nature to explain herself. The exclamation mark of dashing the last few meters to peek over the edge to the next valley. Whether we punctuate with our full bodies, or with the movements of our external appendages or internal organs, our articulated walk through ideas belongs to us, and to us alone. Perhaps it is our individual ability to punctuate the air with our waving hands, and orchestrate the stones with our roving feet, that explains why some of us see an opening among the trees while others see a cavern beneath the bushes, and each in their own time steps off the path into the space of the curious unknowns.

6

6

好奇心开始行动

Curiosity Takes a Walk

对我来说，一天中的时间比走路的动作更重要。坐在椅子上，我的大脑停止思考。移动双腿，思绪开始流动。血液流动将思绪从角落中冲刷出来，文字清晰可见，故事展开。

The time of day is less insistent for me than the motion of walking. Trapped in a chair, my mind shuts down. Moving my legs, thoughts start to flow. Swept out of their corners by the flow of my blood, words come into focus, and stories unfold.

—Anna Tsing，《作家论写作》（2015）

—Anna Tsing, “Writers on Writing” (2015)

在好奇心的驱使下，你的思绪总是在向着某个方向发展。无论是向前急奔、向后跳跃还是漫步，你的好奇心都会在一次跋涉中探索现有地形并重塑一切。因此，问自己如何思考，同样重要的是问自己如何行走。

In the grip of curiosity, your mind is always going somewhere. Whether scurrying forward, leaping back, or meandering along, your curious mind negotiates existing terrain and refashions it all in one trek. To ask, then, how it is that you think is also, and just as importantly, to ask how it is that you walk.

在前面的章节中，我们以多种方式分析了好奇心作为一种运动。我们讨论了好奇心沿着认识论关系的路线行进——或者说是边缘工作。我们将好奇心描述为知识网络增长的动力，为现有知识系统添加（和重新想象）节点和边缘。我们描述了好奇心的动觉特征，辨别了它在收集、调查或想象新事物时不同行程的形状。在上一章中，我们谈到了好奇心作为知识空间中的漫步。在这里，我们将漫步作为一种对哲学和网络科学具有特殊意义的好奇运动。至少早在 17 世纪，网络理论家就将图形空间（代表概念或具体网络）的遍历描述为漫步。例如，数学家伦纳德·欧拉（Leonard Euler）就曾苦苦思索如何穿越一个人不仅可以根据特定的模式和在特定的约束条件下在不同地点和不同想法之间行走，而且正如哲学家们几千年来所坚持的那样，思想空间的穿越和世界空间的穿越之间存在着共生关系。早在古希腊逍遥学派时期，散步就不仅被理解为一种理想的环境，而且被理解为一种自然的哲学反思刺激。1那么，散步——这种日常的漫步形式——为好奇心的网络哲学提供了哪些概念资源？我们怎样才能将好奇的思考视为思想空间中的漫步，将好奇的旅行视为物质空间中的漫步？这种重新概念化又阐明了好奇心本身的哪些方面？

In the preceding chapters, we analyzed curiosity as a movement in several sorts of ways. We discussed curiosity as traveling along the lines of epistemic relations—or as edgework. We described curiosity as the motivator of knowledge network growth, adding (and reimagining) nodes and edges to existing knowledge systems. We characterized curiosity’s kinesthetic signatures, discerning the shapes of its different itineraries as it collects, investigates, or imagines something new. And in the last chapter, we touched upon curiosity as a walk in knowledge space. Here we zero in on walking as one kind of curious movement of special significance to philosophy and network science. At least as early as the seventeenth century, network theorists described the traversal of graphic space—representing either conceptual or concrete networks—as a walk. Mathematician Leonard Euler, for example, grappled with the quandary of how to walk across Königsberg’s seven bridges without crossing any more than once. Not only can one walk between places and between ideas, according to specific patterns and within specific constraints, but, as philosophers have insisted for millennia, there is a symbiotic relationship between traversals of thought-space and traversals of world-space. As early as the ancient Greek Peripatetics, the walk has been understood not only as an ideal setting but also as a natural stimulation for philosophical reflection.1 What conceptual resources, then, does the walk—that quotidian form of perambulation—provide for a network philosophy of curiosity? How might one think of curious thinking as a walk in thought space and of curious travel as a walk in material space? And what does this reconceptualization illuminate about curiosity itself?

重要的是，并非所有的行走都是一样的，好奇心的行程也不尽相同。正如我们所论证的，好奇心是一条路径，一种协商复杂系统的方式，一种知识网络增长和变化的实践。2但它的路径不同，协商模式也不同。好奇心朝不同的方向出发，穿上不同的鞋子、轮子、地图和零食。在网络科学和图论中，穿越节点和边的“行走”具有独特的结构和约束。当简单地通过图“行走”时，任何节点和任何边都可以重复。可以说，世界是你的牡蛎。然而，小径、回路、路径和循环是特定类型的行走，每种都有独特的约束。例如，小径可以重复节点但不能重复边（例如，通过不同的跋涉到达相同的山峰），而路径既不能重复节点也不能重复边（例如，只到达不同的山峰和不同的跋涉）。当一条小径回到起点时，这被称为“回路”，而当一条路径绕回来时，这被称为“循环”。如果好奇心是图形学意义上的行走，那么问题就变成了：好奇心会走什么样的路，在每种情况下，又会受到哪些限制？

Importantly, not all walks are the same, nor are the itineraries of curiosity. As we have argued, curiosity is a pathway, a way of negotiating complex systems, a praxis of knowledge network growth and change.2 But its pathways diverge, as do its patterns of negotiation. Curiosity strikes off in different directions, donning different shoes, wheels, maps, and snacks. In network science and graph theory, the “walks” taken to traverse nodes and edges have unique structures and constraints. When taking a “walk” simpliciter through a graph, any node and any edge can be repeated. The world, one might say, is your oyster. Trails, circuits, paths, and cycles, however, are specific sorts of walks, each with unique constraints. Trails, for example, can repeat nodes but not edges (e.g., hitting the same peaks but by different treks), while paths can repeat neither nodes nor edges (e.g., hitting only different peaks and different treks). When a trail returns to where it started, it is called a circuit, whereas when a path circles back, it is called a cycle. If curiosity is a walk in a graphological sense, then the question becomes this: What sorts of walks does curiosity take and what constraints, in each case, apply?

接下来，我们将认真对待这一邀请，关注步行如何产生各种思考，以及各种思考如何成为步行。我们研究了四种身体步行，它们本身涉及特定形式的好奇思维：哲学步行、精神步行、环境步行和政治步行。通过促进不同类型的思维，这些在物质空间中移动的方式映射到在概念空间中移动的方式。我们甚至可以称它们为好奇心漫步。在关注这些好奇心漫步时，我们描述了每一种漫步和每种相应的思维形式的约束。在这样做的过程中，我们准备好对这些好奇心漫步进行建模和测量，并想象它们在网络理论中的关联图。最终，我们提出，将好奇心的哲学和网络科学结合在一起的一个关键方法正是将这些探究的地理和图形学结合在一起思考。毕竟，将好奇心思维分析为一种漫步扩展了我们以新方式应对好奇心实践和影响的能力。

In what follows, we take this invitation seriously by attending to how walking produces kinds of thinking and how kinds of thinking are kinds of walking. We investigate four sorts of physical walks, which themselves involve specific forms of curious thought: the philosophical walk, the spiritual walk, the environmental walk, and the political walk. By facilitating different kinds of thinking, these ways of moving through material space map onto ways of moving through conceptual space. One might even call them curiosity walks. In attending to these curiosity walks, we characterize the constraints of each sort of walk and each corresponding form of thought. In doing so, we equip ourselves to model and measure these curiosity walks and to imagine their correlative graphs in network theory. Ultimately, we propose that one critical way to cinch together a philosophy and network science of curiosity is precisely by thinking these geographies and graphologies of inquiry together. After all, analyzing curious thought as a walk expands our capacity to tackle the practice and impact of curiosity in new ways.

询问、漫步

Asking, Ambling

长期以来，人们一直认为好奇心和旅行是相辅相成的，仿佛它们是时间道路上的同伴。旅行是一种连接点、探索新领域的方式，而好奇心则是在概念景观中从一个想法轻轻移动到另一个想法的方式。因此，从根本上讲，好奇心是一种穿越空间的方式。好奇心在旅行。甚至可以说，无论好奇心看起来多么抽象和概念化，它都是彻头彻尾的空间性的。古人将好奇心概念化为跨越空间边界的运动。无论是帝国扩张、社会越轨，还是文学中将边注与散文混合，对他们来说，好奇心都是一种不受约束的旅行，既诱人又会造成政治不稳定。3中世纪人认为好奇心是同时在两个空间域中的旅行：物质世界和概念世界。对他们来说，好奇心的特点是心神不定和身体游移不定，即精神的飘忽和身体的飘忽。4因此，好奇的人（或好奇者）本质上是游荡的，不受领土或分类学的限制。当然，没有哪个时代比现代时期更能体现好奇心和旅行的同义性，现代时期本身又被称为大发现时代和好奇时代。5正是在这个时候，好奇心和制图学最紧密地交织在一起。好奇心图表穿越陌生的土地和人迹罕至的海洋（殖民者的好奇心将神秘变成了暴力和资本）。它的意义就是穿越概念和物理空间的某种运动。

Curiosity and travel have long been thought alongside one another, as if they were companions together along the paths of time. Traveling is a way of connecting the dots, exploring new terrains, while curiosity is a way of moving lightly from one idea to another in a conceptual landscape. At some fundamental level, then, curiosity is a manner of traversing space. Curiosity travels. One might even say that, however much it might seem purely abstract and ideational, curiosity is spatial, through and through. The ancients conceptualized curiosity as a movement across spatial boundaries. Whether in imperial expansion, social transgressions, or the literary mixing of marginalia with prose, curiosity was, for them, an untrammeled sort of travel, as deliciously tempting as it was politically destabilizing.3 The medievals conceived of curiosity as simultaneous travel in two spatial registers: the material world and the conceptual world. For them, curiosity was characterized equally by a wandering mind and a wandering body, the evagatio mentis and evagatio corporis.4 As such, the curious person (or curiosus) was essentially errant, on the move regardless of the constraints of territory or taxonomy. And of course, there is no era in which curiosity and travel are more synonymous than the modern period, itself dubbed the Age of Discovery and the Age of Curiosity by turns.5 It is in this moment that curiosity and cartography are most potently intertwined. Curiosity charts a course through strange lands and untraveled seas (with colonial curiosity turning mystery into violence and capital). Its very meaning is a certain movement through conceptual and physical space.

好奇心和步行，作为一种特殊的旅行方式，也被认为是并存的，甚至是相互影响的。好奇心通常被描述为一种攀爬地平线、跨越边界、在陌生的地方跋涉和在未知的风景中漫步的动力。而步行则被描述为一种探索、发现和好奇的实践。然而，人们不仅可以在相互关联的框架中思考好奇心和步行，而且它们还可以以具体的方式相互关联，这样步行就可以促进好奇心，好奇心决定了人们步行的地点、时间和方式。概念空间和物理空间不仅在某种附加意义上彼此并存，而且相互关联，因此相互影响。当一个人好奇时，他总是对特定的地理位置感到好奇。无论一个人是否对那个地理位置感到好奇，那个地理位置都是他好奇心的一个特征。更根本的是，一个人的好奇心是一种地理想象。无论一个人的好奇心是否通过地理移动来表达——或者一个人在何处以及如何移动来调查某事——好奇心都是穿越新奇概念景观的一种方式。6拉丁语solvitur ambulando（意为“通过步行来解决问题”）指的是一种只有在步行时才会发生的思考，而希腊语术语methodos（meta - odos，或“关于道路”）指的是一种只有在思考时才会发生的步行。因此，几个世纪的思想让我们以这种强大的关系意义来思考好奇心和步行。

Curiosity and walking, as a specific kind of travel, have also been thought alongside and indeed through one another. Curiosity is often characterized as a drive to scramble over the horizon, to stride across boundary lines, to traipse around the unfamiliar, and to wander through uncharted landscapes. Walking, in turn, is characterized as a practice of exploration, discovery, and wonder. It is not only the case that one can think of curiosity and walking in interrelated frames, however, but also that they interrelate in concrete ways, such that walking facilitates curiosity, and curiosity shapes where and when and how one walks. Conceptual and physical space exist not simply beside one another in some additive sense but also in relation to one another and therefore mutually affect one another. When one is curious, one is always curious within a specific geographical location. Whether or not one is curious about that geography, that geography is a feature of one’s curiosity. More fundamentally, one’s curiosity is a form of geographical imagination. Regardless of whether or not one’s curiosity is expressed via geographical movement—or where and how one physically moves to investigate something—that curiosity is a way of traversing novel notionscapes.6 The Latin solvitur ambulando (meaning “to solve by walking”) refers to a kind of thinking that happens only when walking, whereas the Greek term methodos (meta-odos, or “concerning the path”) refers to a kind of walking that happens only when thinking. Centuries of thought thus invite us to think curiosity and walking together in this robust, relational sense.

然而，并不是每个人都有平等的机会或鼓励去行走和思考。事实上，好奇心和行走的紧密交织带来了双重偏见，即认为某些性别、种族、能力或阶级的人既不是好奇的思考者，也不是探索性的行走者。正如我们在引言中看到的那样，弗吉尼亚·伍尔夫被大学直接排除在外，在那里，博学的男士们在校园里漫步，然后慢慢地走进图书馆。此外，这种偏见在她之前和之后的几个世纪中都存在。例如，对于亚里士多德来说，女性并不是真正的思想家，因为她们和动物一样缺乏理性。同样，对于二十世纪文化理论家沃尔特·本杰明认为，女性不是真正的步行者。在一段令人震惊的文字中，他沉思道：

Not everyone has equal opportunity or encouragement to walk and to think, however. Indeed, with the rich intertwining of curiosity and walking comes a double prejudice that assumes people of certain genders, races, abilities, or classes are not curious thinkers, nor are they exploratory walkers. As we saw in the introduction, Virginia Woolf was excluded point-blank from the university, where learned men traipsed across the grounds and trailed off into the library. That bias, moreover, saturates centuries both before and after her. For Aristotle, for example, women are not properly thinkers insofar as they—like animals—lack reason. Similarly, for twentieth-century cultural theorist Walter Benjamin, women are not properly walkers. In a shocking passage, he muses:

对于智人种群的女性来说——在其存在的最早时期——身体的水平放置一定具有最大的优势。这使她们更容易怀孕。……从这个考虑出发，人们也许会大胆地问：一般来说，直立行走在男性身上出现的时间难道不会早于女性吗？如果那样的话，女性将是男性的四足同伴，就像今天的狗或猫一样。7

For the females of the species homo sapiens—at the earliest conceivable period of its existence—the horizontal positioning of the body must have had the greatest advantages. It made pregnancy easier for them. . . . Proceeding from this consideration, one may perhaps venture to ask: Mightn’t walking erect, in general, have appeared earlier in men than in women? In that case, the woman would have been the four-footed companion of the man, as the dog or cat is today.7

然而，女性并不是历史上唯一被排除在真正的思想者和行走者类别之外的社会群体。当我们在本章中考虑哲学、精神、环境和政治行走时，我们不仅有意识地使行走文学多样化（这项任务可能令人惊讶地仍然非常必要），而且我们还尖锐地思考谁的好奇行走和思想得到了认可。好奇心的网络哲学如何打破这些偏见并在这个领域开辟新的认可模式？

Women, however, are not the only social group to be historically dismissed from the category of true thinkers and walkers. As we move in this chapter to consider philosophical, spiritual, environmental, and political walks, not only do we consciously diversify walking literature (a task, perhaps surprisingly, still deeply necessary), but we also think pointedly about whose curious walks and thoughts get recognized. How might a network philosophy of curiosity break these biases and open up new patterns of recognition in this space?

哲学之行

The Philosophical Walk

尽管西方哲学起源于古代逍遥学派，但它并不总是将散步视为反思的理想场所。如今，“扶手椅哲学”的抨击之所以如此强烈，正是因为它的存在如此明显。在一个又一个的教室里，人们使用俗话说的“椅子”来支持无休止的思想实验（从形而上学到个人身份），这不可避免地掩盖了哲学的静坐化。然而，思考确实并且应该在静止的位置进行，这在古代是有先例的。希腊人担心那些四处游荡的诡辩家，他们对绩效和报酬比对智慧更感兴趣。而勒内·笛卡尔则以坐在他的火炉旁的椅子上写作《沉思录》而闻名。尽管有这些禁忌，哲学家们散步并不罕见。让-雅克·卢梭经常在树林里漫步，并坦言“我不敢相信”presque penser quand je reste en place [我站在原地几乎无法思考]。” 8伊曼纽尔康德会如此有规律地在一天中的同一时间走同一条路线，以至于据说人们以他为基准来设定时钟。弗里德里希尼采每天会步行八个小时，穿越德国、瑞士和地中海沿岸，去追寻那种在高山上舞动的思想。9西蒙娜德波伏娃也经常连续步行几个小时。10因此，哲学家一直是步行者。然而，不同的哲学家和哲学采用不同的步行方式，具有不同的空间限制。在这里，我们分析了两种最古老的哲学步行，即苏格拉底和柏拉图式的步行，以及它们在当代的反响。11通过在加勒比理论家爱德华格里桑特所说的群岛思维和大陆思维之间移动，我们探索了哲学思想地理的两种原型。12

Despite Western philosophy’s roots in the ancient Peripatetics, it has not always championed walking as an ideal site for reflection. Today, the harpooning of “armchair philosophizing” is so poignant precisely because its presence is so palpable. And in classroom after classroom, the proverbial “chair” is deployed to support endless thought experiments (from metaphysics to personal identity), inevitably belying the becoming-sedentary of philosophy. That thinking does and ought to happen in a stationary position, however, has ancient precedent. The Greeks worried about the traveling sophists, who were more interested in performance and remuneration than in wisdom. And René Descartes is famous for settling into the chair by his cockle stove to write the Meditations. Despite these counterindications, it is not uncommon for philosophers to walk. Jean-Jacques Rousseau would often ramble about in the woods and confessed “je ne puis presque penser quand je reste en place [I can barely think when standing in place].”8 Immanuel Kant would walk the same route at the same time of day with such regularity that people were said to set their clocks by him. And Friedrich Nietzsche would walk up to eight hours a day, across Germany, Switzerland, and the Mediterranean coast, to court the sort of thoughts that dance in the high mountains.9 Simone de Beauvoir, too, regularly walked hours on end.10 Philosophers have been walkers, then. Yet different philosophers and philosophies have assumed different walks, with different spatial constraints. Here we analyze two of the oldest philosophical walks, the Socratic and the Platonic, and their contemporary reverberations.11 By moving between what Caribbean theorist Édouard Glissant might call archipelagic and continental thinking, we explore two archetypes for the geography of philosophical thought.12

尽管苏格拉底非常讨厌出国旅行，但他决心穿越雅典——实际上是步行雅典——以寻找智慧。在当地漫游时，苏格拉底邀请他的雅典同胞与他一起漫游，无论是身体还是思想。苏格拉底难以置信地听说，根据德尔斐神谕，他是雅典最聪明的人，于是发誓要从事“漫游 [ planē ]”的工作，直到他发现智慧的真正源泉，超越自己的无知。13这个誓言使他过上了流浪和行走的生活，处处陷入困境或令人沮丧的认知僵局。14当一个人四处游荡，没有固定的路线或目的地四处走动时，他很容易偶然发现不可通约和不可判定的东西，揭开支撑共同信条的摇摇欲坠的支架。对苏格拉底来说，这永远不是一件私事。承担起神圣使命的苏格拉底，成了同事眼中的“牛虻”。15牛虻会煽动运动，但这种运动并不一定朝着任何特定的方向。苏格拉底的主要目标只是将雅典人从意识形态的沉睡中唤醒，让他们摆脱认识论的自满。他激励并引导他们进入困境——认识到他们并不知道他们认为自己知道的东西。16因此，苏格拉底的行走是一场集体的无知之旅。它本质上是解构的。“苏格拉底的流浪不是为了获取利益”，希腊学者西尔维娅蒙蒂格里奥评论说：“它们引导他做减法，而不是做加法。” 17苏格拉底式的好奇心漫步不是为了填补信息空白，而是旨在扩大这一空白，使其变得奢侈地扩大。

Although Socrates fiercely loathed travel abroad, he was committed to traversing—indeed walking—Athens in search of wisdom. Roaming locally, Socrates invited his fellow Athenians to roam with him, in body and in mind. Having heard in disbelief that he was the wisest man in Athens, according to the Delphic oracle, Socrates vowed to assume the work of “wandering [planē]” until he discovered the true source of wisdom, outside his own ignorance.13 This vow led him to a life of wandering—and walking, prey at every turn to the experience of aporia or consternating cognitive impasse.14 When one routes and rambles, moving hither and thither with no fixed course or destination, one easily stumbles upon the incommensurable and the undecidable, unmasking the rickety scaffolds that support common tenets. For Socrates, this is always more than a private affair. Assuming the mantle of divine calling, Socrates becomes a “gadfly” to his colleagues.15 While a gadfly incites movement, that movement need not be in any specific direction. Socrates’s primary goal is simply to wake the Athenians from their ideological slumber, to shake them out of their epistemic complacency. He goads and guides them into aporia—into the recognition that they do not know what they think they know.16 The Socratic walk, then, is a collective journey of unknowing. It is inherently deconstructive. “Socrates’ wanderings are not acquisitive,” Hellenist Silvia Montiglio remarks; “they lead him to subtract, not to add.”17 Rather than aiming to fill an information gap, Socratic curiosity walks aim to widen that gap, to make it yawn luxuriously.

与苏格拉底不同，柏拉图是一位经验丰富的旅行者，但他更喜欢坐着思考。根据柏拉图主义的信条，真理存在于不变的精神领域。只要物质世界不断运动和变化，它就是一种愚蠢和虚假的力量。因此，对真理的探索必须摒弃身体和智力上的游荡，转而选择清醒、冷静的灵魂之旅。柏拉图写道，哲学家“能够理解永远不变的东西 [即真理]”，而非哲学家“在多种多样的物体之间徘徊”，因此无法获得真理。18虽然柏拉图的大多数对话都以流浪的苏格拉底开始，将他自己和他的同胞悬而未决，但他们很快就集中注意力，每个人都坐下来。19在柏拉图对话的哲学化过程中，牛虻苏格拉底变成了助产士苏格拉底。20在助产方面，对于过程或目的地几乎没有不确定性；有一个既定的计划和预期的结果。因此，对柏拉图来说，苏格拉底式的寻找未知的思考和徘徊最终必须被有效的对话、辩证法和分词法所取代。分词法是一种划分和隔离的方法，通过这种方法，事物沿着关节被解剖。21人们可以通过合作交谈来寻找越来越细微的区别，从而获得理解。正如柏拉图的洞穴寓言所描绘的那样，它是从无知的黑暗到真理的光明的一条直线。通过走一条越来越直、越来越细的线，就可以获得真正的启蒙并获得知识。

Unlike Socrates, Plato is a seasoned traveler who nevertheless prefers to sit while thinking. According to the tenets of Platonism, Truth exists in the unchanging realm of spirit. Insofar as the material world constantly moves and changes, it is a force of folly and falsehood. For this reason, the search for Truth must winnow out physical and intellectual wandering in favor of a clear-eyed, sober journey of the soul. Philosophers, Plato writes, “are able to apprehend that which is forever and always the same [i.e., Truth],” whereas nonphilosophers “wander among multiple and manifold objects,” and thereby fail to attain Truth.18 While most of Plato’s dialogues open with a wandering Socrates, suspending himself and his compatriots in aporia, they quickly center themselves and everyone takes a seat.19 In the becoming-philosophical of Platonic dialogues, then, Socrates the gadfly is transmogrified into Socrates the midwife.20 In midwifery, there is relatively little uncertainty about the course or destination; there is an established plan and an expected outcome. For Plato, then, Socratic wondering and wandering in search of unknowing must ultimately be supplanted by effective dialogue, dialectics, and diairesis. Diairesis is a method of division and isolation by which things are dissected along their joints.21 It is by collaboratively conversing in search of finer and finer distinctions that people can attain understanding. As depicted in Plato’s allegory of the cave, it is a straight ascent from the darkness of ignorance to the light of Truth. By walking an ever-straighter, thinner line, then, true enlightenment can be achieved and knowledge gained.

几个世纪以来，苏格拉底式散步和柏拉图式散步经历了无数次迭代，但它们的区别始终存在。在她的纪录片《审视生活》中，电影制片人阿斯特拉·泰勒采访了边散步边思考的哲学家。22以一种让人联想到苏格拉底的方式，阿维塔尔·罗内尔利用在曼哈顿下城汤姆金斯广场公园散步的机会，反思哲学的使命是“制造麻烦”和“制造冲突”，无论它身在何处。她编织着自己的方式穿过公园时，罗内尔思维敏捷，对周围环境不断变化的问题做出敏捷反应。另一方面，玛莎·努斯鲍姆在芝加哥湖畔散步时，提出了一个条理清晰、连贯一致的论点，说明为什么正义理论不应建立在契约之上，而应建立在人类繁荣的能力之上。穿过相对笔直的湖滨步道时，努斯鲍姆从头到尾都保持着同样紧密、连贯的思路。当然，这两种模式也可以结合起来。朱迪斯·巴特勒和苏娜拉·泰勒在旧金山一起接受采访，对步行本身的社会建构进行了尖锐的探索，但她们这样做的同时，也把街道和路缘切口、陌生人和二手商店作为哲学思考的提示。此外，他们的哲学碰撞从根本上来说是一种关系，他们共同邀请泰勒使用轮椅来有效地打破传统上对独立、健全的步行者/知情者的概念。

Over the centuries, there have been numerous iterations of the Socratic and Platonic walks, but their distinction remains intact. In her documentary Examined Life, filmmaker Astra Taylor interviewed philosophers philosophizing while walking.22 In a manner reminiscent of Socrates, Avital Ronell uses the opportunity of walking around Tomkins Square Park in Lower Manhattan to reflect on philosophy’s calling “to make trouble” and “to create skirmishes” wherever it finds itself. Weaving her way through the park, Ronell thinks quickly, responding with agility to the shifting questions posed by her surroundings. Martha Nussbaum, on the other hand, while walking Chicago’s lakeshore, launches a well-organized and cohesive argument for why theories of justice should be built not on contracts but instead on human capacities for flourishing. Traversing the relatively straight Lakefront Trail, Nussbaum holds a similarly tight, cohesive thread from beginning to end. Of course, the two modes can also be usefully combined. Judith Butler and Sunaura Taylor, who are interviewed together in San Francisco, conduct a pointed exploration of the social construction of walking itself, but they do so while taking the street and the curb cuts, the strangers and the secondhand shop, as prompts to philosophize. Their philosophical encounter, moreover, is fundamentally relational, and they together invite Taylor’s use of a wheelchair to fruitfully derail traditional conceptualizations of the independent, able-bodied walker/knower.

苏格拉底和柏拉图的路径不仅形态各异，而且蕴含着不同类型的哲学思想。对于苏格拉底，或许对于罗内尔来说，任何事物都可能是无知的场所。四处奔波和参与随机小冲突是破坏不合理认知安宁的最佳方式。他们的随机行走不是直接构建知识网络，而是着手拆除、连根拔起节点和孤立边缘。对于柏拉图，或许对于努斯鲍姆来说，通往真理的道路更加严肃和沉稳。每一步都必须经过测试并锁定在原地，就像一个人在不稳定的地形中有条不紊地站稳脚跟一样。如果一条路是死胡同，那么一个人已经迷失了方向；然后他应该回到主路上，更仔细地分析地形。虽然这条路可能以迷失开始，但它会变得越来越专注，离题越来越少。两条路径：一条追求碎片化和不透明性，另一条追求整合和透明性。最终，无论节点是连续添加还是随机添加，无论边缘是得到大力加强还是轻微强调，哲学——以及好奇的思想——都会沿着这些路径前进，好奇地构建知识，同时也将其分解，为新的构建腾出空间。

The Socratic and Platonic walks not only have distinct shapes but also house different kinds of philosophical thinking. For Socrates, and arguably for Ronell, anything and everything could be a locale of ignorance. Scurrying about and engaging in random skirmishes is the best way to cohesively disrupt ill-justified epistemic repose. Rather than straightforwardly building knowledge networks, their random walks set about the work of unbuilding, uprooting nodes and orphaning edges.
