For Plato, and again arguably for Nussbaum, walks toward truth are more somber and staid. Each step must be tested and locked in place, the way one might methodically secure one’s footing in unstable terrain. If a path turns out to be a dead-end, one has wandered; one should then return to the main path and parse the terrain more carefully. While this walk may begin with wandering, it becomes ever more keenly focused, with fewer and fewer digressions. Two walks then: one courting fragmentation and opacity, the other consolidation and transparency. Ultimately, whether nodes are added consecutively or haphazardly, and whether edges are heavily reinforced or lightly underlined, philosophy—and indeed curious thought—proceeds by way of these paths, inquisitively building knowledge as much as breaking it down to make room for new constructions.

精神之旅

The Spiritual Walk

在所有宗教传统中，精神漫步都占有重要地位。有些漫步是成年礼，例如需要在荒野中逗留的漫步。有些漫步是日常冥想练习，例如迷宫漫步，在世界各地的宗教传统中都能找到。还有一些永恒的神圣朝圣，包括麦加朝觐、日本的熊野古道和西班牙的圣地亚哥朝圣之路。还有一些在整个宗教历史中纪念的漫步，包括亚伯拉罕的迁徙和以色列人的逗留。虽然他们的行程各不相同，但它们的功能却非常相似。精神漫步以各自的方式旨在协调心灵，为其旅程赋予形状并为其思想赋予模式。通过同时挑战思想和身体，他们寻求与神的联系。就精神漫步寻求神圣洞察力和道德转变而言，它们是好奇心漫步。这里我们分析两种精神之旅：佛教行禅和新教朝圣。虽然这两种旅程都经历了数千年的发展，但我们关注的是佛教行禅的当代实践和新教朝圣的中世纪形成。在此过程中，我们将到达之旅与目的地之旅进行了对比，到达之旅的每一步都是在圣地上，而目的地之旅的每一步都是到达圣地的手段。前者是一种正念的实践，后者是一种净化的实践。

Across every religious tradition, spiritual walks have had pride of place. Some walks serve as rites of passage, such as those requiring sojourns in the wilderness. Some serve as daily meditative practices, such as the labyrinth walk, which one finds in religious traditions around the globe. There are the timeless holy pilgrimages, including the Hajj to Mecca, the Kumano Kodo in Japan, and the Camino de Santiago in Spain. And there are walks commemorated across religious history, including the migration of Abraham and the sojourn of the Israelites. While their itineraries have been diverse, however, their functions are quite similar. Spiritual walks, each in their own way, aim to attune the mind, to lend shape to its journey and pattern to its thought. In challenging the mind and body at once, they court connection with the divine. Insofar as spiritual walks seek divine insight and moral transformation, they are curiosity walks. Here we analyze two spiritual walks: the Buddhist walking meditation and the Protestant pilgrimage. While both sorts of walks are millennia in the making, we focus on the contemporary practice of the Buddhist walking meditation and the medieval formation of the Protestant pilgrimage. In doing so, we contrast a walk of arrival, in which every step is on holy ground, with one of destination, in which steps are a means to reach a sacred place. The former is a practice of mindfulness, the latter of purification.

越南僧侣一行禅师将佛教行禅描述为一步一步到达的步行。他写道，无论一个人是步行去公交车站、穿过办公室、走进公园、沿河而行，还是爬上山，“每一步都是到达”。不要为了到达某个地方而行走；没有目的地。投入到每一步中。不要急切地等待下一步，也不要从拐弯处向前张望。旅程是一步一步的，每一步都是一步。稳步地让自己时刻保持意识。作为一种正念练习，这样的行走可以培养平静和当下感。通过它，一个人慢慢摆脱过去的遗憾和未来的焦虑。拒绝奔跑，决心抵制干扰，行走将一个人被牵引的“数百万条路径”换成了一步。与一般的佛教冥想练习一致，行者是鼓励人们专注于他们所看到和听到的东西、双脚接触地面和离开地面的感觉以及呼吸的规律性。“当思想专注于呼吸和行走时，”Hanh 反思道，“我们已经回到家了。” 23也许与直觉相反，这种专注的独特性是与行走者脚下的活地球以及他们体内的人类、动物、植物和矿物祖先真正建立联系的先决条件。

Vietnamese monk Thich Nhat Hanh characterizes the Buddhist walking meditation as a walk of arrival, step by step. Whether one walks to the bus stop, across one’s office, in a park, along a river, or up mountains, he writes, “Arrive with every step.” Do not walk in order to get somewhere; there is no destination. Invest oneself in each step. Let no part wait eagerly for the next step or peer ahead around the bend. The journey is a single step, each and every step. Steadily bring oneself to awareness, moment by moment. As a practice of mindfulness, such walking cultivates peace and presentness. By it, one slowly sloughs off past regrets and future anxieties. Refusing to run and determined to resist distraction, walking exchanges the “millions of pathways” along which one is pulled for a singular step. Consistent with Buddhist meditation practices in general, the walker is encouraged to focus on what they see and hear, the feeling of their feet touching and lifting from the ground, and the regularity of their breath. “When the mind is focused on breathing and walking,” Hanh reflects, “we are already home.”23 Perhaps counterintuitively, this singularity of focus is the precondition of true connection with the living earth beneath the walker and the human, animal, plant, and mineral ancestors within them.

相比之下，新教朝圣无疑是一种以目标为导向、以目的地为中心的徒步，通过考验朝圣者的身体和精神耐力，最终确保他们的救赎。24到达圣地——通常是耶路撒冷或其替代地，朝圣者可以净化过去的罪孽，从而与上帝建立新的联系。这种做法建立在圣经先例的基础上，例如以色列人从埃及出埃及到耶路撒冷的四百年出埃及之旅，以及耶稣在地球上逗留并返回天堂。在这种情况下，有两个主要条件：真正的朝圣必须是艰苦的，并且必须从家里开始和结束。走过未圣化的土地，朝圣者将会也应该经历艰辛。这是他们的考验之地。无论是思想还是身体都不应该游离。为了保护朝圣者免受世俗的享乐和干扰，旅程始于祈求神的帮助和拯救。朝圣者随后会穿上特殊的衣服、手杖和经文，并被要求在路上唱着忧郁的圣歌，而不是喧闹的故事。朝圣者半闭着眼睛，低头向前，耐心而坚定地向着开悟的方向前进。

The Protestant pilgrimage, by contrast, is an undeniably goal-oriented, destination-focused walk that, by testing the physical and spiritual endurance of the pilgrim, ultimately secures their redemption.24 Arriving at the holy place—typically Jerusalem or its stand-in, the pilgrim achieves purification of past sins and thereby a new union with God. The practice builds on scriptural precedents such as the Israelites’ four-hundred-year exodus from Egypt to Jerusalem and Jesus’s sojourn on earth and return to heaven. In this context, two primary conditions hold: the proper pilgrimage must be arduous, and it must begin and end at home. Walking through unsanctified land, the pilgrim will and ought to experience hardship. This is their testing ground. Neither the mind nor the body should wander. In an attempt to safeguard the pilgrim from worldly pleasures and distractions, the journey begins with invocations of divine aid and pleas for deliverance. The pilgrim is then equipped with special garments, staff, and script, and enjoined to travel the road with somber hymns rather than boisterous tales. Proceeding with eyes half shut and angled toward the ground, the pilgrim walks patiently and purposefully toward enlightenment.

这两种行走的不同路线对应着不同的思维路径。佛教的行禅很简单：迈步、抬起、迈步。节点、边缘、节点。行走结束，然后再次开始。模仿这种身体运动的简单性，这里的思想应该集中在一个越来越单一的想法上：步伐本身，保持意识并欣赏其简单的组成部分。将步伐与呼吸结合起来，行者以完整的存在到达目的地，身心协调一致。这种思维不是项目思维，而是当下思维。相比之下，新教朝圣之旅则更加复杂：在到达圣地并返回家园之前，步行很长，充满考验和磨难。节点、边缘、节点、边缘、节点、边缘、节点、边缘，节点。这里的思想应该集中于未来，集中于对未曾预见的成就的希望。这种思考一点一点地建立起来，以重新调整一个人的知识并重塑一个人的世界观。它建立起来既是为了消除某些思维模式，也是为了将一个人的思路集中在精神救赎上。到达空间（耶路撒冷）是步行者的中心枢纽。据说，条条大路通耶路撒冷。一个世纪又一个世纪，来往于此地的步行扩大了它的枢纽性，并严重加重了通往它的某些道路的边缘。

The divergent itineraries of these two walks correspond to divergent paths of thought. The Buddhist walking meditation is quite simple: step, lift, step. Node, edge, node. The walk is over and then it begins again. Mimicking the simplicity of this bodily movement, the mind here ought to focus on an increasingly singular idea: the step itself, holding it in awareness and appreciating its simple components. Uniting step with breath, the walker achieves arrival as a whole being, mind and body attuned. Such thinking is not project thinking but instead present thinking. The Protestant pilgrimage, by contrast, is more elaborate: the walk is long, pocked with trials and plagued by tribulations before reaching the holy place and then returning home. Node, edge, node, edge, node, edge, NODE, edge, node. The mind here ought to be focused on the future, on the hope of achievements unforeseen. Such thinking builds, little by little, so as to realign one’s knowledge and revamp one’s worldview. It builds both in order to undo certain patterns of thought and to focus one’s line of thought on spiritual redemption. The space of arrival (Jerusalem) is a central hub for walkers. All roads, it is said, lead to Jerusalem. Walking to and from this place expands its hubness century after century and heavily weights the edges of certain pathways to it.

重要的是，有精神之旅可以弥合和超越项目之旅和存在之旅之间的鸿沟。正如罗宾·沃尔·金默勒 (Robin Wall Kimmerer) 所述，阿尼希那比文化的核心是第一个男人纳纳博佐 (Nanabozho) 的形象，以及他第一次行走。大湖地区的土著民族讲述了纳纳博佐的故事，他走遍了地球的四个角落来收集智慧。他走到东方去学习知识；他走到南方去学习出生和成长的秘密；他走到北方去学习医学和同情心；他走到西方去学习创造和毁灭的相互作用。虽然每个坐标都充当着目的地，但每一步也都充当着目的地。事实上，纳纳博佐的行走方式是“每一步都是对地球母亲的问候”。25每一步都是它自己的旅程，开始时充满希望，结束时心怀感激。通过这种方式，Nanabozho 明确地塑造了一种好奇心，一种求知欲，它既实践着与土地共存，又在土地上开展项目。这种好奇心在两个领域或两个维度上发挥作用，它既深入地下，又向前倾斜，因此知识是时时刻刻建立起来的，既跨越了时间和空间。从一开始，思考就是集体的，因此，精神智慧只能在超越人类的意义网络中和与意义网络的关系中获得。

Importantly, there are spiritual walks that bridge and move beyond this divide between the walks of project and of presence. As recounted by Robin Wall Kimmerer, central to Anishinaabe culture is the figure of Nanabozho, the first man, and his first walk. Indigenous peoples of the Great Lakes tell the story of Nanabozho, who journeyed to the four corners of the earth to gather its wisdom. He walked to the east to learn knowledge; he walked to the south to learn the secrets of birth and growth; he walked to the north to learn about medicine and compassion; and he walked to the west to learn the interplay of creation and destruction. While each coordinate functioned as a destination, so did each step. Indeed Nanabozho walked in such a way that “each step was a greeting to Mother Earth.”25 Each step was its own journey, with its own hopefulness at the outset and gratefulness at its close. In this way, Nanabozho expressly models a kind of curiosity, a kind of coming to know, that practices presence with the land as much as it undertakes projects upon it. Functioning on two registers or in two dimensions, this curiosity sinks deep as much as it leans forward such that knowledge is built moment to moment, as much as across time and space. Thinking here is communal from the get-go and all along the way, and spiritual wisdom is therefore gained only ever within and in relationship to more-than-human webs of meaning.

环境步行

The Environmental Walk

虽然人们长期以来都在自然空间中散步，但自然散步在十八世纪末和十九世纪初才成为一种实质性的实践。从诗人和哲学家威廉·华兹华斯和塞缪尔从泰勒·柯勒律治、卢梭和沃尔夫冈·冯·歌德，到拉尔夫·沃尔多·爱默生、亨利·戴维·梭罗和沃尔特·惠特曼，浪漫主义的漫步者都认为一种“审美流浪”可以“治愈自我与世界破裂的关系”。26 这一传统延伸到（并被重新定义）伍尔夫和南·谢泼德、玛丽·奥利弗和安妮·迪拉德以及格洛丽亚·安扎尔杜阿等作家的近期作品中。与工业革命和随之而来的机械化造成的异化相反，自然漫步是一种重新统一自我、自然和世界的努力。漫步离开城市空间，抵制道路和习俗的限制，只关注土地的形状和居民的习惯。因此，这是一次自由的漫步。卢梭自己的漫步在这方面堪称典范。正如他坦言，“我从来没有想过这么多，存在过这么多，生活过这么多，做自己这么多……就像我独自徒步走过的旅程一样。” 27 作为证明，卢梭写下了《孤独行者的遐想》。28当资本主义环境（及其城市废墟）中充斥着无生命的力量时，灵魂和身体与大地和解时就会活跃起来。这样，人们就可以通过更新的、不同的路径思考新的、充满活力的想法。正是在“事物缓慢的呼吸”中，步行者和他们的思想找到了救赎。29

Although walks have long been taken in natural spaces, nature walks became a substantive practice in the late eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries. From the likes of poets and philosophers William Wordsworth and Samuel Taylor Coleridge, Rousseau and Wolfgang von Goethe, to Ralph Waldo Emerson, Henry David Thoreau, and Walt Whitman, Romantic walkers assumed an “aesthetic vagabondage” that promised “to heal the self’s broken relationship with the world.”26 This tradition extends into (and is reconfigured by) the more recent work of writers such as Woolf and Nan Shepherd, Mary Oliver and Annie Dillard, and Gloria Anzaldúa. Pitched against the alienation of the Industrial Revolution and its consequent mechanization, the nature walk is an effort to reunite self, nature, and world. Leaving urban spaces, and resisting the constraints of road and custom, the ramble is attentive only to the shape of the land and to the habits of its inhabitants. As such, it is a walk of freedom. Rousseau’s own saunters are paradigmatic in this regard. As he confesses, “I have never thought so much, existed so much, lived so much, been so much myself . . . as in the journeys which I have made alone and on foot.”27 As testament, Rousseau penned Reveries of a Solitary Walker.28 While de-animating forces swirl among capitalist environments (and their urban ruins), soul and body can be quickened when reconciled with the earth. In this way, one can think new, dynamic thoughts, via renewed, divergent pathways. It is in “the slow respiration of things” that walkers and their thoughts find redemption.29

梭罗是一名土地测量员、废奴主义者和散文家，他每天至少花四个小时“闲逛”。闲逛是一种不仅需要公民自由，而且需要绝对自由的散步方式。一个人必须摆脱城市及其所有粗暴习俗的束缚，只听从森林的召唤。拒绝驯化。将前草坪换成沼泽。保持内心的野性。在潜入丛林时，一个人必须与大地及其所有居民一起旅行，而不是与之对抗。梭罗“除了狐狸和水貂走过的道路外，不会穿过一条路：先沿着河边，然后是小溪，然后是草地和树林边。”然而，这种闲逛远非漫无目的。梭罗的散步方式总是一种思考的散步，一种“沉思”的散步。他在流浪中写道：“我相信我们的想象力会更加丰富，我们的思想会更加清晰、清新、空灵，如同我们的天空；我们的理解会更加全面、广阔，如同我们的平原；我们的智慧会更加宏大，如同我们的雷电、我们的河流和山脉。和森林。”陷于社会的局限中，“我们心灵的小树林被毁坏了。”然而，如果重新种植在大自然中，那片小树林就会再次繁茂。在户外漫步时思考，可以让人用死气沉沉的事实换取活生生的无知之草。然后，慢慢地，这种“边界生活”允许了边界思想。文字可以移植到纸上，“泥土仍然粘在上面”。30人们可以写一本带有树苗气息而不是沾满图书馆灰尘的书。

Thoreau, a land surveyor, abolitionist, and essayist, spent at least four hours every day “sauntering.” Sauntering is the sort of walking that requires not merely civil freedom but also absolute freedom. Getting the city off one’s back, with all of its crusty customs, one must heed only the call of the woods. Refuse domestication. Exchange the front lawn for a bog. And preserve one’s inner wildness. In diving into the bush, one must travel with rather than against the earth and all of its inhabitants. Thoreau walks “without crossing a road except where the fox and the mink do: first along by the river, and then the brook, and then the meadow and the wood-side.” Such sauntering, however, is far from mindless. Thoreau’s way of walking is always a walking that thinks, that “ruminates.” In wandering, he writes, “I trust that we shall be more imaginative, that our thoughts will be clearer, fresher, and more ethereal, as our sky,—our understanding more comprehensive and broader, like our plains,—our intellect generally on a greater scale, like our thunder and lightning, our rivers and mountains and forests.” Caught in the confines of society, “the grove in our mind is laid waste.” Replanted in nature, however, that grove is allowed to flourish again. Thinking in the open air, while sauntering, allows one to exchange the hay of dead facts for the grass of living ignorance. And then, ever so slowly, this “border-life” permits border-thoughts. Words can be transplanted to the page with “earth still adhering to them.”30 And one can write a book that smells of saplings rather than smudges with library dust.

惠特曼是美国最受喜爱的诗人之一，他同样也是行走的拥护者。他以浪漫主义传统为创作基础，自然而然地喜欢走在“人迹罕至的道路上”，远离“世界的喧嚣”、它的“利益”和“顺从”。31他意识到社会和智力上的限制，经常表达一种渴望“摆脱限制”和“束缚”。他逃离社会精英“那些洗过脸、修过容的面孔”，不仅内心“厌恶和绝望”，而且“胸骨下有死亡”，他试图用诚实换取诚实。惠特曼摆脱了图书馆和文学评论家对适当思想方式的监督，摆脱了象牙大厅和教室的束缚，在那里空洞的想法被当作实质性的建议，他开始行走。他气喘吁吁地追寻“无路”的宇宙，打着哈欠，自由自在。他漫无目的地沿着布满道路的土地走着，试图以另一种方式思考。32最糟糕的命运是与大地疏远，随之而来的是身心衰弱。惠特曼害怕在社交面具下窒息，像一个“未醒的梦游者”一样四处游荡，无法真正思考。33在这里，在开阔的田野里，他思考的思想并不像城市、科学和政治那样被整齐地分散开来，而是关于精神、诗歌，以及最终关于所有人的自由（和废除）的思想。34它们是只有在参天大树中才能找到的那种“宏大的思想” 。35

One of the best-loved US poets, Whitman was likewise a champion of walking. Writing within the Romantic tradition, he naturally preferred to walk on “paths untrodden,” away from “the clank of the world,” its “profits” and “conformities.”31 Cognizant of both social and intellectual constraints, he often expresses a longing to be “loos’d of limits” and “the holds that would hold me.” Scrambling away from “those wash’d and trimm’d faces” of social elites, plagued not only with inner “loathing and despair” but also with “death beneath their breastbones,” he seeks to trade duplicity for integrity. Freeing himself from the libraries and literary critics that police appropriate thought-ways, and unshackling himself from the ivory halls and lecture rooms in which empty ideas pass for suggestions of substance, Whitman takes to walking. He pants after the “pathless” universe, yawning and free. He patters haphazardly down its road-ridden face in a last-ditch effort to think otherwise.32 The worst fate of all would be alienation from the earth and a consequent enervation of the mind and body. Whitman fears suffocation beneath the social mask and walking about as an “unwaked somnambule,” incapable of true thinking.33 Here in the open fields, the thoughts he is given to think are not neatly atomized, as are cities, science, and politics, but rather thoughts of spirituality, of poetry, and ultimately of freedom (and abolition) for all.34 They are the sort of “large thoughts” found only among great trees.35

在浪漫主义的继承者中，奥利弗是一盏明灯。她对自然中发现的思想的简单性和生命的真实性有着无与伦比的承诺。奥利弗是一个臭名昭著的厌世者，她无忧无虑地漫步在森林里，远离社会上“笑脸盈盈、喋喋不休的人”，这些人完全“不适合”在树林里跋涉。36伍尔夫更像是一个城市漫步者，但她认为在世界上行走也具有类似的力量门外。无论你在哪里漫步，即使是在伦敦街头的荒野中，你的“贝壳般的外壳”都可能被打碎，这种光彩让你展现出你应该成为的正确人选，而不是你现在的狂野一面。37令人沮丧的是，小路将我们带入我们自己埋葬生活的丛林，要求我们经历转变的危机。然而，这种自由和它所承诺的转变是有限度的。正如迪拉德所说，你不能“拆开桃子”。你总是带着一些东西，限制你能看到和想到的东西。这对迪拉德来说是非常令人沮丧的。她渴望培养自己对光的敏感性，她写道：“看的秘诀是乘着太阳风航行。磨练和传播你的精神，直到你自己成为一张风帆，磨练、透明、宽阔，哪怕是最轻微的吹拂。” 38要用自然生命转瞬即逝的自由去思考，需要风的轻声调和——这种调和受到社会习惯和等级制度的阻碍，它们不仅充斥着城市景观，也限制了自然本身的范围。39

Among the Romantics’ successors, Oliver is a beacon. Hers is an unparalleled commitment to the simplicity of thought and the authenticity of life to be found in nature. A notorious misanthrope, Oliver blithely wanders off into the forest free of society’s “smilers and talkers,” who are entirely “not suitable” for treks among trees.36 More of an urban ambler, Woolf nevertheless attributes a similar power to walking in the world outside one’s front door. Regardless of where you ramble, even if it be in the wilderness of London’s streets, you are likely to have your “shell-like covering” shattered, that sheen by which you manifest the proper person you ought to be, rather than the wild thing that you are.37 Frustrating that fakery, footpaths lead us into the thickets of our own buried lives, demanding crises of transformation. And yet there is a limit to this freedom and its promise of transformation. As Dillard puts it, you can’t “unpeach the peaches.” There is always something you carry with you that restricts what it is possible to see and to think. This is deeply frustrating for Dillard. Yearning to nurture in herself the very sensitivity of light, she writes, “The secret to seeing is to sail on solar wind. Hone and spread your spirit till you yourself are a sail, whetted, translucent, broadside to the merest puff.”38 To think with the fugitive freedoms of natural life requires the whispered attunements of the wind—attunements stymied by the social habits and hierarchies that not only saturate cityscapes but also constrain the very reach of nature itself.39

虽然梭罗、惠特曼、奥利弗、伍尔夫或迪拉德等作家的环境漫步不会有完全相同的形状，但它们确实具有一致的约束。首先，这种漫步必须在稀疏的网格上进行，远离城市的密度，不受城镇或村庄中心的干扰，或者至少与我们家的龟壳隔绝。其次，它的行程要么创造性地重新配置现有的边缘，异想天开地穿越穿越地球的人类道路网络，要么完全忽略它们，追随最微弱的生物踪迹，专心聆听土地本身的形状。然而，在这两种情况下，这种漫步都将表现出对习俗限制的蔑视，并努力减轻最沉重的边缘，这些边缘在几个世纪以来通过社会不安全感、种族不平等、经济等级制度、文学经典和科学传统得到了强化。最沉重的边界之一就是自然与文化、物质空间与非物质思想之间的区别。安扎尔杜阿富有洞察力地重写了环境之旅，使其成为一种哲学和精神之旅，她沿着“认知之路”前行，寻求自然和谐以及洞察力和启迪。从南德克萨斯州的沙漠到圣塔克拉拉悬崖克鲁兹，她发现自己“在现实之间行走”，并在现实之间写作，只有尼泊尔人才能做到这一点。40在这里，在这个海螺和生物的空间里，思考的工作——好奇的思考——既是逃避，也是参与，既是分离，也是联系。

While an environmental walk à la Thoreau or Whitman, Oliver, Woolf, or Dillard will precisely not have identical shapes, one after the other, they do have consistent constraints. First, walks of this sort must be taken on a sparse grid, far away from the density of the city, unmarred by the hubs of town or village, or at the very least severed from the tortoise shell of our homes. Second, its itinerary will either creatively reconfigure existing edges, whimsically crisscrossing the network of human roads that traverse the earth, or it will ignore them altogether, following the faintest of creaturely trails and attentively listening to the very shape of the land itself. In both cases, however, this walk will manifest a disdain for the confines of custom and work to unweight the heaviest of edges, reinforced over centuries via social insecurities, racial inequities, economic hierarchies, literary canons, and scientific traditions. One of those heaviest of edges is the very distinction between nature and culture, material space and immaterial thought. Insightfully, Anzaldúa rewrites the environmental walk as always already a philosophical and a spiritual one by which she moves along “el camino de conocimiento,” in search of natural harmony as much as insight and enlightenment. From the South Texas deserts to the cliffs of Santa Cruz, she finds herself “walking between realities” and writing between realities, as only a nepantlera could.40 The work of thinking—of curious thinking—here in this space of conch and creature is one of escape as much as engagement, of separation as much as connection.

政治漫步

The Political Walk

虽然哲学、精神和环境步行都是政治性的，因为它们都以自己的方式塑造和重塑社会组织结构，但政治步行本身就是一件事情。它的主要目的是对现有社会结构进行根本批判，并抗议它们损害人类繁荣的方式。这些是好奇心的步行，因为它们旨在将思想和社会从当前的束缚中解放出来，并想象——事实上是体现——其他的思维和存在方式。在这里，我们关注一系列政治步行，从二十世纪后期的欧洲漂移到当代美国的抗议游行。每一个都从根本上与危及人类自由的特定建筑、经济和社会安排进行批判性对话。而且每一个不仅穿越，而且还协商物理空间，以便获得更大的智力和社会空间。

While philosophical, spiritual, and environmental walks are all political insofar as each in their own way figures and refigures the structure of social organization, the political walk is a thing unto itself. It is a walk whose principal aim is to enact a fundamental critique of existing social structures and to protest the ways in which they compromise human flourishing. These are curiosity walks insofar as they aim to free both mind and society from their current strictures, and to imagine—and indeed embody—other ways of thinking and being. Here we focus on a range of political walks, from the late twentieth-century European dérive to the contemporary US protest march. Each is fundamentally in critical dialogue with specific architectural, economic, and social arrangements that jeopardize human freedom. And each not only traverses but also negotiates physical space in such a way as to claim greater intellectual and social space.

在法国著名的 1968 年五月起义之前和之后，一个以巴黎为基地的名为“情境主义者”的团体（部分由理论家 Guy Debord 和 Raoul Vaneigem 领导）发起了一场被称为“漂移”的政治抵抗步行。与通常没有多少幻想空间的从另一个命题中得出一个命题的智力行为不同，漂移是一种创造性地与给定空间的结构限制相矛盾的物理运动。这是一场将本能与制度、玩乐与礼仪、偶然的人际相遇与机械化互动对立起来的步行。情境主义者认为，在发达资本主义下，我们生活在一个围绕娱乐和模拟组织起来的奇观社会中，我们与现实的疏远程度不亚于彼此的疏远程度。这种系统性的“否定生活”在我们的城市中最为明显。41要重新开启参与、交流和自我实现的真正路线，有必要上演有目的地抵制疏远的情景并重新点燃至关重要的摩擦。漂移就是这样一条重新开启的路线。法语单词的意思是漂移、转移和“解开被铆接的东西”。42作为一种实践，漂移涉及一种“短暂的通道”，它抵制继承的城市逻辑，定期改变基本方向，并寻求偶然的迷失方向。它可能采取不间断的搭便车、夜间非法拆除项目或“在禁止公众进入的地下墓穴中徘徊”的形式。43在安排这些情况时，情境主义者创立了心理地理学学科，它不仅分析某些地理配置如何影响人们的思考和感受，还分析空间的戏剧性（如果是短暂的）重新配置如何改变人们的思考和感受。

Preceding and informing the famous May 1968 uprisings in France, a Paris-based group called the Situationists, led in part by theorists Guy Debord and Raoul Vaneigem, developed the walk of political resistance known as the dérive. Unlike the intellectual act of deriving one proposition from another, which typically leaves little room for fancy, a dérive is a physical movement that creatively contradicts the structural constraints of a given space. It is a walk that pits instinct against institution, playfulness against protocol, and chance human encounters against mechanized interactions. Under advanced capitalism, the Situationists argue, we live in a society of the spectacle, organized around entertainment and simulation, in which we are alienated from reality as much as from one another. Such a systemic “negation of life” is nowhere more present than in our cities.41 To reopen real lines of participation, communication, and self-realization, it is necessary to stage situations that purposefully countermand alienation and reignite vital friction. The dérive is one such reopened line. The French word means to drift, to divert, and to “undo what is riveted.”42 As a practice, the dérive involves a form of “transient passage” that resists inherited urban logics, shifts cardinal direction regularly, and courts the disorientations of chance. It might take the form of nonstop hitchhiking, transgressing demolition projects by night, or “wandering subterranean catacombs forbidden to the public.”43 In staging these situations, the Situationists founded the discipline of psychogeography, which analyzes not only how certain geographical configurations make people think and feel but also how dramatic (if transient) reconfigurations of space change what it is possible to think and feel.

尽管漂移可能很强大，但空间破坏及其相关的发散思维并不局限于法国反主流文化知识分子。阿根廷女权主义哲学家玛丽亚·卢戈内斯认为，抵抗性地在物理和概念领域航行也许最好由“街头游荡者”来塑造。街头游荡者是那些虽然无家可归、失业，但仍然在街头工作和在家的人。这些行人走在街道上，不是为了离开家或从工作中休息，而是为了宣称归属和创造意义。他们是边界居住者和边界突破者。街头游荡者生活在“反主流的边界、深渊、边缘、岸边”，他们自己有“定义不明确的‘边缘’”。他们是边缘的“存在者”和边缘编织者。街头游荡者不是两三人一组地行走，而是多个集群地行走，在他们移动的过程中形成和建立“聚会场所”。她们在不该去的地方、不该去的时间、不该去的人身边闲逛。正是在这个叛逆的“混合”之地，街头妓女重新思考世界。街头妓女闯入空间，与他人“碰撞”，创造出“神秘的词汇”，不仅照亮了她们自己的生活，还打破了公共和私人、中心和边缘、可取和可抛弃的区别。44 街头妓女是一种思考方式，一种理论化模式，根植于边缘存在和边缘制造。

As powerful as the dérive might be, spatial disruption—and its correlative divergent thinking—is not limited to French countercultural intellectuals. Argentine feminist philosopher María Lugones argues that resistant navigation of the physical and conceptual realms is perhaps best modeled by “streetwalkers.” Streetwalkers are people who, while they may be homeless and out of work, are at home and at work in the streets. Streets are where these walkers walk not to get out of the house or take a break from work but rather to claim belonging and make meaning. They are border dwellers and boundary breakers. Living “at the border, abyss, edge, shore of countersense,” streetwalkers themselves have “ill-defined ‘edges.’” They are edge “be-ers” and edge weavers. Streetwalkers walk not in couplets of two or three but rather in multiple clusters, forming and founding “hangouts” as they move along. They hang out where they are not supposed to, when they are not supposed to, and with whom they are not supposed to. And it is in this place of rebellious “mixity” that streetwalkers rethink the world. Busting into spaces, and “bumping among and into one another,” streetwalkers generate the “enigmatic vocabularies” that not only illuminate their own lives but therewith defy distinctions of public and private, center and margins, the desirable and the discardable.44 Streetwalking is a way of thinking, a mode of theorizing, rooted in edge beings and edge makings.

虽然漂移和街头游行抗议了各种各样的事情，但它们本身并不是抗议游行。其他类型的政治游行发生在城市中——游行不仅限于两人或三人团体，也不仅限于成群结队，政治游行并不局限于此，而是扩展到数万甚至数十万。社会抗议通常以空间占领的方式进行，即完全重新调整空间的功能（例如，高速公路变成人行道），表明需要进行更大规模的社会变革。虽然这种占领可能采取静坐的形式，但它们也可能采取散步的形式。这种散步大多发生在已经存在步行能力的空间中。45正是在这里，政治游行不仅激发了旁观者的好奇心，更重要的是，它们本身就体现了好奇心。他们问这样的问题：发生了什么？我们需要什么？我们能想象出什么样的美好未来？人们可能会想到从塞尔玛到阿拉巴马州蒙哥马利的标志性民权运动抗议游行。或者一波又一波的抗议浪潮涌入该国首都，呼吁民权、妇女权利、残疾人权利、LGBTQ 权利、劳工权利、环境正义与和平。此外，这样的散步不需要双脚和防止摔倒的良好习惯。正如 1985 年俄亥俄州克利夫兰的公交车无障碍抗议活动以及其他许多残疾人权利运动所表明的那样，人们使用轮椅和其他辅助移动设备在城市中行走，重新配置它，并要求社会转型。46每一次行走都以自己的方式寻找一个新世界和一种新的思维方式。

While the dérive and streetwalking protest a whole range of things, they are not protest walks per se. Other sorts of political walks take place in a city—walks not limited to groups of two or three, or clusters here and there, but that extend to tens and hundreds of thousands. Social protests often proceed by way of spatial occupations, in which the function of a space is completely retooled (e.g., highways become footpaths), signifying the necessity of social change on a larger scale. While such occupations may take the form of a sit-in, they may just as often take the form of a walk. Such walks occur most in spaces of preexisting walkability.45 It is here that political walks not only activate bystander curiosity but more importantly, embody curiosity themselves. They ask the questions: What is going on? What do we need? And what better future can we imagine? One might think of the iconic civil rights movement protest walk from Selma to Montgomery, Alabama. Or the wave upon wave of protests that have flooded the country’s capital, agitating for civil rights, women’s rights, disability rights, LGBTQ rights, labor rights, environmental justice, and peace. Such walks, moreover, need not include two feet and a salubrious habit of arrested falling. As demonstrated by the 1985 bus accessibility protest in Cleveland, Ohio, alongside so many other disability rights actions, people use their wheelchairs and other assistive mobility devices to walk the city, reconfigure it, and demand social transformation.46 Each walk, in its own way, proceeds in search of a new world and a new way of thinking.

以漂移、街头行走和抗议游行的形式，政治行走抵制并改写了城市的建筑。在此过程中，它重新绘制了街道和社会关系的网络；它重新配置了这些枢纽。对于参与者和抗议者来说，在改变具体事物时，他们寻求的是具体的变化。而社会空间的变化需要思想空间的变化。漂移、街头行走和公众抗议旨在改变人们的思维方式。思想如何联系和配置；它们之间的边界如何铺设和加权；以及因此可疑性本身如何形成。当然，它们之间存在重要差异。漂移和街头行走杂乱无章，而政治抗议的道路则大多是经过规划的。漂移批判发达资本主义令人衰弱的习惯，而街头行走和抗议通常批判社会不公平。然而，从某种意义上说，这三者都带有苏格拉底式行走的回声。他们行走的目的是为了了解、解开、重新聆听，因此他们具有明显的解构性。这是一种在街头行走的好奇心。

In the form of the dérive, streetwalking, and the protest march, the political walk resists and rewrites the architecture of a city. In doing so, it redraws the network of streets and social relations; it reconfigures these hubs. For participants and protesters, in changing concrete, they seek concrete change. And that change in social space requires a change in intellectual space. The dérive, streetwalking, and public protest aim to change how people think. How thoughts get linked and configured; how the edges between them are laid and weighted; and thus how questionableness itself is shaped. Of course, there are important differences. The dérive and streetwalking proceed haphazardly, where the path of political protest is largely planned. The dérive critiques the enervating habits of advanced capitalism, while streetwalking and protest typically critique social inequities. In a sense, though, all three carry echoes of the Socratic walk. They are eminently deconstructive insofar as they walk in order to unknow, to undo, and to listen anew. And this is a kind of curiosity given feet on the street.

思想运动

Thought in Motion

旅行有各种各样的形式。人们可以乘汽车、火车或飞机旅行。乘游轮或小艇。乘摩托车或滑板。人们可以跑步或跳跃，笨重地行走或攀爬。或者人们可以步行。这是最古老、最简单的旅行方式。专注于步行可以让我们以无与伦比的方式描述好奇心的动觉运动，尤其是当这些描述受到哲学和网络科学的影响时。在我们的空间世界的网格和我们思想世界的图表中，步行培养了独特的节奏和行程，通过这些节奏和行程，我们可以了解我们的所在和目的。在将这些步行设计为不同的穿越路径时，我们不仅能够描述具体和认知运动的形状，还能探索它们的相互关系。正如我们的身体和思想永远不会完全分离一样，我们的世俗和世俗步行也纠缠在一起、交织在一起。

Travel takes all sorts of forms. One might travel by car, train, or plane. By cruise ship or skiff. By scooter or skateboard. One might run or skip, clomp or clamber. Or one might walk. It is the oldest and simplest form of travel. Focusing on the walk allows for an unparalleled specificity in our accounts of curiosity’s kinesthetic movement, especially when those accounts are informed by philosophy and network science. Across the grids of our space-worlds and the graphs of our thought-worlds, the walk cultivates unique rhythms and itineraries by which we come to know our wheres and our wherefores. In patterning those walks, as divergent pathways of traversal, we are able not only to characterize the shapes of concrete and cognitive movement but also explore their interrelations. Just as our bodies and minds are never fully separate, so too are our worldly and wordly walks entangled and intermeshed.

人类学家蒂姆·英戈尔德（Tim Ingold）大胆地写道：“行走是一种思考和认知的方式……行走者在运动中思考。” 47因此，知识不是获得的东西，也不是捡起来藏在仓库里的东西。它不是人们最终到达的目的地，永远不需要离开。相反，“知识是沿着我们走过的无数条路径成长起来的。” 48它属于人们行走的网络和漫游的图表。英戈尔德区分了“占用者知识”和“居住者知识”。占用者进入一个空间并将其用于自己外部强加的用途，而居住者发现自己已经身处一个空间，并与其他居住者一起了解和分享它。鉴于此，占用者知识通过类别区分和层次组织组装认知成分。另一方面，居住者知识追求的是水平的认知，在世界中“沿着”移动。49 “居住者行走”，英戈尔德指出，因此“他们的知识不是建立起来的，而是沿着他们所走的路发展起来的。” 50对于英戈尔德和我们来说，居住者知识否认了所有认知的隐含模式，这种模式是沿着线和交叉点、轨迹和关系的网络发展的。正是行走揭穿了这种否认。“那么，阅读与阅读有何不同？“我们为什么不能从在风景中行走中学习？”英戈尔德问道。“完全不是。行走既是心灵的旅行，也是在土地上的旅行：这是一种深度冥想练习。阅读既是心灵的旅行，也是书页的旅行。这些地形之间远非严格划分，而是不断交流。” 51我们行走——我们是跑步者和徒步旅行者、艺术家和学者、登山者和通勤者、哲学家和诗人、朝圣者和抗议者——当我们行走时，我们就会了解。

Anthropologist Tim Ingold puts it boldly when he writes, “Walking along is a way of thinking and knowing. . . . [T]he walker is thinking in movement.”47 As such, knowledge is not something acquired, or picked up and stashed away in a storehouse. It is not achieved as a destination to which one finally arrives and need never leave. Rather, “knowledge is grown along the myriad paths we take.”48 It belongs to the networks along which one walks and the graphs through which one wanders. Ingold distinguishes between “occupant knowledge” and “habitant knowledge.” An occupant enters a space and assumes it for their own externally imposed uses, while an inhabitant finds themselves already in a space and works with other inhabitants to know and to share it. Given this, occupant knowledge assembles epistemic components via categorial distinction and hierarchical organization. Habitant knowledge, on the other hand, pursues knowing horizontally, moving “alongly” across, in, and through the world.49 “Inhabitants walk,” Ingold notes, and hence “their knowledge is not built up but grows along the paths they tread.”50 For Ingold, as for us, occupant knowledge disavows the implicit pattern of all knowing, which develops along a network of lines and intersections, trajectories and relations. And it is walking that puts the lie to this disavowal. “How, then, does reading differ from walking in the landscape?” Ingold asks. “Not at all. To walk is to journey in the mind as much as on the land: it is a deeply meditative practice. And to read is to journey on the page as much as in the mind. Far from being rigidly partitioned, there is constant traffic between these terrains.”51 We walk—we runners and hikers, artists and scholars, mountaineers and commuters, philosophers and poets, pilgrims and protesters—and as we walk, we come to know.

文化理论家米歇尔·德·塞托认为，行走是一种阅读方式，也是一种说话方式。行走有语法和修辞。行走阐明了某些路径，融入了某些风格，在这里加入一些花哨的元素，在那里加入一些离题的元素。行走以好奇和创造性的方式制作“它所‘讲述’的轨迹”。在这样做的过程中，行走始终是一种做与不做、说与不说。行走具有变革性。德·塞托解释说，在组织空间时，空间秩序组织了可能性和禁令。人们可以去这里，但不能去那里，可以这样，但不能那样。在实现可能性和藐视禁令的同时，行走者的动作是义务性的，也是超越性的，一会儿沿着主干道行走，一会儿“创造捷径和绕行路线”。行走者在行走过程中即兴发挥，重新分配合法性和非法性的界限。网络被重新配置，图形被重新绘制。这种转变通常结合了提喻和非连词运动。从部分到整体，提喻行走“跳跃”跨越图形，无意中增加了网络的密度。相反，非连词行走跳过被丢弃的连接词，在网格中“跳跃”，使网络变薄。无论其遍历策略（或修辞策略）如何，行走都会将表面变成“筛子”，通过“省略、漂移和意义泄漏”在事物的秩序中打洞。52正是以这种方式，行走是一种好奇的思考，好奇的思考是一种行走。两者都安排和重新安排意义。

Cultural theorist Michel de Certeau argues that walking is a way of reading and a way of speaking. There is a grammar and rhetoric to walking. Walking enunciates certain pathways, incorporates certain styles, throws in a flourish here and a digression there. Walking curiously and creatively crafts “the trajectories it ‘speaks.’” In doing so, walking is always already a doing and an undoing, a saying and an unsaying. Walking is transformative. In organizing space, de Certeau explains, spatial orders organize possibilities and prohibitions. One can go here, but not there, in this way, but not that. Actualizing possibilities and flaunting prohibitions, the walker’s movements are obligatory and transgressive by turns, traipsing down main thoroughfares one moment and “creating shortcuts and detours” the next. Improvising as they go along, the walker redistributes lines of legitimacy and illegitimacy. Networks are reconfigured and graphs redrawn. Such a transformation typically incorporates both synecdochic and asyndetic movements. Catapulting from a part to the whole, a synecdochic walk “leaps” across the graph, inadvertently adding density to the network. Conversely, jumping over dropped conjunctions, an asyndetic walk “skips” around the grid, thinning out the network. Regardless of its traversal tactics (or rhetorical strategies), walking turns surfaces into “sieve(s),” punching holes in the order of things by way of “ellipses, drifts, and leaks of meaning.”52 And it is precisely in this way that walking is a kind of curious thinking, and curious thinking is a kind of walking. Each arranges and rearranges sense.

虽然所有形式的思考都是行走——无论是从哲学意义上还是从网络科学意义上来说，好奇的思考都是通过好奇的行走进行的。这种行走是由今天和过去的探索者进行的，它们塑造和重塑了大陆的道路，也塑造和重塑了意识的道路。在在本章中，我们分析了四种这样的好奇心之旅。哲学之旅要么像柏拉图一样，旨在求知，因此谨慎前行，要么像苏格拉底一样，旨在求知，因此漫无目的。它促进了好奇心，要么要求回答，要么要求揭露错误的答案。在佛教、新教或土著传统中，精神之旅则旨在了解最简单或最神圣的真理。它促进了好奇心，这种好奇心努力欣赏无处不在的真理，或者奋斗数周、数月甚至数年，以获得只有最禁欲的思想家才能获得的洞察力。梭罗、惠特曼、伍尔夫和迪拉德所倡导的环境之旅旨在使知识重新自然化，摆脱常识和集体偏见的束缚。它促进了好奇心，这种好奇心探索了人迹罕至的道路，寻求与大张旗鼓不一致的洞察力，并紧贴地球的诗意。最后，无论是漂移、街头行走还是抗议游行，政治行走都旨在以不同的方式和自由的方式去认识。它促进了那种从习俗和约束中溜走的好奇心，无论是追求奇想还是正义，它都想象了一个世界，在这个世界中，某些问题不会为了他人的舒适而牺牲。这种好奇的行走方式始终是好奇的思考方式。在相互交流中，它们轻轻地跨越了在观念领域和具体领域之间划定的界限。它们跃入了边界思维。

While all forms of thinking are walks—in both a philosophical sense and a network science sense, curious thinking proceeds by way of curious walks. Such walks, undertaken by seekers of today and yesteryear, shape and reshape the roads of continents as much as those of consciousness. In this chapter, we analyzed four such curiosity walks. The philosophical walk either aims to know à la Plato and therefore plods carefully along, or aims to unknow à la Socrates and wanders about wildly. It facilitates the sort of curiosity that either asks to answer or asks to unmask false answers. In Buddhist, Protestant, or Indigenous traditions, the spiritual walk in turn aims to know either the simplest or the most sacred of truths. It facilitates the sort of curiosity that strives to appreciate the truths everywhere present, or struggles for weeks, months, and even years to attain insights only the most ascetic thinkers can achieve. The environmental walk, as heralded by Thoreau and Whitman, Woolf and Dillard, aims to renaturalize knowledge, leaving behind the confines of common sense and collective prejudice. It facilitates the sort of curiosity that explores paths untrodden, courts insights inconsistent with fanfare, and sticks close to the poetry of the earth. Finally, the political walk, whether in the form of the dérive, streetwalking, or the protest march, aims to know differently and to know freely. It facilitates the kind of curiosity that slips out from under custom and constraint, and, whether pursuing whimsy or justice, it imagines a world in which certain questions are not sacrificed for the comfort of others. Such ways of curious walking are always already ways of curious thinking. And in informing one another, they skip lightly across the lines that have been drawn between ideational and embodied realms. They leap into border-thinking.

* * *

* * *

当人们将网络思维概念化时——从一个想法走到另一个想法，跳跃、跳跃；构建基础并协调和谐；纳入反指示或将其砍掉；生长和重新生长新的节点和边缘、想法及其相互关系——好奇心就变成了新的东西。它变成了新的东西和多元的东西。它的形状是什么，它的轨迹是什么？它是像菌丝丝的根茎一样分散，像根一样放射状，还是像头顶的树叶一样交织在一起？还是像这些图案一样遍布全球？我们可以从行动中的思维网络模型和实践中的行走中学到什么来加深我们的理解？好奇心在现实生活中是如何体现的？在什么条件下好奇心会表现为随机游走？还是莱维飞行？格子网络或树形图？但同时，我们可以从哲学中学到什么——哲学深刻理解不同阶层所带来的发散思维——以丰富我们对好奇心在现实生活中的创造力（和限制）的理解？哪些环境支持好奇心——为谁、何时、如何支持？谁的思维路径得到认可，谁被边缘化？谁的行走安全得到保障，谁被忽视？谁的思维方式和人行道权利受到赞扬，谁的权利被抹去？伍尔夫究竟会对本杰明说些什么？在一个概念和物理空间中的移动自由得不到平等保障的世界里，奇思妙想和漫游、创新和想象的能力如何才能民主化？

When one conceptualizes thinking on a network—walking, skipping, leaping from one idea to the next; building fundaments and orchestrating harmonies; incorporating counterindications or lopping them off; growing and regrowing new nodes and edges, ideas and their interrelations—curiosity becomes something new. It becomes something new and something multiple. What are its shapes, its graphological itineraries? Is it dispersed like the rhizomes of mycelium threads, radial like roots, or intermeshed like the leafy canopies overhead? Or is it a mélange of such patterns stretched far and wide across the globe? What can we learn from network models of thinking in action—and walking in practice—to deepen our understanding of curiosity on the ground? Under what conditions might curiosity behave as a random walk? Or a Lévy flight? A lattice network or a tree graph? But also, what can we learn from philosophy—with its deep appreciation of the divergent thinking made possible by different walks of life—to enrich our understanding of curiosity’s creativity (and curtailment) on the ground? What contexts support curiosity—and for whom, and when, and how? Whose mental pathways are recognized and whose sidelined? Whose walking safety is secured and whose ignored? Whose right to thoughtways and footways are extolled, and whose erased? What indeed might Woolf say to Benjamin? In a world where freedom of movement in conceptual and physical space is unequally ensured, how might the capacity for whimsy and wandering, for innovation and imagination, be democratized?

我们对未来哲学和网络科学领域的研究充满期待，希望能够更精确地形式化这些形状和间隙，并更谨慎地形式化它们的自由。这里有巨大的可能性来阐明好奇心的建构，并赋予建构者权力。当我们在行人和制图师之间切换，甚至将行人视为心灵的制图师时，我们可以走进好奇心的扎实知识，它位于学科界限之间，也“沿着”越来越神秘的文字和事物世界的公路和小路。这个故事应该是每个人的故事。

We are excited for future work in both philosophy and network science to formalize these shapes and interstices more precisely, and their freedoms more carefully. There is immense possibility here to illuminate the architectonics of curiosity and to empower the architects. As we toggle between pedestrians and cartographers, and even entertain pedestrians as cartographers of the mind, we can walk into a grounded knowledge of curiosity, situated between disciplinary lines as well as “along” the highways and byways of an ever more mysterious world of words and things. And that story should be everyone’s story.

7

7

你的大脑充满好奇心

Your Brain on Curiosity

[有些词语] 没有表现出任何奇怪的迹象，当它们不是通过打字机打出来而是新鲜地来自人类的大脑时，它们就拥有魔鬼般的力量。

[Some words] show no trace of the strange, of the diabolical power which words possess when they are not tapped out by a typewriter but come fresh from a human brain.

—弗吉尼亚·伍尔夫，《工艺》（1937年）

—Virginia Woolf, “Craftsmanship” (1937)

当我们好奇时，我们的大脑会用不同的词语思考。新鲜的、原始的、未使用过的词语，随着春雨的倾泻而下。当我们在舌头上滚动它们，在呼啸的空气中吮吸它们，并将它们拴在牙齿之间时——脆脆的、未煮过的、仍然绿色的——我们意识到，我们很高兴地用结构换取了陌生感，全心全意地用教条换取了恶魔。指引我们的精神，他们为我们打开钥匙，解开我们的结，保护我们免受保护。因此，我们在自己的好奇家中自由自在。在这里，诗人珀西·比希·雪莱如此热切渴望的“理智之美”精神，是一个永久的庇护房客，以光明、色调和奉献为“人类思想”提供“营养”。1有了这样的准备，我们超凡的力量——或者更简单地说，我们的自由、大胆和想象力——驱使我们肆无忌惮地挖掘、穿越和跳跃概念空间。但是，虽然我们希望秘密地狂欢，在沉默中漫游，但我们却羞愧地意识到，我们无意中背叛了自己。我们的每一个动作都伴随着我们头骨内那块三磅重、十五厘米长的组织的声音：我们内心的白铃鸟（世界上叫得最响的鸟）的叫声，我们内心的肥硕的幼鱼（世界上最小的脊椎动物）的低语，以及我们内心其他更神秘的声音。Nialyod（澳大利亚土著神话中的彩虹蛇，拥有将人类变成景观特征的力量；我可以请求成为一张鲜为人知的悬崖面吗？）。除了尴尬地揭示我们的存在之外，这些喊叫、耳语和其他奇怪的语调意味着什么？它们从何而来？它们如何创造出好奇心驱动下的大脑的和谐音调？

When we are curious, our minds think in different words. Fresh, raw, unused words that well up as the spring rains well down. As we roll them around on our tongues, suck them through the whistling air, and tether them between our teeth—crunchy and uncooked, still green—we realize we’ve happily exchanged structure for strangeness, and wholeheartedly traded dogmas for daemons. Guiding spirits, they unlock us from the keys, untie us from the knots, and protect us from protection. And so we are at liberty in our own house of curiosity. Here, the Spirit of Intellectual Beauty, for whom poet Percy Bysshe Shelley longed so fervently, is a permanently sheltered lodger, offering “to human thought” its “nourishment” in light, in hue, in consecration.1 Thus provisioned, our otherworldly power—or more simply our freedom, audacity, and fancy—drives us to dig into, walk across, and leap about conceptual spaces with abandon. But while we’d hoped to revel in secret, to roam in silence, we blush to realize we’ve inadvertently betrayed ourselves. Each movement we make is prefaced, accompanied, and followed by the sounds of that three-pound, fifteen-centimeters-long piece of tissue inside our skull: shoutings of our inner white bellbird (the world’s loudest fowl), whisperings of our inner stout infantfish (the world’s smallest vertebrate), and other more cryptic sonorizations of our inner Nialyod (a rainbow serpent in Australian Aboriginal mythology with the power to transform humans into landscape features; can I request to be a little-known cliff face?). Aside from awkwardly revealing our existence, what do these shoutings, whisperings, and other odd intonations mean? From whence do they arise? How do they create the euphony that is your brain on curiosity?

这些问题现在才刚刚开始得到解答。新兴的神经技术可以通过拍摄不同类型的大脑结构和功能的照片、图像或影片来阐明思维。MRI 使我们能够看到不同类型组织的空间布局，并评估该布局在多大程度上反映了健康认知景观的轮廓。这类信息类似于建筑师蓝图的结构规划和规格，它显示了我们思维建筑的脚手架和支撑。​​就像医生报告中的 X 光和 CT 扫描一样，MRI 显示了思维身体的骨骼、框架和桁架。但一个人的身体只是自我的一部分。正如建筑师的结构规划与管道、机械和电气规划相辅相成，正如医生的报告可以通过描绘动脉血流的血管造影图来补充，神经科学家使用从功能技术中获取的图像来解读思维的节拍、脉搏和节拍。功能性磁共振成像、脑电图和脑磁图图像使我们能够探测活跃脑细胞的代谢、电场和磁场特征。就像视觉艺术家一样，神经科学家有时可以在静态图像中看到思维的故事，有时他们必须先将这些图像以延时或超延时的形式串联在一起，以跟踪脚步并追踪思维的轨迹。

These questions are only now beginning to be answered. Emerging neurotechnologies can elucidate the mind by taking different sorts of pictures, images, or movies of the brain’s structure and function. An MRI allows us to see the spatial layout of different types of tissue and assess the extent to which that layout reflects the contours of a healthy cognitive landscape. This sort of information is akin to the structural plans and specifications of an architect’s blueprint, which displays the scaffolding and shoring of the building of our minds. Like X-rays and CT scans in a physician’s report, MRIs display the bones, frame, and trusses of the mind’s body. But one’s body is only part of one’s self. Just as an architect’s structural plans are complemented by the plumbing, mechanical, and electrical plans, and just as the physician’s report may be complemented by an angiogram mapping out arterial flow, so the neuroscientist deciphers the beat, pulse, and meter of the mind using images taken from functional technologies. Functional MRI, electroencephalography, and magnetoencephalography images allow us to probe the metabolic, electrical, and magnetic field signatures of active brain cells. Like a visual artist, the neuroscientist can at times see the story of the mind in the static images, and at other times they must first spool those images together in the form of a time-lapse or hyperlapse to follow the footsteps and track the trails of thought.

神经科学家是神秘博士，他使用神经技术的塔迪斯 (TARDIS) 前往心灵的星球、大陆和国家。这个国家是什么？一个心灵的国家与另一个心灵的国家有何不同？你皱巴巴的脑组织盘旋的形状，就像一个国家的边界​​一样，是独一无二的。2你大脑每个区域的厚度，就像地形图上的高程等高线一样，都是不同的。单个神经元和神经群的位置，就像高耸的城市的位置一样，都是为你而设的，位置也是为你而设的。突触或神经线路，就像连接城市的蜿蜒道路。我们每个人的脑电活动传递信息的方式都不一样，就像高速公路、城市街道和乡村道路上的车流一样。每个模式都反映了一系列计算，这些计算与最强大的计算机不同，仍然是个谜。确定信息流量模式的驱动因素是当代神经科学的主要目标之一，因为这样我们就能了解哪些计算是可实现的，哪些计算具有挑战性，哪些计算可以通过认真的训练或经验来学习。换句话说，流量模式是一种指纹，它决定了你今天是谁，以及你明天会是谁。

The neuroscientist is Dr. Who, using the TARDIS of neurotechnologies to travel to the planet, continent, and country of the mind. And what is this country? And how is the country of one mind different from the country of another mind? The convoluted shape of your wrinkly brain tissue, like the borders of a country, are unique.2 The thickness of each area of your brain, like the contour lines of elevation on a topographic map, are distinct. The placement of individual neurons and neural populations, like the location of towering cities, is specific to you, as is the location of synapses or wiring, like winding roads connecting the cities. And each of us has a different pattern by which electrical activity carries information throughout our brain, like coursing traffic on highways, city streets, and country roads. Each pattern reflects a string of computations that—unlike those of the most powerful computer—remain a mystery. Identifying what drives traffic patterns of information is one of the key goals of contemporary neuroscience because then we would understand which computations are accessible versus challenging, and which can be learned through careful training or experience. In other words, that traffic pattern is a fingerprint that makes you who you are today and who you could be tomorrow.

大脑是好奇心的家园。当你好奇时，这里会发生什么？要回答这个问题，我们必须首先问大脑是如何组织的。大脑与它试图获取的知识网络是否具有任何共同的架构特征？大脑的不同部分与获取知识所必需的不同人体功能有何关系，如运动、视觉、决策，当然还有好奇心？当我们对一个“事物”感到好奇时，这个“事物”在我们大脑的哪个位置？当我们将知识碎片连接起来时，边缘在哪里划出一条线？网络是在哪些组织中建立的？当我们积累新经验、学习新技能或产生新想法时，“事物”的神经位置及其关系会移动或改变吗？（我想起了我和我的十个兄弟姐妹挤进我们家 15 座的天蓝色福特面包车（大约 1999 年）：”让开！没有空间了。“）当我们思考时，大脑如何配置和重新配置？我们可以提出的问题数量庞大，而我们还不知道如何提出的问题则更多。但我们必须从某个地方开始。通过沿着神经科学研究的当前轨迹前进，我们为理解铺平了道路。我们开始看到知识网络构建的神经基础。

The brain is the home country of your curious mind. What happens here when you are curious? To answer this question, we must first ask how the brain is organized. Does the brain share any architectural features with the knowledge networks it seeks to acquire? How do different sectors of the brain relate to different human functions necessary for knowledge acquisition, like motion, vision, decision-making, and—yes—curiosity? When we are curious about a “thing,” where does that “thing” live in our brain? When we engage in the edgework of connecting pieces of knowledge, where do the edges lay down their lines? In what bits of tissue are the networks built? Does the neural location of a “thing” along with its relations move or change as we gather new experiences, learn new skills, or entertain new thoughts? (I am thinking of me and my ten siblings piling into our family’s fifteen-seat sky-blue Ford van circa 1999: “Move over! There’s no more room.”) How does the brain configure and reconfigure while we are figuring? The number of questions we can formulate is vast, and the number we know not yet how to ask is even larger. But we must start somewhere. By walking the current trajectory of neuroscientific inquiry, we lay down paths toward an understanding. We begin to see the neural basis of knowledge network building.

道路规则

Rules of the Road

大脑是如何组织的？许多神经科学家会通过考虑纳米尺度的脑组织元素来回答这个问题（人类头发直径的五十分之一的千分之一）。在这里，离子通道控制钾和钠通过细胞膜的流动，从而形成大脑的电信号。细胞本身的跨度为微米级（仅为人类头发直径的五十分之一）。例如，神经元的细胞体直径通常在 4 微米（0.004 毫米）到 100 微米（0.1 毫米）之间。星形胶质细胞的细胞体直径通常为 10-20 微米。神经元和星形胶质细胞都有从细胞体向外延伸的附属物，使它们能够与其他细胞连接。在神经元中，这些延伸是轴突，在人体内可以跨越 1 米，以及树突，可以跨越 15 到 1,500 微米。在星形胶质细胞中，这些延伸过程向外辐射 20-30 微米。作为延伸手臂和腿的身体，这两种关键细胞类型（神经元和星形胶质细胞）的体附肢形态强调了这样一个事实：连接行为（和能力）是大脑功能的核心。而这种连接能力得到了一个令人印象深刻的事实的支持：细胞膜约 50 纳米区域中的离子活动可以仅通过一个细胞影响 50 厘米外的身体另一部分。这是一个 100 万倍的系数！（肥硕的幼鱼有一条很长的尾巴。）

How is the brain organized? Many neuroscientists will answer this question by considering the elements of brain tissue at the nanometer scale (one-thousandth of one-fiftieth of the diameter of a human hair). Here ion channels gate the flow of potassium and sodium through the membranes of cells, thereby shaping the brain’s electrical signals. The cells themselves span the micrometer scale (just one-fiftieth of the diameter of a human hair). For example, the cell body of a neuron is typically between 4 micrometers (0.004 millimeters) and 100 micrometers (0.1 millimeters) in diameter. The cell body of an astrocyte is typically 10–20 micrometers in diameter. Both neurons and astrocytes have appendages that extend outward from the cell body allowing them to connect with other cells. In neurons, those extensions are axons, which can span up to 1 meter in the human body, and dendrites, which can span from 15 to 1,500 micrometers. In astrocytes, those extending processes radiate out for 20–30 micrometers. As a body extending arms and legs, the corpus-appendage morphology of these two key cell types—neurons and astrocytes—underscores the fact that the act of (and capacity for) connecting is central to brain function. And that connective capacity is undergirded by the impressive fact that the activity of ions in an approximately 50-nanometer region of a cell membrane can affect another part of the body 50 centimeters away through only a single cell. That’s a factor of 1 million! (The sounds of the stout infantfish have a very long tail.)

神经元是如何连接的？要测量神经连接，最简单的方法是从非人类动物组织（例如大鼠或小鼠）中提取神经元，并将这些细胞放入培养皿中，加入适当的基质和营养液。单个细胞通过突触快速相互连接，突触通常从一个细胞的轴突到另一个细胞的树突，从而产生互连结构。这种连接往往表现出一种小世界组织，其中大多数连接存在于附近的神经元之间，形成紧密互连的簇，而远距离神经元之间只有少数连接，允许电活动跨越簇。小世界性是一种被认为可以赋予大型系统间通信便利性的属性。它可以在许多不同类型的网络中发现，这些网络以通信为中心功能（例如社交网络和电信网络）。3事实上，正是这种架构，特别是长距离网络的存在连接，这使得客厅游戏“六度空间之凯文·贝肯”得以发挥作用。4 （在这个游戏中，玩家互相挑战，随机选择一名演员，然后通过说出两位演员都出演的电影将他们与另一位演员联系起来；这个过程重复进行，直到找到多产的美国演员凯文·贝肯。由于演员网络的小世界性质，通常需要六轮才能找到贝肯。）

How do neurons connect? To measure neural connectivity, the simplest approach is to extract neurons from nonhuman animal tissue (e.g., from rats or mice) and place those cells in a petri dish with appropriate substrate and nutrient liquid. The individual cells quickly link with one another through synapses typically from one cell’s axon to another cell’s dendrite, generating a fabric of interconnectivity. That connectivity tends to show a small-world organization where most connections exist between nearby neurons creating densely interconnected clusters, and only a few connections exist between distant neurons allowing electrical activity to span between clusters. Small-worldness is a property that is thought to confer ease of communication across large systems. It can be found in many different sorts of networks for which communication is a central function (e.g., social and telecommunication networks).3 In fact, it is precisely this architecture, and specifically the existence of the long-distance connections, that allows the parlor game Six Degrees of Kevin Bacon to work.4 (In this game, players challenge each other to choose an actor at random and then connect them to another actor by naming a film in which both actors appeared; the process is repeated until the prolific US actor Kevin Bacon is reached. The typical number of rounds needed to reach Bacon is six due to the small-world nature of the actor network.)

网络组织的小世界特征不仅存在于细胞尺度，也存在于更大规模。5轴突在长距离移动时往往会相互对齐，因此脑组织的宏观组织由束组成，每个束由许多轴突投射组成。就好像他们发现走一条有人走过的路比走一条没人走过的路要容易得多。在非人类动物中，束追踪技术可用于测量这些轴突束。无论是顺行（从细胞体到轴突末端）还是逆行（从轴突末端到细胞体），这些技术在历史上都是从将可视化示踪分子注射到大脑的特定区域开始的。示踪分子被注射部位的细胞吸收，然后沿着神经元的投射运输。通过向不同的大脑区域进行多次这样的注射，可以获得区域间连接的完整图谱。从猕猴和猫到老鼠和果蝇，许多物种的束状连接组都表现出小世界特性。每个动物大脑的“多产”区域——神经组织的培根——是那些有许多连接的区域，只需在这个高效的信息传输网络上走几步，就可以轻松地从其他区域到达这些区域。

The small-world feature of network organization is not only present at the cellular scale but also at larger scales.5 Axons tend to align with one another when traversing long distances and thus the macroscopic organization of brain tissue is composed of tracts, each comprised of many axonal projections. It is as if they find it much easier to walk a path that is trodden than to strike out on a path that is untrodden. In nonhuman animals, tract-tracing techniques can be used to measure these bundles of axons. Whether anterograde (from cell body to axonal terminus) or retrograde (from axonal terminus to cell body), such techniques historically began with the injection of a visualizable tracer molecule into a given area of the brain. The tracer molecules were absorbed by the cells local to the injection and then transported along the neuron’s projections. By performing many such injections into different brain areas, a full map of interareal connectivity could be obtained. Across many species, from macaque monkeys and cats to mice and the fly Drosophila, tract-based connectomes display small-world properties. The “prolific” areas of each animal brain—the Bacons of neural tissue—are those that have many connections and can easily be reached from other areas simply by taking a few steps on this highly efficient, information trafficking network.

人类也是如此，包括我们的朋友奥勒·沃姆和弗吉尼亚·伍尔夫？人类的相关测量与动物略有不同。非人类动物的连接研究提供了细胞和中尺度测量的途径，但人类的相同研究只能提供大规模测量的途径。尽管图像较粗略，但即使在这里，连接架构的原理似乎也得到了保留。使用 MRI 机器，科学家可以获得所谓的扩散加权图像，该图像提供有关大脑中自然产生的水分子扩散的信息。至关重要的是，扩散受到轴突束的位置和方向的限制；水分子沿着轴突束扩散，就像雨滴沿着树枝滚动一样。通过从扩散图像推断束的位置，我们可以为个人构建连接组。这个过程有点像推断通往孩子们秘密堡垒的森林小径；就像水分子一样，孩子们会停下来转身，喋喋不休，来回曲折前进，但从他们的动作和声音中，我们最终可以追踪到从连翘臂下、铁杉树干周围、穿过纤细的箱杨花帘、越过鹅掌楸树的老木头的通道。追踪完成后，我们离它们足够近，它们可以听到我们叫它们进来吃饭。当大脑中的追踪完成时，我们就可以开始了解连接组的结构。这些人类连接组中最大的束是胼胝体，它由 2 亿到 2.5 亿个轴突投影组成。从大数据块到小数据块，连接组显示出清晰的小世界结构，该结构会因神经系统疾病和精神疾病而改变，并且会随着规范发展和健康老龄化而改变。

Is the same true for humans, including our friends Ole Worm and Virginia Woolf? The relevant measurements in humans are a bit different from those in animals. Connectivity research in nonhuman animals provides access to cellular and mesoscale measurements, but the same research in humans only provides access to large-scale measurements. Despite the coarser picture, even here the principles of connection architecture appear to be conserved. Using an MRI machine, scientists can acquire a so-called diffusion weighted image, which provides information about the diffusion of naturally occurring water molecules in the brain. Critically, that diffusion is constrained by the placement and orientation of axonal tracts; water molecules diffuse along tracts like raindrops rolling along tree branches. By inferring the location of tracts from the diffusion images, we can construct connectomes for individual humans. The process is a bit like inferring the forest path to the kids’ secret fort; like water molecules, the kids stop and turn, chatter and chitter, and zigzag backward and forward, but from their movements and the sounds of their voices we can eventually track the passage under the arms of the forsythia, around the trunk of the hemlock, through the curtain of wispy box elder flowers, and over the old log of a tulip tree. Tracking complete, we are close enough for them to hear us call them in for dinner. When tracking is complete in the brain, we can begin to understand the connectome structure. The largest tract in these human connectomes is the corpus callosum, which is composed of between 200 and 250 million axonal projections. From large tracts to small, the connectome displays a clear small-world structure that is altered by neurological disease and psychiatric disorders, and that changes in normative development and healthy aging.

大脑中非平凡连接模式的明确存在凸显了现代神经科学面临的关键挑战和重大机遇。这就是对连接如何解释大脑功能以及人类认知和行为的准确理解。6解决这些问题的学术子领域被称为网络神经科学，因为它结合了网络科学和神经科学领域的最新进展。7普遍的观点是，大脑中的网络组织是解释大脑功能的关键组成部分，与组成部分（区域、神经递质和基因）和原因（一个部分影响另一个部分的因果过程）并列。8重要的是，尽管通路（束和投射）不是机制，但它们有可能成为原因和原因的渠道，就像森林小径是原因（父母边走边叫）的渠道，从而推动结果（孩子们回家吃饭）。9由于路径和原因之间的关系，了解大脑中的连接模式为理解信息如何传输以及如何执行支持我们日常行为的计算提供了重要的先决条件。

The clear existence of nontrivial connection patterns in the brain underscores a critical challenge and marked opportunity for modern neuroscience. And that is the precise understanding of how connectivity explains brain function, and by extension, human cognition and behavior.6 The academic subfield tackling these questions is known as network neuroscience because it combines recent advances in the fields of network science and neuroscience.7 The commonly shared view is that network organization in the brain is a key component of an explanation of brain function, alongside component parts (regions, neurotransmitters, and genes) and causings (causal processes whereby one part influences another part).8 Importantly, although pathways (tracts and projections) are not mechanisms, they have the potential to be causes and the conduits of cause, just as forest paths are the conduit for a cause (a parent meandering while calling) driving an effect (kids coming in for dinner).9 Because of the relations between paths and causes, understanding the pattern of connections in a brain provides an important prerequisite for understanding how information is routed and how computations are performed that support our everyday behavior.

创造和谐

Making Harmony

2013 年 4 月 2 日，美国总统巴拉克·奥巴马宣布了“通过推进创新神经技术进行大脑研究”计划，该计划将在十年内投入大量联邦资金用于神经科学研究。该计划与欧盟（人类大脑计划）、中国（中国大脑计划）、日本（大脑/MINDS）等国家的努力相得益彰。总的来说，该领​​域的财政刺激导致了变革性技术的发展，并获得了更多、越来越准确和全新的数据。这些努力涉及多个物种和一系列实验领域，包括分子、细胞、发育、临床和认知神经科学。与我们在此讨论相关的是，美国的一个主要目标是通过人类连接组计划绘制人类连接组图。通过这些互补的举措，人们越来越清楚地认识到，大脑的网络结构为思维的运作方式提供了简单而直观的解释。为什么人类大脑中大约 800 亿个神经元的活动不会产生杂音？为什么我们大脑中主要表达的两万个基因中约有三分之一不会产生噪音？为什么神经元之间约一百万亿个突触不会将信息混入听觉环境中，而这会让卡科福努斯·A·迪斯霍德博士（诺顿·贾斯特的经典作品《幽灵收费亭》中的不和谐音研究者）感到欣喜？10阻止（L. prohibere）迪斯霍德的​​紫色云怪兽，可怕​​的 Dynne，神经系统组成部分之间的连接形成精确的模式，使单个声音融合成令人愉悦的交响乐。这些模式不仅代表信息流的许可，也代表信息流的禁止，从而实现和谐与和谐。

On April 2, 2013, President Barack Obama announced the Brain Research through Advancing Innovative Neurotechnologies Initiative, devoting significant federal funding over a ten-year period to neuroscience research. The focus complemented efforts in the European Union (Human Brain Project), China (China Brain Project), Japan (Brain/MINDS), and elsewhere. Collectively, that financial stimulus to the field led to the development of transformative technologies and the acquisition of ever more, increasingly accurate, and altogether new data. Efforts have spanned across multiple species and a range of experimental domains, including molecular, cellular, developmental, clinical, and cognitive neuroscience. Pertinent to our discussion here, a key goal in the United States has been to develop a map of the human connectome through the Human Connectome Project. Through these complementary initiatives, it has become increasingly clear that the network architecture of the brain provides simple and intuitive explanations for how the mind works. Why is it that the activity of approximately eighty billion neurons in the human brain does not produce cacophony? Why is it that approximately one-third of our twenty thousand genes primarily expressed in the brain do not create noise? And why is it that the approximately hundred trillion synapses between neurons do not smear information into an auditory milieu that would have delighted Dr. Kakofonus A. Dischord, a scholar of dissonance in Norton Juster’s classic, The Phantom Tollbooth?10 To hold at bay (L. prohibere) Dischord’s purple cloud monster, The Awful Dynne, connections between the component parts of neural systems create precise patterns, allowing the individual voices to blend in a pleasing symphony. The patterns represent not only permission but also prohibition for the flow of information, allowing concordance and harmony.

为了支持和谐，神经系统中的连接模式不仅仅是小世界模式。它们是模块化的。模块化连接模式在一组特定的大脑区域之间提供密集的管道，这些区域共同支持给定的功能。11模块的直观示例是那些支持我们的感觉和运动能力的模块。支持身体运动的大脑在运动模块中紧密相连；同样，支持视觉和听觉的大脑在视觉和听觉模块中连接。就像管弦乐队中的弦乐部分一样，许多部分（音乐家或大脑区域）通过连接管道（共享旋律或物理线路）协同工作，创造出心灵的音乐。除了运动、视觉和听觉之外，大脑的模块化还解释了复杂的认知能力，包括一个人对自我的理解和进行复杂推理的能力。支持工作记忆、抑制不当行为和做出艰难决定的大脑区域在执行模块中紧密相连；支持自愿部署注意力和重新适应意外事件的大脑区域在注意力模块中紧密相连；支持自我参照和自我参照处理的大脑区域在默认模式模块中紧密相连。后一个模块的区域在静息时也往往高度活跃，这表明人类的运作方式至少在一定程度上是将经验与自我联系起来。12

To support harmony, the connection patterns in neural systems are more than simply small-world ones. They are modular. Modular connection patterns provide dense conduits among a particular set of brain areas that collectively support a given function.11 Intuitive examples of modules are those that support our sensory and motor abilities. Regions of the brain that support body movements are densely intraconnected in a motor module; similarly, those that support vision and audition are connected in visual and auditory modules. Like the string section in an orchestra, the many parts (musicians or brain regions) work together through connection conduits (of shared melody or physical wiring) to create the music of the mind. Beyond motion, vision, and audition, brain modularity also explains complex cognitive capacities that include one’s understanding of one’s self and one’s ability to engage in complex reasoning. Regions of the brain that support working memory, inhibition of inappropriate behavior, and the making of difficult decisions are densely intraconnected in an executive module; regions of the brain that support the voluntary deployment of attention and the reorientation to unexpected events are densely intraconnected in an attention module; and regions of the brain that support self-reference and self-referential processing are densely intraconnected in a default mode module. The regions of the latter module also tend to be highly active at rest, suggesting that the modus operandi of humans is, at least in part, one of contextualizing experiences in relation to the self.12

但是模块之间如何相互沟通呢？我如何将一片树叶握在手中，注意到其叶脉的奇特分支（视觉模块）；然后向内反思自己血管中流动的血液，欣赏树叶与我之间的相似之处（自我参照模块）；然后利用这种欣赏转向树叶，更详细地研究其脉管系统（注意模块），为此我移动身体以便更仔细地观察（运动模块）？很明显，即使是最简单的好奇体验也需要模块之间协调的信息流和对信息流的精湛编排（执行模块）。这种协调支持简单的好奇心，是的。但更重要的是，它支持基本的生存，以及追求目标和为幸福的所有其他维度收集各种资源的能力。认知过程的相互交织——从好奇心到真诚，从节制到真实——是由将一个模块连接到另一个模块的连接支持的，确保每个过程不是完全封闭的，而是自然地与其他过程联系在一起。13密集模块和它们之间宽松的紧固允许系统通过拉伸、加强或移动一个模块而不干扰其他模块来最佳地适应或发展。14模块化的这些适应性功能被认为可以解释大脑发育过程中发生的模块间连接的明显微调，以及模块化可用于预测大脑在认知训练、有氧运动和其他活动后的可塑性。

But how do modules communicate with one another? How do I hold a leaf in my hand and note the curious branching of its veins (visual module); then reflect inward to the blood coursing through my own veins, appreciating the similarities between the leaf and I (self-reference module); and then use that appreciation to turn back to the leaf to study its vasculature in even greater detail (attention module), for which I move my body to get a closer look (motor module)? It is clear that even the simplest of curious experiences requires a coordinated flow of information between modules and a masterful orchestration of that flow (executive module). This coordination supports simple curiosity, yes. Yet more than that, it supports basic survival as well as the ability to pursue my goals and gather various resources for all the other dimensions of well-being. The interdigitation of cognitive processes—from curiosity to sincerity, from temperance to authenticity—is supported by connections that link one module to another, ensuring that each process is not fully encapsulated but instead naturally tethered to others.13 The delicate balance of dense modules and lenient fastenings among them allows a system to optimally adapt or evolve by stretching, strengthening, or shifting one module without perturbing the others.14 These adaptive affordances of modularity are thought to explain the marked fine-tuning of intermodular connections that occurs as the brain develops, and the fact that modularity can be used to predict how plastic the brain will be in response to cognitive training, aerobic exercise, and other activities.

模块化有助于解释好奇心的过程或实践。但仍有几个问题。如第 1 章所述，有证据表明好奇心由两个回路支持：奖励和动机回路以及认知控制回路。前者在好奇的搜索和采样过程中处于活跃状态，部分反映了获取新信息的动机以及获得新信息时的奖励感。15 后者控制搜索和采样的时间和性质，部分通过监控认知资源是否应保持朝向当前目标还是重新定向到其他潜在目标。这两个回路都没有与我们刚刚描述的模块完美一对一映射。相反，这两个回路跨越这些模块，表明存在一个协调的（有时是顺序的，有时是并行的）功能，使我们能够参与好奇心的复杂过程。好奇心就像一只手，将大脑的模块交错成一个精神游戏的手掌。或者更进一步说，好奇心就是我们拉动一个轻轻系住的模块的绳子并松开另一个轻轻系住的模块的绳子时编织的织物的轮廓。好奇心是当地派对商店工人的熟练之手，耐心地拉动丝带，将气球排列成一个形状优美的花束，仿佛它是某种沉默、活泼、色彩缤纷的思想丛林。

Modularity helps to explain the process or practice of curiosity. But several questions remain. As reviewed in chapter 1, evidence suggests that curiosity is supported by two circuits: the reward and motivation circuit, and the cognitive control circuit. The former is active during curious search and sampling, partially reflecting both the motivation to obtain novel information and the feeling of reward when that novel information is obtained.15 The latter controls the timing and nature of both search and sampling, in part by monitoring whether cognitive resources should be maintained toward the current goal or redirected toward other potential ones. Neither circuit has a perfect one-to-one mapping onto the modules we just described. Instead, the two circuits span among those modules, indicating the existence of a coordinated—sometimes sequential, sometimes parallel—function, allowing us to engage in the complex process that is curiosity. Curiosity is like a hand interdigitating the modules of the brain into a palm of mental play. Or more than that, curiosity is the contours of the fabric we weave when we pull on the string of one lightly tethered module and slacken the string of another lightly tethered module. Curiosity is the skilled hand of a worker at the local party shop, patiently tugging ribbons to align the balloons into a shapely bouquet as if it were some silent, buoyant, colorful thicket of thought.

单一旋律在何处？

Where Is a Single Melody?

在好奇心的神经过程中，我们看到好奇心的概念过程。支持好奇行为的神经回路反映了通过一系列大脑中轻度束缚模块的时间路径。当思维通过遍历大脑网络从一个局部功能转移到另一个局部功能时，大脑区域相互连接，这让我们想起人类思维通过在相互连接的知识网络上行走从一个概念转移到另一个概念。换句话说，就好像单个人脑网络中好奇心的神经机制反映了整个人类知识网络中好奇心的心理过程。我们的电信号在网络上行走，就像我们的思想和身体在网络上行走一样。大脑和思想之间的镜像促使我们更深入地理解每一步，不仅要理解脚步所穿越的空间，还要理解在调整步态以进行下一步运动时脚所处的位置。在物理领域，脚放在一块土地上；在概念领域，思想放在一点信息上；在神经领域，活动暂停在一点组织上。这一停顿强调了不仅要理解模块或电路中所有区域的集体作用（如管弦乐队的管乐部分），还要理解每个区域在这一过程中的单一作用（如英国管演奏的旋律）。大脑中的组织是否反映了思维中的信息，而思维又反映了世界上的地球？如果是这样，那么是如何反映的？

In the neural processes of curiosity, we see reflected the conceptual processes of curiosity. Neural circuits supporting curious behavior reflect a temporal path through a series of lightly tethered modules of the brain. As the mind moves from one local function to another by traversing a network of interconnected brain regions, we are reminded of the human mind moving from one concept to another by walking upon a network of interconnected pieces of knowledge. In other words, it is as if the neural mechanism of curiosity in a single human’s brain network reflects the mental process of curiosity across the collective humans’ knowledge network. Our electrical signals walk on networks, as much as our minds and our bodies walk on networks. The mirroring between brain and mind motivates a deeper understanding of each step, and not only of the space traversed by the step but also of the location on which the foot is planted while the gait is adjusted for the next movement. In the physical realm, the foot is placed on a bit of earth; in the conceptual realm, the mind is placed on a bit of information; and in the neural realm, the activity pauses in a bit of tissue. That pause underscores the importance of understanding not just the collective role of all regions in a module or circuit (like the wind section of an orchestra) but also the singular role of each region in the process (like the melody carried by the English horn). Does the bit of tissue in the brain reflect the information in the mind, which in turn reflects the bit of earth in the world? And if so, how?

一点脑组织确实可以保存眼睛看到的、手握的或脚感觉到的图像。该图像通常被称为表征，通常由跨神经元或神经元群的活动模式组成。16想象一个灰度像素化图像；每个像素都是一个神经元，每个神经元都有一定的活动水平（或发放率），这决定了该像素在图像中包含的灰度。通过首先了解神经图像和现实世界图像之间的关系，可以破译图像、解码含义并读懂思想。我们仍在研究哪些图像在哪里最容易破译。一些脑组织倾向于提供我们世界中特定物品的图片。例如，存在一条从后脑勺到中脑勺的组织带，其中包含一些子区域，这些子区域的像素化活动图像首先编码形状（最靠后；侧枕叶皮层），然后编码单词形式（梭状回），然后编码面孔（梭状脸部区域），然后编码位置（最靠前；海马旁回区域）。是否也存在一个和谐的焦点？一块用于湿润的泥土？

A bit of brain tissue can indeed hold within it a picture of what the eye sees, the hand holds, or the feet feel. That picture is commonly referred to as a representation and is typically comprised of a pattern of activity across neurons or groups of neurons.16 Imagine a pixelated image in gray scale; each pixel is a neuron, and each neuron has a level of activity (or rate of firing) that determines the shade of gray that pixel contains in the image. The image can be deciphered, the meaning can be decoded, and the mind can be read by first learning the relation between the neural and real-world images. We are still learning which images are best deciphered where. Some bits of brain tissue have a tendency to provide pictures of particular items in our world. For example, there exists a swath of tissue that tracks along the bottom of the brain from the back to the center, and contains subregions whose pixelated image of activity encodes first shapes (furthest back; lateral occipital cortex), then word forms (fusiform gyrus), then faces (fusiform face area), and then places (furthest forward; parahippocampal place area). Is there also a focal point for harmony? A bit of earth for humicubation?

读心术——或者更准确地说，读脑术——是一种解码的形式。它是一种根据大脑神经活动模式预测你所看到的东西的能力。虽然这听起来有点像魔术，但它与逆向操作密切相关：根据一个人所看到的东西预测大脑神经活动的模式。换句话说，通过研究神经图像和现实世界图像之间的关系，我们可以推断大脑如何编码世界。我们可以开始构思密码并破解密码。大脑将体验转化为电信号的规则是什么？一个人真正“看到”或实际处理了这些体验（或其中包含的图像）的哪些部分？我们从简单的日常事件中知道，比如坐在一个三岁孩子旁边，一起仰望夏日天空中的云层，我们每个人对世界的感知都不同：“我看到一头大象拿着一根拐杖糖！”“在哪里？哦。我以为那是一杯放在生菜上的咖啡。你的大象比我的咖啡可爱多了。”通过研究现实世界的图像如何编码到神经图像中，我们可以开始了解云的哪些部分对于一个观察者来说是植物，哪些部分对于另一个观察者来说是动物。

Mind reading—or more accurately, brain reading—is a form of decoding. It is the capacity to predict what you are seeing from the pattern of neural activity in the brain. While it sounds a bit like magic, it is closely related to the reverse operation: predicting the pattern of neural activity in the brain from what a person is seeing. In other words, by studying the relation between the neural and real-world images, we can infer how the brain encodes the world. We can begin to conceive of the cipher and crack the code. What are the rules whereby the brain transforms experiences into electrical signals? And which parts of those experiences (or the images they contain) does a given human truly “see” or actually process? We know from simple everyday events, like sitting by a three-year-old and together looking up at the cloud formations in a summer sky, that each of us perceives the world differently: “I see an elephant holding a candy cane!” “Where? Oh. I thought it was a mug of coffee on a bed of romaine. Your elephant is much cuter than my coffee.” By studying how real-world images are encoded in neural images, we can begin to understand which bits of the cloud became flora for one observer, and which bits of the cloud became fauna for another.

现实世界的图像不必只在大脑的一个区域呈现。相反，实验证据表明，同一图像的不同部分可以在大脑的不同部分呈现。例如，物体的身份可能被编码在颞叶皮层的一部分中，其形状可能被编码在侧枕叶皮层的一部分中，其颜色可能被编码在视觉皮层的一部分中。这一事实使神经科学家开始理解整体与部分之间的关​​系。部分是否简单地相加（或相乘）就成为整体？在整体的呈现方式上，某些部分是否比其他部分有更多发言权？（伍尔夫可能不会感到惊讶。）各部分在大脑的哪里组合？科学家们开始为“汇聚区”提供证据，某些整体形成发生在这里，真正的概念也出现在这里。此外，我们开始看到一个大脑区域编码的信息如何与另一个大脑区域共享，以及这些信息在传输过程中是如何转换或改变的。17通过这些努力，我们听到了单个大脑区域的旋律，并了解了它们如何结合在一起形成交响乐。

A real-world image need not be represented solely in one brain region. Instead, experimental evidence indicates that different parts of the same image can be represented in different parts of the brain. For example, an object’s identity might be encoded in a bit of temporal cortex, its shape might be encoded in a bit of lateral occipital cortex, and its color might be encoded in a bit of visual cortex. That fact allows neuroscientists to start to understand how the whole relates to the parts. Are the parts simply added (or multiplied) to become the whole? Are some parts given more say than others in how the whole is represented? (Woolf likely wouldn’t be surprised.) And where do the parts get combined in the brain? Scientists are beginning to build evidence for a “convergence zone” where some kinds of whole-making happen and the true concept emerges. Moreover, we are starting to see how information encoded in one brain region is shared with another brain region as well as how that information is transformed or changed in the process of transmission.17 From these efforts, we hear the melody of single brain regions and learn how they join together to form the symphony.

我们如何构建一种完整的音乐语言？

Where Do We Build a Fully Musical Language?

如果某人被判处了痛苦和刑罚，法官将对他进行严厉的判决，

If a harsh sentence from the judges awaits someone, once He has been condemned to afflictions and penalties,

不要让他因加工原材料而疲惫不堪

Let workhouses not fatigue him with raw material to be wrought

不要让金属地雷伤到他僵硬的手：

Nor let mines of metal pain his stiffened hands:

让他编字典吧。我还需要多说吗？这

Let him make dictionaries. Need I say more? This

一项劳动具有每一种惩罚的特点。

One labour has aspects of every punishment.

——约瑟夫·贾斯特斯·斯卡利格，《诗》（1615）

—Joseph Justus Scaliger, Poemata (1615)

约瑟夫·斯卡利杰是文艺复兴时期的语言学家、历史学家和宗教领袖，他想不出比编纂字典更辛苦的劳役刑罚。18他尖刻的观点具有讽刺意味，而现代人也清楚地认识到，人类的大脑——每个人的大脑——都会编纂字典。字典位于大脑的球形范围内——这个形状是亚历山大图书馆圆形建筑、博德利图书馆圆形穹顶或法国国家图书馆圆形阅览室中精选藏品的生物学镜像。那么什么是字典？字典是词汇的收集、词汇的排列和词汇的“定义”。大脑如何收集、排列和定义词汇？我们从婴儿开始，通过自然的语言习得过程收集词汇及其背后的概念，对许多人来说，这种过程一直持续到老年。19正如我们刚才所见，我们将单词、概念和概念特征放在大脑的特定部位。正如伍尔夫所说，“单词不存在于词典中，而是存在于大脑中。” 20但是大脑中的单词在哪里？定义在哪里？交叉引用在哪里？单词之间相似点和不同点的澄清在哪里？回答这些问题需要我们更深入地挖掘概念及其关系在大脑中如何、在哪里以及为什么被表达。

A philologist, historian, and religious leader in the Renaissance, Joseph Scaliger could think of no more laborious sentence of penal servitude than to make dictionaries.18 The irony of his scathing opinion, as evident to a modern ear, lies in the fact that the human mind—every human mind—makes a dictionary. That dictionary is housed in the spherical confines of the brain—the shape being a biological mirror of the curated collections housed in the circular building of the Bibliotheca Alexandrina, the circular dome of the Bodleian, or the circular reading rooms of the Bibliothèque Nationale de France. And what is a dictionary? A dictionary is a collection of words, a placement of words, and a “definitionary” of words. How does the mind collect, place, and define words? We collect words and the concepts behind them through the natural processes of language acquisition starting as infants and, for many, continuing into old age.19 And as we have just seen, we place words, concepts, and features of concepts in particular bits of brain tissue. As Woolf notes, “Words do not live in dictionaries; they live in the mind.”20 But where are the words in the mind? Where are the definitions? The cross-references? The clarifications of similarities and differences between words? Answering these questions requires us to dig more deeply into how, where, and why concepts and their relations are represented in the brain.

想象一下，你躺在一间漆黑的房间里，盖着一条温暖的毯子，听着 MRI 机器发出的令人安心的撞击声、叮当声、嘎嘎声和砰砰声，这些声音包围着你的头部和上半身。（别担心。如果你有幽闭恐惧症，你已经被排除在研究之外了。）在铿锵有力的小夜曲中，你听到了皮博迪奖获奖作品中的一集Moth Radio Hour 是 PRX 和 Atlantic Public Media 的 Jay Allison 制作的每周系列节目，在 450 多个广播电台播出，播出现场舞台上讲述的真实故事，没有脚本、笔记、道具或伴奏。21每隔一两秒，就会拍摄一张四万像素的大脑活动快照。科学家仔细比较转录故事中每个字的朗读时间和大脑图像中每个像素显示活动的时间。通过比较，科学家建立了一个计算模型，可以根据你听到的每个字预测你的大脑活动。为了确定模型的有效性，他们还会预测当你听到一个新故事时你的大脑会表现出什么样的活动模式（想象一下玛格丽特·卡文迪什的《炽热的世界》、弗朗索瓦·拉伯雷的《巨人传》或乔纳森·斯威夫特的《书籍之战：上周五圣詹姆斯图书馆中古书与现代书籍之间战斗的完整真实记录》）；然后他们让你听这个新故事并测试他们预测的准确性。

Imagine you are lying down in a dark room, covered in a warm blanket, hearing the comforting bang, clang, rattle, and thump of the MRI machine engulfing your head and upper torso. (Don’t worry. If you have claustrophobia, you were already excluded from the study.) Above the sonorous serenade, you hear an episode from the Peabody award-winning Moth Radio Hour, a weekly series produced by PRX and Jay Allison of Atlantic Public Media, airing on over 450 radio stations, and featuring true stories told live onstage without scripts, notes, props, or accompaniment.21 Every second or two, a forty-thousand-pixel snapshot of your brain’s activity is taken. Scientists carefully compare the time at which each word of the transcribed story was spoken and the time at which each pixel of your brain image showed activity. From that comparison, the scientists build a computational model that predicts your brain activity from each word you heard. To determine the model’s validity, they also predict what patterns of brain activity you will show when you hear a new story (imagine Margaret Cavendish’s The Blazing World, François Rabelais’s Gargantua and Pantagruel, or Jonathan Swift’s Battle of the Books: A Full and True Account of the Battle Fought Last Friday between the Ancient and the Modern Books in Saint James Library); then they have you listen to that new story and test the accuracy of their predictions.

这项实验对旧金山湾区的几位成年人来说已成为现实。22加州大学伯克利分校的科学家通过他们的数据，可以直观地看到每个皮层中存储的语义信息。他们看到的是一张极其复杂的语义图，覆盖了整个大脑，而不仅仅是之前参与语义处理的区域。每毫米的脑组织都与一个单词相关联，类似的单词往往会引起附近组织的活动。有时，同一大脑区域甚至可以激活多个单词，尽管方式不同。回到斯卡利杰，我们意识到心灵的词典将其精选的藏书分布在整个大脑空间中；没有一毫米是未被发现的。这个图书馆没有将其一半的资料用于其他用途（咖啡馆、计算机实验室、中庭）。没有。在心灵的国度，图书馆将其整个结构都用于书架。即使在同一块空间（相同的组织切片）上，大脑也会存储许多不同的单词，就像图书馆在单个书架上存储许多卷书籍，或者字典在单个页面的列中存储许多条目一样。

This experiment became a reality for several adults living in the San Francisco Bay Area.22 From their data, University of California at Berkeley scientists could visualize what semantic information was stored in every piece of the cortex. What they saw was an incredibly complex semantic map that tiled the entire brain, and not just areas that had previously been implicated in semantic processing. Every millimeter of brain tissue was associated with a word, and similar words tended to elicit activity in nearby pieces of tissue. Sometimes the same bit of the brain could even activate to more than one word, albeit differently. Returning to Scaliger, we realize that the mind’s dictionary lays out its curated collections across the entire real estate of the brain; no millimeter is left uncovered. This library has not converted half of its footage to other uses (the café, the computer lab, the atrium). No. In the country of the mind, libraries devote their entire structure to the stacks. And even on the same bit of real estate (the same tissue section), the mind stores many different words, just as a library stores many volumes on a single bookshelf’s footprint or a dictionary stores many entries on a single page’s column.

但是，除了词语的集合和词语的排列之外，心灵还是词语的定义者。定义在哪里可以找到，那么，它们是如何阅读的呢？利用类似的实验，科学家可以测量一个词引起的大脑活动，并计算出它与另一个词引起的大脑活动的相似性。23通过测量多对词之间的相似性，我们发现大脑对某些词组产生相似的活动模式，因此每组词都形成一个大脑定义的类别，反映了大脑对意义的编码。《牛津英语词典》将语言词汇分为科学词汇、外来词汇、文学词汇、普通词汇、技术词汇、俚语词汇和方言词汇；英国自然作家罗伯特·麦克法兰将英国风景词汇分为平原、高地、水域、沿海地区、地下世界、北部地区、边缘地区、地球和林地；人类大脑可能会将词语分为动物、车辆、自然物体等，以及哺乳动物、船只和草原等子类别。24（苏格兰诗人诺曼·麦凯格在 1983 年写下以下诗句后，对最后一个子类别尤其感到自豪：“学者们，我恳求你们，你们关于风和草的词典在哪里？” 25至少，这个大脑是一个不会令人失望的学者。）大脑在这个实验中“看到”的类别比我们之前想象的要丰富得多。26因为类别提供了关于词语含义的粗略信息，所以它们可能因文化和时代、社会和时间、身体和经历的不同而不同。

But beyond a collection of words and a placement of words, the mind is also a definitionary of words. Where can the definitions be found, and how are they read?
