Using analogous experiments, scientists can measure the brain activity evoked by one word and calculate its similarity to the brain activity evoked by another word.23 By measuring this similarity between many pairs of words, we see that the brain produces similar activity patterns to certain sets of words, and each set thus forms a brain-defined category reflecting the brain’s encoding of meaning. The Oxford English Dictionary may categorize words of the language into scientific, foreign, literary, common, technical, slang, and dialectical; British nature writer Robert Macfarlane may categorize words of the UK landscape into flatlands, uplands, waterlands, coastlands, underlands, northlands, edgelands, earthlands, and woodlands; a given human brain might categorize words into animal, vehicle, natural objects, and so on, as well as into subcategories such as mammals, boats, and grasslands.24 (Scottish poet Norman MacCaig would be particularly proud of that last subcategory after penning the following in 1983: “Scholars, I plead with you, Where are your dictionaries of the wind, the grasses?”25 This brain, at least, is a scholar that does not disappoint.) The categories that the brain “sees” in this experiment are far richer than previously thought.26 Because the categories provide broad strokes information regarding words’ meanings, they may differ across cultures and eras, societies and times, bodies and experiences.

每个词的确切含义都可以从类别、子类别和范例（或单个词）之间的关系模式中读出。该模式本身就创建了一个充满复杂分支排列和高度中心节点的网络，反映了与许多其他词具有相似神经激活模式的词。在该网络的一个可视化中，从大脑活动推断出的类别及其关系形成了一种树状结构，让人想起德国解剖学家马克西米利安·弗布林格的进化树：当时用于飞行形式，现在用于幻想飞行。27当我们好奇地穿过思维的概念空间时，我们将脚踩在编码每个想法的每个单词的脑组织上；我们漫步在脑沟和脑回的山丘和山谷中。就像作家威廉·乔伊斯笔下的书呆子人物莫里斯·莱斯莫尔一样，我们在解剖线上嬉戏，在弯曲的 J 字形中荡来荡去，手里握着完整的语言，顺着我们心灵词典的皱褶封面滑下。28

The precise meanings of each word can be read in the pattern of relations among categories, subcategories, and exemplars (or single words). That pattern itself creates a network replete with complex branching arrangements and hub nodes with high degree, reflecting words that share similar patterns of neural activation with many other words. In one visualization of that network, the categories and their relations inferred from brain activity form a treelike structure reminiscent of the phylogenetic trees of German anatomist Maximilian Fürbringer: then for forms of flight, now for flights of fancy.27 As we walk curiously through the mind’s conceptual space, we plant our feet on bits of brain tissue that code each word of each thought; we meander across the hills and valleys of the brain’s sulci and gyri. Like writer William Joyce’s bookish character Morris Lessmore, we cavort across lines of anatomy, swing from trailing J’s of curvature, and slide down the creased binding of the dictionary of our mind with a full language in hand.28

网络在哪里编码？

Where Are Networks Coded?

为什么有些树我从未走过，而广阔而美妙的想法却降临到我身上？

Why are there trees I never walk under but large and melodious thoughts descend upon me?

（我想它们冬天和夏天都挂在那些树上，而且在我经过时总会掉下果实）。

(I think they hang there winter and summer on those trees and always drop fruit as I pass).

—沃尔特·惠特曼，《公路之歌》（1858）

—Walt Whitman, “Song of the Open Road” (1858)

谁编写了我们的词典？是否有一位与罗伯特·考德瑞（1604 年）、塞缪尔·约翰逊（1755 年）、乔治·巴罗（1873 年）、詹姆斯·雷丁·韦尔（1909 年）甚至我们的朋友奥勒·沃姆（1636 年出版了第一本古挪威语词汇集）相当的作者？还是这些词语像那些宏大而优美的思想一样，在我们散步经过树时从树上掉下来？29据我们所知，我们词汇表的创造者是大自然，它用经验之笔和时间之墨书写。经验——贯穿社会和文化——为我们提供了一个概念空间，并构建了该空间的架构。我们将建筑师的概念空间平面图放在哪里呢？我们如何使用这些平面图来探索概念世界？去思考我们会思考的事情？还是避开我们不思考的事情？

Who penned our dictionary? Does it have a creator equivalent to Robert Cawdrey (1604), Samuel Johnson (1755), George Barrow (1873), James Redding Ware (1909), or even our friend Ole Worm, who published the first collection of Old Norse vocabulary in 1636? Or did the words, like thoughts large and melodious, fall from trees as we passed them on our walks?29 As far as we know, the creator of our word list is Nature, who writes with the pen of experience and the ink of time. Experience—shot through with the social and cultural—provides us with a conceptual space and builds the architecture of that space. Where do we house the architect’s floor plans of our conceptual spaces? And how do we use those plans to navigate the conceptual world? To think the thoughts we do? To eschew the thoughts we do not?

要回答这些问题，首先考虑一下我们如何构建物理空间而非概念空间的地图是很有用的。绘制物理世界地图的过程似乎很简单，而且肯定比绘制概念世界地图的过程更容易理解。此外，正如我们将看到的，绘制物理空间地图与绘制概念空间地图有着明显的相关性。绘制地图主要发生在大脑深处一个叫做海马体的区域，该区域大约有 3 到 40 厘米宽，占大脑总体积的 0.25%。30很小。这里存在一种称为位置细胞的特殊类型的神经元。31当你站在房间、家里、工作场所、田野或山上的某个特定位置时，一个特定的位置细胞就会激发。当你站在给定空间的每个位置时，不同的位置细胞就会激发。但位置细胞并不是大脑中唯一的绘制机制。邻近区域，即内嗅皮层，只有海马体大小的一小部分。更小。这里存在一种称为网格细胞的不同类型的神经元。32 个网格细胞通过以下方式创建给定空间的地图用等边三角形镶嵌该空间，从而构建一个周期性的六边形格子。海马体中的位置细胞和内嗅皮层中的网格细胞共同使典型人类能够在真实的物理空间中导航，使非典型人类（经验丰富的出租车司机）能够熟练地在伦敦街道上导航，并让（希望不是非典型）无畏精神在脑海中旅行。

To answer these questions, it is useful to first consider how we build maps of physical rather than conceptual spaces. The process of mapping our physical world seems simple and is certainly more well understood than the process of mapping our conceptual world. Moreover as we shall see, mapping physical spaces has marked relevance to mapping conceptual spaces. The mapping largely occurs deep inside the brain in an area called the hippocampus, which spans approximately three to forty centimeters, thus making up 0.25 percent of the brain’s total volume.30 Tiny. Here a particular type of neuron exists called a place cell.31 A given place cell fires whenever you stand in a particular spot in your room, home, or workplace, in a field, or on a mountain. As you stand in each spot in a given space, a different place cell fires. But place cells are not the sole mapping mechanism in the brain. A neighboring region, the entorhinal cortex, is only a fraction of the size of the hippocampus. Tinier. Here a different type of neuron exists called a grid cell.32 Grid cells create a map of a given space by tessellating that space with equilateral triangles, thereby building a periodic hexagonal lattice. Together, place cells in the hippocampus and grid cells in the entorhinal cortex allow the typical human to navigate true physical spaces, allow the atypical human (a seasoned taxi driver) to expertly navigate the London streets, and allow the (hopefully not untypical) fearless spirit to travel in the mind.

基于这些发现，科学家们试图超越对我们如何在空间（无论是陆地空间还是天体空间）进行导航的理解，转向对我们如何在概念空间中进行导航的理解。他们想知道、猜测甚至试图预测大脑如何与概念所处的空间互动、计算和处理这些空间。这些深思熟虑的探索中有一个共同点，那就是大脑将概念组织成心理地图的方式与将位置组织成物理地图的方式相同。大脑用网格编码物理空间的性质，因此它也可能用网格编码概念空间的性质。如果这是真的，那么也许让我们在物理空间中导航的原理也让我们在概念空间中导航：地标、距离和可用路径。最近对人类的研究为这种网格状代码提供了精确的证据，这种代码将我们的抽象知识组织在二维概念空间中。33密码的美妙之处在于它不仅存在于内嗅皮层（在其他哺乳动物中也观察到了这一点），还存在于与记忆、想象和心理理论有关的其他大脑区域，以及当我们使用从以前经历的情况中获得的工具应对新情况时活跃的区域。换句话说，我们的记忆可能被映射，我们的想象可能存在于一个维度的世界中，我们对他人的概念可能使用经过仔细测量的距离概念，当我们探索广阔的新体验时，我们会将这些地图放在我们的工装裤的后口袋里。34

Building on these discoveries, scientists have sought to press beyond an understanding of how we navigate space, either terrestrial or celestial, and toward an understanding of how we navigate conceptual spaces. They have wondered, guessed, and even attempted to predict how the brain engages with, computes about, and processes the spaces in which concepts live. Common among those thoughtful engagements is the notion that the brain organizes concepts into a mental map in the same way that it organizes locations into a physical map. As the brain codes the nature of physical spaces with a grid, so might it code the nature of conceptual spaces with a grid. If true, perhaps the same principles that allow us to navigate physical spaces also allow us to navigate conceptual spaces: landmarks, distances, and available pathways. Recent work in humans provides precise evidence for just such a grid-like code that organizes our abstract knowledge in a two-dimensional conceptual space.33 What is particularly beautiful about the code is that it exists not just in the entorhinal cortex where it has been observed in other mammals but also in other areas of the brain implicated in memory, imagination, and theory of mind, and in areas that are active as we navigate new situations with tools we have acquired in previously experienced situations. In other words, our memories may be mapped, our imaginations may live in a dimensional world, our conceptions of others may use carefully measured notions of distances, and we keep these maps in the back pocket of our cargo pants as we explore the vast lands of new experiences.34

总的来说，这些数据表明，心灵的空间并不像我们以前想象的那么虚无缥缈，而是有形的、可行走的、可攀爬的，甚至是可跳跃的。我们如何学习在地图上绘制路径？我们如何绘制英格兰南部的下沉式小巷、法国北部的十字路口、西班牙西北部的走廊，西威尔士和叙利亚的洼地、日本的海道、北美沉没的纳奇兹小道，以及我们脑海中那些反映我们自己和世界的真相的陈旧路径？从本质上讲，这些问题归结为一个科学问题：我们如何学习知识网络，即定义事物之间关系的路径（我们回忆亨利·庞加莱的一句话：“在这些关系之外，没有可知的现实”）。35回答这个问题的一个特别有用的实验方法是向人类展示一串物体，其中某些物体倾向于跟随某些其他物体，正如我们在第 5 章中讨论的那样。人类观察者不知道，物体串来自物体之间的关系模式（或网络），相关物体经常以系列形式出现，而不相关的物体永远不会以系列形式出现。利用这样的网络学习实验，科学家们发现了海马-内嗅系统看到物体之间的联想关系并将其编码为距离的证据。36这些距离以两种方式映射。在第一个映射中，内嗅皮层的一部分编码了概念空间中两个对象之间是否存在路径（道路或关系）。在第二个映射中，内嗅皮层的另一部分编码了，对于不相连的对象，从概念空间中的第一个对象到第二个对象需要经过多少条路径（多条道路或关系）。这两个代码一起构成了一个地图般的知识结构，它隐藏在我们潜意识的黑暗中，照亮我们行走世界的道路。

Collectively, these data suggest that the space of the mind is not so ethereal as we might have previously imagined but rather is tangible, walkable, climbable, and even leapable. How do we learn the pathways to draw on the map? How do we lay down the sunken lanes of Southern England, the chemin creux of Northern France, the corredoiras of northwestern Spain, the holloways of West Wales and Syria, the Kaidō of Japan, the sunken Natchez Trace of North America, and the well-worn paths of our minds reflecting the truths about ourselves and our world? In essence, these questions amount to the scientific question of how we learn knowledge networks, the pathways that define the relations among things (“outside these relations there is no reality knowable,” as we recall from Henri Poincaré).35 An especially useful experimental approach to answering this question is to show humans a string of objects in which certain objects tend to follow certain other objects, as we discussed in chapter 5. Unbeknownst to the human observer, the string of objects comes from a pattern of relations (or a network) between the objects, with related objects often being seen in series and unrelated objects never being seen in series. Using such a network learning experiment, scientists have uncovered evidence that the hippocampal-entorhinal system sees the associative relations among objects and codes them as distances.36 Those distances are mapped in two ways. In the first mapping, a bit of entorhinal cortex codes whether there exists a path (a road or relation) at all between the two objects in this conceptual space. In the second mapping, a different bit of entorhinal cortex codes, for disconnected objects, how many paths (multiple roads or relations) must be traversed to get from the first object to the second object in this conceptual space. Together, these two codes make a maplike knowledge structure that lies in the dark of our subconscious, lighting the way as we walk our world.

灵活性和学习

Flexibility and Learning

苏格兰诗人、登山家和博物学家南·谢泼德 (Nan Shepherd) 曾写到在凯恩戈姆山 (Cairngorms) 徒步数小时的经历，他指出“眼睛看到了以前没有看到的东西，或者以新的方式看到了已经看到的东西。耳朵和其他感官也是如此……这些瞬间来得不可预知，但似乎受一种我们难以理解的法则所支配。” 37当我们在自然和概念世界的风景中行走时，我们常常会被新的感知所震撼，增加独特的出没地点，开辟一条不同的道路，或者通过在道路中间不听话地跺脚和溅水来改变旧有的感知。暴雨过后无忧无虑的小溪。景观在变化，集体知识也在变化。路径在变化，知识之间的关系也在变化。我们的网络在变化。随着我们从轻盈的青年变老为更加冷静的老年人，我们行走的方式也在变化。地图在变化，我们使用地图的方式也在变化。不同的地图伴随着压迫结构，而抵抗行为则改变了地图并重新夺回了它们的用途。什么规则支配着所有这些大胆的变化？

The Scottish poet, mountaineer, and naturalist Nan Shepherd writes of hours of walking in the Cairngorms, noting that “the eye sees what it didn’t see before, or sees in a new way what it had already seen. So the ear, the other senses . . . These moments come unpredictably, yet governed, it would seem, by a law whose working is dimly understood.”37 As we walk in the landscapes of the natural and conceptual worlds, we are often struck by new perceptions, add distinct haunts, forge a different path, or change an old one by stamping and splashing disobediently down the middle of the carefree rivulets after a rainstorm. Landscapes change, as does collective knowledge. Paths change, as do the relations among bits of knowledge. Our networks change. As we age from lithe youth to calmer elder, the very manner in which we walk changes. The maps change, and the way we use the maps changes. Different maps accompany structures of oppression, while acts of resistance change the maps and reclaim their use. What rules govern all of this audacious changeability?

大脑需要灵活性。它需要灵活性来随着新数据的到来而学习，随着身体的变化而变化，随着世界的变化而变化。然而，大脑的大部分——它的结构甚至功能——都是硬连线的或相对固定的。我们一生中不会长出新的大脑区域；本章前面描述的大轴突束在整个成年期都保持其排列。因此，也许我们最大的希望只能是让大脑像猎豹在糖蜜中奔跑一样迅速移动，或者像一棵树一样巧妙地试图超越猎豹，在一个永无止境的拔根再移植、拔根再移植的循环中。大脑如何在（无可否认的庞大）不灵活硬件的限制下解决灵活性的难题？最近的证据表明，它部分是通过交通管制来实现的：可更改的停车标志、可编辑的交通信号灯、可充气（和可放气）的减速带等等。大脑精心安排信息在连接（人行道、道路和高速公路）中的传输方式，尤其是连接一个模块到另一个模块的方式。38模块间通信灵活性更高的大脑比模块间灵活性较低的大脑学习效率更高。此外，一个人大脑的模块灵活性程度可以预测他们未来的学习能力。这种灵活性受睡眠、情绪和心理健康的调节，从根本上使大脑能够适应而不进行改革。

The brain needs flexibility. It needs flexibility to learn as new data arrives, to morph as the body morphs, and to change as the world changes. Yet much of the brain—its structure and even its function—is hardwired or relatively fixed. We do not grow new brain areas during our lifetime; the large axonal tracts described earlier in this chapter maintain their arrangement throughout adulthood. Hence perhaps our greatest hope can only be for the brain to move as swiftly as a cheetah running through molasses, or as adroitly as a tree attempting to outpace the cheetah in a never-ending cycle of uprooting and then replanting, uprooting and then replanting. How does the brain solve the quandary of flexibility within (the admittedly massive) constraints of inflexible hardware? Recent evidence suggests that it does so in part by traffic control: changeable stop signs, editable traffic lights, inflatable (and deflatable) speed bumps, and so on. The brain carefully orchestrates the manner in which information is shuttled along connections (footpaths, roads, and highways) and particularly along those connections that bridge one module to another.38 Brains with more flexibility of intermodular communication learn more effectively than those with less intermodular flexibility. Moreover, the degree of modular flexibility in a person’s brain can predict their capacity to learn in the future. Such flexibility is modulated by sleep, mood, and mental health, and fundamentally allows for the brain to adapt without reforming.

作为一种自由机制，模块和电路之间的灵活通信可以让我们构建、使用和修改我们的知识认知地图。连接到注意力回路可以决定关注或感知世界的哪些部分（拿着拐杖糖的大象或放在生菜上的咖啡杯），以及随后将哪些部分画在我们后口袋里的地图上（海马体-内嗅球）连接奖励回路可以决定使用地图是积极的还是消极的体验，从而影响哪些地图需要继续构建，哪些需要搁置。连接动机和评价回路可以决定何时使用地图，以及对一个认知空间（数学？）与另一个认知空间（戏剧？）的地图的评价有多高。与运动回路的连接可以决定身体如何以新的方式移动（行走、跑步、跳跃、跳舞、运动或演奏乐器），以在地图上找到新的认知或情感位置或新的道路。与视觉和听觉回路的连接可以决定我们如何看待和聆听世界的每个部分，并将其编码在我们的概念空间中。

As a mechanism for freedom, flexible communication between modules and circuits could allow us to build, use, and revise our cognitive maps of knowledge. Connecting to the attention circuit could determine which pieces of the world to attend to or perceive (the elephant holding a candy cane or the mug of coffee on a bed of romaine), and which pieces to subsequently draw on the map in our back pocket (the hippocampus-entorhinal system). Connecting to the reward circuit could determine whether using the map was a positive or negative experience, influencing which maps to continue building and which to lay aside. Connecting to the motivation and valuation circuits could determine when to use the map, and how much to value the map of one cognitive space (math?) versus another cognitive space (theater?). Connections to the motor circuit could determine how the body moves in new ways (walking, running, leaping, dancing, athletics, or playing an instrument) to find fresh cognitive or emotional places on the map or novel roadways to lay down. Connections to the visual and auditory circuits could determine how we see and hear each part of our world, and encode it in our conceptual space.

灵活的连接可允许信息在模块或电路之间以不同的方式传输，反过来，这种灵活的传输可以改变我们表征世界的方式以及我们在词典中放置条目的方式。随着社会、文化、科学和许多其他因素的变化，单词的含义通常会随着时间而改变；此外，单词背后的概念也会发生变化。例如，考虑一下imply这个词。在 14 世纪，它的意思是“包围、包裹、纠缠”；其含义“将未说明的事物作为逻辑结果涉及”最早记录于 1400 年左右；而“暗示”的含义则来自 16 世纪 80 年代。39或者考虑一下impertinent这个词。在 14 世纪，它的意思是“不相干、不相关、不切题”，但“粗鲁无礼、不文明、冒犯性冒犯”的意思来自 1680 年代，来自早期的“不适合情况”（16 世纪 80 年代）的含义。词语的可变性意味着无拘无束，即某种假定的摆脱固定意义的严格限制。这种可变性是任何语言中词语的显著特征。大脑语言也不例外。随着代表这些词语的神经活动的变化，大脑中词语的含义也会发生变化。我们世界中的事物所引起的表征（跨神经单元的活动模式）可以随着我们的生活而加强、具体化和适应。尽管目前还不太清楚，但神经表征的这种变化可能是通过整个大脑网络中灵活、不同且自适应的信息路由实现的。40

Flexible connections can allow information to be shuttled differently between modules or circuits, and in turn that flexible shuttling can change how we represent the world and the entries we place in our dictionary. Words commonly change their meaning over time in response to changes in society, culture, science, and many other factors; moreover, the concepts behind the words can also change. For example, consider the word imply. In the fourteenth century, it meant “to enfold, enwrap, entangle”; the meaning “to involve something unstated as a logical consequence” was first recorded circa 1400; and that of “to hint at” is from the 1580s.39 Or consider the word impertinent. In the fourteenth century, it meant “unconnected, unrelated, not to the point,” but the sense of “rudely bold, uncivil, offensively presumptuous” is from 1680s, from the earlier sense of “not appropriate to the situation” (1580s). The changeability of words implies impertinence, a certain presumptive freedom from the rigorous constraints of fixed meanings. That changeability is a celebrated feature of words in any language. And the language of the brain is no exception. The meanings of words in the brain change as the neural activity representing those words changes. Representations (patterns of activity across neural units) evoked by items in our world can strengthen, crystallize, and adapt as we go through life. Although not yet well understood, such changes in neural representations could be made possible by the flexible, different, and adaptive routing of information throughout the network of the brain.40

实践的灵活性

The Flexibility of Practice

大脑的灵活性不仅让我们能够改变和加深对周围世界的理解，还能让我们以不同的方式与世界互动。它不仅让我们好奇，还能让我们实践好奇心，好奇地改变，并适应我们的好奇心。实践好奇心意味着什么？好奇心真的可以改变，可以真正成长吗？许多科学研究都假设好奇心是一种天生的或默认的状态：这种能力最好被描述为一个人的特质或一个人运作的常见模式。41这种观念类似于一个人天生具有夸夸其谈、书呆子气或才华横溢的观念。然而，证据表明，我们的个性和人格的许多方面可以在很短的时间内发生变化。让我们考虑一下人类专注力的核心能力。正念远非固定在一个人身上，可以通过训练明显改变，从而从根本上调节一个人的思维模式，导致他们的决策、工作记忆、空间记忆、语言流畅性和认知灵活性发生变化。所有这些改变都是可能的，因为正念改变了大脑特定区域的活动。同样，新数据表明，好奇心在人身上远非固定不变；相反，它会时时刻刻自然地增强和减弱。此外，好奇心可以受到外部因素的调节，包括学习环境中的因素。好奇心可以变化，而且会不断变化，这一事实为以自我完善为目标的好奇心实践开辟了可能性。也许，这也为与其他人一起实践好奇心以改善我们的社会开辟了可能性。

The flexibility of our brains allows us not only to change and grow our understanding of the world around us but also to engage with the world ever differently. It allows us not only to be curious but to practice curiosity, to change curiously, and to adapt our curiousness. What does it mean to practice curiosity? Is curiosity something that can actually change and that can truly grow? Many scientific studies operate under the assumption that curiosity is an innate or default state: a capacity that is best characterized as a trait of a person or the common mode in which the person operates.41 This notion is similar to the one that a person has a natural level of bombastry, bookishness, or brilliance. Yet the evidence suggests that many dimensions of our personality and personhood can vary over quite short timescales. Let’s consider the central human capacity for mindful attention. Far from fixed in a single person, mindfulness can be demonstrably altered by training, thereby fundamentally modulating a person’s patterns of thought, leading to a change in their decision-making, working memory, spatial memory, verbal fluency, and cognitive flexibility. And all of this change making is possible because mindfulness alters the activity of specific areas of the brain. Similarly, new data indicate that curiosity is far from fixed in a person; instead, it can wax and wane naturally from moment to moment. Further, curiosity can be modulated by external factors including those present in learning environments. The fact that curiosity can vary and be varied opens up the possibility of practicing curiosity with the aim of self-betterment. Perhaps it also opens up the possibility of practicing curiosity alongside other humans for the betterment of our society.

练习是一种训练。在正念训练中，人们练习一组特定的心理状态和它们之间的一组过渡（或缺乏过渡）。在好奇心训练中，人们可以练习好奇的心理状态和遵循探究路线的心理状态转换。此外，人们可以练习选择好奇的对象，遵循好奇搜索的模式，并在生活中腾出时间和空间来根据自己的信息搜索倾向采取行动。打个比方，人们沿着自己的知识网络行走，寻求建立新的网络，添加新的边缘，添加新节点，或跳入超出我们知识范围的黑色（或空白）空间，希望获得一些意想不到的惊喜想法。我们行走、建造和跳跃的方式可能受到我们的个性、教育经历、学习能力以及对打猎、忙碌或跳舞的偏好的影响。我们寻找什么类型的节点？它们是单一概念还是更大的想法？我们愿意建立什么类型和距离的链接？两个想法有多大的不同才能让我们仍然承认它们的关系？我们将新节点和边缘纳入我们现有的知识网络的方式是什么（如果有的话）？我们希望构建什么样的架构？它是密集的还是稀疏的？有序的还是无序的？低维的还是高维的？废纸篓还是珠宝盒？这些问题的答案需要一些明确的距离、几何和空间概念：想法之间的距离、网络的几何形状以及网络存在的空间。42以认知科学家 Peter Gärdenfors 的研究为基础，我们可以问：好奇思维的几何形状是什么？它与一个人自己的概念空间（无论是禁欲主义的还是诗意的）有何关系？43

Practice is a form of training. In mindfulness training, one practices a certain set of mental states and a set of transitions (or lack of transitions) between them. In curiosity training, one might practice mental states of curiosity and mental state transitions following a line of inquiry. Moreover, one might practice choosing the objects of curiosity, following patterns of curious search, and making time and space in one’s life to act upon one’s information-seeking proclivities. Metaphorically, one walks along one’s network of knowledge, and seeks to build new webs, add new edges, append new nodes, or leap into the black (or blank) space beyond one’s knowledge in the hopes of landing on some deliciously unexpected idea. The manner in which we walk, build, and leap may be informed by our personalities, educational experiences, learning capacities, and predilections for hunting, busybodying, or dancing. What types of nodes do we seek? Are they single concepts or larger ideas? What type and distance of links are we willing to make? How distinct may two ideas be for us to still acknowledge their relationship? What is the manner in which we incorporate the new node and edge into our existing knowledge network (if at all)? What sort of architecture do we wish to build? Is it dense or sparse? Ordered or disordered? Low dimensional or high dimensional? A wastebasket or jewel casket? The answers to these questions require some explicit notions of distance, geometry, and space: the distance between ideas, the geometry of the network, and the space in which the network exists.42 Building on the work of cognitive scientist Peter Gärdenfors, one can ask, What is the geometry of curious thought? And how does it relate to one’s own conceptual space, whether ascetic or poetic?43

当我们观察他人的好奇心时，我们构建的网络的几何形状可能会发生变化。人类可以通过视觉或听觉观察进行隐性学习，即通过看到或听到他人的好奇行为，而无需意识到自己正在学习或学习什么。我们还可以通过阅读他人的书面作品进行隐性学习，好奇行为在页面上以无声的符号形式出现。在认知科学中，一种常见的隐性学习形式是统计学习，通过统计学习，我们可以了解环境中发生了哪些事件、这些事件发生的频率以及给定事件转换为其他事件的频率。在大脑中，支持这种学习的神经计算可以促进对象或概念之间成对关系的编码以及它们之间高阶关系模式（网络）的编码，正如我们所见。在向他人学习好奇心的实践时，这种人类能力可以体现在获取有关他人搜索的想法类型、他们如何将它们联系起来以及随着时间的推移，这些小步骤如何导致知识网络的增长的知识上。44作为对这些途径的补充对于隐性学习，人类可以通过显性学习成长和改变，显性学习涉及有意识的观察、理解和记忆内容。当我们意识到自己会得到回报时，我们经常会进行显性学习——例如，在课堂上取得好成绩或得到朋友的一句善意的话语。在这里，我们的好奇行为可能受到父母、老师、导师或同伴的经历的影响，他们将我们的天性称为“好奇”，或将我们最近的想法称为“好奇”，从而激励我们保持这种天性或获得并分享类似的想法。我们在哪些地方向他人学习好奇心的实践，无论是隐性还是显性？在典型的课堂上，人们是否会学习要寻找哪一类节点、要绘制哪一类边以及要构建哪种网络？老师或教授是否会在展示自己的同时传授一些关于好奇心实践的知识？导师是否会在一对一互动中传递知识网络构建模式？朋友是否会握住我们的手，带我们走进风景、爬上高山、穿过森林，让我们手牵手沿着小路和山谷奔跑？

The geometry of the network that we build may change as we watch others practice curiosity. Humans can learn implicitly—without any awareness that they are learning or of what they are learning—simply from visual or auditory observation—that is, by seeing or hearing another’s curious acts. We can also learn implicitly from reading another’s written work, where curious acts caper in silent symbols across a page. In cognitive science, a commonly studied form of implicit learning is statistical learning, whereby we acquire knowledge about which events happen in our environment, how frequently those events occur, and how often a given event transitions to some other event. In the brain, the neural computations that support this type of learning can facilitate the encoding of pairwise relationships between objects or concepts as well as the encoding of higher-order relational patterns (networks) between them, as we have seen. In learning the practice of curiosity from others, this human capacity could manifest in acquiring knowledge about the types of ideas that others search for, how they connect them, and, over time, how these small steps lead to the growth of knowledge networks.44 As a complement to these pathways for implicit learning, humans can grow and change through explicit learning, which involves conscious observation, understanding, and memorization of content. We often engage in explicit learning when we realize that we will be rewarded—for example, by a good test score in class or a kind word from a friend. Here our curious behaviors might be shaped by our experiences of a parent, teacher, mentor, or companion referring to our nature as “curious,” or our most recent ideas as “curious,” thus motivating us to maintain that nature or acquire as well as share similar ideas. What are the places in which we learn the practice of curiosity from others, whether implicitly or explicitly? In a typical classroom, does one learn what category of nodes to look for, types of edges to draw, and sort of networks to build? Does a teacher or professor impart some knowledge about the practice of curiosity, as a by-product of demonstrating their own? Does a mentor transfer a mode of knowledge network building in one-on-one interactions? Does a friend grasp our hand and draw us into the landscape, up the mountain, and through the forest, such that we run together hand in hand along the byways and holloways?

* * *

* * *

有了这种灵活的大脑，这种从他人和世界学习的适应性思维，我们可以问，我们构建的知识结构是什么？知识是否像大脑一样，在约束条件下结合了灵活性？有些部分比其他部分更刚性吗？有些部分比其他部分更灵活吗？为什么？想象一下建筑师搭建新建筑的脚手架，工程师建造机器人系统的骨架，或者自然选择进化出活体动物的力学。45苏格兰物理学家詹姆斯·克拉克·麦克斯韦在 19 世纪中期指出，这些结构的稳定性、寿命和刚性是由其连杆的几何形状决定的。46由铰链连接的钢筋制成的三角形是刚性的，因为施加在任何一根钢筋上的压力都不会改变三角形的形状。相反，用相同材料制成的正方形是柔性的，因为施加在任何一根钢筋上的压力都会使正方形塌陷成菱形。通过将刚性部分与非刚性部分相结合，可以构建兼具灵活性和约束性的大型结构。弯曲的结构风吹过，不会开裂。灵活性和约束性的结合也可以进行微调，以支持单一的运动学。一种在风中行走而不溅起水花的结构。荷兰雕塑家 Theo Jansen 在建造 Strandbeests 时正是利用了这一事实，这是一个荷兰语术语，大致翻译为“海滩野兽”。海风沿着海岸的沙滩吹拂，推动着这些动物般的机械雕塑在海浪中行走，仿佛活了过来，柔性部分与刚性部分结合在一起，完美地引导 Strandbeest 的步态。

Equipped with this flexible brain, this adaptive mind that learns from others and from our world, we can ask, What are the structures of knowledge that we build? Does knowledge, like the brain, combine flexibility within constraints? Are some parts more rigid than others? Are some parts more flexible than others? Why? Consider an architect constructing the scaffolding of a new building, an engineer constructing the skeleton of a robotic system, or natural selection evolving the mechanics of a living animal.45 The stability, longevity, and rigidity of such structures is made possible by the geometry of their linkages, as Scottish physicist James Clerk Maxwell pointed out in the mid-1800s.46 A triangle made from steel bars connected by hinges is rigid because pressure on any bar does not change the triangle’s shape. Conversely, a square made from the same materials is flexible because pressure applied to any bar will collapse the square into a rhombus. By combining rigid sections with nonrigid ones, larger structures can be built that marry flexibility and constraints. A structure that bends in the wind, without cracking. The marriage of flexibility and constraints can also be fine-tuned to support a single kinematics. A structure that walks in the wind, without dabbing. It was precisely this fact that Dutch sculptor Theo Jansen used in constructing the Strandbeests, a Dutch term that roughly translates to “beach beasts.” The power of the ocean wind sweeping along the sands of the shore propels these animal-like mechanical sculptures to walk by the waves as if brought to life, the flexible sections being coupled with the rigid sections in a way that perfectly guides the Strandbeest’s gait.

这些关于结构和运动之间关系的直觉是否只局限于物质力学？还是它们可以成为我们理解知识力学的有用支架？正如我们所见，知识可以有用地建模为概念及其关系的网络。47 无论是众所周知的还是尚未发现的，其中一些关系是固定的和不可变的（例如整数之间的关系），而另一些关系则是灵活的，因为它们可以通过上下文或周围概念的添加、删除或变换而改变。48 作为后者的一个例子，请考虑亚瑟·本森 (Arthur Benson) 为诗人兼艺术家但丁·加布里埃尔·罗塞蒂 (Dante Gabriel Rossetti) 所写的传记中的这段话：

Are these intuitions regarding the relations between structure and movement sequestered to the mechanics of matter alone? Or might they prove to be a useful scaffolding for our understanding of the mechanics of knowledge? As we have seen, knowledge can be usefully modeled as a network of concepts and their relations.47 Whether well-known or as yet undiscovered, some of those relations are fixed and immutable (such as the relations among whole numbers), while others are flexible in the sense that they can be altered by context or the addition, deletion, or transmutation of concepts around them.48 As an example of the latter, consider this passage from Arthur Benson’s biography of poet and artist Dante Gabriel Rossetti:

我们发现这样的句子：“不受约束的不可逆转的目标”，“用冷漠的纪念眼神不眠不休”。请注意这样的结构——

We find such lines as “the unfettered irreversible goal,” “Sleepless with cold commemorative eyes.” Note such textures as—

“哦！这是什么，它知道我来时的路，

“Oh! what is this that knows the road I came,

火焰变成了云，云又变成了火焰，升起的山坡发生了移动，一直到最后？——

The flame turned cloud, the cloud returned to flame, The lifted shifted steeps and all the way?—

终于，这温暖的风把我包围，让我重新陶醉在狂喜之中

That draws round me at last this wind-warm space, And in regenerate rapture turns my face

在令人沮丧的狡猾隐蔽处？”

Upon the devious coverts of dismay?”

或者

Or

“啊！谁敢去寻找那悲伤的迷宫，从此以后他们的无法沟通的道路

“Ah! who shall dare to search through what sad maze Thenceforth their incommunicable ways

追随死亡的散漫食粮吧！”

Follow the desultory feed of death!”

在这些最后的引文中，可以观察到，一些词的通常含义发生了轻微的变化，如纪念性的、再生的和无法传达，但又增添了一些普通语言中没有的细微差别。这种精致自有其魅力，这种语言处理方式，这种对词语使用的精妙运用，在很大程度上决定了精湛文笔大师作品的乐趣。49

It will be observed in these last quotations there is a certain slight shifting of the usual meanings of words like commemorative, regenerate, and incommunicable, some slight nuance added to them which is not found in ordinary speech. This preciosity has a charm of its own, and upon this handling of language, this delicate straining of the use of words, depends much of the pleasure derivable from the work of masters of elaborate style.49

本森在这里指出，语言大师罗塞蒂倾向于通过在文章中放置单词来扩展、拉伸、改变和增加单词含义的细微差别。视觉艺术和表演艺术同样在限制范围内进行创新；它们认识到大多数人共有的结构和期望，但又寻求以适当的程度改变结构或挑战期望的方法，以便人们可以欣赏这种转变而不会完全破坏结构。正是在给定时期的限制内，从这种对声音或颜色的处理，这种对和声或形状的微妙运用的拉伸，我们获得了如此的乐趣。我们感觉到我们脑海中的网络在风中弯曲，在沙滩上行走。

Here Benson notes the tendency for Rosetti—a master of language—to stretch, strain, shift, and add nuance to the meaning of words by their placement within a passage. Visual and performing arts similarly innovate within constraints; they recognize the structure and expectations common to most people, and yet seek ways to shift the structure or challenge the expectations just the right amount so that the shift can be appreciated without breaking the structure entirely. And it is from this handling of sound or color, this delicate straining of the use of harmonies or shapes, within the constraints of a given period, that we derive such pleasure. We feel the networks in our mind bend in the wind and walk on the sand.

但网络弯曲不仅仅是艺术家的作品。它是每个人的作品。当我们通过好奇的实践构建我们的知识网络时，我们是否会轻轻地束缚住一些词语，甚至可能让一些词语相对不受束缚，让它们在我们未来经验的风中移动？我们是否将刚性（三角形）概念关系的部分与柔性（方形）概念关系的部分结合起来，让我们的思想行走，甚至跳舞？50当机械网络的形状变形时，就像海滩仿生兽行走时的形状一样，我们说网络发生了构象变化。51这种变化使生物学中的蛋白质具有复杂的功能，工程材料具有巨大的能力，甚至雕塑具有美感。在生物学、材料物理学和艺术领域，经历构象变化的能力提供了灵活、可执行的功能。知识，无论是在一个人的头脑中，还是在人类的集体智慧中，是否可以根据关系三角形和关系正方形的精确位置发生构象变化？是不是通过这种形状变形过程，我们才能获得洞察力——当两个看似遥远的概念在我们的概念空间中足够接近时，就会出现“啊哈！”的时刻，触觉？当我们在性别、性别认同、性取向、种族、民族、阶级和能力等维度上了解普遍存在的隐性偏见的证据时，我们是否通过这种变形过程改变了我们的信念？当我们看到同情的好处和冷漠的破坏时，我们是否通过这种变形过程塑造了我们最亲密的价值观？如果是这样，我们寻求一种好奇心，使我们能够建立一个融合了灵活和刚性、正方形和三角形的知识网络，以支持持续的构象变化。在我们的脑海中，在一片对他人的风和经验的雨作出反应的风景上，我们希望跳舞。

But network bending is not only the work of artists. It is the work of every human. As we build our knowledge networks through curious practice, do we tether words lightly or even perhaps leave some relatively untethered to allow for their movement in the winds of our future experience? Do we combine sections of rigid (triangular) conceptual relations with sections of flexible (squarish) conceptual relations, allowing our minds to walk or—even more—to dance?50 When the shape of a mechanical network morphs, like the shapes of the Strandbeests as they walk, we say that the network has undergone a conformational change.51 Such a change allows proteins in biology to have complex functions, engineered materials to have immense capabilities, and even sculptures to have beauty. Across biology, materials physics, and art, the capacity to undergo a conformational change provides flexible, actuatable function. Could knowledge, whether in a single person’s head or in the collective wisdom of the human species, undergo conformational change depending on the precise placement of relational triangles and relational squares? Is it by this shape-morphing process that we gain insight—the “Aha!” moment as two seemingly distant concepts come close enough in our conceptual space to touch? Is it by this shape-morphing process that we bend our beliefs as we educate ourselves about the evidence for pervasive implicit bias along the dimensions of sex, gender, sexual orientation, race, ethnicity, class, and ability? Is it by this shape-morphing process that we mold our closest-held values as we see the benefits of compassion and the devastation of indifference? If so, we seek a kind of curiosity that allows us to build a network of knowledge that blends the flexible and rigid, the squares and triangles, to support continual conformational change. In our minds, upon a landscape that responds to the winds of others and rains of experience, we hope to dance.

8

8

重新构想教育

Reimagining Education

我们被压成线，就像线是这种压力时刻的积累一样。

We are pressed into lines, just as lines are the accumulation of such moments of pressure.

—Sara Ahmed，《酷儿现象学》（2006）

—Sara Ahmed, Queer Phenomenology (2006)

在大湖地区的土著民族和整个阿尼希那比文化中，好奇心的故事经常通过枫糖浆的甜蜜秘密来讲述。根据密西沙加尼什纳比作家 Leanne Betasamosake Simpson 的复述，一个孩子（Binoojiinh）在树林里游荡，收集木柴——折断细枝，掰断粗枝。1我们可以想象他们好奇地观察脚下和头顶上来来往往的东西。苔藓群落，它们将树木和石头分解成未来森林的肥沃土壤。蘑菇，它们从腐烂中汲取生命，与水和风协同工作。老鹰滑翔而过，然后转身捕捉新的水流。还有树冠的茅草，树枝和嫩枝的裸露卷须，叶芽等待绽放。Binoojiinh 在一棵枫树下停下来休息。接下来发生的事情尚不清楚。他们是否抬起头，注意到了能量的流动，看到树皮从上方飘落，听到细小的牙齿啃食树冠的声音？他们是否感觉到树皮下方最细微的震动？或者，也许 Binoojiinh 不需要细致的观察，也不需要不寻常的关注，因为两只互相追逐的松鼠跌跌撞撞地爬上了树干。不管怎样，Binoojiinh 注意到一只松鼠（Ajidamoo）在树枝上蹦蹦跳跳，啃着树皮吸食树液。Binoojiinh 想知道树皮的味道。

Among Indigenous peoples of the Great Lakes region and across Anishinaabe culture, the story of curiosity is often told through the sweet secret of maple syrup. According to Mississauga Nishnaabeg writer Leanne Betasamosake Simpson’s retelling, a child (Binoojiinh) was wandering out in the woods, collecting firewood—snapping skinny branches and cracking thick ones.1 We can imagine them curiously observing the comings and goings of things underfoot and things overhead. Moss colonies, as they break down tree and stone into the fertile earth of future forests. Mushrooms, as they draw life from decay, working in tandem with water and wind. The eagle, as it glides by and then pivots to catch a new current. And the thatch of tree canopy, naked tendrils of bough and twig, with leaf buds waiting to burst. Binoojiinh pauses to rest beneath a maple tree. What happened next is unclear. Did they tilt their head up and notice the flurry of energy, or see a bit of bark waft down from above, or hear tiny teeth gnawing the overstory? Did they feel the smallest of tremors in the bark below? Or perhaps Binoojiinh needed no delicate sense of observation, no unusual practice of attention, because two squirrels chasing each other went blundering by and up the trunk. However it happened, Binoojiinh noticed a squirrel (Ajidamoo) scampering about on a limb, gnawing at the bark to sip the sap. Binoojiinh wondered how bark tastes.

他们用手刮擦树皮，用嘴唇贴近树皮，很快就发现了这一点。Binoojiinh 迅速制作了一个临时的雪松分流器，用桦树皮容器收集树液，然后小心翼翼地将其带回家，将一堆柴火留在树边。回到家后，他们受到了热情的欢迎，并将树液直接加入家庭餐中。当晚罐中的残渣很厚。第二天，Binoojiinh 带着家人和朋友回到树下。榨糖浆成为他们与自己和森林共同承担的任务，他们从不从任何一棵树上榨取太多。因此，知识随着社区实践以及 Binoojiinh 自己对自己与周围世界互动和学习的能力的认识而增长。

Scratching the surface and pressing their lips to the tree, they soon found out. Quickly constructing a makeshift cedar shunt, Binoojiinh collected the sap in a birchbark vessel and then carefully carried it home, leaving their pile of firewood by the tree-side. Reaching their dwelling, they were greeted with excitement and the sap was forthrightly incorporated into the family meal. The residue in the pot that night was thick. The next day, Binoojiinh returned to the tree with family and friends in tow. Syruping became a task they undertook together with themselves and with the forest, never taking too much from any one tree. As such, knowledge grew alongside community practice as well as Binoojiinh’s own sense of their capacities to engage with and learn from the world around them.

在阿尼希那比文化中，孩子们被要求通过发现、使用和庆祝他们自己的内在天赋来参与社区实践和知识建设。是什么给 Binoojiinh 带来了幸福？他们更喜欢独自实验吗？他们用手和嘴、手指和舌头学习效果最好吗？他们在休息时最好奇，还是在手头的任务分散注意力时最好奇？虽然有些孩子更关注脚下或头顶的东西，但 Binoojiinh 是否更关注中间的东西？毕竟，松鼠是一种可以轻松地从草皮移动到树冠的动物。树液在一个季节从根部流向芽，在另一个季节从叶子流向根部。天地的馈赠以及中间的馈赠很重要，每个居住在世界和世界之间的人的馈赠也很重要。正是这些礼物在与其他人类和地球的社区中焕发了生机。请注意，Binoojiinh 与松鼠同步获得的新知识也受到了欢迎。情况可能并非如此。我们可以想象这样一种情况，即某些人重视苔藓和蘑菇、鹰和风的知识，但并不重视松鼠的知识。在这种情况下，松鼠知识受到贬低，被认为不是严肃的知识（太跨学科？太无纪律？）。对他们来说，真正的知识是脚下或头顶的东西，而不是中间的东西。但当然，Binoojiinh 的社区是不同的，他们欢迎任何知识，无论它来自哪里，只要它植根于对 Binoojiinh 自己的天赋和他们所处土地的尊重。

In Anishinaabe culture, children are enjoined to participate in community practice and knowledge building by finding, using, and celebrating their own inner gifts. What brings Binoojiinh bliss? Do they prefer to experiment alone? Do they learn best with their hands and mouth, fingers and tongue? Are they most curious when at rest or distracted from the task at hand? While some children attend more closely to things underfoot or to those overhead, does Binoojiinh attend best to things in between? After all, the squirrel is a creature that moves easily from turf to canopy in a single scurry. And tree sap, too, travels from the roots to the buds in one season and from the leaves to the roots in another. The gifts of earth and sky and those in between matter, as do the gifts of each dweller in and between worlds. And it is these gifts that are brought to life in community with other humans and the earth. Note that Binoojiinh’s newfound knowledge, built in synchrony with the squirrel, moreover, was welcomed. It might have been otherwise. One can imagine a situation in which a particular people prize knowledge of moss and mushroom, eagle and wind, but not squirrel. In this scenario, squirrel knowledge is disparaged, considered to be not serious knowledge (too interdisciplinary? too undisciplined?), so to speak. For them, true knowledge is of things underfoot or overhead, not in between. But of course, Binoojiinh’s community is different, and welcomes whatever the knowledge is and from wherever it has come, as long as it is rooted in respect for Binoojiinh’s own gifts and those of the land in which they find themselves.

正如罗宾·沃尔·金默勒 (Robin Wall Kimmerer) 所说，早在比诺吉因发现之前，土著人民就已经忘记了这些关系好奇心的价值观，这种价值观是通过个人天赋和社区努力与土地的教导相结合来激发的。2在这个传说中的过去，问题不再是谁更适合园艺或狩猎、保护或创新。一切都陷入混乱，因为整个社区都站在枫树下，目瞪口呆，毫无顾忌地喝着甜糖浆。他们不顾树木，不尊重互惠的价值，也不关心平衡，无论是他们自己的营养平衡还是森林的营养平衡。为了纠正这种不平衡，一位精神领袖稀释了枫树，直到只剩下一丝甜味：树液。当我们与辛普森复述的比诺吉因的故事一起阅读时，我们想知道这是否是一个好奇心出错的故事。目瞪口呆：这是一种自私的知识获取方式吗？这是为了创新而创新吗？这是与资本挂钩的好奇心吗？这是关于什么的好奇心，而不是与什么有关的好奇心？这两个故事似乎提出了一个关键问题：如何培育学习环境，这种环境的特点不是大量消费信息的个人（从 iPhone 上大量获取信息或不顾道德地进行研究），而是一个由年轻人和老年人组成的网络，他们在发现新边界的过程中，构建出更加丰富的存在和认知联系网络。

Long before Binoojiinh’s discovery, as Robin Wall Kimmerer tells it, Indigenous peoples forgot these values of relational curiosity, activated via individual gifts and community efforts in concert with the teachings of the land.2 In this fabled past, it was no longer a question of who was better suited to gardening or hunting, safeguarding or innovating. Everything lay in disarray as entire communities parked their bodies beneath the maple trees, mouths agape, drinking the sweet syrup without care or context. They paid no regard to the trees, paid no respect to the value of reciprocity, and paid no mind to balance, whether the balance of their own nourishment or that of the forest. To right that imbalance, a spirit leader diluted the maples until there was only a hint left of their sweetness: sap. When read alongside Simpson’s retelling of Binoojiinh’s story, we wonder if this isn’t a story of curiosity gone wrong. Mouths agape: is this an egoistic form of knowledge acquisition? Is this innovation for innovation’s sake? Is this curiosity hitched to capital? Is this curiosity-about, rather than curiosity-with? The two stories alongside one another seem to pose the critical question of how to foster learning environments that are characterized not by a sea of individuals consuming information (guzzling from their iPhones or researching without regard for ethics) but rather a network of young and old folks who, in discovering new edges, build ever-richer webs of existential and epistemic connection.

在本章中，我们不仅要努力解决使学习成为可能的条件，还要努力解决我们想要实现的学习类型。在 Kimmerer 邀请我们将土著智慧与西方科学“配对”之后，我们在此将 Binoojiinh 的故事、网络科学和其他批判性教学法联系起来，同时牢记土著人重新兴起的主张，即学习必然超越主流教育机构。3我们这样做是基于这样的理解，即土著本体论和网络方法的基础是这种基本见解：在看似随机的事物之下，存在着一种结构——实际上是多种结构——连接。鉴于这些复杂关系系统的现有动态，我们如何才能最好地学习和教育、领导和跟随？为了回答这个问题，我们重新考虑了神经、社会和知识网络的多样性。一种根植于好奇心的好奇心我们认为，在每个学习者的天赋和社会世界中，必然会导致知识网络朝着意想不到的、往往难以控制的方向发展，具有不同的——和反抗性的——架构。在探索将好奇心重新概念化为边缘工作的实际意义时，我们假设学习空间必然会发生变化。而且这种变化不仅是为了任何数量的近端目标，也是为了许多尚未被听到的松鼠——和松鼠知识——的利益。

In this chapter, we grapple not only with the conditions that make learning possible but also with the kind of learning we want to make possible. Following Kimmerer’s invitation to “pair” Indigenous wisdom and Western science, we herein stage certain resonances between Binoojiinh’s story, network science, and other critical pedagogies, all while taking to heart the resurgent Indigenous claim that learning necessarily exceeds mainstream educational institutions.3 We do so with the understanding that fundamental to both Indigenous ontologies and a network approach is this foundational insight: that beneath the seemingly random smattering of things, there lies a structure—indeed multiple structures—of connection. Given the existing dynamics of these complex relational systems, how might we best learn and educate, lead and follow? To answer, we reconsider the diversity of neural, social, and knowledge networks. A curiosity rooted in the gifts and social worlds of each learner, we argue, necessarily results in knowledge networks that grow in unexpected, often unruly directions, with divergent—and defiant—architectures. Exploring the practical implications of reconceptualizing curiosity as edgework, we posit that the space of learning must necessarily change. And this change must come about not merely for any number of proximal goals but also for the sake of the many squirrels—and squirrel knowledges—yet to be heard.

从粒子到图案

From Particles to Patterns

我们如何实践好奇心？我们如何调查、探索和发现？我们如何共同做到？作为人类，我们在自然界和城市中、在实验室和舞池中、在宇宙飞船中和散步中、在抗议和祈祷中追寻我们的问题。然而，在所有促进人类集体好奇心的空间中，最典型的也许是教育场所。在这些空间里，我们聚集在一起纪念和创造知识的轨迹。我们轮流沿着沟壑引领和跟随彼此，纵横交错于已知和未知的事物的世界。然而，正如学术研究和个人证言一再证实的那样，当今的教育机构一直面临着好奇心丧失、惊奇感滞后和发现乐趣缺乏的威胁。4很多时候，顺从和自满、官僚主义限制和平凡的交付成果会损害追求知识所必需的创造自由环境。而且，社会不平等、残疾歧视和学科壁垒常常在学习者、他们的潜力和社区之间筑起一道墙。正是出于这些原因，学习者和教育者都反复问自己：好奇心机构本身可以通过什么途径保持好奇心？我们如何才能想象出不同、更公平的学习方式？这些空间如何与知识者的多样性和关系结构以及知识本身的结缔组织协同工作？

How do we practice curiosity? How do we investigate, explore, and discover? And how do we do it together? As the human species, we pursue our questions in nature and in the city, in the lab and on the dance floor, through spacecrafts and on walks, protesting and in prayer. Of all the spaces that facilitate collective human curiosity, however, perhaps the most paradigmatic are places of education. These are spaces in which we gather to commemorate and to create tracks of knowledge. By turns, we lead and follow one another along the furrows, crisscrossing the world of things known and yet to be known. Nevertheless, as academic studies and personal testimonials repeatedly confirm, educational institutions today are consistently threatened with the loss of curiosity, a lagging of wonder, and a dearth of delight in discovery.4 Too often, compliance and complacency, bureaucratic constraints and mundane deliverables compromise the environments of creative freedom necessary for the pursuit of knowledge. And far too often, social inequalities, ableism, and disciplinary silos build walls between learners, their potentialities, and their communities. It is for these reasons that learners and educators alike repeatedly ask, By what pathways can the very institutions of curiosity remain curious? How can we imagine learning differently, more equitably? How can these spaces work in concert with the diversity and relational fabric of knowers as well as the connective tissue of knowledge itself?

主流教育实践的一个根本问题是，它仍然主要针对单个学生，通过一套固定的课程，以标准思维为目标。我们的命运之星的缺陷在于，它们在当我们从赋予它们意义和功能的星座和星系中抽出双手时，我们就会失去学习环境的复杂性。很多时候，学习环境的复杂性被忽略，取而代之的是标准学生的隐含能力和需求。从历史上看，课堂在很大程度上是同质的，通过隔离女性、有色人种学生和残疾学生而人为地设计。随着当代课堂变得越来越多样化，同质化的幽灵在标准化课程和评估中仍然显而易见。正如社会文化差异经常被边缘化或定型一样，学习差异也经常被忽视或强化。虽然残疾学生被安排到不同的课程中，但即使是以绝大多数方式学习的神经正常学生也会受到主流教学法的不利影响，这些教学法仍然假设大脑网络结构大致同质。因此，有必要在语言、文化遗产、社会行为、智力能力和亲和力的复杂性方面制定灵活的方法，以使课堂成为所有学生都能蓬勃发展的课堂。此外，这样做意味着放弃严格的学科划分和学科孤岛。促进学习者思想和社区以及主题和探究方法之间的生动联系，将孤立的教育转变为深度网络学习。

One of the fundamental problems with mainstream educational practice is that it still largely targets the single student, with a standard mind, through a set curriculum. The fault in our stars is that they fall to dust in our hands when extracted from the constellations and galaxies that lend them meaning and function. Too often, the complexity of the learning environment is lost in favor of the implicitly presumed capacities and needs of the standard student. The classroom has historically been largely homogeneous, artificially crafted through the segregation of women, students of color, and students with disabilities. As contemporary classrooms have become increasingly diverse, the specter of homogeneity remains palpable in standardized curricula and evaluations. Just as sociocultural differences are often either sidelined or stereotyped, so learning differences are often either ignored or reinforced. While students with disabilities are shuttled into different programs, even neurotypical students who learn in a vast majority of ways are disadvantaged by mainstream pedagogies that continue to presume largely homogeneous brain network structures. Developing a flexible approach across the complexities of language, cultural heritage, social behavior, intellectual capacities, and affinities is therefore necessary in order to make the classroom one in which all students can flourish. Doing so, moreover, means forgoing stiff subject divisions and disciplinary silos. The act of facilitating the living connections in learners’ minds and communities, as well as between topics and methods of inquiry, trades an isolated education for deep network learning.

通过突出网络视角，具体应用于大脑结构、社会群体和知识系统，我们可以设想好奇心并非是个人的独立能力，而是各种架构中相互联系的增长原则。虽然好奇心在残障人士的环境中很容易受到限制，但好奇心可以作为一种多元化的实践蓬勃发展，灵活地跨越不同的大脑结构和能力。同样，虽然好奇心在隔离的环境或充满刻板印象威胁的空间中很容易被压制，但好奇心也可以成为跨群体的粘合剂，将人们从原始环境的束缚中解放出来，以欣赏的态度参与差异。理想情况下，学习促进者不会问谁好奇，而是问每个人是如何好奇的？他们探索的风格和询问的语气是什么？这种方法为那些思维不同的人开辟了可能性，让他们真正引领潮流，培养新的观点、尖锐的批评和信号迄今为止，好奇心被误认为是噪音。最后，虽然好奇心可能会屈服于仪式化方法和脆弱区别的破坏，但好奇心在最好的情况下是独立于学科的，在现有学科范围和程序之外发挥作用。因此，欣赏知识网络、社会纽带和神经基础不仅为教育的重新配置提供了前提，而且还重新定义了好奇心是什么，以及如何以更有活力和更公平的方式促进好奇心。5

By foregrounding a network perspective, as specifically applied to brain structures, social groups, and systems of knowledge, we can envision curiosity as precisely not a discrete capacity of individuals but rather as a growth principle for interconnections in and among various architectures. While curiosity is easily curtailed in ableist settings, curiosity can flourish as a pluriform practice flexible across different brain structures and capacities. Likewise, while curiosity is easily squelched in segregated settings or spaces saturated in stereotype threat, curiosity can also serve as a bonding agent across groups, lifting people from the confines of their original contexts to appreciatively engage across difference. Ideally, learning facilitators would ask not who is curious, but how is each person curious? What is the style of their exploration and the timbre of their queries? Such an approach opens up the possibility for people who think differently to, in a real sense, lead the way, cultivating fresh perspectives, trenchant critiques, and signals heretofore mistaken for noise. Finally, while curiosity can succumb to the blight of ritualized methods and brittle distinctions, curiosity at its best is discipline independent, functioning across and through and outside of existing disciplinary purviews and procedures. Thus, appreciating the networks of knowledge, social bonds, and neural substrates not only preconditions a reconfiguration of education but also reframes what curiosity is, and how it can be facilitated in more vibrant and equitable ways.5

因此，本章是一次想象力的实验。它设想让好奇心多样化。它设想让好奇心民主化。它设想让好奇心去纪律化。我们致力于减少社会不平等，软化学院粗略的学科界限，旨在让每个人的好奇心都能自由地追求看似无法比较的想法和应用。我们勾勒出可能性的道路，引领我们走向更具包容性、跨学科的教学法。我们坚信，随着我们对好奇心的理解越来越深入，我们就能更好地支持更加好奇的未来。

This chapter, then, is an experiment in imagination. It imagines diversifying curiosity. It imagines democratizing curiosity. And it imagines de-disciplining curiosity. Committed to reducing the social inequities and softening the coarse disciplinary boundaries that subtend the academy, we aim to facilitate freedom for everyone’s curiosity to pursue seemingly incommensurable ideas and applications. We sketch out the paths of possibility that beckon us into a more inclusive, transdisciplinary pedagogy. And we wager that as we understand curious minds better, we can better support more curious futures.

点线外：关于神经非典型好奇心

Dots Out of Line: On Neuroatypical Curiosity

你的大脑是如何构造的？它的神经网络是如何构成的？哪条神经轨道喜欢在什么情况下与哪条神经轨道发生相互作用？火有多大？哪条神经轨道喜欢跳舞？它们的风格是什么？两个和两个如何交织在一起，一起或飘散？所有这些与学习空间中你旁边的人有何不同或相似之处？一些好奇心看起来像飞翔的松鼠或老鹰，而另一些则像脚下的青苔一样被忽视。但好奇心不必华而不实，甚至不需要强烈。就像苔藓一样，它只需要一点多孔的表面来沉入根状茎，以及最微弱的微风来展开。然而，没有苔藓，松鼠和老鹰的世界就不可能存在。苔藓将酸性物质分泌到石头中，为林地让路。几条裂缝和一点耐心——缓慢的批评和一点惊奇——让位于生命。

How is your brain built? How are its neural networks structured? Which neural tracks prefer to fire with which and in what context? And how big is the fire? Which like to dance and what is their style? How do two and two get interlaced, and hang together or float away? And how is all of this different from or similar to the person next to you in a space of learning? Some curiosities look like scampering squirrels or eagles in flight, while others get overlooked like moss underfoot. But curiosity need not be flashy or even strong. Much like moss, it needs only a bit of porous surface in which to sink its rhizoids and the barest of breezes toward which to unfurl. And yet without moss, the world of squirrel and eagle would be impossible. Secreting acids into stone, moss makes way for woodlands. A few cracks and a light patience—the slow burn of critique and a little wonder—give way to life.

东田直树出生于 1992 年，被诊断患有“重度”和“非语言”自闭症，是数十首诗歌、短篇小说的作者，和非小说类书籍。他在青年时期就读过许多教育机构，包括一所以神经典型为中心的小学、一所特殊需要初中和一所远程教育高中。东田观察到残疾人士迅速脱离正常生活，进入特殊需要圈子（如果幸运的话，则是低薪工作），他想要自己做出选择。在“自我质疑”并确定自己的天赋和希望之后，他决定成为一名作家。6 在学校期间，他对持续的幼稚化和“校长式的教学”越来越感到沮丧，因为这些否定了他的创造力并扼杀了他的好奇心。事实上，科学家和教育家都一再将自闭症患者描述为缺乏任何可衡量的——因此也是有意义的——好奇心。7东田在他的写作和行动主义中抵制这种说法，他一再强调自己的好奇心：“我总是渴望学习”、“渴望知识”，他写道； “我希望长大后能学到一百万种东西！” 8他说，其他自闭症患者在这方面与他非常相似，“不断挑战自己，问自己问题。” 他在一首名为《好奇心》的诗中写道，这并不奇怪，因为好奇心是人类的本能；它“是我们继续前进的原因”。9

Born in 1992 and diagnosed with autism of a “severe” and “nonverbal” type, Naoki Higashida is the author of dozens of poems, short stories, and nonfiction books. He attended a number of educational institutions in the course of his youth, including a neurotypically centered primary school, a special needs junior high, and a distance learning high school. Observing the many ways in which people with disabilities are fast-tracked out of normal life and shuttled into special needs circles (and low-wage jobs, if they are lucky), Higashida wanted to make his own choice. After “questioning things” for himself, and identifying his gifts and hopes, he decided to become a writer.6 While in school, he had become increasingly frustrated with the steady infantilization and “schoolmaster-type instruction” that denied his creativity and squashed his curiosity. Indeed, scientists and educators alike repeatedly characterize people with autism as lacking any measurable—and therefore meaningful—curiosity.7 Resisting this narrative in his writing and activism, Higashida repeatedly asserts his own curiosity: “I’m always hungry to learn,” “hungry for knowledge,” he writes; “I want to grow up learning a million things!”8 Other autistic people, he says, are much like him in this respect, “constantly challenging and asking questions of themselves.” This should be no real surprise, he writes in a poem called “Curiosity,” given that curiosity is fundamentally human; it “is why we carry on.”9

当然，由于东田大脑中的神经结构不同寻常，他的好奇心会以不同的方式发挥作用，并表现出来。对他来说，他与世界的互动具有一定的专注力。时间和空间是模糊的，他的身体和思想内容的边界也是如此。因此，探索呈现出不同的音色，感知扰动也呈现出不同的色调。东田评论说，在向世界问好时，“细节会直接跳出来”，而物体本身则徘徊在背景中；因此，“看到一个东西和知道它是什么之间有着天壤之别”。10了解、认识和参与事物需要在当前体验和一系列信息记忆之间穿梭。然而，东田的记忆并没有存储在精心编排和按时间顺序排列的插槽中。它们是一堆乱七八糟的“点”，四处漂浮着“散弹”。11有时他能耐心地“钓”到正确的那颗星，而有时他却像要去抓一颗“几亿光年外”的星星。他的本领在海里或银河系中跳跃和游动的过程是一种魔力，而文字有助于实现这种魔力。通过键盘交流，东田变成了一只“海豚”，能够在语言的浩瀚海洋中游泳和翻腾，并与同伴们聊天。通过写作，他以热情和耐心编织出他的知识与经验、他自己的思想与他人思想之间的“联系” 。12

Of course, because the neural structures in Higashida’s mind are atypical, his curiosity functions—and manifests itself—differently. For him, there is a certain absorption that characterizes his interaction with the world. Time and space are nebulous, as are the boundaries of his body and the contents of his mind. Exploration therefore takes on a different timbre and perceptual perturbation a different hue. In greeting the world, Higashida remarks, “details jump straight out,” while objects themselves linger in the background; as such, there is “a world of difference between seeing a thing and knowing what it is.”10 Coming to know, to recognize, and to engage with things requires shuttling between the present experience and a series of informative memories. Higashida’s memories, however, are not stored in carefully indexed and chronologically arranged slots. They are a jumble of “dots” that float about “scattershot.”11 Sometimes he can patiently “fish” for the right one, while at other times it’s like reaching for a star hung “hundreds of millions of light-years away.” His facility in jumping in and out of the sea—or in and out of the galaxy—is a bit of magic, and words help make that magic happen. Communicating via keyboard, Higashida is transformed into a “dolphin,” able to swim and flip in the vast ocean of language, and chatter away with his companions. Through writing, he weaves together, with passion as much as patience, the “connections” between his knowledge and his experience, his own mind and that of others.12

如果神经典型记忆（以及所有已学到的东西）的结构更像索引，那么该索引的架构是什么？它的形状是什么，或者反过来说，它如何赋予事物形状？它的褶皱是按照什么逻辑形成的？相比之下，当一个人的知识看起来更像一群鱼或一个星系时会发生什么？圆点和海豚又会怎样？在这种情况下，形状和运动具有完全不同的物理特性。一个人如何走这张图？好奇心移动的步骤是什么，它的路径是如何交织在一起的？首先，东田的作品证明了他自己的好奇心，充满了痴迷和执着、兴趣和迷恋。他声称，他的好奇心按照不同的逻辑呈现不同的形状和功能，而这种逻辑本身就可以很美。其次，他的作品要求神经典型人不要把他和其他自闭症患者视为“王子或替身”，而要以同情的态度对待他们。13他坚持认为，我们的能力和好奇心——我们的未来——是“相互联系”的。14在一个学习的空间——实际上是一个学习的世界里，鱼类好奇心、星形好奇心和索引卡好奇心并存，这看起来会是什么样子？我们如何相互并肩甚至相互接触这个世界？在鱼类和文件系统能够同样蓬勃发展的学习环境中，有哪些标志？

If neurotypical memories—and all the things that have been learned—are structured more like an index, what is the architecture of that index? What is its shape, or conversely, how does it lend shape to what is? By what logic are its folds fashioned? In contrast, what happens when one’s knowledge looks more like a school of fish or a galaxy of stars? And what about dots and dolphins? Shape and movement in this case have an entirely different physics. How does one walk that graph? What are the steps by which curiosity moves and how are its paths interwoven? First and foremost, Higashida’s work testifies to his own curiosity, flush with obsessions and fixations, interests and fascinations. He asserts that his curiosity takes different shapes and functions by a different logic, and that this logic can be beautiful all on its own. His work secondarily enjoins neurotypical people to treat him and other autistic people as “neither a princeling nor a spare part” but rather with compassion.13 Our capacities and curiosities—our futures, he insists—are “connected” with one another.14 What does that look like in a space—indeed a world—of learning, where fish curiosities, star curiosities, and index card curiosities sit side by side? How do we engage the world alongside each other and even with one another? What are the markers of a learning environment in which fish and filing systems can equally flourish?

研究好奇心的学者很少关注神经非典型学习者，更不用说神经非典型好奇心了。然而，关注不同的神经网络恰恰需要这一点。网络方法使我们能够更深入地思考不同好奇心模式的有效性。想象一下，一屋子学生的学习差异各不相同，从阅读障碍和自闭症，到焦虑、抑郁和躁郁症，或者再次从多动症和强迫症开始。倾向一直到加德纳的多元智能。每个学习者都有自己的学习架构。15好奇心特征的范围有多广？16还有很多工作要做，以理解和庆祝好奇心的通常非标准表达方式。17需要新的方法来识别非语言、感官和亲和力兴趣，以尊重那些长期被认为缺乏好奇心的人的好奇心。18在很大程度上被视为零维点的人本身可能就是精通点指挥的人。这样的项目需要一系列新的问题。是什么让某件事对这个人有疑问或对那个人有吸引力？问题是如何以不同的方式提出和表述、产生和形成的？最终，每个人​​寻求什么样的信息，以何种不同的方式，并导致什么样的行动？19好奇心的实践即使在个人内部和跨时间尺度上也是如何变化的？20每个学习者的好奇心风格与他们的神经结构和社会文化环境有何关联？那么这种容量在课程中是如何体现的呢？

Scholars who study curiosity have paid remarkably little attention to neuroatypical learners, let alone neuroatypical curiosity. Attention to diverse neural networks, however, requires precisely this. The network approach equips us to think much more richly about the validity of different modes of curiosity. Consider a room full of students with a range of learning differences, from dyslexia and autism, to anxiety, depression, and bipolar disorder, or again from hyperactivity and obsessive-compulsive tendencies all the way to Gardner’s multiple intelligences. Each learner has their own architectures of learning.15 How wide is that slate of curiosity signatures?16 So much more could be done to understand and celebrate the often nonstandard ways in which curiosity is expressed.17 New means of recognizing nonverbal, sensory, and affinity interests are needed in order to honor the curiosity in people who have long been thought incurious.18 People largely treated as zero-dimensional dots may themselves be masterful dot conductors. Such a project demands a new series of questions. What makes something questionable for this person or intriguing for that one? How are questions differently asked and formulated, generated and shaped? Ultimately, what sorts of information does each seek, in what distinct manners, and resulting in what actions?19 How is the practice of curiosity variable even within the individual and across timescales?20 How is each learner’s style of curiosity correlated with their neural structures and sociocultural environments? And how is that capaciousness reflected in the curriculum?

这类工作必须始于对残障社区和残障研究的基本承诺：残障和神经非典型是身心正常的变异，因此，具有这些变异的人同样是知识领域的好奇心培养者。网络神经科学提供了非常有用的工具，可以阐明各种典型和非典型学习者的神经结构和功能广度。它对注意力、记忆过程、大脑可塑性、个体差异以及遗传和表观遗传因素的研究不仅能够阐明学习器官（即大脑）的架构，还能阐明学习能力本身的架构。21所有这些都让我们能够提出这样的问题：什么促成了新方式的最佳学习以及谁的最佳学习？然而，从残障理论家的角度来看，神经非典型学习者及其适当的教学法并非旨在加入其中，而是要改变所有人的学习过程。22通用设计（最初是一种建筑概念）将多维和多感官的学习机会置于教育的中心，以便为最广泛的思想提供便利。23通用设计明确指出了大脑网络的差异，框架增加了教育途径，无论是用于好奇的表达和参与，还是用于指导和评估。24为每个人而不是大多数人设计，学习者和教育者都可以享受更广泛的知识构建实践，无论是非典型的还是其他的。

Such work necessarily begins with a commitment foundational to disability communities and disability studies: that disability and neuroatypicality are normal variations in bodyminds and that, as such, people with those variations are equally curious cultivators in the field of knowledge. Network neuroscience provides exceptionally useful tools for illuminating the breadth of neural structures and functions across a variety of typical and atypical learners. Its research into attentional capacities, memory processes, brain plasticity, individual differences, and genetic and epigenetic factors has the capacity, moreover, to clarify not only the architecture of the learning organ (i.e., the brain) but also the architectures of learnability itself.21 All of this equips us to ask the question, What makes for optimal learning in new ways and optimal learning for whom? From the vantage point of disability theorists, however, neuroatypical learners and their appropriate pedagogies are not meant to be added to the mix but rather to transform the learning process for all.22 Universal design (originally an architectural concept) puts multidimensional and multisensory learning opportunities at the center of education in order to facilitate access for the broadest swath of minds.23 Expressly citing differences in brain networks, the universal design framework multiplies educative avenues, whether for curious expression and engagement or for instruction and assessment.24 Designing for everyone instead of for most, learners and educators alike can enjoy a greater range of knowledge-building practices, atypical or otherwise.

多样化的好奇心需要扩大公认的好奇心实践和情感的范围。无论学生来自哪个行业，他们都有各种各样的方式在社会和概念空间中移动，并且他们在任何一天的知识网络中都会进行各种各样的行走。他们奔跑、跳跃、跛行、跋涉、轮转和拖拽；有时他们绕圈，有时他们向远处冲去。网络方法可以帮助教育者促进知识的增长，在一个由结构和功能差异的“生物繁荣”所丰富的景观中——整个森林的生态。25

Diversifying curiosity involves enlarging the range of recognized inquisitive practices and affects. From whatever walk of life students hail, there is a vast range of ways in which each moves through social and conceptual space, and a real variety of walks they take on knowledge networks in any given day. They run, skip, and limp, trudge, wheel, and drag; sometimes they circle, other times they strike out yonder. The network approach to curiosity helps educators to facilitate epistemic growth in a landscape enriched by the “biological exuberance” of structural and functional difference—the whole ecology of the forest.25

灵魂力量：边缘的好奇心

Soul Power: On Curiosity at the Margins

在不同的社会网络内部和跨社会网络之间，知识是如何构建的？好奇心是如何实践的？学习的形式是如何随着地理和历史的变化而变化的？文化价值观和习惯是如何嵌入到提问的内容、时间和地点以及如何提出的？就像森林生物群落一样，在森林生物群落中，某些树木、植物和动物在彼此纠缠的网络中兴衰，知识生态系统也各不相同，轮流衰退。有时，大片的知识者和知识被夷为平地，就像砍伐树木一样。在他们之后，一种知识者和一种知识被种植，让人想起树木种植园。然而，知识单一文化会降低增长速度，同时增加对枯萎病、土壤侵蚀和营养物质枯竭的敏感性。相比之下，在知识多元文化中，来自不同社会群体的各种知识者和知识在彼此身边培育，跨群体的增长和恢复力得到增强。如何庆祝不同的知识社区？如何解决知识社区之间的不平等？以及如何培育知识世界之间的交流，以挫败消除性和提取性的认识论，并促进尊重和问责？

How is knowledge built—and how is curiosity practiced—within and across different social networks? How does the shape of learning change across geography and history? How are cultural values and habits embedded in what gets asked, when and where it gets asked, and how? Much like forest biomes, within which certain trees, plants, and animals wax and wane in the tangled web of one another’s company, ecosystems of knowledge differ and decay by turns. Sometimes vast swaths of knowers and knowledges are razed to the ground, much like clear-cuts. In their wake, one sort of knower and one sort of knowledge is planted, reminiscent of tree plantations. Epistemic monocultures, however, reduce growth while increasing susceptibility to blight, soil erosion, and nutrient depletion. By contrast, in epistemic polycultures, where a range of knowers and knowledges from different social groups are cultivated beside one another, growth and resilience across groups is enhanced. How might different knowledge communities be celebrated? How might inequities between knowledge communities be addressed? And how might the traffic between worlds of knowing be cultivated so as to frustrate eliminative and extractive epistemologies, and instead facilitate respect and accountability?

1964 年夏天，自由学校应运而生，这是一项更大规模的免费、解放教育运动的一部分，尤其是针对美国南部的黑人高中生。民权活动家们已经清楚地认识到，教育年轻人，“无论白人还是黑人，富人还是穷人”，对这场运动至关重要。26虽然课程包括基础数学和语言教育，但其主要贡献是一种深刻的存在主义和政治体验。自由学校旨在提供一个诚实、充满活力的环境，让学生可以探究自己和世界的本质，以及他们如何融入其中或与世界疏远。27这与他们一年中其他时间的学习体验形成了鲜明对比。在公立学校，课程反映了白人欧美人的历史和价值观，让非洲侨民陷入沉默。那里只有老师，没有领导者。他们教授的是材料，而不是促进关系。学生们被教导要客观，并通过信息倾倒来处理材料，他们学习的内容是从日常生活中抽象出来的。 “如果人们什么都知道，就是不知道自己的生活，那么他们还算‘受过教育’吗？”一位组织者问道。28在普通学校里，黑人学生通常不会被要求亲自去质疑。如果他们真的试图调查种族政治，他们通常会被停学或开除。每个学生都被教导要以孤立的学习者的身份去学习“事物”，脱离他们的社区，与他们的世界疏远。

In the summer of 1964, the Freedom Schools arose as part of a larger effort to offer free, liberatory education especially to Black high school students in the US South. It had become patently clear to civil rights activists that educating the youth, “whether white or black, rich or poor,” was essential to the movement.26 While the curriculum included basic math and language education, its primary contribution was a deeply existential and political experience. Freedom Schools aimed to provide an honest, vibrant context in which students could ask about the nature of themselves and their world, and how they fit into it or were alienated from it.27 This is in stark contrast to the sort of learning experience they had the rest of the year. In the public schools, the curriculum reflected white Euro-American history and values, leaving the African diaspora submerged in a well of silence. There were teachers rather than leaders. And they taught material instead of facilitating relationships. Taught to be objective and to process material via information dumping, students learned content abstracted from their daily lives. “Are people ‘educated,’” though, “if they know everything except their own lives?” one of the organizers asked.28 In their regular schools, Black students were typically not asked to question things themselves. And if they did try to investigate racial politics, they were often suspended or expelled. Each student was taught to learn “things” as an isolated learner, abstracted from their communities and alienated from their world.

如果说公立学校引导和控制好奇心的方式是为了维护美国的白人至上主义和种族隔离的现状，那么自由学校则以不同的方式促进好奇心。学校重新开启了好奇心，并将其重新引导到所有学生特别是黑人学生的生活现实中，因为政治就存在于存在的现象中。自由学校的推动者和课程一再将“质疑”确定为他们努力的核心——质疑一切，并认真地质疑。提出“真正的问题”，让黑人学生以他们从未有过的方式倾听自己、他人和他们的世界。29组织者承认这项工作很痛苦，但它也是赋权的唯一来源。它是成为社会变革“积极推动者”以及建立种族和阶级联盟的“重要工具”。自由学校的课程本身一半是问题，其“公民教育”的核心几乎全部由问题构成。这些问题涵盖教育、就业、住房、医疗、治安、投票权、刻板印象、恐惧、权力结构和抵抗力量（即真理力量和灵魂力量）等问题，组织者解释说，这些问题不仅仅是问题的集合，而是一个网络，其中每个问题都“源于一个问题”并“引出另一个问题”。通过这个问题网络，可以建立一个活跃而积极的社会网络，一个建立在真正的民主实践之上的网络。30

If public schools channeled and policed curiosity in a way that served to maintain white supremacy in the United States and a segregated status quo, the Freedom Schools facilitated curiosity differently. The schools opened curiosity back up, and redirected it to the lived realities of all students and especially Black students, for it is in the very phenomena of existence that politics dwells. Repeatedly, the Freedom Schools’ facilitators and curriculum identified “questioning” as the heart of their effort—to question everything and to question it earnestly. To ask the “real questions” that invite Black students to listen to themselves, others, and their world in a way that they never have.29 Organizers granted that this work is painful, but it is also the sole source of empowerment. It is “the vital tool” to becoming “active agents” of social change along with building racial and class coalition. The Freedom Schools’ curriculum itself was half questions, with a centerpiece of its “citizenship education” almost entirely constituted by questions. These questions—which covered issues of education, employment, housing, medical care, policing, voting rights, stereotypes, fears, power structures, and powers of resistance (i.e., truth power and soul power)—were not simply a collection of questions, organizers explained, but instead a web in which each question “springs from a question” and “leads on to another question.” Through this web of questions, an activated and activist social network can be built, one founded—for them—on true democratic practice.30

密西西比自由学校提出了几个基本问​​题来指导他们的所有调查。其中两个是最重要的：“主流文化有什么是我们想要的？”和“我们有什么是我们想要保留的？”特别是黑人高中生，他们被反复邀请审视知识网络中社会不平等的影响，然后坚持要求学校适当配备人才，并要求学校认真对待他们自己。但学生们也被反复邀请思考美国南部黑人社区现有的好奇心和知识构建实践。哪些习惯是重要的，需要保留，哪些形式的意义构建对于恢复至关重要？最终，自由学校不仅证明了学校制度化的好奇心可以服务于现状，也证明了抵抗性好奇心的力量，这种好奇心专门在黑人社区、贫困社区和政治边缘建立起来，可以重新想象和重新配置社会世界——或者更确切地说是社会世界。虽然原子化的好奇心可能会巩固公认的知识，但关系型好奇心却迫使促进者和学习者同样批判性地重新设计不同社交网络中建立的知识及其之间的传播路径，并解决长期继承的严重不平等现象。

The Mississippi Freedom Schools posed several fundamental questions to guide all of their inquiries. Among them, two are paramount: “What does the majority culture have that we want?” and “What do we have that we want to keep?” Black high school students, in particular, were repeatedly invited to interrogate the effects of social inequity across knowledge networks, and then to insist, for example, that their schools be stocked appropriately and that they themselves be taken seriously. But students were also repeatedly invited to think about existing practices of curiosity and knowledge building within Black communities of the US South. What habits were important to preserve and what forms of meaning making were critical to recover? Ultimately, the Freedom Schools were a testament not only to the ways in which institutionalized curiosity in schools can serve the status quo but also to the power of resistant curiosity, built specifically in Black communities, in poor communities, and at the political margins, to reimagine and reconfigure the social world—or rather social worlds. While atomized curiosity may solidify accepted knowledge, relational curiosity forces facilitators and learners alike to critically reengineer knowledge built in and across different social networks, and the pathways of travel between them, as well as to address the virulent inequities so long inherited.

这里重要的是谁一起学习以及他们学习什么。哪些社会世界、哪些历史和哪些问题与学习空间密切相关？对于代表性不足的学生来说，在定居者空间、白人空间、健全主义空间、父权制空间和异性恋/顺性别主导的空间中学习显然要付出代价。由于顽固的同质性和顽固的守门人，尤其是在特权阶层中，以及社交网络的中心地位与社会经济地位之间永恒的相关性，边缘化行为者在塑造教育空间和自身未来的能力方面始终受到限制。虽然强大的社交网络与学习成绩高度相关，但来自边缘化群体的学生（包括女性、有色人种学生以及第一代、残疾和/或 LGBTQ 学生）传统上缺乏这些网络。31这种差异化的联系分布损害了学生对自己和世界提出要求的能力。但正如自由学校所证明的那样，虽然必须重新构想教育机构，但它们并不是唯一的希望之源。长期的拒绝历史促进了在非官方场所和未经授权的时间进行的激进学习。追踪这些非法的社会归属和社会探究流不仅阐明了法外学习空间的必要性，而且阐明了其可能性——以及它们的好奇心的力量——从根本上破坏了社会等级制度。32

What matters here is both who learns together and what they learn. What social worlds, what histories, and what queries are germane to the space of learning? For underrepresented students, there is a clear cost to learning in settler spaces, white spaces, ableist spaces, patriarchal spaces, and straight/cisgender-dominated spaces. With obdurate homophily and recalcitrant gatekeepers, especially among the more privileged classes, and the timeless correlation of a social network’s central positions with socioeconomic status, marginalized actors are consistently limited in their ability to shape the educational space as well as their own futures. While robust social networks are highly correlated with learning performance, students from marginalized groups—including women, students of color, as well as first-generation, disabled, and/or LGBTQ students—traditionally lack those networks.31 This differential distribution of connectedness compromises what students can be empowered to ask of themselves and of their world. But as the Freedom Schools attest, while educational institutions must be reimagined, they are not the only source of hope. Long histories of refusal have facilitated radical learning in unofficial venues and at unauthorized times. Tracking these illicit streams of social belonging and social inquiry illuminates not only the necessity but also the possibility of extrajudicial learning spaces—and the power of their curiosity—to fundamentally disrupt social hierarchies.32

好奇心既是社会培养的，也是社会策划的。即使有些学生在独处时最好奇，他们也会在更大的矩阵中提问。如何才能在教育中实现更大的公平？批判教育家认为，习得性好奇心实际上有助于学习环境的同质化。那么，从理论上讲，好奇心作为一种边缘工作——即从根本上讲是一种关系——可能会以知识分歧的承诺和不当行为有效地破坏学习环境。例如，教育家保罗·弗莱雷“拒绝”了教师向普通学生传授标准信息的银行教育模式。相反，他支持一种“社区实践”教学法，对他来说，全球南方学习者在他们的经验空间内一起思考，从而成为“历史的创造者和梦想家”。33民主化好奇心需要重新平衡几个世纪以来使某些知识系统和知识者处于知识生产主导结构的边缘，甚至与知识生产主导结构隔绝的枢纽和辐条。这涉及扩展和重新定位图表，并更认真地创建跨越图表的路径。女权主义作家和活动家贝尔·胡克斯在她对美国学校的性别歧视和反黑人种族主义的思考中，将真正的教育描述为“自由的实践”，学习本身就是一场“革命”。这种学习的基础是重新绘制我们的关系网，以突出“我们对彼此的兴趣，倾听彼此的声音，[和]承认彼此的存在”，跨越性别、种族和民族、阶级、能力和性取向。34它涉及敢于提升来自世界边缘角落和人类经验各个角落的长期探究历史。它涉及在不同探究社区之间培养具体的、实用的倾听习惯。

Curiosity is socially curated as much as it is socially cultivated. Even if some students are most curious in solitude, they query within a larger matrix. What would it take to generate greater equity in education? Critical pedagogues suggest that acquisitional curiosity actually contributes to the homogenization of the learning environment. Theoretically, then, curiosity as edgework—that is, as fundamentally relational—might fruitfully disrupt the learning environment with the promises and improprieties of epistemic divergence. Educator Paulo Freire, for example, “refused” the banking model of education whereby teachers impart standard information to standard students. Instead, he endorsed a pedagogy of “communitarian praxis” whereby, for him, Global South learners think together and from within the space of their experience, and thereby become “makers and dreamers of history.”33 Democratizing curiosity necessitates rebalancing the hubs and spokes that have for centuries kept certain knowledge systems and knowers peripheral to, if not isolated from, reigning structures of knowledge production. It involves extending and reorienting the graph, and more conscientiously creating the pathways across it. Feminist author and activist bell hooks, in her consideration of sexism and anti-Black racism in US schools, characterizes true education as a “practice of freedom,” wherein learning itself is a “revolution.” Such learning is predicated on redrawing the webs of our relationships to foreground “our interest in one another, in hearing one another’s voices, [and] in recognizing one another’s presence,” across gender, race and ethnicity, class, ability, and sexual orientation.34 It involves daring to elevate long histories of inquiry from marginalized corners of the world—and from all the corners of human experience. And it involves developing concrete practical habits of listening between and across different communities of inquiry.

社交网络本质上是共享的，但它们本质上并不公平。在学习社区内外建立健康的社交网络以及与之相关的强大的好奇心网络需要重新配置现有的架构。这涉及新的（有时是非常古老的）学习模式，这些学习模式本身与新的（有时是非常古老的）自我塑造和世界塑造模式相关。35这些在传统教育空间内外的学习模式可能包括讲故事、政治组织、艺术创作、即兴演奏（音乐和机械）、冥想、陆上实践、访问地图绘制等。当社会差异和不平等被突出时，民主教育必然会超越改革师生二元组，深入重新分配探究和好奇心网络。在这一努力中，好奇心的社会性质，即学习者逐渐模仿他们的导师和朋友所塑造的主题和探究方法，不仅仅是事实，而是一项沉重的责任。36

Social networks are inherently shared, but they are not inherently equitable. Developing healthy social networks in and around learning communities, and correlatively robust networks of curiosity, requires reconfiguring existing architectures. This involves new (or sometimes very old) modes of study, which are themselves correlated with new (or sometimes very old) modes of self making and world making.35 These modes of study in and outside traditional educational spaces may include storytelling, political organizing, artistic creation, jamming (music and machinery), meditation, land-based practice, access mapping, and so on. When social differences and inequities are foregrounded, democratic education necessarily moves beyond reforming the teacher-to-student dyad to deeply redistributing networks of inquiry and of inquisitiveness. In this effort, the social nature of curiosity, whereby learners grow to mimic the topics and methods of inquiry modeled by their mentors and friends, is no mere fact but instead a weighty responsibility.36

不存在这样的事：论失去纪律的好奇心

No Such Thing: On Curiosity De-disciplined

课程是如何决定的？科学是如何巩固的？知识经典是如何形成的？认识论话语是如何形成和塑造的？它们是通过什么技术转化的，无论是在受认可的环境中还是其他环境中？人们常常把知识看作是生活在筒仓里，只从这个领域而不是那个领域收获的。但知识是在野外生长的，好奇心的逆流就像菌根网络一样在地下流动，在知识生物和知识系统之间运送思想的食物。绝大多数植物交换资源和通过脚下数英里的丝状菌丝相互交流。真菌使单子森林的任何幻觉都成为谎言。同样，知识企业之间的鲜明区别最终也是愚蠢的。这些相互联系和亲密关系如何浮现在学习空间并改变学习空间？

How does curriculum get decided? How are sciences solidified and canons of knowledge crafted? How are epistemic discourses formed and fashioned? And by what techniques are they transformed, whether in sanctioned settings or otherwise? People often treat knowledge as if it lives in silos, and is harvested only from this field and not that one. But knowledge grows in the wild and the crosscurrents of curiosity run underground like mycorrhizal networks, shuttling food for thought between knowing organisms and knowledge systems. The vast majority of plants exchange resources and communicate with one another through the miles of threadlike hyphae underfoot. Fungi give the lie to any illusion of a monadic forest. So, too, are the stark distinctions between knowledge enterprises ultimately foolish. How might those interconnections and those intimacies surface in and transform the space of learning?

人们一再称赞列奥纳多·达·芬奇是“有史以来最有好奇心的人”之一。37据说，证据就在于他的思维范围之广，从数学、科学技术到艺术、音乐和面相学，无所不包。然而，达·芬奇的与众不同之处不仅在于他兴趣之广，还在于他的兴趣跨越时间。有时他沉浸在眼前复杂的解剖学知识中（例如熊和青蛙），有时他又兴高采烈地设计迄今为止尚无法理解的发明（例如液压泵和直升机）。达·芬奇可以一举把握现在，又一举冲向未来。也许正是出于这个原因，精神分析学家西格蒙德·弗洛伊德将达·芬奇的好奇心描述为“一种非常强烈地发展起来的冲动”。38而且这种好奇心势不可挡。达芬奇每天都会强迫性地记笔记和画草图，他的草稿既一丝不苟，又具有临时性，仿佛好奇心是一位严谨而又多变的缪斯女神。作为文艺复兴时期的典型人物，达芬奇却是一个没有文字的人，令人惊讶的是，他读不懂希腊文，几乎看不懂拉丁文。因此，他是一个自学成才、自发的博学之人，他的好奇心驱使着他，而这种好奇心并没有受到当时对学者敏锐度的期望的约束。

Leonardo da Vinci is repeatedly celebrated as one of “the most curious minds to ever have existed.”37 The proof, it is said, lies in the very range of his mind, moving raucously from math, science, and technology, to art, music, and physiognomy. What is distinctive about da Vinci, however, is not only the breadth of his interests but also the way those interests straddle time. At one moment he is buried in anatomical intricacies right before his eyes (e.g., bears and frogs), while at others he is blithely blueprinting inventions as yet impossible to comprehend (e.g., hydraulic pumps and helicopters). Da Vinci could cradle the now and catapult into the future in a single flourish. It is perhaps for this reason that psychoanalyst Sigmund Freud characterizes da Vinci’s curiosity as “a single impulse very forcibly developed.”38 And it was unstoppable. Da Vinci would go about his days compulsively note taking and sketching, his drafts as meticulously crafted as they were provisional in nature, as if Curiosity were an exacting and yet changeable muse. The paradigmatic Renaissance man, da Vinci was nevertheless a man without letters, being surprisingly unable to read Greek and barely able to pick out Latin. His was therefore a self-taught, self-driven erudition, fueled by a curiosity untamed by the expectations of scholarly acumen of his time.

并非所有人都因这些事情而受到赞扬。跨学科和反学科性——跨越既定知识框架思考的能力——可能会受到严重的贬低，这取决于你是谁以及你的好奇心会将你带到何处。请考虑以下一系列简短的证言。金默勒 (Kimmerer) 是一位土著植物学家。在她第一年的咨询会议上，她谈到了她对紫苑花和黄花紫菀的审美和谐的迷恋；她的大学顾问很快回答说：“那不是科学。那根本不是植物学家所关心的事情。” 39艾莉森卡弗 (Alison Kafer) 是一位残疾理论家。在读研究生期间，她提交了一篇关于当时最前沿的残疾文化方法的论文；她的教授以“学术性不足”为由拒绝了它。40格洛丽亚·安扎尔杜亚 (Gloria Anzaldúa) 是第三波女权主义的代表人物。在攻读比较文学博士学位期间，她立志研究奇卡诺女权主义；她的导师说“奇卡诺文学不是一门正规学科……它不存在”，并建议她坚持“红、白、蓝”学科和认知方式。41谢伊·韦尔奇( Shay Welch) 是一位美洲原住民哲学教授。她申请了国家人文基金会的资助，以支持一个关于土著认识论的项目，并被一位审稿人告知，“美洲原住民哲学根本不存在。土著人民没有创造出任何足够复杂或系统的东西来构成真正的哲学。” 42如今，这些女性是其子领域、领域的基石或新领域的创始人，她们听从了扎根于她们自己和她们的社区的好奇心的召唤，却被告知“不”。值得庆幸的是，他们没有听。

Not everyone is celebrated for such things. Interdisciplinarity and antidisciplinarity—the capacity to think across and beyond established frames of knowledge—can be heavily disparaged depending on who you are and where your curiosity takes you. Consider a brief series of testaments. Kimmerer is an Indigenous botanist. During her first-year advising session, she spoke of her enthrallment with the aesthetic harmony of asters and goldenrod; her college adviser quickly replied, “That is not science. That is not at all the sort of thing with which botanists concern themselves.”39 Alison Kafer is a disability theorist. During graduate school, she proposed a paper on then cutting-edge cultural approaches to disability; her professor rejected it as “insufficiently academic.”40 Gloria Anzaldúa is a third-wave feminist icon.
