During her PhD in comparative literature, she purposed to study Chicana feminism; her adviser said that “Chicana literature was not a legitimate discipline, . . . it didn’t exist,” and recommended she stick with “red, white, and blue” disciplines and ways of knowing.41 Shay Welch is a professor of Native American philosophy. She applied for funding from the National Endowment for the Humanities to support a project on Indigenous epistemologies and was told by a reviewer, “There is no such thing as Native American Philosophy. Native peoples did not produce anything sophisticated or systematic enough to constitute proper Philosophy.”42 Now cornerstones of their subfields, fields, or founders of new fields, these women, following the beck and call of their curiosities, rooted in themselves and their communities, were nevertheless told “no.” Thankfully, they didn’t listen.

虽然在某些情况下，边缘好奇心会受到赞扬，但在其他情况下，它却受到严格的管制。成为这些边缘行者中的一员会是什么感觉？从这么多生命、他们的社区和他们的另类历史中学习会是什么感觉？当好奇心植根于个人天赋和社区参与时，知识将朝着意想不到的方向发展，并呈现出迄今为止无法想象的形状。这种运动可能会因偏见、成见和其他形式的狭隘思想而受阻，也可能因过于纯粹地依赖现有的知识结构而不是可能的架构而受阻。

While curiosity at the edge is celebrated in some contexts, it is starkly policed in others. What is it like to be one of these remolinos, these edge-walkers? What would it be like to learn from these many lives, their communities and their alternative histories? When curiosity is rooted in individual gifts and community engagement, knowledge will move in unexpected directions and take on heretofore-unimaginable shapes. Such movement can be frustrated by bias, prejudice, and other forms of small-mindedness, but also by too pure an attachment to knowledge structures as they are instead of to the architectures that might be.

如果知识是一个通过增加和减少节点、加权和挖空边缘而增长和变化的网络，那么好奇心又是什么呢？当然，好奇心可以在严格限制的环境中发挥作用，只在最受认可的方向上，通过认可的手段和方法构建新知识。43然而，好奇心的救赎承诺在于它的超越性和动态潜力。它从一个中心跳到另一个中心，随机地在网格表面上行走，轻轻地从核心位置跳到边缘。因此，将知识视为网络，特别是应对模块化网络之间认知正义的挑战，需要对好奇心进行去约束。44对我们来说，“对好奇心进行去约束”并不意味着在任何简单意义上对好奇心进行去约束。它并不意味着放弃去学科化并不是对所有方法和规范进行研究，而是在这些方法和规范之内，同时也跨越和超越这些方法和规范，以富有成效的方式重新定位、重新调整，在某些情况下甚至推翻它们。毕竟，新事物正是通过学科内部和边缘的裂缝才能成长起来。从这个意义上说，去学科化带有跨学科、跨学科甚至反学科的回声。与跨学科工作一样，去学科化的好奇心可能会结合离散的概念、理论或方法，以追求相互关联的认知方式，但也会对特定领域的界限进行批判性质疑。45与跨学科工作一样，去学科化的好奇心可能会跨越规范和立场，以重新塑造地形。它可能出于一种错误的“冒险”意识，而这种意识往往是“重燃希望”的特征。46最后，与反学科工作一样，去学科化的好奇心可能与既定的实践没有固定的关系，而是追求非功利主义和解放性探究所必需的灵活性。47无论学术界和教育界如何大声宣称，学科和课程科目是隔离和孤立的，蓬勃发展的知识生态系统必然会涉及更多动态特征和好奇心的贡献。

If knowledge is a network that grows and changes by adding and subtracting nodes, weighting and hollowing out edges, then what is curiosity? Of course, curiosity can function within severely restricted contexts, building new knowledge in only the most sanctioned of directions, via approved means and methods.43 The redemptive promise of curiosity, however, lies in its transgressive and dynamic potential. It leaps from hub to hub, randomly walks the grid surface, and lightly skips from core positions to peripheries. Reckoning with knowledge as a network, and specifically with the challenge of epistemic justice between modular networks, then, entails de-disciplining curiosity.44 For us, “de-disciplining curiosity” does not mean undisciplining curiosity in any simple sense. It does not mean forswearing all methods and canons but rather working within, yet also across and beyond, those methods and canons in ways that productively resituate, reorient, and in some cases undo them. It is, after all, through disciplinary cracks both within and at the edge that new things can grow. In this sense, de-disciplining carries echoes of the interdisciplinary, transdisciplinary, and even antidisciplinary. Like interdisciplinary work, de-disciplined curiosity might combine discrete concepts, theories, or methods so as to pursue interconnected ways of knowing, but also subject field-specific boundaries to critical questioning.45 Like transdisciplinary work, de-disciplined curiosity might crisscross norms and positions so as to recontour the terrain. And it might do so from an errant, “risk-taking” consciousness often characteristic of “rekindlers of hope.”46 Finally, like antidisciplinary work, de-disciplined curiosity might have no settled relation to established practices but instead court the flexibility necessary to nonutilitarian and emancipatory inquiry.47 Insofar as disciplines and curricular subjects are segregated and siloed, however loudly academic and educational spaces claim otherwise, a flourishing ecosystem of knowledge must necessarily engage more dynamic characteristics and contributions of curiosity.

这对教育意味着什么？特别是对充满活力的教育意味着什么？学生和教师在进入课堂或学习小组时，都已经形成并形成了独特的知识网络。这些知识网络是由地缘文化定义的人类子群体所掌握的集体知识形成的，而知识者在某种程度上属于这些子群体。同样，集体知识网络也由跨时间和空间的现存人类知识形成。学生和教师进入学习环境是为了成长为知识者。但他们的知识网络将向哪个方向扩展？他们将发展到尊重哪些不熟悉的知识？由于集体知识体系受到偶然的限制，某些知识者和知识轮流被限制在某些象限中，而被排除在其他象限之外，因此学生和教师的知识网络增长很可能也会出现同样的偏差。塑造我们所有人理解世界的类别的过程不仅建立在社会偏见和历史不平等以及认识论必然性经济的基础上，还建立在学科和学术纯粹主义。48网格上还有大量空间留给局外人理论，留给不时髦的人的不时髦思想，留给那些被排除在学术界之外或被排除在学术界之外的人。49并且还有整个知识世界彼此之间是看不见的。鉴于相关的小世界网络，枢纽之间或跨网格的长链接远不如短的内部链接常见。然而，它们标志着无限的知识情节留在了社交图谱的边缘，如果不是完全未被铭刻的话。积极地去纪律化限制性知识网络将有助于主流教育体验减少以无知的认识论为前提，而更多地参与跨网络的创造力和欣赏行为。

What does this mean for education? And for vibrant education specifically? Students and teachers alike each enter the classroom or study group with unique knowledge networks already formed and fashioned. Those knowledge networks are informed by the collective knowledge held by the geoculturally defined subgroups of humans to which the knower somehow belongs. That collective knowledge network, likewise, is informed by extant human knowledge across time and space. The student and teacher enter the learning environment in order to grow as knowers. But in which direction will their knowledge networks extend? And what unfamiliar knowledges will they grow to honor? Because collective knowledge regimes are subject to contingent constraints, whereby certain knowers and knowledges are, by turns, restricted to certain quadrants and excluded from others, it is more than likely that student and teacher knowledge network growth will skew likewise. The processes that shape the categories by which we all understand the world are not only built on social bias and historical inequities, as well as economies of epistemic necessity, but also on disciplinary and academic purism.48 There is vast space left on the grid for outsider theory, for unfashionable ideas by unfashionable people, those excluded from or excluded within the academy.49 And there are whole worlds of knowledge invisible to one another. Given the relevant small-world networks, the long links between hubs or across grids are far less common than the short, internal ones. Yet they signal the infinite plots of knowledge left to the peripheries of social graphs, if not uninscribed entirely. An active de-disciplining of restrictive knowledge networks would help mainstream educational experiences to be less predicated on epistemologies of ignorance and more engaged in acts of cross-network creativity and appreciation.

因此，为了使好奇心民主化和多样化，知识网络理论坚持要去约束好奇心。这种去约束好奇心的做法绝不是允许人们进行半心半意和肤浅的询问，而是将探究重新纳入模块化世界中对自由的脆弱要求之中。在教育环境中，它不仅将学习重新植根于现实世界的项目和整体教学法中，而且还重新植根于实践社区内部和跨社区，通过这些社区，人们可以提出目前尚不可想象、难以想象的问题。通过这样做，好奇心重新激发了图表的核心和污垢，增强了其间隙中和边缘之外的奥秘。

To democratizing and diversifying curiosity, then, knowledge network theory contributes an insistence on de-disciplining curiosity. Far from a license to make half-hearted and superficial queries, such a de-disciplining of curiosity reinscribes inquiry within the fragile demands of freedom in a modular world. In educational settings, it reroots learning not only in real-world projects and wholistic pedagogy but also within and across communities of practice through which one might ask as yet unthinkable, inconceivable questions. In doing so, curiosity reinvigorates the gut and grime of the graph, enhancing the mysteries that lie in their interstices and just beyond the edge.

从模式到教学法

From Patterns to Pedagogy

那么，我们该如何教学，又该如何学习？当我们适应网络生活的美丽复杂性时，哪些路径和小路会突然出现在我们眼前？即使是这个如此广阔的框架，其固有的对差异和集体如此敏感，其隐含的局限性又是什么？我们认为，在将网络理论应用于大脑结构、社会群体和知识生产系统时，我们更有能力以不同的方式想象好奇心。好奇心远非个体认知者或多或少存在的一种离散能力，而是人与人、神经与社会之间相互联系的一种增长原则。好奇心是知识体系和结构的一部分。因此，好奇心最好是多样化、民主化和去学科化的。因此，网络科学和好奇心哲学为更具包容性、跨学科的教学法铺平了道路。然而，重要的是要认识到，虽然这种教学法允许教育中更大的个性化，但个性化只有通过好奇心的更大集体化才能实现。它首先需要认识到，跨越和交叉知识和待知事物的“我们”代表着各种各样的知者和知晓方式。

How might we then teach and how might we then learn? What pathways and byways suddenly present themselves before our eyes as we attune ourselves to the beautiful complexity of a networked life? And what might be the limitations implicit in even this expansive framework, so inherently sensitized to difference and collectivity? We have argued that, in applying network theory to brain structures, social groups, and systems of knowledge production, we become more equipped to imagine curiosity differently. Far from a discrete capacity more or less present in individual knowers, curiosity is a growth principle for interconnections among people, neural architectures, and bodies of knowledge. As such, curiosity is best diversified, democratized, and de-disciplined. A network science and philosophy of curiosity therefore clears the path for a more inclusive, transdisciplinary pedagogy. It is important to recognize, however, that while such a pedagogy allows for greater individualization in education, that individualization is won only through a greater collectivization of curiosity. It requires first appreciating the ways in which the “we” who cross and crisscross the furrows of knowledge and things to be known represent a vast array of knowers and ways of knowing.

未来，探索网络融合教学法的方法多种多样。在此过程中，重要的是要记住，我们学习的社会、神经和认知网络比以前认识到的更加多样化。但同样重要的是要认识到，这些网络并不是凭空出现的，其目前的形式并不完整。我们所学的和我们所教的，我们的归属和意义网络，从来都不是零点，也从来都不是真正单一的。万事万物都有其网状生长的历史和其网络结构的故事。公认的学习形式和公认的学习者类型都有其历史。讲述社会历史和裁决社会差异的方式都有其历史。而那些被认为对在这个或那个领域接受教育（或实际上接受教育）很重要的事情也有其历史。学习过程的一部分包括认识到所有这些网络都来自某个地方，并将去往某个地方。它们植根于价值观和投资、派系和辩论之中。我们可以从这些历史中学到什么？我们能根据这些历史创造什么样的未来？在当代，教与学就是跳入一场关于探究的斗争场景，探究过去如何做、现在如何做以及未来如何做。我们突然有能力参与其中，提出学习可能是什么样子、如何获取知识以及如何最好地实践好奇心。我们有机会共同重新描绘世界的面貌。

There are a whole host of ways to explore network-infused pedagogies in the future. As we do so, it is important to remember that the social, neural, and epistemic networks in and through which we learn are more diverse than previously acknowledged. But it is equally important to recognize that those networks did not just appear on the scene fully baked in their present formations. What we learn and what we teach, our networks of belonging and sense making, are never ground zero, nor are they ever truly singular. Everything has a history to its reticular growth and a story to its network structure. The recognized forms of learning and recognized types of learners have a history. The ways in which social histories get told and social differences get adjudicated have a history. And the things deemed important to know in order to be educated in this or that field—or indeed to be educated at all—have a history. Part of the learning process involves appreciating that all of these networks come from someplace and are going somewhere. They are embedded in values and investments, factions and debates. What can we learn from those histories and what futures can we create in light of them? To teach and to learn in our contemporary moment is to leap onto a scene of struggle over inquiry, how it has been done, is done, and might yet be done. And it is to suddenly have in our hands the capacity to enter the fray and propose what learning might look like, how knowledge might be acquired, and how curiosity might best be practiced. We get the chance to redraw the shape of our worlds together.

学校和大学有责任培养对网络的批判意识，这些网络为我们和我们的后代提出了什么样的问题学生在教育环境中会问和不会问。作为好奇心的实践者，我们和我们的学生同样有责任让我们的机构对这种批判意识负责。但这些地方并没有耗尽学习的空间。我们可能认为老鹰只会在头顶飞翔，但它们栖息在树上和悬崖上，在开阔的田野和湖泊之间俯冲，在全球潮流中飘荡。学习也很难局限于机构。正如辛普森和金默勒所坚持的那样，整个世界都需要参与。而这正是土著思想从根本上比我们在这里提供的网络方法更深刻的地方。土著复兴的基础不仅是土地权，而且是与土地和土地网络的关系。50仅仅参考人类大脑网络、人类社交网络和人类知识网络来重新想象好奇心，就是没有意识到好奇心在其中流通的超越人类的世界。土著思想深深地挑战了主流教育系统，要求它们考虑对其功能至关重要的环境异化和成本。它强调要向周围世界的智慧学习。这一号召使我们更加迫切地认识到，我们的问题总是来自某个地方，并产生某种作用。作为调查者和学习者，我们越清楚好奇心的谁、什么、在哪里和为什么，我们就越能欣赏我们复杂的历史，参与我们与地球息息相关的现在，并创造联合的未来。

Schools and universities have a responsibility to cultivate a critical awareness of the networks that inform what kinds of questions we and our students do and do not ask in the educational setting. As practitioners of curiosity, we and our students likewise have a responsibility to hold our institutions accountable to that critical awareness. But these places do not exhaust the spaces of learning. We might think of eagles as only ever flying overhead, but they rest on trees and cliff faces, dive between open fields and lakes, and waft on global currents. Learning, too, can hardly be confined to institutions. As Simpson and Kimmerer insist, there is a whole world to be engaged. And this is where Indigenous thought is fundamentally still deeper than the network approach we have offered here. Basic to Indigenous resurgence is not only a right to land but a relationship with land and the networks of that land.50 To reimagine curiosity only with reference to human brain networks, human social networks, and human knowledge networks is to fail to appreciate the more-than-human world in which curiosity circulates. Indigenous thought deeply challenges mainstream educational systems to account for the environmental alienations and costs that are basic to their function. And it insists on an apprenticeship to the wisdoms of the world around us. This call lends a greater urgency to the recognition that our questions are always coming from somewhere and doing something. The clearer we get about the who, what, where, and why of curiosity, as investigators and learners alike, the better we can appreciate our complicated histories, engage our earth-bound presents, and craft coalitional futures.

* * *

* * *

让我们回到松鼠的话题上。根据许多人的说法，松鼠似乎体现了好奇心的所有最坏倾向。松鼠似乎反复无常，它们的双关节脚跟助长了这种行为。它们喋喋不休的叫声为它们赢得了神话中一流的麻烦制造者的名声。它们似乎不可靠，在脚下和头顶的世界之间来回穿梭，甚至有传言说它们曾吞食过太阳一两次。它们当然会吸食树液，但更多的时候，它们会吃它们储藏的坚果和种子，这些坚果和种子是它们在冬季前几个月里不懈地积累起来的。但我们怀疑这是否完全不像是获取。对于松鼠来说，它们的记忆库是一个围绕着森林的仓库，一直延伸到峡谷和起伏的山丘。每一点营养都被种植（而不是储存在干燥的地窖或私人阁楼中）。种植的方式是，有一天它会滋养松鼠或其他生物，或者——次数不少——它会发芽开花。松鼠就像园丁和生态学家一样，收集和种植，为仍然无法想象的其他地方和其他时间建立一个可能性的关系网络。它张开双手拥抱自己的发现。无论教育的未来如何，也许这种生物可以教会我们更多关于好奇心的知识。

But back to squirrels. By many accounts, squirrels seem to embody all of curiosity’s worst tendencies. Squirrels seem erratic, aided and abetted by their double-jointed heels. And their constant chatter has earned them the mythological reputation of first-class troublemakers. They appear unreliable, catapulting between worlds underfoot and overhead (there and back again), and they are even fabled to have swallowed the sun once or twice. They sip the sap, sure, but more often they eat from their cache of nuts and seeds, which they have accumulated relentlessly in the prewinter months. But we wonder if this isn’t much like acquisition at all. For squirrels, theirs is a storehouse of memories, edging around their forests, down into ravines, and round rolling hills. Every bit of nutrition is planted (not stockpiled in an arid cellar or private attic). Planted in such a way that someday it will nourish a squirrel or some other creature, or—a not insignificant number of times—it will germinate and flower. Something of a gardener and ecologist, the squirrel gathers and plants, gathers and plants, building a relational network of possibilities for a still-unimaginable elsewhere and elsewhen. It holds its discoveries with an open hand. Whatever the future of education might be, perhaps this creature can teach us still more about curiosity.

结论：关于好奇的未来

Conclusion: On Curious Futures

当我们思考好奇的未来，思考好奇的活力和变化的更大自由的未来时，我们不仅思考可以建造什么，还思考这些建筑中的裂缝。裂缝诞生于过去。裂缝今天才打开。裂缝仍在等待未来。好奇的生活需要自由，以打破继承的界限，甚至打破自我和社会的新线索，以及以各种方式束缚我们的轨迹。好奇的生活带来了一种解开编织的勇气，一种耐心的解开方式，以及一种渴望去除巨石的树脂，露出裂缝，削弱石头的渴望。好奇的生活怀有一种坚韧不拔的精神，去未知和看不见，去重新审视和解决问题，去在没有的地方打一个洞，去想象通过裂缝进入外面和超越的东西。最灵活的形成方式是自由地形成、书写、擦除和重写、剪切和粘贴、铆接和铆接。“织网然后吃掉它——一天三次，”我们的八足朋友明智地建议道。

When we think of curious futures, futures of greater freedom for the vivacity and variability of curiosity, we think not only about what can be built but also about the cracks in those edifices. Cracks birthed in the past. Cracks just opening today. Cracks still waiting to inhabit the future. Curious lives need freedom to break from lines inherited, even from fresh threads of self and society, and from trails that bind us in any number of ways. Curious lives bring with them a bravery to unweave that which is woven, a patient mode of undoing, and a hankering to de-resin the monolith, reveal the fissures, and weaken the stone. Curious lives harbor a tenacity to unknow and unsee, to reexamine and problematize, to make a hole where there wasn’t one before, and to imagine through a crack into that which is outside of and beyond. The most flexible mode of formation is one that freely unforms, writes and erases and rewrites, cuts and pastes, rivets and rives. “Build a web and then eat it—three times a day,” wisely advises our eight-legged friend.

奇怪的破解

Curiously Cracking

好奇心是一种填补信息空白的驱动力，这已经成为一种真理。我们提出，好奇心是一种边缘工作。它是在寻求了解事物的过程中建立事物之间的联系和关系的过程。边缘跨越事物之间的间隙不是为了填补它们，而是为了穿越空间，侦察形状苏格拉底是一位典型的好奇心强的人，他总是用问题纠缠人们，不断追问，直到人们发现一个基本事实：他们对自己以为自己知道的事情一无所知。从某种意义上说，苏格拉底的好奇心是那种破裂的好奇心。他希望我们有点失去理智。他的好奇心非但没有填补信息空白，反而让空白越来越大，仿佛一个洞穴突然从我们脚下的地面裂开。虽然我们在整本书中都关注好奇心的构建工作，但我们以对裂缝的思考作为结束，以便突出好奇心同样起作用的破坏和未知的力量。裂缝使边缘工作得以发挥作用；它们给它一些事情做。那么，如果好奇心要有一个健全而充满活力的未来，它就必须破裂。

It has become something of a truism that curiosity is a drive to fill information gaps. We have proposed instead that curiosity is edgework. It is a process of building connections and relations between things in the quest of coming to know them. Edges cross gaps between things not in order to fill them but in order to traverse the space, to reconnoiter the shapes of solid things and draw new lines. Socrates, a paradigmatically curious fellow, is remembered for pestering people with questions, relentlessly pressing them until they discover one fundamental fact: they are ignorant of the thing they thought they knew. In a sense, Socrates’s curiosity was the cracking kind. He hoped we would lose our heads a bit. Rather than filling information gaps, his curiosity made the gap grow ever wider, as if a cavern suddenly yawned from the ground beneath our feet. While we have focused throughout this book on curiosity’s building work, we close with this musing on cracks in order to bring to the fore the forces of unbuilding and unknowing that are equally at work in curiosity. Cracks allow edgework to work; they give it something to do. If, then, curiosity is to have a sound and vibrant future, it must crack.

大约一千年前， “crack”这个词首次出现在古英语中。几百年来，它一直以动词的形式存在。在动词的一生中，它经历了许多奇妙的冒险，从诗人的笔下跳到市民的哼哼声中。它比任何东西都更能标记声音。声音当然是波浪式的，但破裂的声音就像波浪冲进裂缝或翻过悬崖。Crack！破裂的爆炸声。破裂声可以大，也可以小（有点噼啪声）。天空和大地因暴风雨而破裂，或者暴风雨从深处而来。但也有清晨老骨头或壁炉里新木头的声音。一两个不羁的伙伴一会儿在开玩笑，一会儿在对方头上敲打蜂蜜酒瓶，这并不罕见。三四百年后，“ crack”这个词被重新编码，现在是一个名词。它变成了发出爆炸声的破裂声，而不是爆炸本身。不管有没有人听过，它都是断裂或裂痕形成的。而且它从来没有发出任何声音，就像门下无声的裂缝，空气悄悄地从中溜过，旋转，飘荡，没有紧迫感，也没有真正的开始。裂缝就像悬崖上的裂痕，可能是由于突然断裂或经过几个世纪的磨损造成的。它是一种不健全的东西，也许没有声音来讲述这个故事。基础排除了某种好奇心，而裂缝使好奇心成为可能。或者也许是好奇心使事物破裂。问题的裂缝发出声音并回响某些力量长期主宰着精心设计的沉默，怀疑被压制，疑问迅速被扼杀。好奇心涌入裂缝。好奇的心灵以最美丽、最生动的方式破裂。他们不惧怕思想和情感的破裂，也不回避理智和忠诚的破裂。他们耐心而又热切地等待着它们，就像人们等待春天新发现的热情一样。事实上，好奇的未来充满了我们自己、我们的世界和我们的地平线上这些丰富的裂缝，我们可以通过首先观察自然界来学习如何驾驭这些裂缝，在那里，永久的、诱导的或自愿的裂缝为生命的循环提供了动力。就像省略号一样，裂缝是“从可见走向不可见的出口点”。1好奇心通过耐心而准确地使更多的事情变得不可能，使更多的事情成为可能。通过打破它们并将它们打开。

The word crack first appeared on the scene in Old English about one thousand years ago. It lived for several hundred years exclusively as a verb. In its verb life, it had many amazing adventures, leaping from poet’s pen to Bürgermeister’s harrumph. It marked, more than anything, sound. Sound, of course, moves in waves, but the sound of cracking moves like waves toppling into a cleft or over a cliff. Crack! The blast of a break. Cracking can come in big ways and small (a bit of crackling). There are the cracks of sky and earth from a storm overhead or from deep within. But there is also the sound of old bones in the morning or of young wood on the hearth. And it is not uncommon for the rogue companion or two to find themselves cracking jokes one moment and cracking bottles of mead over each other’s heads the next. Three or four hundred years later, the word crack was recodified, now as a noun. It became the break that sounded the blast rather than the blast itself. It was the fracture—or fissure—that formed, whether anyone ever heard it or no. And it was the crack that never even had a sound, like the silent crack beneath a door through which air slips quietly, eddying, wafting, with little urgency and no real beginning. A crack, then, much like a cleft in a cliff face, may be from a sharp break or worn away over centuries. It is a certain unsoundness of a thing, with, perhaps, no sound to tell the tale. Fundaments foreclose a certain kind of curiosity, whereas cracks make curiosity possible. Or perhaps it is curiosity that cracks things up. The crack of a question sounds and resounds where certain forces have long presided over a crafted silence, where doubts have been muffled and queries quickly suffocated. Curiosity surges into the break. And curious minds are cracked in the most beautiful and vibrant of ways. They do not fear fractures of mind and of feeling, nor do they avoid ruptures of sense and of fealty. They wait for them, patiently and yet eagerly, as one waits for the newfound fervor of spring. Indeed, curious futures are filled with these fecund cracks in ourselves, in our world, and on our horizon, and we can learn to navigate these cracks by looking first to the natural world, where permanent, induced, or volunteered fissures fuel the circle of life. Much like an ellipsis, a crack is “a point of exit, from the visible toward the invisible.”1 Curiosity makes more things possible by making more things, patiently and precisely, impossible. By breaking with them and cracking them open.

* * *

* * *

“那就让我们开始破解吧！”我们说，然后开始一起做我们最喜欢的事情。我们首先打开了“好奇心”的字典，找到了以下条目：

“Here’s to cracking, then!” we say, as we settle down to a day spent together doing our favorite things. We begin by cracking open Curiosity’s dictionary and we find the following entry:

（vb.）破裂（永久地）；裂开，断裂；内部从外部脱离。

(vb.) to crack (permanently); to split apart, to fracture; when that within breaks free of that without.

当材料在其下方、内部或后方必须穿过、超出或超越它们时，各种表面都会出现物理断裂。在一瞬间，表面变得粗糙，固体被撕裂。材料边界的突破就像是冒险穿越虚空，随之而来的是新的生命、平衡和自由。当胚根或胚根从种皮中慢慢突破充满水的囊壳时，它呈现出纯白色和半透明绿色色调，新生命就存在于胚根中。当熔岩在火山爆发中冲破地壳时，它呈现出炽热的光辉，平衡就存在于熔岩中。当卵齿以输送氧气的种子刺穿小鸡壳时，它呈现出柔和的粉红色、浅灰色和灰黄色，自由就存在于卵齿中。这些裂缝是确定的；如果经过无限长的时间，表面可能仍未重新形成。种皮、蛋壳和地幔并不用抗衰老的针线缝补，认真地掸去身上的灰尘，抬起充满希望的脸，重新焕发光彩。不。永久的自由穿着完全不同的服装：一根线舀出三磷酸腺苷的储存器，释放出数百万吨的热能，并让胚胎身体旋转数天。

Physical ruptures appear in all kinds of surfaces when the materials under, within, or behind them must pass through, without, or beyond them. In the work of a moment, the surface is roughened and the solid is riven. The transgression of the material’s boundary feels much like an adventurous traipsing across the void, and with it comes new life, balance, and liberty. New life in the clear-white and translucent-green tones of the embryonic root, or radicle, as it emerges from the seed coat in a slow breach of the water-laden capsule. Balance in the fiery brilliance of molten rock as it breaks through the earth’s crust in a volcanic explosion. Liberty in the gentle pinks, soft grays, and dusty yellows of the egg tooth as it pierces through the chick’s shell in an oxygen-delivering pip. These sorts of cracks are definitive; should an infinitely long period of time elapse, the surface may still not have reformed. Seed coats, egg shells, and earth mantle do not primly mend with age-defying stitching, conscientiously brushing themselves off and lifting up their hopeful faces to shine anew. No. Permanent freedom dresses in an altogether different fashion: a thread that ladles reservoirs of adenosine triphosphate, releases megatons of thermal energy, and gyrates an embryonic body for days.

裂缝引导运动并增加熵。好奇心的裂缝让隐藏的得以展翅飞翔，让未经思考的得以熔岩般的流动，让埋藏的得以在营养丰富的土壤中生根。生根的根茎。激进的概念。思想被连根拔起、重新扎根，从根部改变为激进的思想。好奇的头脑和幼苗的第一次成熟非常相似，这是一个谜一样的相似之处。正如博物学家查尔斯·达尔文在《植物的运动力量》中所写，“毫不夸张地说，这样赋予的根茎尖端……就像大脑一样……大脑位于身体前端，从感觉器官接收印象，并指挥各种运动。” 2胚根低下头，躲在草皮深处安全的黑暗与匿名之中，肆意地将白色强健的手臂伸进浅表的泥土中，将绿色的叶状腿伸向空中。然后它们行走。行走在空中。行走在天空。行走在太阳的上方。它们沿着一条绕圈的小径行走，思考着——思考着从这个角度、从那个距离、从上面、下面和旁边看世界是什么样子。它们的吸收是叠覆的管道；胚根第一次从浸湿的种皮上的裂缝中窥视，这是奇妙行走的先决条件，通过这种行走，区别的边缘重叠，感知层形成，实现网络增长。下次下雨时，我们必须在天空下停下来，浸湿我们的羊毛大衣。然后我们倒立着，迈开双腿跨过云层。

Cracks conduct movement and advance entropy. The crack of curiosity allows the hidden to fly with hatchling wings, the unthought to effuse in a lavalike flow, and the buried to root through nutrient-rich soil. A rooting radicle. A radical conception. A thought uprooted, rerooted, changed from the root as radicalized. A riddled similarity, the curious mind and the first fruition of the seedling are notably alike. As naturalist Charles Darwin penned in his The Power of Movement in Plants, “It is hardly an exaggeration to say that the tip of the radicle thus endowed . . . acts like the brain . . . ; the brain being situated within the anterior end of the body, receiving impressions from the sense-organs, and directing the several movements.”2 Tucking their head down in the safe darkness and anonymity deep beneath the turf, the radicle riotously flings their white sinewy arms into the superficial dirt and spreads their green leafy legs into the air. And then they walk. Walk the air. Walk the sky. Walk over the face of the sun. They walk a circumnutating trail and think—think about how the world looks from this angle, from that distance, from above, beneath, and aside. Their imbibition is a conduit for imbrication; the crack in the soaked seed coat from which the radicle first peers is the prerequisite for the curious walk by which edges of distinction overlap, layers of perception form, and networks of realization grow. When next it rains, we must pause beneath the sky to soak our woolen coats. Then we will stand on our heads and step our legs across the clouds.

* * *

* * *

我们继续读下去，当纸张轻轻地沿着“好奇号”词典中的“C”条目列向下移动时，我们相同的右手食指感受到纸张的光滑度：

We read on, our identical right pointer fingers feeling the smoothness of the paper as it gently moves down the column of “C” entries in Curiosity’s dictionary:

（动词动词）被破解（引起）；被打开，如前门、分子孔、私人壁橱或记忆盒。

(vb.) to be cracked (induced); to be opened, as in a front door, a molecular pore, a privy closet, or a memory box.

任何铰链都是潜在性的裂缝，是将两个相邻部分彼此分开的机会，是找到分界线并撬开的机会。与破裂、断裂和爆炸的永久性不同，这些裂缝是要诱导然后重新诱导的；我们打开一扇窗户，感受春风的轻柔，然后我们再次打开它，闻到雪的清脆声、雨的柔和空气或花粉的傻傻嬉戏。季节性铰链。就像旋转的曲柄手柄打开然后关闭窗格一样，天体的旋转打开然后关闭天体铰链，让太阳的光线从月亮上反射回来，照亮我们的夜晚。满月时，裂缝是打开的；新月时，裂缝是关闭的。月亮落下时，昏昏欲睡的叶子围绕着它的细胞铰链叶枕旋转，从与其他叶子的安静交流转变为对空气的充满活力的探索，伸展开来。就像孩子一样，它每天早晨提醒我们它的独立性。在白天，裂缝是打开的；在月光下，裂缝是关闭的。在日日夜夜、月月月月和季节月月中，我们有机会好奇地打开或吱吱作响地关闭生命的铰链部分。

Any hinge is a crack in potentiality, an opportunity to separate two abutting bits from one another, a chance to find the line of demarcation and pry apart. Unlike the permanence of rupture, fracture, and explosion, these cracks are meant to be induced and then reinduced; we crack a window to feel the light spring breeze, and then we crack it again to smell the crisp note of snow, the soft air of rain, or the silly frolic of pollen. A seasonal hinge. As the rotating crank handle drives open and then closed the panes, so the spinning of the heavenly bodies drives open and then closed a celestial hinge, permitting the sun’s rays to ricochet off the moon, brightening our night. At the full moon, the crack is open; at the new moon, the crack is closed. As the moon sets, the sleepy leaf pivots on its cellular hinge, the pulvinus, turning from its quiet communion with others to a vibrant exploration of the air, stretching out and away. Like a child, it reminds us of its independence each morning. In the daylight, the crack is open; in the moonlight, the crack is closed. Through days, months, and seasons, we have the opportunity to curiously crack open or creak shut the hinged parts of life.

翻开树叶，我们闻到微风的气息、阳光的照耀，以及一片树叶的广阔视野。透过树叶张开的角，我们可以看到被遗忘的、有用的、珍贵的，或者未来可能成为珍贵的东西。这些是我们用来安装铰链或盖上盖子的材料。我们从我们内心、周围和我们之间的自然史中抓住并收集。在《卡勒瓦拉》中，我们从寒冷中学习符文，从风中学习歌唱，这是一部由语言学家埃利亚斯·伦罗特于 19 世纪编纂的史诗，改编自卡累利阿和芬兰的口头传统。我们把“树木创造的句子”卷成捆，绑在雪橇上。收集完毕后，我们就回家。我们打开行李，把它们绑在椽子上，挂在门框上，搭在裸露的横梁上。我们想知道有些句子是否会掉到地上，或者会沿着地毯飘出前门。我们想知道句子是像阳光一样透明，还是像尘埃流一样半透明，它们看起来或感觉起来是否像披着我们裸露肩膀的柳枝。挂起来后，我们把它们放在“盒子 / 盒子里衬着闪闪发光的铜。” 3它们就在那里，安全地免受风吹雨淋，隐藏在眼睛之外，珍藏在脑海中。直到某一刻，某一天，一个月，一个季节，当我们忘记了自己，或者当我们希望重新学习时，我们打开了旧箱子的雕花盖子。我们闻到树木的香味：外面是箱子的谷物，里面是文字的木质。房间里的灯光落入铜衬的黑暗中。句子像叶子一样伸展开来。

By cracking open, we perceive the scent of the breeze, the light of the sun, and the wide vista of an open leaf. By peering through the open angle, we see the forgotten, the useful, the treasured, or those that might become so in the future. These are the materials about which we fix a hinge or place a lid. We grasp and we gather, from the annals of nature in, around, and among us. In the Kalevala, an epic poem compiled by philologist Elias Lönnrot in the nineteenth century from Karelian and Finnish oral tradition, we learn runes from the cold and songs from the wind. We take the “sentences the trees created,” roll them together into bundles, and fasten them onto our sledges. When we have finished gathering, we head for home. There we unpack, tying them to the rafters, hanging them from the door frames, draping them over the exposed beams. We wonder whether some sentences reach the floor, or traipse along the rug and out the front door. We wonder whether sentences are transparent like sunbeams or translucent like dust streams, and whether they look or feel like willow branches cloaking our bare shoulders. After they’ve hung, we lay “them in the chest of boxes / Boxes lined with shining copper.”3 There they stay, safely protected from the elements, hidden from the eyes, treasured in the mind. Until one moment, one day, one month, one season, when we have forgotten ourselves, or perhaps when we are hopeful to learn anew, we crack open the carved lid of the old trunk. We smell the scent of the trees: the grains of the chest without, the woodiness of the words within. The light of the room falls into the copper-lined darkness. The sentences stretch and open like leaves.

* * *

* * *

我们合上字典，看着句子卷起来。我们再次打开它，看着句子舒展和伸展。我们合上又打开，合上又打开，再合上又打开 ……一遍又一遍，注意着句子运动的特殊性。然后，我们终于读了下去：

We close the dictionary, watching the sentences curl up. We open it again, watching the sentences unwind and stretch. We close and open, close and open, again . . . and again, noting the peculiarity of the sentences’ movements. And then, eventually, we read on:

（动词动词）破裂（自愿）；1. 发出破裂的声音，如冰川崩裂的表面，或（更谦虚地说）一碗脆米，或（更诚实地说）纸张被揉皱；每个声音都发出自己的破裂声。2. 有目的地打开，如下巴打开关节，手指打开关节，手打开手掌，或腿打开膝盖。

(vb.) to be cracking (voluntarily); 1. to be sounding an opening, as the calving face of a glacier, or (more humbly) a bowl of Rice Krispies, or (more honestly) paper being crumpled; each voice calls out its own cracking. 2. to be doing the opening, purposefully, as a jaw at the joint, a finger at the knuckle, a hand at the palm, or a leg at the knee.

虽然有些裂开是永久性的或被诱发的，但这种裂开是重复的和有意识的。在过去、现在和未来，裂开是一种生活方式，一种存在方式。通过选择好奇地裂开，我们打开了思想，移动了身体，并启动了感官。对于捕蝇草和座头鲸来说，它们的选择是张开嘴，等待猎物，然后闭上嘴，享受它。对于昆虫和扇贝来说，它们的选择是按下翅膀或铰链处的阀门，驱使动物在空中或水中寻找食物或安全。对于兔子的耳朵和人类的眼睛来说，它们的选择是弯下腰去接受声音或光线、动作或生物、事件或古玩。没错，是耳朵和眼睛。但真的是那双眼睛！扇贝的外套膜上排列着数百只蓝眼睛。每只眼睛都位于自己可伸缩的触手上，并包含由数百万块方形瓷砖组成的水晶镜；每个伸缩装置都完美地反射蓝光的每个光子。眼睛是镜子的裂缝，也是通风的裂缝。眼睛是通向世界的一道缝隙，也是通向灵魂的一道缝隙；它是一扇探索之门，一个可逆的视野：在眼睑边缘，它们的空间和我们的地球交汇在一起，形成一团乱糟糟的纠结。当我们向内看时，我们会看到什么？我们偷看、窥视、四处打探。当我们注视时，我们会因为爱管闲事而脸红。这是一个喧闹的地方。文字在这里生存，“多样而奇特，就像人类一样，四处游荡，坠入爱河，交配”，弗吉尼亚·伍尔夫写道。

While some cracking is permanent or induced, this type of cracking is repeated and volitional. Across the past, the present, and the future, cracking is a way of life, a manner of being. By choosing to crack curiously, we open the mind, move the body, and prime the senses. For the Venus flytrap and the humpback whale, the choice is to crack open the mouth, wait for prey, clap shut, and enjoy. For insects and scallops, the choice is to press the wings or valves at the hinge to drive the animal through the air or water, whether in search of food or safety. For the rabbit’s ear and the human’s eye, the choice is to bend toward and be receptive to a sound or light, a movement or being, an event or curio. Ears and eyes, yes. But really those eyes! The hundreds of blue eyes lining a scallop’s mantle. Each sits atop its own extendable tentacle and contains crystal mirrors composed of millions of square tiles; each telescoping to perfectly reflect every photon of blue light. Eyes are cracks that mirror and they are cracks that vent. The eye is a crack forward into the world, but also backward into the soul; it is a gate of inquiry, an invertible vision: the horizon where the space of them and the earth of us meet in an unruly tangle along the line of the lid. What do we see when we crack our eyes inward? We peak in, peep on, and snoop about. While eyeing, we blush for nosying. It’s a raucous place. Words live here, “variously and strangely, much as human beings live, by ranging hither and thither, by falling in love, and mating together,” writes Virginia Woolf.

他们似乎喜欢人们在使用之前先思考和感受，但思考和感受的对象不是他们，而是其他东西。……他们讨厌有用；他们讨厌赚钱；他们讨厌在公共场合被说教。简而言之，他们讨厌任何给他们打上一种含义或将他们限制在一种态度上的东西，因为改变是他们的天性。……当语言被束缚时，它们就会收起翅膀死去。

They seem to like people to think and to feel before they use them, but to think and to feel not about them, but about something different. . . . They hate being useful; they hate making money; they hate being lectured about in public. In short, they hate anything that stamps them with one meaning or confines them to one attitude, for it is their nature to change. . . . When words are pinned down they fold their wings and die.

当我们审视内心时，我们看到的词语保持着对自身的真实性，以及它们对改变的好奇需求；它们要求我们去反映，而不是去隐藏。去反映和发泄。词语在头脑中存在时，它们聚集在问题中，这些问题“敏感、冲动，而且往往是愚蠢的”，这些问题“吵闹着”要求被问到，要求“公开地”发泄。然而，它们对什么样的公众很挑剔，知道“权力和威望会全力以赴地”提出早熟的问题。问题“在权力、繁荣和陈旧的石头的氛围中萎缩。它们悄悄溜到不那么受欢迎、不那么繁荣的地方，那里的人们很穷，因此没有什么可以给予的，他们没有权力，因此也没有什么可以失去的。” 4当我们审视内心时，我们看到的问题要求我们和他们一起聆听，在一个权力结构被拆除、威望的限制被颠覆的空间里。是的，这是一个充满可能性的喧嚣之地，我们只需睁开眼睛就能看到。观察、反思、传承。

When we look within, we see words that maintain an authenticity to themselves and their curious need to change; they ask us to mirror, not to conceal. To mirror and to vent. While living in the mind, words hang together in questions, “sensitive, impulsive, and often foolish,” that “clamour” to be asked, to be vented “openly in public.” And yet they are particular about what kind of public, knowing that “power and prestige come down upon” precocious questions “with all their weight.” Questions “shrivel up in an atmosphere of power, prosperity, and time-worn stone. They slink away to less favoured, less flourishing quarters where people are poor and therefore have nothing to give, where they have no power and therefore have nothing to lose.”4 When we look within, we see questions that demand an audience both with us and with them, in a space where power structures are dismantled and constraints of prestige are subverted. Yes, here is a boisterous place of possibilities that we need only crack our eyes to see. To see, to reflect, and to pass on.

* * *

* * *

我们从书页上抬起头来。有人问道：“你们俩又在看字典吗？”

We look up from the page. “Are you two reading the dictionary again?” we are asked.

“当然，”我们异口同声地回答。我们决定翻到《好奇号》字典的最后，动词终于结束了，名词也开始了。我们互相看了一眼。“那就让我们为裂缝干杯吧！”我们的眼睛说。

“Naturally,” we reply in unison. We decide to flip to the back of Curiosity’s dictionary, where the verbs finally end and the nouns begin. We look at one another. “Here’s to cracks, then!” our eyes say.

（n.）我们自身存在的裂缝。（条目尚未写入。）

(n.) the crack in ourselves. (Entry yet to be written.)

我们中的一些人就像普通的乌龟：每天早上我们都会把壳拉到脖子上，练习几次缩头，以防当天晚些时候需要进一步撤退。但实际上，我们所有人都生活在自己的壳里。习惯和自我认知的壳。社会期望和想象力的失败。这些碳酸钙笼子比它们的同类更温柔，更坚韧。有些人经常出现裂缝，而另一些人则偶尔会出现裂缝。我们的信仰和事实出现裂缝，我们身体的能力和行程出现裂缝，我们的同伴和将我们与他们紧密联系在一起的东西出现裂缝。我们自身的地理位置出现裂缝。但这正是我们所需要的。

Some of us are much like the average tortoise: we pull our shells up to our neck each morning and practice a few head scrunches in case further retreat might prove necessary later that day. But all of us, really, live inside ourshells. Shells of habit and self-perception. Of social expectation and failures of imagination. And these cages of calcium carbonate are by turns tenderer and tougher than their compatriots. Cracks come commonly for some, and once in a blue-tinted moon for others. Cracks in our faith and in our facts, cracks in our body’s capacities and itineraries, cracks in our companions and what glues us to them. Cracks in the very geographies of ourselves. But that is precisely what is needed.

格洛丽亚·安萨尔杜亚 (Gloria Anzaldúa) 邀请我们去寻找我们的水井和旋风、我们的天然井和雷莫利诺斯 (remolinos)。在那里，生命还未在一组杰出的词语中找到家，围坐在一张杰出的食物桌旁，滋养着一群杰出的认知者。当我们崩溃时，创造力就会产生。当我们崩溃时，不当行为就会发生。没有那种脆弱性、那种边界思维和这些问题，我们将被困在自己的岛屿上（或者更糟的是，被困在大陆上），没有能力架桥、划船，甚至跳入赋予一切不敬（和非启示性）背景的大海。安萨尔杜亚写道，让那些“解放性的见解 / conocimientos ”冲破我们潜意识的裂缝，从我们的天然井中流淌出来。让它们让我们对新的身份认同敞开心扉，打破我们的分类，揭示我们社会文化的缺陷和先入之见的缺陷。问题让人迷失方向、混乱不堪。但正是这样，它们才使得新的自我和无形的事物成为可能。“有一个裂缝，”她提醒我们，“万物皆有裂缝 / 那是光照进来的地方。” 5

Gloria Anzaldúa invites us to find our wells and our whirlwinds, our cenotes and remolinos. Where what lives has yet to find home in a distinguished set of words sitting around a distinguished table of vittles nourishing a distinguished lineage of knowers. When we crack, creativity can happen. When we crack, impropriety can happen. Without that vulnerability, that border-thinking, those questions, we will be stuck on our own islands (or perhaps what’s worse, stuck up on the mainland), without the capacity to bridge, to paddle about, or even to leap into the sea that lends everything an irreverent (and nonrevelatory) context. Let those “liberating insights/conocimientos,” Anzaldúa writes, “burst through the cracks of our unconscious and flow up from our cenotes.” Let them crack us open to new identifications, disrupting our categories, showing the flaws in our social cultures and the faults in our preconceptions. Questions disorient and dislocate. And in so doing, they make new selves and nonshells possible. “There is a crack,” she reminds us, “a crack in everything / That’s how the light gets in.”5

* * *

* * *

我们小心翼翼地翻动着书页，因为字典的页面太薄了。为什么薄书页比厚书页更能发出声音呢？一缕阳光在风铃上闪烁，在下一条记录上划出一道亮光：

We turn the page, gingerly because dictionary pages are so thin. Why is it that thin pages make more sound than thick? A bit of sunlight glints off the wind chime and draws a bright dash across the next entry:

（n.）我们世界的裂缝。（条目仍为空白。）

(n.) the crack in our world. (Entry still blank.)

包围着我们的不仅仅是我们自己，还有我们的世界。我们有宏伟的建筑，我们可以在其中行动；我们有巨大的网络，我们可以潜行其中。有已知的历史，也有被淹没的历史，在我们周围形成冰山。信仰之河、书籍之山、政策简报之沙漠——更不用说古老的错误和偏见之森林——在整个世界里包围着我们，而且是千百年来如此。看不见的、说不出来的事物，却预先定义了我们如何出生、如何成长、做什么以及在哪里死去。我们如何找到我们世界的裂缝并穿过它？我们如何打破和打开一切空洞？打破和打开一切长期以来被神圣化的东西？在什么尺度上，“可能”变得可信？

It is not merely ourselves that encircle us but also our worlds. There are grand architectures within which we make our moves and vast webs across which we slink. There are known histories and there are submerged histories, forming icebergs all around us. Rivers of beliefs, mountains of books, and deserts of policy briefs—not to mention the old, old forests of blunders and biases—surround us the whole world over and for eons too. Unseeable things and unsayable things that nevertheless define in advance how it is we are born, how we grow, what we do, and where we die. How do we find the crack in our world and walk through it? How do we break and break open everything that is hollow? Break and break open everything that has been so long hallowed? By what measure does “might” become plausible?

对于弗里德里希·尼采来说，我们必须站稳脚跟，将问号的闪电般的裂缝拉到简单或简化的答案上。我们必须邀请突然出现的天空之火，照亮我们熟悉的、有时是强迫的事实体系中的断层线。还有赤裸裸的风，它吹散了可见和可说的东西的缝隙。还有倾盆大雨和侵蚀的溪流，没有任何确定性可以与之抗衡。Fragezeichen ：问号。尼采称之为将所有事物标记为可疑的问号。6打开我们世界的裂缝。没有人知道这些“奇怪、邪恶、可疑的问题”何时会袭来。7但愿它们袭击得更频繁，更接近那些我们尚未意识到的毫无意义地、毫无道理地站在我们头顶上的基础。有什么比用问号压住它们更好的方法来摆脱这些东西的重量，就像一个铅锚挂在一个想法的脖子上，看着它沉没一样？这或许可以证明是“一种怀疑的教育”，但同样也是“勇气和大胆”的教育。8

For Friedrich Nietzsche, we must set ourselves round and stretch ourselves long, and draw down the lightning crack of a question mark over easy or simplified answers. We must invite the sudden flash of sky-fire that illuminates the fault lines in our familiar, sometimes forced systems of facts. And the bald wind that brushes free the seams of what is seeable and sayable. And the pelting rain and rivulets of erosion, against which no certainty can stand. Fragezeichen: question mark. Nietzsche would call it the question mark that marks all things as questionable.6 The crack that opens our world. There is no telling when these “strange, wicked, questionable questions” will strike.7 But would that they struck more often, and ever closer to those fundaments we have yet to realize stand unceremoniously and unjustifiably overhead. What better way to throw off the weight of such things than to weigh them down with a question mark, slung like a leaden anchor round the neck of an idea and just watch it sink? Such might prove to be “a schooling in suspicion,” but just as equally an education in “courage and audacity.”8

* * *

* * *

我们对这些页面上的大片空白感到惊奇。大多数词典不是都塞得满满的吗？内容溢出，文本大小缩小，需要放大镜吗？为什么要打印一本列出术语但没有提供定义的词典？这种做法值得怀疑。

We marvel at the large, empty white space on these pages. Aren’t most dictionaries full to the brim? Spilling over, text size shrinking, magnifying glass needed? Why print a dictionary with terms listed and no definition provided? Questionable practice that.

（n.）地平线上的裂缝。（空白。）

(n.) the crack on the horizon. (Blank.)

裂缝可以被追求和浪漫，被浪费和迷失。但只要我们还活着，有一条裂缝就永远不会消失，那就是地平线上那条又长又浅的裂缝。毕竟，地平线是脚下的世界和头顶的世界之间的裂缝，天地在这里相遇，但并不混合。中间地带永远存在。地平线召唤我们向前，背叛了我们既定的假设，表明总有比我们知道的更多的东西，也总有更多方法将我们所知道的东西抛入奇怪的混乱之中。走遍世界并不意味着事实并非如此。因为地平线有一个神秘的结构，它是不可改变的，因此是可靠的。正是在那条地平线上，任何对未来（而不是现在）的希望都悬而未决。

Cracks can be courted and romanced, squandered and lost. But one crack never leaves so long as we breathe, and that is the long, shallow crack on the horizon. The horizon is, after all, a crack between the worlds of things underfoot and things overhead, where the sky and the earth meet, but do not intermingle. Where the Between beds down permanently. The horizon beckons us onward, betrays our settled assumptions, suggests there is always more than we know and more ways in which what we know can be thrown into curious disarray. Having traveled the world over doesn’t make this not so. For there is a structure of mystery to the horizon that is irrevocable and therefore faithful. And it is upon that horizon that any hope of the future, as precisely not the present, hangs.

现象学家莫里斯·梅洛-庞蒂认为，视界使我们的问题保持开放。视界是一条通往其他事物的边缘，是通往更多事物的边缘。它始终存在，但永远无法到达。从某种意义上说，万物皆有视界。因此，任何探究——当然也包括任何探究对象——都永远无法真正被封闭、最终确定、封存和索引。道路总有弯路，总有拐角，总有待探索的视角。这使我们的探索——以及我们自己——保持开放，以进行变革。而且，奇怪的是，这也将我们团结在一起。“视界就像天空和大地一样，是事物聚集在一起的集合，”梅洛-庞蒂写道，“它是一种新的存在，一种多孔的存在……而视界向其敞开的人，将被它所吸引和包裹。” 9视界不仅仅是一条下垂的边缘，也是一条连接的边缘。正是它的不确定性吸引了我们。只要地平线总是处于某种事物的边缘，它也是所有边缘工作的先决条件，所有归属感和背景感。那么，愿我们的问题永远诞生于这种归属与成长的联系中。让我们在共同的疑问空间中保持好奇心，始终关注当下，为下一步做好准备。

Phenomenologist Maurice Merleau-Ponty speaks of the horizon as what keeps our questions open. The horizon is an edge that opens onto something else, something more. It is always there and yet it can never be reached. In a sense, everything has a horizon. As such, no inquiry—and certainly no object of inquiry—can ever really be closed down, finally decided, boxed up and indexed. There is always a bend in the road, a corner to turn, a perspective yet to be taken. This keeps our quests—as much as ourselves—open to transformation. And, oddly enough, that unites us. “No more than the sky and the earth is the horizon a collection of things held together,” Merleau-Ponty writes, “it is a new kind of being, a being by porosity . . . and the one before whom the horizon opens is caught up and englobed within it.”9 The horizon is not simply an edge that drops off but also an edge that connects. Its very uncertainty draws us in. Insofar as the horizon is always on the edge of something, it is also the precondition of all edgework, all sense of belonging and context. May our questions, then, be ever born in this nexus of belonging and becoming. Let us be curious in the space of our shared questionableness, always present to what is and ready for what is next.

* * *

* * *

在好奇号字典末尾的几页空白页上，我们停顿了一下，拿出一模一样的黑色钢笔，慢慢地开始书写。

On the few completely blank pages at the end of Curiosity’s dictionary, we pause. We take out our identical black pens and slowly begin to write.

（vb.）具有（n.）易碎性；预示着可能性。

(vb.) having (n.) crackability; portending the possible.

植物种子具有可破碎性，铰链和眼睛、句子和疑问也一样。我们中的许多人常常害怕我们自己的可破碎性——事实上，我们的世界和视野也具有可破碎性。我们担心，也许这是正确的，这表明我们具有深厚的失落感。我们宁愿避免不安定。我们担心被重塑。可破碎性所固有的迷失方向，对于那些整天制作固定物品的生物来说，是令人深感不安的。但可破碎性是可以建模的，可破碎性是可以学习的。再看看那棵小幼苗，试着引导它愿意破土而出，让位于成长、美丽和新的生命形式。在过去和未来的循环中，可破碎性是关键。这是好奇心最天真的简报之一。

Plant seeds have crackability, as do hinges and eyes, sentences and queries. Many of us are often afraid of our own crackability—and indeed the crackability of our worlds and our horizons. We fear, perhaps rightly, that it signals a deep capacity for loss. We would rather avoid being unsettled. We worry about being remade. The disorientation inherent in crackability is deeply disconcerting for creatures who spend their days crafting settled things. But crackability can be modeled, and crackability can be learned. Look again to the small seedling, and try channeling its willingness to break open and to give way to growth and beauty and new forms of life. In the cycle of what was and what will be, crackability is key. And this is among the most innocent of briefs for curiosity.

要想追求易碎性，就必须既要严肃，又要愚蠢。以海蛞蝓为例。海蛞蝓以吸食汁液和消耗阳光的习性而闻名，因为它们以附近的藻类为食，因此海蛞蝓也以易碎性而闻名。当海蛞蝓因某种原因感染寄生虫或其他疾病时，它就会破裂！它的脖子变成了“断裂面”，身体完全脱落。确实很严肃，但也很愚蠢。海蛞蝓只用头和一根触角猛击，摆出一副喜剧姿态。但这里也有严肃性，因为它再生了心脏、四肢和其他一切。什么不再对它有用？什么妨碍了它的繁荣？什么危害了世界各地海蛞蝓的健康？海蛞蝓表现出一种意愿，愿意一次又一次地松开（并失去）它的节点，并重新长出它的边缘。摆脱熟悉的方式并以不同的方式看待同一件事物，这是一种奇怪的任性行为。因此，苏格拉底很可能会意外地发现舌骨鱼是他的伙伴。想象一下，他们俩在雅典城里四处游荡，赞美可破解性的优点。

To court crackability, one must be willing to be severe but also silly. Consider the sacoglossan sea slug. Known for their sap-sucking and sun-guzzling habits, as they feed from nearby algae, the sacoglossans are also famed for their crackability. When for whatever reason a sacoglossan acquires a parasite or some other disease, the slug cracks! Its neck becomes a “breakage plane” and its body falls clean off. Severe indeed. But also silly. Slugging about with barely its head and a bit of antennae, the sacoglossan strikes a comedic pose. But there is seriousness here too as it regenerates its heart, limbs, and everything else. What no longer serves it? What detracts from its flourishing? And what jeopardizes the health of sea slugs everywhere? The sea slug manifests a certain willingness to loose (and lose) its node over and over again and to regrow its edge. It is a curious willfulness to throw off familiar ways and look at the same thing in a different way. As such, Socrates might well find in the sacoglossan an unexpected companion. Imagine the two out about town in Athens, extolling the virtues of crackability.

在人类世界中，我们可以从那些不得不为自己和自己的疑问打开空间的人那里学到很多关于可破解性的知识。例如，如果不破解父权制及其神话和基础，女权主义又是什么呢？10学者兼作家萨拉·艾哈迈德（Sara Ahmed）在思考女权主义精神时，重述了一个女孩的故事，她的好奇欲望和怀疑被解读为叛逆任性。11我们可以想象她的手不断地举过头顶。可怕的是，她的顽固导致了她的死亡，但在她下葬时，她的手却不顾一切地从地上伸出来。这是一个关于地球可破解性的故事，是生与死之间的枢纽，也​​是无法抑制的任性好奇心（和好奇任性）的种子。由于文化不完全同化，孩子们往往比我们更能看清我们外表的裂缝和社会习俗的裂缝（似乎？）。同样，在特定社会体系中被边缘化的人也是如此——那些社会体系不适合他们，社会体系对他们不起作用的人。如果我们要追求破解性，我们需要每个人。我们需要一种新的倾听架构，让被边缘化的声音得以发声。

In the human world, we can learn a lot about crackability from people who have had to crack open spaces for themselves and their own queries. What is feminism, for example, if not the cracking of patriarchy, its myths and foundations?10 Musing upon a feminist ethos, scholar and writer Sara Ahmed retells the story of a girl whose curious desires and doubts were interpreted as rebellious willfulness.11 We can imagine her hand constantly shooting up above her head. Grimly, her recalcitrance led to her deathbed, but, upon her burial, her hand shot up through the ground regardless. It is a story of the crackability of the earth, the hinge between life and death, and indeed the irrepressible seed of willful curiosity (and curious willfulness). Children often see the cracks in our facades and the seams (seems?) in our social mores better than we do, having been incompletely acculturated. Likewise, too, do people marginalized within a given social system—those for whom it was not made and for whom it does not work. If we are to court crackability, we need everybody. And we need a new architecture of listening by which sidelined voices slide forward.

有无数的总体结构几乎没有留下任何裂缝和好奇心的空间——事实上，它们完全否认了可破解性。关于什么算作知者、什么算作知识体系以及什么算作一种知晓方式，有着悠久的传统。但好奇心让我们在节点和节点枢纽之间的裂缝中忘记了数，又重新数。诗人兼学者弗雷德·莫顿 (Fred Moten) 在他的书《在断裂中》中反思了黑人激进传统的抵抗和重新想象的能力。他思考了爵士乐的即兴演奏。他特别思考了断裂：音乐暂停，打击乐或乐器独奏切入的那一刻。乐曲被打破，其主题和节奏被带入意想不到的方向。他观察到，“这种对结束的拒绝，是一场持续的、重建的合奏即兴表演”，是与彼此一起思考、通过彼此思考。莫顿写道，黑人激进传统欣赏这种停顿的创造力，它动员了“漏网之鱼”，实践“一种持续的狡猾”。12这是抵抗性的发明。这是逃避性的好奇心。

There are innumerable totalizing structures that leave little room for cracks and for curiosity—indeed, that deny crackability outright. Long traditions of what counts as a knower, what counts as a system of knowledge, and what counts as a way of knowing. But curiosity invites us to lose count and to count again in the crack between nodes and nodal hubs. In his book In the Break, poet and scholar Fred Moten reflects upon the Black radical tradition’s capacity to resist and to reimagine. He thinks about jazz improvisation. And he thinks specifically about the break: that moment when the music is suspended, and a percussive or instrumental solo cuts in. The piece is broken open, and its motifs and rhythms are taken in unexpected directions. “This refusal of closure,” he observes, is “an ongoing and reconstructive improvisation of ensemble,” of thinking with and through one another. Appreciating the creative power of this caesura, Moten writes, the Black radical tradition mobilizes what “slips through the cracks” and practices “an ongoing shiftiness.”12 This is resistant invention. This is fugitive curiosity.

好奇的未来具有可破解性。破坏可以实现更大的成就，断开连接可以实现新的连接。

Curious futures have crackability. The undoing that allows for greater doing, the disconnections that allow for new connections.

* * *

* * *

我们合上书。“让我们好奇的未来出现裂缝吧！”我们无言地说道，点头表示我们特有的姿态。我们打开前门（或者是后门、侧门或天窗？）走出去。

We close the book. “Here’s to the cracks in our curious futures!” we say—wordlessly, in our characteristic nod of the head. We open the front door (or is it a back door, side door, or skylight?) and head out.

附录：一本奇妙的动物寓言集

Appendix: A Curious Bestiary

本着增加好奇心模型和实践的精神，我们在此提供一份简短的动物图鉴。我们列出了几个世纪以来，尤其是西方思想认为特别好奇（或特别好的好奇心模型）的动物，并加入了一些我们自己的动物图鉴。我们认识到，任何这样的图鉴永远都是不完整的，而且会有很多不完整之处。尽管如此，我们还是将其作为一个开端。在适应这些动物生活的过程中，我们倾向于它们独特的知识和认知方式，我们赞美它们多样的好奇心，并从中汲取灵感，以尊重我们内心和超越我们的动物好奇心。

In the spirit of multiplying models and practices of curiosity, we offer here a brief bestiary. We catalog a few of the animals that have been thought especially curious (or especially good models of curiosity) over centuries of especially Western thought and throw in a few of our own. We recognize that any such compendium will always be incomplete, and in multiple ways. Nevertheless, we offer it as an opening. In attuning ourselves to these animal lives, we tend to their distinct knowledges and ways of knowing, we celebrate their diverse curiosities, and from them we draw inspiration to honor the animal curiosity within us and beyond us.

驴：你有没有想过变成一只鸭子会是什么感觉？或者是一只蜻蜓或花栗鼠？这种好奇心是一个历史悠久的传统。卢修斯是第一部完整保存的拉丁小说阿普列乌斯的《变形记》的主人公，他总是想知道变成一只鸟会是什么感觉。1而且不是普通的鸟——不是鸽子、金丝雀、知更鸟或山雀，而是一只鹰！卢修斯非常“好奇”，他寻找精通魔法并可以监督他变形的女人。然而不幸的是，咒语出了问题，他变成了一头驴。卢修斯既不光滑也不鹰钩鼻，变成了一只笨拙的野兽，蹄子粗壮，鼻子宽大。卢修斯习惯了在名门望族和有教养的人中间穿梭，突然间他陷入了贫困、非法和不幸的命运。卢修斯的故事让我们不得不提出一系列问题。贫穷能教会我们什么好奇心？好奇心又能被怎样的贫穷所改变？谦卑？缺乏和损失使什么变得值得怀疑（和不容置疑）？好奇心在日常生活中会以何种形式呈现？事实上，无论一个人发现自己在拍打翅膀还是在顽强地抓住土地，斗争在好奇的心灵中会形成什么？

Ass: Have you ever wondered what it would be like to be a duck? Or perhaps a dragonfly or a chipmunk? Such wonderment is a time-honored tradition. Lucius, the protagonist of the first fully preserved Latin novel, Apuleius’s Metamorphoses, always wondered what it would be like to be a bird.1 And not just any bird—not a pigeon or a canary, a robin or a titmouse, no, but an eagle! Ever so “curious,” Lucius sought out women who were skilled in the magical arts and might oversee the transformation. Unfortunately, however, the spell went wrong, and he was turned into an ass. Neither sleek nor aquiline, Lucius became a lumbering beast with thick hoofs and a broad snout. Used to circulating among the wellborn and the well-bred, Lucius was suddenly thrown into poverty, illegality, and ill-starred fate. Lucius’s tale, then, begs us to ask a series of questions. What might poverty teach curiosity? How might curiosity be transformed by humility? What do lack and loss make questionable (and unquestionable)? What shape does curiosity take in the mundane bluntness of the everyday? And indeed, what does struggle train in the curious heart, whether one finds oneself beating one’s wings or pawing tenaciously at the earth?

蜜蜂：人类的性格并不总是那么友善。然而，弗里德里希·尼采在慷慨大方的时候，提出了一个性格。他写道，我们“天生就是有翅膀的生物，是精神的采蜜者”。2我们收集知识，珍惜知识，用知识建造蜂巢。“大脑就像一把精确布置的梳子”，17 世纪的哲学家和科学家玛格丽特·卡文迪什评论道，每个想法“都单独存在于一个隔开的细胞中”。3每个蜂巢平均有十万个细胞，我们一直很忙碌。但尼采警告说，在我们嗡嗡作响、忙碌地学习和发现这些的过程中，我们常常无法安顿下来。我们很少抽出时间问自己一些基本的问题，比如“我们到底是谁？”当然，蜜蜂及其花粉采集路径的奇妙之处在于，在为蜂群觅食时，蜜蜂使植物本身成为可能。它们在采集者和被采集者之间共同工作。从这个角度来看，好奇心似乎不值得尼采的担心。蜜蜂的好奇心远离导致普遍自我异化的消费资本主义轨道，而是关系性和尊重性的，它会回馈尽可能多的滋养机会。有翅膀的生物、蜂蜜采集者、给予者。

Bee: Characterizations of the human species are not always kind. Nevertheless, in a moment of largess, Friedrich Nietzsche offers one. We are “by nature winged creatures and honey-gatherers of the spirit,” he writes.2 We collect knowledge, we treasure it, and we build our beehives full of it. “The brain is like a comb exactly laid,” seventeenth-century philosopher and scientist Margaret Cavendish remarks, such that every thought lies “each by itself within a parted cell.”3 With an average of a hundred thousand cells per hive, we are kept quite occupied. But in our buzzing and our busyness, learning this and discovering that, Nietzsche warns, we often fail to settle into the present. We rarely get around to asking basic questions of ourselves like, “Who are we really?” Of course, the wonderful thing about bees and their pollen-collecting trails is that, in foraging food for their colonies, bees make plant life itself possible. They work communally among the gatherers and among the gathered. From this vantage point, curiosity seems not to warrant Nietzsche’s worry. Far from a consumer-capitalist track that contributes to widespread self-alienation, the bee’s curiosity is relational and respectful, giving back as many nourishing opportunities as it takes. Winged creatures, honey-gatherers, givers.

书虫：“它们闻起来真香！”我们的鼻子惊呼；“真美味！”我们的味蕾赞叹。甲虫、白蚁、蚂蚁、蛾子、蟑螂、蠹鱼、书虱和书蝎也同意这一点。书籍在口中和脑海中味道鲜美，在手中和爪子中感觉美味，看起来也美味，无论是整齐地排列在书架上还是随意地散落在地上，咀嚼中也是如此。我们想要更多，所以我们会找到更多。我们把它们握在掌心，放在心上。有时我们甚至会收集它们，……或者我们可能希望这样做。“为什么在五个世纪、六个国家中，女性藏书者似乎如此之少？”玛丽·海德·埃克尔斯在格罗利尔俱乐部 1990 年的展览“十五位女性藏书者”中问道。“答案是显而易见的：任何规模的认真收藏家必须具备三大优势：充足的资源、教育和自由。” 4我们赞美少数人：黛安·德·波蒂埃、凯瑟琳·德·美第奇、加布里埃尔·德·埃斯特雷、瑞典王后克里斯蒂娜、蓬巴杜夫人和艾米·洛厄尔。但我们是否都可能是更常见意义上的收藏家？收藏家兼食客，收集最美味的东西。弗吉尼亚·伍尔夫在描述十七世纪作家塞维涅夫人时写道：“她胃口很大，书籍是她的天然居所……她不是在读这本书，而是把它铭刻在脑海里。” 5书籍成为我们内心的一部分，就像苹果成为孩子的眼睛的一部分一样。我们被木质词语的果肉所滋养，被多刺句子的胶水所填充，被皮革语言的装订所满足。文本成为我们的组织，但更重要的是，它活在我们体内。 “身体和文本都在不断变化，”文学翻译学者艾米莉·罗斯写道。6而文本滋养的身体则具有混合变化。就像从未充分利用的食物一样，来自早已被遗忘的书页的意义线索可能会潜伏多年，无人发现，无人知晓，但总有可能从内部拜访我们。有一天——也许是今天——我们可能会在头发的闪光、动脉的脉搏、指关节的弯曲、召唤体验的急促呼吸中注意到它们。

Bookworm: “They smell so tasty!” exclaim our Noses; “So delicious!” rave our Tastebuds. And beetles, termites, ants, moths, cockroaches, silverfish, book lice, and book scorpions agree. Books taste delicious in the mouth and mind, feel delicious in the hand and claw, and look delicious whether lined up neatly on a shelf or left open on the floor—haphazardly strewn, mid-chew. We want more, and so we find more. We grasp them in our palms and hold them to our hearts. At times we even collect them, . . . or we might wish to. “Why, in five centuries, in six countries, do there seem to have been so few women book collectors?” asked Mary Hyde Eccles at the Grolier Club’s 1990 exhibition Fifteen Women Book Collectors. “The answer is obvious: a serious collector on any scale must have three advantages: considerable resources, education, and freedom.”4 We celebrate the few: Diane de Poitiers; Catherine de’ Médicis; Gabrielle d’Estrées; Christina, queen of Sweden; Madame de Pompadour; and Amy Lowell. But might we all be collectors in some more common sense of the term? Collectors-cum-ingestors, gathering up the tastiest bits. “She has a robust appetite,” pens Virginia Woolf, describing seventeenth-century writer Madame de Sévigné, “a natural dwelling-place in books . . . not read by her so much as embedded in her mind.”5 Books become a bit of our inmost selves, just as an apple becomes a bit of a child’s eye. We are nourished by the pulp of woody words, filled by the glue of spiny sentences, satisfied by the binding of leathery language. The text becomes the tissue of us, but more than that, it lives on within us. “Both bodies and texts are constantly becoming,” writes Emily Rose, scholar of literary translation.6 And the body nourished by text has a hybrid becoming. As a food never fully used, strands of meaning from a long-forgotten page may lie dormant, unseen, unknown for years, always with the potential of visiting us from within. Someday—perhaps today—we may notice them in the glint of a hair, the pulse of an artery, the crook of a knuckle, the quickening breath of a beckoning experience.

金丝雀：虽然好奇心通常被认为是自我点燃的，但好奇心的常见体验是他人点燃的。内心的火焰被他人的火花点燃，点燃了新的激情。对于美国作家露丝·斯泰尔斯·甘尼特来说，这种具有感染力、传染性和可传播性的好奇心就是金丝雀的好奇心。弗鲁特是一只因羽毛岛病而燃烧的金丝雀。统治者国王肯十一世“实际上正死于此病”。这一切都始于国王肯一世，他从来都不是身体健康或快乐的人。当他的臣民问他为什么时，他只是说：“我快要死于好奇了。”金丝雀们很好奇他为什么这么好奇，所以他们很快也患上了好奇心病，每一代人最终都死于好奇心。埃尔默是一个带着蓝黄条纹的幼龙和金色翅膀一起旅行的男孩，他想知道“他们为什么这么好奇”。弗鲁特反驳道：“看，你开始好奇了！那将是多么美好的一天这座岛战胜好奇心瘟疫后会怎样！” 7但厄运并没有降临，受感染的埃尔默与金丝雀一起挖掘新的认知路线，以赞美勇敢、慷慨和归属感。分享我们当前的传染病可能会燃起什么新的希望？

Canary: Although a common account of curiosity is as self-ignited, a common experience of curiosity is as other-ignited. An internal fire lit by another’s stray spark, inflaming a new passion. To US author Ruth Stiles Gannett, this infectious, contagious, transmissible curiosity is canary curiosity. Flute is a canary combusting from Feather Island’s disease. The ruler King Can the XI is “actually dying of it.” It all started with King Can I, who was never well or happy. When his subjects asked him why, he would simply say, “I’m dying of curiosity.” The canaries were curious to know why he was so curious and so they quickly also became sick with curiosity, and each successive generation eventually died of it. Elmer, a boy traveling with a blue-and-yellow-striped baby dragon with burnished gold-colored wings, wondered “what they could have been so curious about.” To which Flute retorted, “See, there you go getting curious! What a great day it will be when this island gets over the plague of curiosity!”7 But rather than any doom materializing, the infected Elmer joins the canaries in excavating new lines of knowing that celebrate bravery, generosity, and belonging. What new hopes might burn from sharing our current contagions?

猫：如果你对好奇心有所了解，你就知道好奇心会害死猫。这意味着，你知道这一点：好奇心是有风险的。它很危险。即使是九条命也不足以在这种危险中生存。这句俗语有着非常悠久的历史，可以追溯到 16 世纪的剧作家（以及才华横溢的威廉·莎士比亚）。好奇心会让你措手不及，打破你的期望。这可能是致命的——尤其是对猫来说。但如果好奇心不是罪魁祸首，死亡也不是惩罚呢？如果像诗人阿拉斯泰尔·里德所说的那样，猫只是“好奇地想看看死亡是什么样的”呢？毕竟，“死亡是活着的人所做的事情”，“死亡是每个人为了活着必须做的事情”。8从这个意义上说，死亡不是某种令人遗憾的后果或因果报应，而是一个自然的探索对象。日复一日，猫咪时刻保持警惕，它们的胡须永远在探测空气和物质的细微振动。死亡只是注意力的另一种形式——比单纯的探索性要小。一种不同的振动方式。

Cat: If you know anything about curiosity, you know it killed the cat. And that means, you know this: curiosity is risky. It is dangerous. Even nine lives are not enough to survive its hazards. The saying has a remarkably long and storied history, traceable all the way back to playwrights of the sixteenth century (and the luminous William Shakespeare). Curiosity will catch you unawares and shatter your expectations. And that can be fatal—especially for cats. But what if curiosity were not the culprit nor death the sanction after all? What if, as poet Alastair Reed puts it, the cat was simply “curious to see what death was like”? After all, “dying is what the living do” and “dying is what, to live, each has to do.”8 In this sense, dying is not some regrettable repercussion or karmic comeuppance but a natural object of exploration. Day in and day out, cats are on the alert, their whiskers forever detecting the slightest vibrations of air and matter. Dying is but another form of attention—less risky than it is merely exploratory. A way of vibrating differently.

水鸫：在炎热的夏日，没有什么比泡一泡更令人神清气爽的了。当我们感到头脑闷热时，我们常常会浏览博客、播客、书籍、曲目、视频或进行交谈。我们溅起水花，跳入水中，随波逐流。像水鸫一样，我们是矮壮的深灰色鸟类，在水下潜水、行走和飞行，出来时叼着蜻蜓幼虫、小龙虾、石蛾幼虫或蝌蚪作为午餐。作家兼博物学家 Jean Craighead George 在她的书《铜溪的水鸫》中跟踪记录了一只水鸫“掠过磨碎的浮冰，飞过喷涌的水花，仿佛是溪流创造了它，而人们却不愿将它放飞到天空。然后它回到了它似乎从哪里冒出来的地方——溪流汹涌的白色水流。” 9这水就是我们的来源，也是我们的归宿，我们将如海浪般喷涌而出。在游了好几个小时之后，我们“彻底筋疲力尽”和“浑身湿透”地出来，就像《幻影收费亭》中的迈罗和托克一样，难以置信这个骗子（和其他像他一样的人）“可以在知识的海洋里游一整天却还能完全干爽地出来”。10我们觉得湿润令人兴奋。那种感觉是水成为我们一部分，知识改变我们。过了一会儿，我们心灵的手指看起来就像皱巴巴的梅干，有了它们，我们可以更容易地抓住水下的物体：那些被讨厌的藤壶覆盖的滑溜溜的想法，那些被硅藻和蓝绿藻覆盖的沉思的岩石。在抓住它们之前，我们首先要通过水斗透明的第三眼睑看到它们，打开水下的全景。当我们浮出水面时，我们唱着一首“无人听见”的歌，因为我们的歌声“伴随着山间奔腾的流水”而来。11我们下次如何才能潜入水中，被淋湿，透过不同的盖子看东西，为无人而歌唱？

Dipper: Nothing feels quite as refreshing as a cool dip on a sweltering summer’s day. When we feel hot and stuffy in our heads, we often dip into a blog, a podcast, a book, a track, a reel, or a conversation. We splash about, take a plunge, drift and float. Like the water ouzel (or dipper), we are stocky, dark-gray birds that dive under water, walk, and fly beneath the surface, coming out with a dragonfly nymph, crayfish, caddis fly larva, or tadpole for lunch. In her book The Dipper of Copper Creek, writer and naturalist Jean Craighead George follows a dipper as he “skimmed the grinding ice floes and flew through the bursting sprays as if the stream had created him, and were reluctant to release him to the sky. Then he went back where he seemed to have sprung from, the lashing white waters of the opening creek.”9 This water is where we have come from, where we are going, and from which we will burst forth like sea spray. After swimming and swimming and swimming for what feels like hours, we come out “thoroughly exhausted” and “completely soaked,” like Milo and Tock in The Phantom Tollbooth, incredulous that the Humbug (and others like him) “can swim all day in the Sea of Knowledge and still come out completely dry.”10 We find the wetness exhilarating. That feeling of the water becoming part of us, the knowledge changing us. After a while, our mind’s fingers look like wrinkled prunes, with which we can more easily grasp underwater objects: those slippery thoughts covered in bothersome barnacles, those ruminative rocks coated in diatoms and blue-green algae. Before we grasp them, we first see them thanks to the dipper’s transparent third eyelid, opening up the underwater panorama. And when we surface, we sing a song “heard by none,” for we sing “to the accompaniment of the pounding waters of the mountains.”11 How might we next dip, get wet, see through a different lid, and sing for no one?

苍蝇：多么令人分心的犹豫和无聊的嗡嗡声！圣奥古斯丁担心，在适当的反思之外，有一种好奇心会被诸如“蜥蜴捕捉苍蝇或蜘蛛用网缠住苍蝇”之类的干扰所吸引。12对轻浮和微不足道的事物的这种徒劳兴趣，拒绝植根于神圣的价值或实用用途。这是为好奇而好奇。然而，勒内·笛卡尔却从这种做法中获得了极大的乐趣。他喜欢睡懒觉，在床上躺上几个小时，看着苍蝇在天花板上飞来飞去。传说他开发了笛卡尔坐标（或 x 轴和 y 轴）来绘制苍蝇降落的位置。苏格拉底也藐视礼仪，当他成为雅典人的牛虻时，他向他们抛出坚持不懈、令人恼火的问题，以动摇他们的信心并阐明无知。13就像一只有翅膀的昆虫在挑衅它的宿主一样，可耻的苏格拉底把雅典从睡梦中唤醒了。这是否都是双翅好奇心的一个例子？伍尔夫想知道，当双翅好奇心在大学里被释放时会发生什么。那种“三条腿的苍蝇”在沉闷、冰冷的经院哲学的冬天“幸存了下来”，而威望贩子们拒绝让阳光照进来？14

Fly: What distracted dithering and banal buzzing! Saint Augustine worried that just outside of proper reflection, there is a kind of curiosity drawn to distractions such as “a lizard catching flies or a spider entangling them in her nets.”12 Such a vain interest in light and insignificant things refuses to root itself in divine value or pragmatic use. It is curiosity for curiosity’s sake. René Descartes, however, took great pleasure in precisely this practice. Preferring to sleep late and lounge in bed for hours, he would watch flies scuttle-hop across the ceiling. As legend has it, he developed the Cartesian coordinates (or the x and y axes) as a way of mapping where the flies would land. Socrates, too, flouted propriety when he became a gadfly to the Athenians, lobbing insistent, irritating questions at them to unsettle surety and illuminate ignorance.13 Like a winged insect goading its host, the ignominious Socrates woke Athens from its sleep. Could this be, in each instance, a case of dipterous curiosity? And what happens when dipterous curiosity is let loose in the university, Woolf wonders. The sort of “three-legged fly” that has “survived the winter” of a dreary, bone-cold scholasticism whose prestige mongers refuse to let in the light?14

青蛙：图像是强有力的沟通工具。17 世纪早期，意大利图像画家 Cesare Ripa 创作了一幅或许是有史以来最令人难忘的好奇心图像。15他画了一个大胆地站在空旷风景中的女人。她头上的头发、肩上的翅膀和侧边的手臂都高高地举向天空。她引人注目、举止优雅，但她的长袍却出人意料地覆盖着大耳朵和更大的青蛙。请注意，不是耳朵和青蛙的图像，而是这些东西本身，它们沉重地挂在那里，仿佛随时准备被拔掉或自行跳出。Ripa 坚持认为，这就是好奇心的写照。她渴望听到和看到最新消息，这是不可否认的。她沉浸在那一刻。但青蛙？为什么是青蛙？他解释说，青蛙是“好奇心的象征……因为它们有凸出的眼睛。”青蛙的眼睛确实特别大，这是有原因的。它们能看清前方、侧面和后方的情况。那么，如果像青蛙一样的好奇心不是在传播新闻，而是在为我们提供背景信息，让我们在空间和时间上都处于某种位置，那会怎样呢？同时关注过去、现在和未来？

Frog: Images are powerful communicators. Working in the early seventeenth century, Italian iconographer Cesare Ripa created perhaps the most memorable image of curiosity before or since.15 He drew a woman standing boldly against a bare landscape. The hair on her head, the wings at her shoulders, and the arms at her side all lifted to the sky. She is striking and elegant, but for her robe, which is, quite unexpectedly, covered in large ears and still-larger frogs. Not images of ears and frogs, mind you, but the things themselves, hanging there heavily as if ready to be plucked or to leap free of their own accord. This, Ripa insists, is the spitting image of curiosity. Her eagerness to hear and to see the newest news is undeniable. She’s lost in the moment. But frogs? Why frogs? Frogs, he explains, are special “emblems of inquisitiveness . . . by reason of their goggle-eyes.” Frogs do in fact have unusually large eyes, and for good reason. They enable them to see out in front, to the side, and a bit behind. What if a frog-like curiosity, then, was not newsmongering so much as contextualizing, situating us spatially, but also temporally? A certain simultaneous eyeing of the past, the present, and the future?

蚱蜢：你知道那种必须行动的感觉吗？在你的脑海里、耳朵里、指尖里，你跳跃着、飞跃着、弹跳着。有时——正如美国作家阿诺德·斯塔克·洛贝尔所熟知的那样——你最近的好奇之旅会被三只看似一模一样的亮粉色蝴蝶打断，它们有着大大的、空洞的黄色眼睛和完美卷曲的喙。它们强行邀请你成为它们日常生活的一部分：

Grasshopper: You know that feeling when you simply must be on the move? In your mind, your ears, the tips of your fingers, you hop, jump, leap, and spring. Sometimes—as US author Arnold Stark Lobel well knows—your latest curiosity road trip is interrupted by three seemingly identical bright-pink butterflies with wide, vacant yellow eyes and perfectly curled proboscides. They forcibly invite you to become a part of their daily life:

每天我们都会在同一时间做同样的事情……我们早上醒来……我们挠三次头……总是……然后我们张开、闭合翅膀四次。我们飞六圈……总是……我们每天去同一棵树下，吃同样的午餐……总是……午饭后我们坐在同一朵向日葵上。我们睡同样的觉。我们做同样的梦……总是……当我们醒来时，我们再挠三次头。我们再飞六圈。然后我们来到这里……我们坐在这个蘑菇上……总是。

Each and every day we do the same thing at the same time. . . . We wake up in the morning. . . . We scratch our heads three times. . . . Always. . . . Then we open and close our wings four times. We fly in a circle six times. . . . Always. . . . We go to the same tree and eat the same lunch every day. . . . Always. . . . After lunch we sit on the same sunflower. We take the same nap. We have the same dream. . . . Always. . . . When we wake up, we scratch our heads three more times. We fly in a circle six more times. Then we come here. . . . We sit on this mushroom. . . . Always.

它们告诉你，它们每天都会在那蘑菇那里和你见面，它们会告诉你它们抓挠、飞翔、打盹和做梦的故事，而你会倾听，“就像你现在在听一样。”在你礼貌地拒绝，并表示你会“继续前进”和“做新的事情”之后，它们难以置信地问道：“蚱蜢，你真的每天都在做不同的事情吗？”“永远”，你回答，“永远，永远！” 16

They tell you that they will meet you at that exact mushroom every day, and that they will tell you about their scratching, flying, napping, and dreaming, and that you will listen, “just the way you are listening now.” After you politely decline, citing that you will be “moving on” and “doing new things,” they ask incredulously, “Grasshopper, do you really do something different every day of your life?” “Always,” you reply, “Always and always!”16

刺猬与狐狸：古希腊帕罗斯岛诗人阿尔基洛科斯有句名言：“狐狸知道很多事，而刺猬知道一件大事。” 17德西德里乌斯·埃拉斯谟后来将这句诗拉丁化：Multa novit vulpes, verum echinus unum magnum。英国儿童作家比阿特丽克斯·波特将这些古老的象征描绘得栩栩如生，将狐狸托德先生描绘成“有六间房子”，却“很少在家”，而刺猬蒂姬温克尔太太是整个动物群落干净衣服的唯一提供者，她的鼻子会“抽泣、抽泣、抽泣”，眼睛会“一闪一闪”。18几个世纪以来，人们一直在争论狐狸和刺猬哪个更好，谁是谁。有人说散文家米歇尔·蒙田是狐狸，柏拉图是刺猬，而另一些人则说科学是狐狸，人文学科是刺猬。还有人认为，我们应该同时具备这两种特质：神秘的狐狸猪，好奇地想要同时了解一件事和许多事。但也许在静下心来反思时，我们可能会意识到，在了解许多事情时，我们被迫只知道一件事，而在了解一件事时，我们就会了解许多事情。正如狐狸和刺猬属于一个更大的生态系统一样，知识也有自己的生命周期。我们越是集中好奇心，我们的无知就越分散，就像我们的好奇心越是游离，我们就越有可能找到一条贯穿始终的线索。

Hedgehog and fox: An ancient Greek poet from the island of Paros, Archilochus famously penned, “The fox knows many things, but the hedgehog knows one big thing.”17 Desiderius Erasmus later Latinized the line: Multa novit vulpes, verum echinus unum magnum. British children’s author Beatrix Potter brings these ancient icons to life in depicting Mr. Tod the fox as having “half a dozen houses,” but being “seldom at home,” whereas Mrs. Tiggy-Winkle the hedgehog is the sole provider of clean clothes to the entire animal community, while her nose goes “sniffle, sniffle, snuffle” and her eyes go “twinkle twinkle.”18 For centuries, people have debated which is better, the fox or the hedgehog, and who is who. Some say essayist Michel Montaigne is a fox and Plato is a hedgehog, while others say the sciences are the fox and the humanities are the hedgehog. Still others suggest we ought to be both: the mystical foxhog, curious to know one and many simultaneously. But perhaps in a moment of quiet reflection, we might realize that in knowing many things, we are forced to know really only one thing, and in knowing one thing, we come to know many things. Just as the fox and hedgehog belong to a larger ecology, so too does knowledge have its own cycle of life. The more we focus our curiosity, the more diffuse our ignorance becomes, just as the more our curiosity wanders, the more likely we are to find a through-line.

猎犬：猎犬是一种非常受人尊敬的动物，甚至可以说是高贵的动物，它被训练来追踪和追赶。为了捕猎，猎犬必须在饱和的场景中保持单一的气味，在喧闹的感官世界中保持一定的嗅觉忠诚度。在对好奇心的沉思中，罗马散文家普鲁塔克用猎犬来描述来拟人化地表现一种专注的好奇心。他评论说，猎犬不会“转身追随每一种气味”，而是“保持嗅觉的纯净，不受污染，以完成它们应有的任务”。19可以说，它们拯救了自己。虽然这种苦行显然使它们能够定位——在某些情况下是杀戮——但它也可以做其他事情。它允许猎犬倾听和关注，并将自己的存在屈服于另一只狗的生命力。它使思想谦卑，清除蛛网，使跟随的行为成为可能。这是一种什么样的奇怪做法，让一个人只有在跟随的情况下才有机会找到答案？猎犬是不是在告诉我们，好奇心需要放弃一定的控制，并致力于陪伴？

Hound: An eminently respectable, even regal creature, the hound is trained to track and to chase. In order to hunt, the hound has to hold a single scent in a saturated scene, a bit of olfactory fidelity in a riotously sensuous world. In his ruminations on curiosity, Roman essayist Plutarch uses the hound to personify a focused inquisitiveness. Hounds, he remarks, do not “turn aside and follow every scent” but instead “keep their sense of smell pure and untainted for their proper task.”19 They save themselves, so to speak. And while this ascesis clearly equips them to locate—and in some cases to kill—it can also do something else. It allows the hound to listen and to attend and to submit their existence to the life force of another. It humbles the mind and clears the cobwebs so that the act of following becomes possible. What curious practice is this that gives someone the chance to find only insofar as they follow? Might the hound teach us that curiosity requires a certain renunciation of control and a certain commitment to companionship?

尺蠖：好奇心并不总是那么强烈和广泛。有时它并不引人注目，而且非常非常微小。就像尺蠖一样，我们可能会在局部提出问题，在附近移动，缓慢前进。我们可能会问一些别人认为太小而不能问的问题。但是，我们的渺小和微小的动作带来了特殊的力量，米沃克人对此深有体会。米沃克人是四个语言上相关的土著部落，居住在现在的北加利福尼亚州。在各种讲述和复述中，米沃克人讲述了 Tu-Tok-A-Nu'-La 的传说，意思是“测量虫”。两个男孩在小溪里游泳后躺在阳光下休息，进入了神奇的睡眠。当他们睡着的时候，他们躺下的地面越来越高。花岗岩继续上升了好几年，直到男孩的脸“擦过天空”和“刮到月亮”。20动物们商量好，决定救出男孩们，把他们送回母亲身边。每只动物都试图爬上花岗岩墙。老鼠、浣熊、灰熊和美洲狮都失败了，而尺蠖却“一步一步、一寸一寸地”成功了，朱莉·帕克 (Julie Parker) 回忆道，她出生于海岸米沃克族和卡沙亚波莫族。尺蠖走着走着，它就唱着“Tu-Tok，Tu-Tok，Tu-Tok-A-Nu-La；Tu-Tok，Tu-Tok，Tu-Tok-A-Nu-La”。21 爬到墙顶后，尺蠖邀请男孩们坐在它的背上，然后它“带着他们沿着一条连续的、迂回的滑道”滑到墙脚，现在这堵墙以它的名字命名（西班牙语中也叫 El Capitan），孩子们“高兴地大笑着，尖叫着” 。22 通过缓慢移动，测量虫可以到达其他人无法到达的空间，并在其他人无法到达的地方建立社区。 当地问题、小空间以及其他人未注意到的、更广泛的社会看不到的岩石表面的细小纹理，邀请我们迈步、行走、好奇地、相互联系地缓慢移动。

Inchworm: Curiosity need not always be dramatic and expansive. Sometimes it is unobtrusive and very, very small. Like an inchworm, we might question locally, move nearby, and progress slowly. We might ask something others think is too small to ask. But with our littleness and our minute movements come special powers, as is well appreciated by the Miwok, a group of four linguistically related Indigenous tribes who live in what is now Northern California. In various tellings and retellings, the Miwok recount the legend of Tu-Tok-A-Nu’-La, which means “measuring worm.” Laying down to rest in the sun after swimming in a creek, two boys fell into a magical sleep. As they slept, the ground on which they lay rose higher and higher into the air. The granite continued to rise for years until the boys’ faces “brushed the sky” and “scraped the moon.”20 The animals took council with one another, and determined to save the boys and return them to their mother. Each animal attempted to scale the granite wall. Where mouse, rat, raccoon, grizzly bear, and mountain lion failed, the inchworm succeeded “step by step, inch by inch,” recounts Julie Parker, born to a family of the Coast Miwok and Kashaya Pomo tribes. And as the inchworm steps, the inchworm sings, “Tu-Tok, Tu-Tok, Tu-Tok-A-Nu-La; Tu-Tok, Tu-Tok, Tu-Tok-A-Nu-La.”21 Reaching the top, the inchworm invited the boys to sit on his back, and then he “led them on a continuous, circuitous slide” to the base of the wall that now carries his name (also known by the Spanish name El Capitan) as they “laughed and screamed with delight.”22 By inching, the measuring worm reaches spaces that others cannot and builds community where others fail. Local questions, small spaces, and the fine textures of rock face that go unnoticed by others, invisible to the broader society, invite us to step, to walk, to inch curiously and relationally.

猴子：好奇的动物的典型代表可能是好奇的乔治，他是深受喜爱的儿童读物人物，自 20 世纪 40 年代以来，他一直在世界各地游荡，探索、实验，最终陷入无尽的麻烦之中。23他无法与人类社会无缝地生活，通常会破坏社会的每一个机制。然而，最奇怪的是，乔治从来不对他的殖民历史感兴趣——那个戴着黄帽子的白人把他从非洲带走的那一刻。因此，乔治不敬的、超越人类的好奇心是一种边缘的好奇心，但它却无法看到它所处的社会政治背景。有趣的是，有血有肉的猴子对反事实有着不懈的好奇——也就是说，不同的选择如何产生不同的结果。24那么，猴子本身是否会让好奇的乔治更加好奇，想知道他来自哪里，如果不是这样，会是什么样子？为了制造一些反事实的麻烦？只有通过去殖民化的想象才有可能产生这样的骚动？

Monkey: Perhaps paradigmatic of inquisitive creatures is Curious George, a beloved children’s book character who, since the 1940s, wanders about the world exploring, experimenting, and ultimately getting into endless trouble.23 He is unable to live seamlessly in human society and generally throws a wrench into every bit of its machinery. Perhaps most curiously, however, George is never curious about his colonial past—that moment when the white man in the yellow hat scooped him up from Africa. As such, George’s irreverent, more-than-human curiosity is a curiosity at the edge, but it is nevertheless unable to catch sight of the sociopolitical context within which it swims. Intriguingly, flesh-and-blood monkeys are relentlessly curious about counterfactuals—that is, how different choices produce different outcomes.24 Might it be, then, that monkeys themselves invite Curious George to be still more curious, to wonder where he came from and what could have been otherwise? To get up to some counterfactual trouble? The sort of ruckus only possible with a decolonial imagination?

章鱼：章鱼有很多不同之处。除了三颗心脏外，章鱼还有九个大脑：一个位于双眼之间，八条触手各有一个，触手上布满了多达 2,240 个吸盘。我们人类通常（但并非总是）只有一个心脏、一个大脑、两条手臂和十个指垫。因此，章鱼似乎是一颗永不放弃的、开放的心、开放的、张开双臂的好奇心的完美象征，一心想从海岸和裂缝的每个角落收集新信息，这并不奇怪。纽约现代艺术博物馆建筑与设计部高级策展人 Paola Antonelli 将自己描述为“一只好奇的章鱼”，并解释说：“我总是伸手去抓，从各个地方获取东西。” 25毫无疑问，这是一种重要的策展本能。但章鱼不仅用它那温暖、聪明的“手”来捕捉和收集，还能游泳、跳跃、在芦苇中跳舞，甚至在附近的鱼群中嬉戏。这些摆动和挥动的手臂，如此吸引人、如此情境化、如此嬉戏，这是什么奇怪的活动？

Octopus: Much distinguishes the octopus. Aside from its three hearts, the octopus has nine brains: one between its eyes, and one in each of its eight tentacles, themselves lined with as many as 2,240 suction cups. We humans typically (although not always) have but one heart, one brain, two arms, and ten finger pads. It is no surprise, then, that the octopus seems the perfect figure of a relentlessly open-hearted, open-minded, open-armed curiosity, bent on collecting new information from every corner of coast and crevice. Paola Antonelli, a senior curator in the Department of Architecture and Design at the Museum of Modern Art in New York, describes herself as “a curious octopus,” explaining, “I am always reaching out and taking in things from everywhere.”25 No doubt an important curatorial instinct. But the octopus uses its warm, intelligent “hands” not only to catch and to collect, but also to swim, to cut a caper, to dance in the reeds, and even to play among nearby schools of fish. What curious activity is this, these swinging and swooshing arms that compel and contextualize and frolic?

兔子：爱丽丝——她还不是《爱丽丝梦游仙境》中的一员——百无聊赖地坐在河岸边，无所事事，更无暇思考。直到她看到一只穿着背心的白兔紧张地嘟囔着，看着手表。“好奇心燃烧着”，爱丽丝跟在它后面，整个世界都颠倒了。26近 150 年后，尼奥在类似的疲倦状态下看到了杜若尔肩上的白兔，头朝下掉进了黑客帝国。导演拉娜和莉莉·沃卓斯基承认，这个故事是对性别转变的一种不加掩饰的评论；黑客帝国是一个“跨性别隐喻”。27因此，兔子与红皇后和红色药丸只有一线之隔。但为什么每次都是兔子呢？兔子不喜欢走路。兔子不喜欢焦急地漫步或鬼鬼祟祟的脚步，它们更喜欢跳跃。兔子在躲避危险或跳入灌木丛时，会通过一系列跳跃来移动，它们会用后腿同时跳跃。当它们最开心时，它们会稍微改变跳跃的高度。正如爱丽丝和尼奥所知道的那样，某些奇怪的变化、某些生命维度之间的旅行，需要一种不同寻常的推进和愉悦练习。让跳跃成为一种习惯。

Rabbit: Alice—for she was not yet Alice in Wonderland—sat bored on a riverbank, with little to do and still less to think. That is, until she saw a white rabbit in a waistcoat nervously mumbling and checking his timepiece. “Burning with curiosity,” Alice dove after him and all the world turned upside down.26 Almost 150 years later, Neo, in a similar state of lassitude, sees the white rabbit on Dujour’s shoulder and falls headfirst into the Matrix. Directors Lana and Lilly Wachowski confess the story is a thinly veiled commentary on gender transition; the Matrix is a “trans metaphor.”27 Rabbits, then, are a short hop from Red Queens and red pills. But why rabbits, in each case? Rabbits prefer not to walk. Not the sort for an anxious amble or furtive footstep, rabbits prefer to hop. Darting out of danger or bounding into the underbrush, rabbits move by a series of leaps, launching from their hind legs at once up and over. When happiest, they add a little twist to the height of the hop. As Alice and Neo came to know, certain kinds of curious change, certain travels between dimensions of being, require an unusual practice of propulsion and pleasure. Making a habit out of the hop.

知更鸟：知更鸟有着一双充满疑问的黑色眼睛，在每个孩子的脑海中，它都呆呆地盯着窗外，若有所思。英裔美国小说家、剧作家弗朗西丝·霍奇森·伯内特在她的作品《秘密花园》中记录了这双好奇的眼睛。当玛丽问米瑟斯韦特庄园的园丁本·韦瑟斯塔夫，是什么鸟在跟着他们时，本回答说：“你不知道吗？它是一只知更鸟，它们是世界上最友好、最好奇的鸟……它总是来看看我种的什么。” 28知更鸟的好奇心是为了观察，而观察是为了了解。它想知道什么植物加入了它的世界，什么新叶子和什么新花会装饰它家的花园。知更鸟沿着蜿蜒的小路跳跃，好奇地加入花园里的其他居民。正如人类学家蒂姆·英戈尔德所说，知更鸟“沿着它们所踏过的路径”增长知识。29 《秘密花园》中的叙述者继续说道：“知更鸟跳来跳去，忙着啄食土壤，不时停下来看看它们。玛丽觉得它那双黑色的露珠般的眼睛非常好奇地注视着她。它真的似乎在了解她的一切。” 30知更鸟般的好奇心是否承认只有看到才能知道的事情？没有问题可问。没有声音可发出。没有喧闹的动作可做。人们必须只是静止不动，静静地观看。

Robin: With its dark, questioning eyes, the robin sits in the mind of every child, staring, lost in thought, peering out a window. British American novelist and playwright Frances Hodgson Burnett notes those curious eyes in her book The Secret Garden. When Mary asks the gardener of Misselthwaite Manor, Ben Weatherstaff, what kind of bird was following them, Ben replied, “Doesn’t tha’ know? He’s a robin redbreast an’ they’re th’ friendliest, curiousest birds alive. . . . He’s always comin’ to see what I’m plantin’.”28 The robin’s curiosity looks to see, and sees to know. He wants to know what plant is joining his world, what new leaf and what new flower will decorate the garden of his home.
