By hopping along the meandering walkways, the robin joins the other inhabitants of the garden in curiously growing his knowledge “along the paths they tread,” as anthropologist Tim Ingold puts it.29 The narrator in The Secret Garden continues by observing that “the robin hopped about busily pecking the soil and now and then stopped and looked at them a little. Mary thought his black dewdrop eyes gazed at her with great curiosity. It really seemed as if he were finding out all about her.”30 Might robin-like curiosity acknowledge the times when what must be known can only be seen? There is no question to ask. No sound to make. No boisterous action to perform. One must simply be still and look on, quietly.

蛇：蛇在林下灌木丛中来来去去。有时它沿着地面悄悄地走，在草丛间、河石上或灌木丛下偷偷溜走。有时，它会爬上树干，缠绕在树枝上，然后懒洋洋地盘旋一会儿。在犹太教和基督教传统中，蛇——或者更险恶地说是毒蛇——是好奇心的象征。31毕竟，是蛇用好奇心诱惑了夏娃。它在她耳边低语，在她思想的小径中穿梭，在这里溜来溜去，在那里沉重地悬在那里，在事物之间的空间里制造出各种形状。夏娃利用这个空间伸出手去抓知识树上的禁果，整个世界都陷入了黑暗。蛇被指责为狡猾、欺骗甚至诱人，但或许我们更应该认为它只是滑溜溜的，因此它具有令人羡慕的能力，可以好奇地探测周围事物的滑溜溜，无论是思想、言语还是在地面上和周围发现的东西。格洛丽亚·安扎尔杜阿 (Gloria Anzaldúa) 在将蛇描述为“更多生命”的象征时也表达了同样的观点，这种扭动、蠕动的动作加深了人们对这个不安世界的认识，并最终“推动了它的转变” 。32

Snake: The snake slips in and out of the understory. Sometimes it slinks along the ground, sidling between grasses, over river rocks, or under shrubs. Other times, it slithers up tree trunks, winds around their branches, and hangs for a bit in lazy loops. In the Judeo-Christian tradition, the snake—or the serpent, to put it more sinisterly—is the icon of curiosity.31 It was the serpent, after all, who tempted Eve with curiosity. He whispered in her ear, winding through the byways of her mind, slipping here and hanging heavily there, making shapes in the space between things. And with that space, Eve reached out her hand to grasp the forbidden fruit from the tree of knowledge and all the world fell into darkness. Accused of being sly, deceptive, even seductive, however, the snake is perhaps better thought as simply slippery and, as such, as having the enviable ability to curiously plumb the slipperiness of things around them, whether things thought, things said, or things found in and around the ground. Gloria Anzaldúa said as much when she characterized the snake as a figure for “more life,” the sort of writhing, wriggling movement that deepens an awareness of a restless world and ultimately “fuels [its] transformation.”32

要想探索这个湿滑的世界，还有什么比拥有一个柔韧的丝状身体更好呢？它一边生活一边探索——难以捉摸，难以抓住，也不可能站在上面。我们以前在蝴蝶触角中看到过这种形式和功能之间的关系：一个细长的身体形状和一个探索、好奇的存在方式。17 世纪的植物学家玛丽亚·西比拉·梅里安注意到蛇和蝴蝶的触角在视觉上有着惊人的相似性。对于一个物种，她指出“它的触角看起来像两条五颜六色的蛇，白色和黑色”，而对于另一个物种，她写道“触角就像黑蛇。” 33蛇状的好奇心是否进一步体现了细长触角状的探究线的滑溜性，这些探究线以丝状问题或丝状问题的形式从自己身上伸出？动物界的卷须；动物界的藤蔓。蜿蜒而出，蜿蜒而行，蜿蜒而过。

And how better to plumb a slippery world than to have a flexible, filamentous body, searching as it lives—elusive, difficult to hold, and impossible to stand on? We’ve seen this relation between form and function before in the butterfly antennae: a long, thin bodily shape and a searching, curious way of being. Maria Sibylla Merian, seventeenth-century botanist, noticed the striking visual similarity between the snake and butterfly antennae. Regarding one species, she notes that “its antennae look like two colourful snakes, white and black,” whereas for another she writes that “the antennae are like black snakes.”33 Might snakelike curiosity further embody slipperiness in the thin antennae-like lines of inquiry that strike out from oneself in filamentous questions or filamentary questioning? Tendrils of fauna; vines of animalia. Snaking out, snaking round, snaking through.

致谢

Acknowledgments

这样的嬉戏会引发各种回忆。我们情不自禁地回忆起那些让我们找到了好奇心的甜蜜自由的人。当我们在此向某些人表示感谢时，我们也想提到那些未提及姓名的人：作家和科学家，无论是肉体上的还是精神上的，如果没有他们，我们的道路就会变得贫乏甚至不可能。尽管我们倾向于孤独，但好奇心对我们来说从来都不是个人作品。它是一项友谊和交流的项目。但愿这只是我们见证的开始。

A romp of this sort prompts all sorts of reminiscing. We cannot help but recollect those with and against whom we have found the sweet freedoms of curiosity. As we extend our thanks herein to certain folks, we also want to mention those unnamed: the writers and scientists, both of flesh and of spirit, without whom our path would have been impoverished or even impossible. Curiosity for us has never been a solo production, despite our propensities for the solitary. It has been a project of friendship and communion. May this be but the beginning of our testimony.

我们要感谢好奇心课程的学生，包括宾夕法尼亚大学的“好奇心：关于思考的古代和现代思考”课程（2018 年秋季和 2020 年春季）、汉普郡学院的“好奇心伦理”课程（2016 年春季）以及美国大学的“好奇心哲学”以及“好奇心、政治和公共领域”课程（2018 年春季和 2019 年秋季）。如果没有学生们在本课程内外提出的尖锐问题和丰富的探索路线，这本书就不会有现在的一半趣味。

We wish to thank the students in our curiosity classes, including the Curiosity: Ancient and Modern Thinking about Thinking course at the University of Pennsylvania (fall 2018 and spring 2020), the Ethics of Curiosity course at Hampshire College (spring 2016), and the Philosophy of Curiosity as well as Curiosity, Politics, and the Public Realm courses at American University (spring 2018 and fall 2019). Without students’ incisive questions and rich lines of flight both within and beyond this material, this book would not be half as interesting.

我们感谢来自世界各地的众多听众，他们与我们讨论了与好奇心相关的研究。特别感谢美国教育研究协会、美国哲学协会、批判谱系研讨会、德里达今日、存在主义的多元谱系、philoSOPHIA、现象学和存在主义哲学学会和跨哲学项目会议，以及阿德尔菲国际学术项目的听众大学、伦敦情感脑实验室、美国大学、阿巴拉契亚州立大学、布鲁克林公共哲学家、复杂科学中心、选择好奇播客、复杂空间 - CSS 卫星、德保罗大学、德堡大学、五所大学妇女研究中心、汉普郡学院、哈弗福德学院、麻省理工学院媒体实验室、科罗拉多大学丹佛分校、北卡罗来纳大学夏洛特分校、想象力研究所、宾夕法尼亚网络可视化项目、李小学、开放连接、麦克莱恩研究所精神病学技术峰会、都柏林圣三一学院、维拉诺瓦大学、西城学校和维基媒体基金会。

We are grateful to the many audiences with which we have discussed our curiosity-related research, stretching around the globe. Specific thanks goes out to the American Educational Research Association, American Philosophical Association, Critical Genealogies Workshop, Derrida Today, Diverse Lineages of Existentialism, philoSOPHIA, Society for Phenomenology and Existential Philosophy, and Trans Philosophy Project conferences as well as audiences at Academic Programs International, Adelphi University, Affective Brain Lab in London, American University, Appalachian State University, Brooklyn Public Philosophers, Centro de Ciencias de la Complejidad, Choose to Be Curious podcast, Complex-Space—CSS Satellite, DePaul University, DePauw University, Five College Women’s Studies Research Center, Hampshire College, Haverford College, MIT Media Lab, University of Colorado at Denver, University of North Carolina at Charlotte, Imagination Institute, Penn Network Visualization Program, Lea Elementary, Open Connections, Technology in Psychiatry Summit at the McLean Institute, Trinity College Dublin, Villanova University, Westtown School, and Wikimedia Foundation.

我们感谢我们的老师和教授激发了我们的好奇心，特别是 Sandy Feinstein、Thomas J. Lynn、David Mills、Michael Naas 和 Emily Zakin。特别感谢 Barry 和 Mary Hannigan 向我们介绍了 JRR Tolkien 以及约翰内斯·勃拉姆斯和弗里德里克·弗朗索瓦·肖邦的奇迹。

We offer appreciation to our teachers and professors for igniting our curiosity, especially Sandy Feinstein, Thomas J. Lynn, David Mills, Michael Naas, and Emily Zakin. A special thanks goes out to Barry and Mary Hannigan for introducing us to J. R. R. Tolkien along with the wonders of Johannes Brahms and Frédéric François Chopin.

我们要感谢那些早已逝去的人们，他们创作的书籍和诗歌继续滋养着我们的思想，无论是在我们年轻时收藏在Borders书店，还是最近的鲍德温书店、Myopic Books书店、Raven Used Books书店和Montague Book Mill书店。

We wish to thank the minds of those people long past who wrote books and poems that continue to nourish our thinking, whether housed in the Borders bookstores of our youth, or more recently, Baldwin’s Book Barn, Myopic Books, Raven Used Books, and the Montague Book Mill.

我们向所有密切合作者表示感谢。特别是我们在好奇心研究方面的合作者：Arjun Shankar、Peter T. Struck、David M. Lydon-Staley 和 Dale Zhou。还有那些同事，他们塑造了一种广阔的、不受约束的好奇心，让我们以不同的方式看待世界：Andrew Dilts、Andrea Pitts、Rachel & Jenn、Christopher Macklin、Edward T. Bullmore 和 Mason A. Porter。和你们一起好奇地漫步在我们领域的核心和边缘之外是一种难以言表的快乐。

We extend our thanks to all our close collaborators. Especially to our collaborators in curiosity studies: Arjun Shankar, Peter T. Struck, David M. Lydon-Staley, and Dale Zhou. And to the colleagues who have modeled an expansive, de-disciplined curiosity by which we saw the world differently: Andrew Dilts, Andrea Pitts, Rachel & Jenn, Christopher Macklin, Edward T. Bullmore, and Mason A. Porter. Rambling curiously with you in the very heart of our fields and out past their edges has been an unspeakable pleasure.

我们要感谢麻省理工学院出版社的 Bob Prior 确保了该项目并指导其出版。我们非常感谢我们亲切的评论者和读者，包括 Lynn Borton（来自“选择好奇”播客）、Sophia U. David 和 Dale Zhou，以及我们热心的索引编制者 Mark Hineline。我们非常荣幸能与 Poonam Mistry 合作，并对她的创造性艺术感到敬畏。我们特别感谢好奇心中心的支持为完成这项工作提供了大量的时间和空间。

We wish to thank Bob Prior at the MIT Press for securing the project and guiding it through to publication. We are so grateful to our gracious reviewers and readers, including Lynn Borton (of the Choose to Be Curious podcast), Sophia U. David, and Dale Zhou, and to our keen indexer, Mark Hineline. We are deeply honored to have worked with Poonam Mistry and are in awe of her creative artistry. And we offer special appreciation to the Center for Curiosity, whose support provided much of the time and space to complete this work.

我们深深感谢母亲守护着我们探索大事小事的魔力。感谢祖母成为我们的私人 Ole Worm。感谢 Silas、Simi 和 Remy，他们确实是充满好奇心的孩子。特别感谢 Asia 慷慨地为 Perry 提供了这些文字的空间。

We offer profound thanks to our mother for safeguarding the magic of questioning things large and small. To our grandmother, for being our own personal Ole Worm. And to Silas, Simi, and Remy, who are indeed great big bundles of curiosity. Special thanks to Asia for so generously cultivating the space in which Perry could find these words.

最重要的是，我们彼此感激。以后有机会我们再来一次吧。

And most of all, we are grateful for each other. Let’s do this again sometime.

介绍

Introduction

1.参见苏珊·恩格尔，《饥饿的心灵：童年好奇心的起源》（马萨诸塞州剑桥：哈佛大学出版社，2015 年），第 5 页。恩格尔在书的开头描述了吃虫子这一典型的好奇行为，而在这里，我们想象好奇心本身的行为就像虫子一样。

1. Cf. Susan Engel, The Hungry Mind: The Origins of Curiosity in Childhood (Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press, 2015), 5. Engel opens her book with the paradigmatically curious act of eating a bug, while here we imagine curiosity itself behaving like a bug.

2.参见弗吉尼亚·伍尔夫，《为什么？》（1942），《散文集》（纽约：哈考特出版社，1966 年），第 2 卷，第 278-283 页。在这篇文章中，她对大学讲座的做法进行了精彩的讽刺。

2. Cf. Virginia Woolf, “Why?” (1942), in Collected Essays (New York: Harcourt, 1966), 2:278–283. In this essay, she wonderfully lampoons the practice of university lectures.

3.弗吉尼亚·伍尔夫，《一间自己的房间》（纽约：Harcourt Brace Jovanovich，1929年），第5页。

3. Virginia Woolf, A Room of One’s Own (New York: Harcourt Brace Jovanovich, 1929), 5.

4.伍尔夫，《一间自己的房间》，4-8页。

4. Woolf, A Room of One’s Own, 4–8.

5.有关我们合作中科学与人文学科之间关系的更多信息，请参阅 Perry Zurn 和 Danielle S. Bassett 的《抓住机遇》，《eLife Magazine》第 8 卷，第 e48336 期（2019 年）：1-5。

5. For more on the relationship between the sciences and humanities in our work together, see Perry Zurn and Danielle S. Bassett, “Seizing an Opportunity,” eLife Magazine 8, no. e48336 (2019): 1–5.

6.圣奥古斯丁，《忏悔录》（剑桥：洛布古典图书馆，2014 年），尤其是第二卷、第十卷。另请参阅约瑟夫·托奇亚，《不安的心：圣奥古斯丁心理学中的好奇心和探究范围》（密尔沃基：马凯特大学出版社，2013 年）。

6. Saint Augustine, The Confessions (Cambridge: Loeb Classical Library, 2014), especially Book II, Book X. See also Joseph Torchia, Restless Mind: Curiositas and the Scope of Inquiry in St. Augustine’s Psychology (Milwaukee: Marquette University Press, 2013).

4.在认识的过程中，我们始终是知者也是不知者，在已知和未知的世界中穿梭，而这些已知和未知本身属于知识（即已知事物的系统）和未知（即未知事物的神秘网络）。同样重要的是，认识的过程需要实践未知——松开边缘、连根拔起节点并重新配置网络。虽然本书的大部分内容都集中在知识网络构建上，但我们在结论中又回到了必要的配套项目——解构（或“破解”）。

4. In the process of coming to know, we are always both knowers and unknowers, navigating a world of knowns and unknowns, which themselves belong to knowledges (i.e., systems of things known) and unknowledges (i.e., mysterious networks of things not yet known). And just as important, that project of coming to know requires the practice of unknowing—loosening edges, uprooting nodes, and reconfiguring networks. While much of this book focuses on knowledge network building, we return to the necessary companion project of unbuilding (or “cracking”) in the conclusion.

第四章

Chapter 4

1.我们通过诸如polypragmosyne（希腊语）、periergia（希腊语）、curiositas（拉丁语）、curiosité（法语）、Neugier（德语）、curiosity（英语）等来追踪“curiosity”一词。

1. We track the word “curiosity” through, for example, polypragmosyne (Greek), periergia (Greek), curiositas (Latin), curiosité (French), Neugier (German), curiosity (English), and so on.

2.当然，正如哲学家罗曼·弗瑞格所说，文学人物和理论模型的共同点比人们想象的要多得多。例如，请参阅罗曼·弗瑞格的《模型与虚构》，《Synthese 》第 172 卷（2010 年）：第 251-268 页。

2. Of course, as philosopher Roman Frigg would argue, literary figures and theoretical models have far more in common than one might think. See, for example, Roman Frigg, “Models and Fiction,” Synthese 172 (2010): 251–268.

3. Stephen Hartmann 和 Roman Frigg，《科学模型》，《科学哲学：百科全书》，Sahotra Sarkar 和 Jessica Pfeifer 编辑（纽约：劳特利奇，2005 年），第 2 卷：740–749 页。

3. Stephen Hartmann and Roman Frigg, “Scientific Models,” in The Philosophy of Science: An Encyclopedia, ed. Sahotra Sarkar and Jessica Pfeifer (New York: Routledge, 2005), 2:740–749.

4.马修·利，《从多面手到好奇：好奇和爱管闲事的行为的古代概念》（牛津：牛津大学出版社，2013年），第16-53页；杰森·范·尼克尔克，《八卦的美德》，《南非哲学杂志》第27卷，第4期（2013年）：第400-416页。

4. Matthew Leigh, From Polypragmon to Curiosus: Ancient Concepts of Curious and Meddlesome Behavior (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2013), 16–53; Jason van Niekerk, “The Virtue of Gossip,” South African Journal of Philosophy 27, no. 4 (2013): 400–416.

5 . Philo Judaeus，“De Agricultura”，收录于Philo Judaeus 的著作，译。查尔斯·杜克·央格（Charles Duke Yonge）（伦敦：HG Bohn，1854–1890），§34。

5. Philo Judaeus, “De Agricultura,” in The Works of Philo Judaeus, trans. Charles Duke Yonge (London: H. G. Bohn, 1854–1890), §34.

13. The word explore stems from the Latin verb plorare, meaning to cry out, wail, or lament. As ancient authors attest, the earliest sense of explorare was to reconnoiter a new hunting ground for game by shouting from different coordinates. This is an early connection between the art of hunting and the practice of curiosity.

第五章

Chapter 5

1 .约翰·沃尔夫冈·冯·歌德，《植物的变形》，摄影师戈登·L·米勒（马萨诸塞州剑桥：麻省理工学院出版社，2009 年）。

1. Johann Wolfgang von Goethe, The Metamorphosis of Plants, photographer Gordon L. Miller (Cambridge, MA: MIT Press, 2009).

2.这些社会文化过程在科学知识的增长中尤为明显，科学文化决定了每种问题的价值。参见例如，Karine Chelma 和 Evelyn Fox Keller 著《没有文化主义的文化：科学知识的形成》（北卡罗来纳州达勒姆：杜克大学出版社，2017 年）。不幸的是，这种文化是由人类创造的，从而使科学探究的愿景变得不那么光明。人类通常对边缘化性别、种族和族裔的人有显性和隐性的偏见，因此人类的科学文化会比其他人更推崇某些提问者的问题。例如，见 Jordan D. Dworkin、Kristin A. Linn、Erin G. Teich、Perry Zurn、Russell T. Shinohara 和 Danielle S. Bassett 著《神经科学参考文献列表中性别不平衡的程度及其驱动因素》，《自然神经科学》第 23 卷，第 8 期 (2020)：第 918–926 页；Paula Chakravartty、Rachel Kuo、Victoria Grubbs 和 Charlton McIlwain 著《#CommunicationSoWhite》， 《传播学杂志》第 68卷，第 8 期 (2020)：第 918–926 页2 (2018)：254–266；Michelle L. Dion、Jane Lawrence Sumner 和 Sara McLaughlin Mitchell，“政治科学和社会科学方法论领域的性别引文模式”，《政治分析》 26，第 3 期 (2018)：312–327。因此，科学中的未知数，无论是局部空洞还是已知事物周围的巨大空间，在一定程度上都是边缘化思想家提出的问题的答案。例如，请参阅 Bas Hofstra、Vivek V. Kulkarni、Sebastian Munoz-Najar Galvez、Bryan He、Dan Jurafsky 和 ​​Daniel A. McFarland，“科学中的多样性-创新悖论”，《美国国家科学院院刊》 117，第 17 期 (2020)：9284–9291。我们的工作是制定一条公平的科学探究轨迹，以自由探索真理的方式规划我们探索未知领域的旅程，摆脱将我们限制在少数人道路上的枷锁。例如，请参阅乔丹·德沃金、佩里·祖恩和丹尼尔·S·巴塞特的《（鼓励）采取行动实现公平的未来》，《神经元》 106，第 6 期（2020 年）：第 890-894 页。

2. These sociocultural processes are particularly evident in the growth of scientific knowledge, where the culture of science determines the value placed on each kind of question. See, for example, Karine Chelma and Evelyn Fox Keller, Cultures without Culturalism: The Making of Scientific Knowledge (Durham, NC: Duke University Press, 2017). Unfortunately, that culture is created by humans, thereby making the vision of scientific inquiry somewhat less bright. Humans generally share explicit and implicit biases against people of marginalized genders, races, and ethnicities, and thus human scientific culture extols the questions of some questioners more than others. See, for example, Jordan D. Dworkin, Kristin A. Linn, Erin G. Teich, Perry Zurn, Russell T. Shinohara, and Danielle S. Bassett, “The Extent and Drivers of Gender Imbalance in Neuroscience Reference Lists,” Nature Neuroscience 23, no. 8 (2020): 918–926; Paula Chakravartty, Rachel Kuo, Victoria Grubbs, and Charlton McIlwain, “#CommunicationSoWhite,” Journal of Communication 68, no. 2 (2018): 254–266; Michelle L. Dion, Jane Lawrence Sumner, and Sara McLaughlin Mitchell, “Gendered Citation Patterns across Political Science and Social Science Methodology Fields,” Political Analysis 26, no. 3 (2018): 312–327. The unknowns in science, both the local holes and the giant space surrounding the knowns, are therefore in part the answers to the questions posed by marginalized thinkers. See, for example, Bas Hofstra, Vivek V. Kulkarni, Sebastian Munoz-Najar Galvez, Bryan He, Dan Jurafsky, and Daniel A. McFarland, “The Diversity-Innovation Paradox in Science,” Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences 117, no. 17 (2020): 9284–9291. Our work is cut out for us in developing an equitable trajectory of scientific inquiry that charts our forays into the space of the unknowns in a way that freely searches for the truth, throwing off the chains that constrain us to the paths of an arbitrarily select few. See, for example, Jordan Dworkin, Perry Zurn, and Danielle S. Bassett, “(In)citing Action to Realize an Equitable Future,” Neuron 106, no. 6 (2020): 890–894.
